4.1.2.3 Anatomy of a Rust Program
.................................

Let's review this ‚ÄúHello, world!‚Äù program in detail.  Here's the first
piece of the puzzle:

fn main() {

}

These lines define a function named ‚Äòmain‚Äô.  The ‚Äòmain‚Äô function is
special: it is always the first code that runs in every executable Rust
program.  Here, the first line declares a function named ‚Äòmain‚Äô that has
no parameters and returns nothing.  If there were parameters, they would
go inside the parentheses ‚Äò()‚Äô.

The function body is wrapped in ‚Äò{}‚Äô.  Rust requires curly brackets
around all function bodies.  It's good style to place the opening curly
bracket on the same line as the function declaration, adding one space
in between.

Note: If you want to stick to a standard style across Rust projects, you
can use an automatic formatter tool called ‚Äòrustfmt‚Äô to format your code
in a particular style (more on ‚Äòrustfmt‚Äô in *note Appendix D: Appendix D
- Useful Development Tools.).  The Rust team has included this tool with
the standard Rust distribution, as ‚Äòrustc‚Äô is, so it should already be
installed on your computer!

The body of the ‚Äòmain‚Äô function holds the following code:

println!("Hello, world!");

This line does all the work in this little program: it prints text to
the screen.  There are four important details to notice here.

First, Rust style is to indent with four spaces, not a tab.

Second, ‚Äòprintln!‚Äô calls a Rust macro.  If it had called a function
instead, it would be entered as ‚Äòprintln‚Äô (without the ‚Äò!‚Äô).  We'll
discuss Rust macros in more detail in Chapter 20.  For now, you just
need to know that using a ‚Äò!‚Äô means that you're calling a macro instead
of a normal function and that macros don't always follow the same rules
as functions.

Third, you see the ‚Äò"Hello, world!"‚Äô string.  We pass this string as an
argument to ‚Äòprintln!‚Äô, and the string is printed to the screen.

Fourth, we end the line with a semicolon (‚Äò;‚Äô), which indicates that
this expression is over and the next one is ready to begin.  Most lines
of Rust code end with a semicolon.


