4.1.2.4 Compiling and Running Are Separate Steps
................................................

You've just run a newly created program, so let's examine each step in
the process.

Before running a Rust program, you must compile it using the Rust
compiler by entering the ‚Äòrustc‚Äô command and passing it the name of your
source file, like this:

$ rustc main.rs

If you have a C or C++ background, you'll notice that this is similar to
‚Äògcc‚Äô or ‚Äòclang‚Äô.  After compiling successfully, Rust outputs a binary
executable.

On Linux, macOS, and PowerShell on Windows, you can see the executable
by entering the ‚Äòls‚Äô command in your shell:

$ ls
main  main.rs

On Linux and macOS, you'll see two files.  With PowerShell on Windows,
you'll see the same three files that you would see using CMD. With CMD
on Windows, you would enter the following:

> dir /B %= the /B option says to only show the file names =%
main.exe
main.pdb
main.rs

This shows the source code file with the ‚Äò.rs‚Äô extension, the executable
file (‚Äòmain.exe‚Äô on Windows, but ‚Äòmain‚Äô on all other platforms), and,
when using Windows, a file containing debugging information with the
‚Äò.pdb‚Äô extension.  From here, you run the ‚Äòmain‚Äô or ‚Äòmain.exe‚Äô file,
like this:

$ ./main # or .\main.exe on Windows

If your ‚Äòmain.rs‚Äô is your ‚ÄúHello, world!‚Äù program, this line prints
‚ÄòHello, world!‚Äô to your terminal.

If you're more familiar with a dynamic language, such as Ruby, Python,
or JavaScript, you might not be used to compiling and running a program
as separate steps.  Rust is an ‚Äòahead-of-time compiled‚Äô language,
meaning you can compile a program and give the executable to someone
else, and they can run it even without having Rust installed.  If you
give someone a ‚Äò.rb‚Äô, ‚Äò.py‚Äô, or ‚Äò.js‚Äô file, they need to have a Ruby,
Python, or JavaScript implementation installed (respectively).  But in
those languages, you only need one command to compile and run your
program.  Everything is a trade-off in language design.

Just compiling with ‚Äòrustc‚Äô is fine for simple programs, but as your
project grows, you'll want to manage all the options and make it easy to
share your code.  Next, we'll introduce you to the Cargo tool, which
will help you write real-world Rust programs.


