4.1.3.1 Creating a Project with Cargo
.....................................

Let's create a new project using Cargo and look at how it differs from
our original ‚ÄúHello, world!‚Äù project.  Navigate back to your ‚Äòprojects‚Äô
directory (or wherever you decided to store your code).  Then, on any
operating system, run the following:

$ cargo new hello_cargo
$ cd hello_cargo

The first command creates a new directory and project called
‚Äòhello_cargo‚Äô.  We've named our project ‚Äòhello_cargo‚Äô, and Cargo creates
its files in a directory of the same name.

Go into the ‚Äòhello_cargo‚Äô directory and list the files.  You'll see that
Cargo has generated two files and one directory for us: a ‚ÄòCargo.toml‚Äô
file and a ‚Äòsrc‚Äô directory with a ‚Äòmain.rs‚Äô file inside.

It has also initialized a new Git repository along with a ‚Äò.gitignore‚Äô
file.  Git files won't be generated if you run ‚Äòcargo new‚Äô within an
existing Git repository; you can override this behavior by using ‚Äòcargo
new --vcs=git‚Äô.

Note: Git is a common version control system.  You can change ‚Äòcargo
new‚Äô to use a different version control system or no version control
system by using the ‚Äò--vcs‚Äô flag.  Run ‚Äòcargo new --help‚Äô to see the
available options.

Open ‚ÄòCargo.toml‚Äô in your text editor of choice.  It should look similar
to the code in Listing 1-2.

[package]
name = "hello_cargo"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

# See more keys and their definitions at https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/reference/manifest.html

[dependencies]

This file is in the ‚ÄòTOML‚Äô (https://toml.io) (‚ÄòTom's Obvious, Minimal
Language‚Äô) format, which is Cargo's configuration format.

The first line, ‚Äò[package]‚Äô, is a section heading that indicates that
the following statements are configuring a package.  As we add more
information to this file, we'll add other sections.

The next three lines set the configuration information Cargo needs to
compile your program: the name, the version, and the edition of Rust to
use.  We'll talk about the ‚Äòedition‚Äô key in *note Appendix E: Appendix E
- Editions.

The last line, ‚Äò[dependencies]‚Äô, is the start of a section for you to
list any of your project's dependencies.  In Rust, packages of code are
referred to as ‚Äòcrates‚Äô.  We won't need any other crates for this
project, but we will in the first project in Chapter 2, so we'll use
this dependencies section then.

Now open ‚Äòsrc/main.rs‚Äô and take a look:

Filename: src/main.rs

fn main() {
    println!("Hello, world!");
}

Cargo has generated a ‚ÄúHello, world!‚Äù program for you, just like the one
we wrote in Listing 1-1!  So far, the differences between our project
and the project Cargo generated are that Cargo placed the code in the
‚Äòsrc‚Äô directory and we have a ‚ÄòCargo.toml‚Äô configuration file in the top
directory.

Cargo expects your source files to live inside the ‚Äòsrc‚Äô directory.  The
top-level project directory is just for README files, license
information, configuration files, and anything else not related to your
code.  Using Cargo helps you organize your projects.  There's a place
for everything, and everything is in its place.

If you started a project that doesn't use Cargo, as we did with the
‚ÄúHello, world!‚Äù project, you can convert it to a project that does use
Cargo.  Move the project code into the ‚Äòsrc‚Äô directory and create an
appropriate ‚ÄòCargo.toml‚Äô file.  One easy way to get that ‚ÄòCargo.toml‚Äô
file is to run ‚Äòcargo init‚Äô, which will create it for you automatically.


