If a type you want to use isn't in the prelude, you have to bring that
type into scope explicitly with a ‚Äòuse‚Äô statement.  Using the ‚Äòstd::io‚Äô
library provides you with a number of useful features, including the
ability to accept user input.

As you saw in Chapter 1, the ‚Äòmain‚Äô function is the entry point into the
program:

fn main() {

The ‚Äòfn‚Äô syntax declares a new function; the parentheses, ‚Äò()‚Äô, indicate
there are no parameters; and the curly bracket, ‚Äò{‚Äô, starts the body of
