5.2.1 Storing Values with Variables
-----------------------------------

Next, we'll create a ‚Äòvariable‚Äô to store the user input, like this:

    let mut guess = String::new();

Now the program is getting interesting!  There's a lot going on in this
little line.  We use the ‚Äòlet‚Äô statement to create the variable.  Here's
another example:

let apples = 5;

This line creates a new variable named ‚Äòapples‚Äô and binds it to the
value 5.  In Rust, variables are immutable by default, meaning once we
give the variable a value, the value won't change.  We'll be discussing
this concept in detail in the *note ‚ÄúVariables and Mutability‚Äù:
Variables and Mutability. section in Chapter 3.  To make a variable
mutable, we add ‚Äòmut‚Äô before the variable name:

let apples = 5; // immutable
let mut bananas = 5; // mutable

Note: The ‚Äò//‚Äô syntax starts a comment that continues until the end of
the line.  Rust ignores everything in comments.  We'll discuss comments
in more detail in *note Chapter 3: Comments.

Returning to the guessing game program, you now know that ‚Äòlet mut
guess‚Äô will introduce a mutable variable named ‚Äòguess‚Äô.  The equal sign
(‚Äò=‚Äô) tells Rust we want to bind something to the variable now.  On the
right of the equal sign is the value that ‚Äòguess‚Äô is bound to, which is
the result of calling ‚ÄòString::new‚Äô, a function that returns a new
instance of a ‚ÄòString‚Äô.  ‚ÄòString‚Äô
(https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/../std/string/struct.String.html) is a
string type provided by the standard library that is a growable, UTF-8
encoded bit of text.

The ‚Äò::‚Äô syntax in the ‚Äò::new‚Äô line indicates that ‚Äònew‚Äô is an
associated function of the ‚ÄòString‚Äô type.  An ‚Äòassociated function‚Äô is a
function that's implemented on a type, in this case ‚ÄòString‚Äô.  This
‚Äònew‚Äô function creates a new, empty string.  You'll find a ‚Äònew‚Äô
function on many types because it's a common name for a function that
makes a new value of some kind.

In full, the ‚Äòlet mut guess = String::new();‚Äô line has created a mutable
variable that is currently bound to a new, empty instance of a ‚ÄòString‚Äô.
Whew!


