5.2.2 Receiving User Input
--------------------------

Recall that we included the input/output functionality from the standard
library with ‚Äòuse std::io;‚Äô on the first line of the program.  Now we'll
call the ‚Äòstdin‚Äô function from the ‚Äòio‚Äô module, which will allow us to
handle user input:

    io::stdin()
        .read_line(&mut guess)

If we hadn't imported the ‚Äòio‚Äô library with ‚Äòuse std::io;‚Äô at the
beginning of the program, we could still use the function by writing
this function call as ‚Äòstd::io::stdin‚Äô.  The ‚Äòstdin‚Äô function returns an
instance of ‚ÄòstdioStdin‚Äô
(https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/../std/io/struct.Stdin.html), which is a
type that represents a handle to the standard input for your terminal.

Next, the line ‚Äò.read_line(&mut guess)‚Äô calls the ‚Äòread_line‚Äô
(https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/../std/io/struct.Stdin.html) method on
the standard input handle to get input from the user.  We're also
passing ‚Äò&mut guess‚Äô as the argument to ‚Äòread_line‚Äô to tell it what
string to store the user input in.  The full job of ‚Äòread_line‚Äô is to
take whatever the user types into standard input and append that into a
string (without overwriting its contents), so we therefore pass that
string as an argument.  The string argument needs to be mutable so the
method can change the string's content.

The ‚Äò&‚Äô indicates that this argument is a ‚Äòreference‚Äô, which gives you a
way to let multiple parts of your code access one piece of data without
needing to copy that data into memory multiple times.  References are a
complex feature, and one of Rust's major advantages is how safe and easy
it is to use references.  You don't need to know a lot of those details
to finish this program.  For now, all you need to know is that, like
variables, references are immutable by default.  Hence, you need to
write ‚Äò&mut guess‚Äô rather than ‚Äò&guess‚Äô to make it mutable.  (Chapter 4
will explain references more thoroughly.)


