5.2.3 Handling Potential Failure with ‚ÄòResult‚Äô
----------------------------------------------

We're still working on this line of code.  We're now discussing a third
line of text, but note that it's still part of a single logical line of
code.  The next part is this method:

        .expect("Failed to read line");

We could have written this code as:

io::stdin().read_line(&mut guess).expect("Failed to read line");

However, one long line is difficult to read, so it's best to divide it.
It's often wise to introduce a newline and other whitespace to help
break up long lines when you call a method with the ‚Äò.method_name()‚Äô
syntax.  Now let's discuss what this line does.

As mentioned earlier, ‚Äòread_line‚Äô puts whatever the user enters into the
string we pass to it, but it also returns a ‚ÄòResult‚Äô value.  ‚ÄòResult‚Äô
(https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/../std/result/enum.Result.html) is an
*note ‚Äòenumeration‚Äô: Enums and Pattern Matching, often called an ‚Äòenum‚Äô,
which is a type that can be in one of multiple possible states.  We call
each possible state a ‚Äòvariant‚Äô.

*note Chapter 6: Enums and Pattern Matching. will cover enums in more
detail.  The purpose of these ‚ÄòResult‚Äô types is to encode error-handling
information.

‚ÄòResult‚Äô's variants are ‚ÄòOk‚Äô and ‚ÄòErr‚Äô.  The ‚ÄòOk‚Äô variant indicates the
operation was successful, and inside ‚ÄòOk‚Äô is the successfully generated
value.  The ‚ÄòErr‚Äô variant means the operation failed, and ‚ÄòErr‚Äô contains
information about how or why the operation failed.

Values of the ‚ÄòResult‚Äô type, like values of any type, have methods
defined on them.  An instance of ‚ÄòResult‚Äô has an ‚Äòexpect‚Äô method
(https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/../std/result/enum.Result.html) that you
can call.  If this instance of ‚ÄòResult‚Äô is an ‚ÄòErr‚Äô value, ‚Äòexpect‚Äô will
cause the program to crash and display the message that you passed as an
argument to ‚Äòexpect‚Äô.  If the ‚Äòread_line‚Äô method returns an ‚ÄòErr‚Äô, it
would likely be the result of an error coming from the underlying
operating system.  If this instance of ‚ÄòResult‚Äô is an ‚ÄòOk‚Äô value,
‚Äòexpect‚Äô will take the return value that ‚ÄòOk‚Äô is holding and return just
that value to you so you can use it.  In this case, that value is the
number of bytes in the user's input.

If you don't call ‚Äòexpect‚Äô, the program will compile, but you'll get a
warning:

