    // --snip--

    println!("You guessed: {guess}");

    match guess.cmp(&secret_number) {
        Ordering::Less => println!("Too small!"),
        Ordering::Greater => println!("Too big!"),
        Ordering::Equal => println!("You win!"),
    }
}

First we add another ‚Äòuse‚Äô statement, bringing a type called
‚Äòstd::cmp::Ordering‚Äô into scope from the standard library.  The
‚ÄòOrdering‚Äô type is another enum and has the variants ‚ÄòLess‚Äô, ‚ÄòGreater‚Äô,
and ‚ÄòEqual‚Äô.  These are the three outcomes that are possible when you
compare two values.

Then we add five new lines at the bottom that use the ‚ÄòOrdering‚Äô type.
The ‚Äòcmp‚Äô method compares two values and can be called on anything that
can be compared.  It takes a reference to whatever you want to compare
with: here it's comparing ‚Äòguess‚Äô to ‚Äòsecret_number‚Äô.  Then it returns a
variant of the ‚ÄòOrdering‚Äô enum we brought into scope with the ‚Äòuse‚Äô
statement.  We use a *note ‚Äòmatch‚Äô: The match Control Flow Construct.
expression to decide what to do next based on which variant of
‚ÄòOrdering‚Äô was returned from the call to ‚Äòcmp‚Äô with the values in
‚Äòguess‚Äô and ‚Äòsecret_number‚Äô.

A ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression is made up of ‚Äòarms‚Äô.  An arm consists of a
‚Äòpattern‚Äô to match against, and the code that should be run if the value
given to ‚Äòmatch‚Äô fits that arm's pattern.  Rust takes the value given to
‚Äòmatch‚Äô and looks through each arm's pattern in turn.  Patterns and the
‚Äòmatch‚Äô construct are powerful Rust features: they let you express a
variety of situations your code might encounter and they make sure you
handle them all.  These features will be covered in detail in Chapter 6
and Chapter 19, respectively.

Let's walk through an example with the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression we use here.
Say that the user has guessed 50 and the randomly generated secret
number this time is 38.

When the code compares 50 to 38, the ‚Äòcmp‚Äô method will return
‚ÄòOrdering::Greater‚Äô because 50 is greater than 38.  The ‚Äòmatch‚Äô
expression gets the ‚ÄòOrdering::Greater‚Äô value and starts checking each
arm's pattern.  It looks at the first arm's pattern, ‚ÄòOrdering::Less‚Äô,
and sees that the value ‚ÄòOrdering::Greater‚Äô does not match
‚ÄòOrdering::Less‚Äô, so it ignores the code in that arm and moves to the
next arm.  The next arm's pattern is ‚ÄòOrdering::Greater‚Äô, which ‚Äòdoes‚Äô
match ‚ÄòOrdering::Greater‚Äô!  The associated code in that arm will execute
and print ‚ÄòToo big!‚Äô to the screen.  The ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression ends after
the first successful match, so it won't look at the last arm in this
scenario.

