We switch from an ‚Äòexpect‚Äô call to a ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression to move from
crashing on an error to handling the error.  Remember that ‚Äòparse‚Äô
returns a ‚ÄòResult‚Äô type and ‚ÄòResult‚Äô is an enum that has the variants
‚ÄòOk‚Äô and ‚ÄòErr‚Äô.  We're using a ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression here, as we did with
the ‚ÄòOrdering‚Äô result of the ‚Äòcmp‚Äô method.

If ‚Äòparse‚Äô is able to successfully turn the string into a number, it
will return an ‚ÄòOk‚Äô value that contains the resultant number.  That ‚ÄòOk‚Äô
value will match the first arm's pattern, and the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression
will just return the ‚Äònum‚Äô value that ‚Äòparse‚Äô produced and put inside
the ‚ÄòOk‚Äô value.  That number will end up right where we want it in the
new ‚Äòguess‚Äô variable we're creating.

