6.2 Variables and Mutability
============================

As mentioned in the *note ‚ÄúStoring Values with Variables‚Äù: Storing
Values with Variables. section, by default, variables are immutable.
This is one of many nudges Rust gives you to write your code in a way
that takes advantage of the safety and easy concurrency that Rust
offers.  However, you still have the option to make your variables
mutable.  Let's explore how and why Rust encourages you to favor
immutability and why sometimes you might want to opt out.

When a variable is immutable, once a value is bound to a name, you can't
change that value.  To illustrate this, generate a new project called
‚Äòvariables‚Äô in your ‚Äòprojects‚Äô directory by using ‚Äòcargo new variables‚Äô.

Then, in your new ‚Äòvariables‚Äô directory, open ‚Äòsrc/main.rs‚Äô and replace
its code with the following code, which won't compile just yet:

Filename: src/main.rs

fn main() {
    let x = 5;
    println!("The value of x is: {x}");
    x = 6;
    println!("The value of x is: {x}");
}

Save and run the program using ‚Äòcargo run‚Äô.  You should receive an error
message regarding an immutability error, as shown in this output:

$ cargo run
   Compiling variables v0.1.0 (file:///projects/variables)
error[E0384]: cannot assign twice to immutable variable `x`
 --> src/main.rs:4:5
  |
2 |     let x = 5;
  |         - first assignment to `x`
3 |     println!("The value of x is: {x}");
4 |     x = 6;
  |     ^^^^^ cannot assign twice to immutable variable
  |
help: consider making this binding mutable
  |
2 |     let mut x = 5;
  |         +++

For more information about this error, try `rustc --explain E0384`.
error: could not compile `variables` (bin "variables") due to 1 previous error

This example shows how the compiler helps you find errors in your
programs.  Compiler errors can be frustrating, but really they only mean
your program isn't safely doing what you want it to do yet; they do
‚Äònot‚Äô mean that you're not a good programmer!  Experienced Rustaceans
still get compiler errors.

You received the error message ‚Äòcannot assign twice to immutable
variable `x`‚Äô because you tried to assign a second value to the
immutable ‚Äòx‚Äô variable.

It's important that we get compile-time errors when we attempt to change
a value that's designated as immutable because this very situation can
lead to bugs.  If one part of our code operates on the assumption that a
value will never change and another part of our code changes that value,
it's possible that the first part of the code won't do what it was
designed to do.  The cause of this kind of bug can be difficult to track
down after the fact, especially when the second piece of code changes
the value only ‚Äòsometimes‚Äô.  The Rust compiler guarantees that when you
state that a value won't change, it really won't change, so you don't
have to keep track of it yourself.  Your code is thus easier to reason
through.

But mutability can be very useful, and can make code more convenient to
write.  Although variables are immutable by default, you can make them
mutable by adding ‚Äòmut‚Äô in front of the variable name as you did in
*note Chapter 2: Storing Values with Variables.  Adding ‚Äòmut‚Äô also
conveys intent to future readers of the code by indicating that other
parts of the code will be changing this variable's value.

For example, let's change ‚Äòsrc/main.rs‚Äô to the following:

Filename: src/main.rs

fn main() {
    let mut x = 5;
    println!("The value of x is: {x}");
    x = 6;
    println!("The value of x is: {x}");
}

When we run the program now, we get this:

$ cargo run
   Compiling variables v0.1.0 (file:///projects/variables)
    Finished `dev` profile [unoptimized + debuginfo] target(s) in 0.30s
     Running `target/debug/variables`
The value of x is: 5
The value of x is: 6

We're allowed to change the value bound to ‚Äòx‚Äô from ‚Äò5‚Äô to ‚Äò6‚Äô when
‚Äòmut‚Äô is used.  Ultimately, deciding whether to use mutability or not is
up to you and depends on what you think is clearest in that particular
situation.

