6.3.1 Scalar Types
------------------

A ‚Äòscalar‚Äô type represents a single value.  Rust has four primary scalar
types: integers, floating-point numbers, Booleans, and characters.  You
may recognize these from other programming languages.  Let's jump into
how they work in Rust.  Integer Types An ‚Äòinteger‚Äô is a number without a
fractional component.  We used one integer type in Chapter 2, the ‚Äòu32‚Äô
type.  This type declaration indicates that the value it's associated
with should be an unsigned integer (signed integer types start with ‚Äòi‚Äô
instead of ‚Äòu‚Äô) that takes up 32 bits of space.  Table 3-1 shows the
built-in integer types in Rust.  We can use any of these variants to
declare the type of an integer value.

Table 3-1: Integer Types in Rust

Length    Signed    Unsigned
------------------------------
8-bit     ‚Äòi8‚Äô      ‚Äòu8‚Äô
16-bit    ‚Äòi16‚Äô     ‚Äòu16‚Äô
32-bit    ‚Äòi32‚Äô     ‚Äòu32‚Äô
64-bit    ‚Äòi64‚Äô     ‚Äòu64‚Äô
128-bit   ‚Äòi128‚Äô    ‚Äòu128‚Äô
arch      ‚Äòisize‚Äô   ‚Äòusize‚Äô

Each variant can be either signed or unsigned and has an explicit size.
‚ÄòSigned‚Äô and ‚Äòunsigned‚Äô refer to whether it's possible for the number to
be negative--in other words, whether the number needs to have a sign
with it (signed) or whether it will only ever be positive and can
therefore be represented without a sign (unsigned).  It's like writing
numbers on paper: when the sign matters, a number is shown with a plus
sign or a minus sign; however, when it's safe to assume the number is
positive, it's shown with no sign.  Signed numbers are stored using
two's complement (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Two%27s_complement)
representation.

Each signed variant can store numbers from -(2^n - 1) to 2^n - 1 - 1
inclusive, where ‚Äòn‚Äô is the number of bits that variant uses.  So an
‚Äòi8‚Äô can store numbers from -(2^7) to 2^7 - 1, which equals -128 to 127.
Unsigned variants can store numbers from 0 to 2n - 1, so a ‚Äòu8‚Äô can
store numbers from 0 to 2^8 - 1, which equals 0 to 255.

Additionally, the ‚Äòisize‚Äô and ‚Äòusize‚Äô types depend on the architecture
of the computer your program is running on, which is denoted in the
table as ‚Äúarch‚Äù: 64 bits if you're on a 64-bit architecture and 32 bits
if you're on a 32-bit architecture.

You can write integer literals in any of the forms shown in Table 3-2.
Note that number literals that can be multiple numeric types allow a
type suffix, such as ‚Äò57u8‚Äô, to designate the type.  Number literals can
also use ‚Äò_‚Äô as a visual separator to make the number easier to read,
such as ‚Äò1_000‚Äô, which will have the same value as if you had specified
‚Äò1000‚Äô.

Table 3-2: Integer Literals in Rust

Number literals    Example
-----------------------------------
Decimal            ‚Äò98_222‚Äô
Hex                ‚Äò0xff‚Äô
Octal              ‚Äò0o77‚Äô
Binary             ‚Äò0b1111_0000‚Äô
Byte (‚Äòu8‚Äô only)   ‚Äòb'A'‚Äô

So how do you know which type of integer to use?  If you're unsure,
Rust's defaults are generally good places to start: integer types
default to ‚Äòi32‚Äô.  The primary situation in which you'd use ‚Äòisize‚Äô or
‚Äòusize‚Äô is when indexing some sort of collection.

Integer Overflow Let's say you have a variable of type ‚Äòu8‚Äô that can
hold values between 0 and 255.  If you try to change the variable to a
value outside that range, such as 256, ‚Äòinteger overflow‚Äô will occur,
which can result in one of two behaviors.  When you're compiling in
debug mode, Rust includes checks for integer overflow that cause your
program to ‚Äòpanic‚Äô at runtime if this behavior occurs.  Rust uses the
term ‚Äòpanicking‚Äô when a program exits with an error; we'll discuss
panics in more depth in the *note ‚ÄúUnrecoverable Errors with ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô‚Äù:
Unrecoverable Errors with panic!. section in Chapter 9.

When you're compiling in release mode with the ‚Äò--release‚Äô flag, Rust
does ‚Äònot‚Äô include checks for integer overflow that cause panics.
Instead, if overflow occurs, Rust performs ‚Äòtwo's complement wrapping‚Äô.
In short, values greater than the maximum value the type can hold ‚Äúwrap
around‚Äù to the minimum of the values the type can hold.  In the case of
a ‚Äòu8‚Äô, the value 256 becomes 0, the value 257 becomes 1, and so on.
The program won't panic, but the variable will have a value that
probably isn't what you were expecting it to have.  Relying on integer
overflow's wrapping behavior is considered an error.

To explicitly handle the possibility of overflow, you can use these
families of methods provided by the standard library for primitive
numeric types:

   ‚Ä¢ Wrap in all modes with the ‚Äòwrapping_*‚Äô methods, such as
     ‚Äòwrapping_add‚Äô.
   ‚Ä¢ Return the ‚ÄòNone‚Äô value if there is overflow with the ‚Äòchecked_*‚Äô
     methods.
   ‚Ä¢ Return the value and a boolean indicating whether there was
     overflow with the ‚Äòoverflowing_*‚Äô methods.
   ‚Ä¢ Saturate at the value's minimum or maximum values with the
     ‚Äòsaturating_*‚Äô methods.

Floating-Point Types Rust also has two primitive types for
‚Äòfloating-point numbers‚Äô, which are numbers with decimal points.  Rust's
