in size, respectively.  The default type is ‚Äòf64‚Äô because on modern
CPUs, it's roughly the same speed as ‚Äòf32‚Äô but is capable of more
precision.  All floating-point types are signed.

Here's an example that shows floating-point numbers in action:

Filename: src/main.rs

fn main() {
    let x = 2.0; // f64

    let y: f32 = 3.0; // f32
}

Floating-point numbers are represented according to the IEEE-754
standard.  Numeric Operations Rust supports the basic mathematical
