6.4 Functions
=============

Functions are prevalent in Rust code.  You've already seen one of the
most important functions in the language: the ‚Äòmain‚Äô function, which is
the entry point of many programs.  You've also seen the ‚Äòfn‚Äô keyword,
which allows you to declare new functions.

Rust code uses ‚Äòsnake case‚Äô as the conventional style for function and
variable names, in which all letters are lowercase and underscores
separate words.  Here's a program that contains an example function
definition:

Filename: src/main.rs

fn main() {
    println!("Hello, world!");

    another_function();
}

fn another_function() {
    println!("Another function.");
}

We define a function in Rust by entering ‚Äòfn‚Äô followed by a function
name and a set of parentheses.  The curly brackets tell the compiler
where the function body begins and ends.

We can call any function we've defined by entering its name followed by
a set of parentheses.  Because ‚Äòanother_function‚Äô is defined in the
program, it can be called from inside the ‚Äòmain‚Äô function.  Note that we
defined ‚Äòanother_function‚Äô ‚Äòafter‚Äô the ‚Äòmain‚Äô function in the source
code; we could have defined it before as well.  Rust doesn't care where
you define your functions, only that they're defined somewhere in a
scope that can be seen by the caller.

Let's start a new binary project named ‚Äòfunctions‚Äô to explore functions
further.  Place the ‚Äòanother_function‚Äô example in ‚Äòsrc/main.rs‚Äô and run
it.  You should see the following output:

