6.4.1 Parameters
----------------

We can define functions to have ‚Äòparameters‚Äô, which are special
variables that are part of a function's signature.  When a function has
parameters, you can provide it with concrete values for those
parameters.  Technically, the concrete values are called ‚Äòarguments‚Äô,
but in casual conversation, people tend to use the words ‚Äòparameter‚Äô and
‚Äòargument‚Äô interchangeably for either the variables in a function's
definition or the concrete values passed in when you call a function.

In this version of ‚Äòanother_function‚Äô we add a parameter:

Filename: src/main.rs

fn main() {
    another_function(5);
}

fn another_function(x: i32) {
    println!("The value of x is: {x}");
}

Try running this program; you should get the following output:

$ cargo run
   Compiling functions v0.1.0 (file:///projects/functions)
    Finished `dev` profile [unoptimized + debuginfo] target(s) in 1.21s
     Running `target/debug/functions`
The value of x is: 5

The declaration of ‚Äòanother_function‚Äô has one parameter named ‚Äòx‚Äô.  The
type of ‚Äòx‚Äô is specified as ‚Äòi32‚Äô.  When we pass ‚Äò5‚Äô in to
‚Äòanother_function‚Äô, the ‚Äòprintln!‚Äô macro puts ‚Äò5‚Äô where the pair of
curly brackets containing ‚Äòx‚Äô was in the format string.

In function signatures, you ‚Äòmust‚Äô declare the type of each parameter.
This is a deliberate decision in Rust's design: requiring type
annotations in function definitions means the compiler almost never
needs you to use them elsewhere in the code to figure out what type you
mean.  The compiler is also able to give more helpful error messages if
it knows what types the function expects.

When defining multiple parameters, separate the parameter declarations
with commas, like this:

Filename: src/main.rs

fn main() {
    print_labeled_measurement(5, 'h');
}

fn print_labeled_measurement(value: i32, unit_label: char) {
    println!("The measurement is: {value}{unit_label}");
}

This example creates a function named ‚Äòprint_labeled_measurement‚Äô with
two parameters.  The first parameter is named ‚Äòvalue‚Äô and is an ‚Äòi32‚Äô.
The second is named ‚Äòunit_label‚Äô and is type ‚Äòchar‚Äô.  The function then
prints text containing both the ‚Äòvalue‚Äô and the ‚Äòunit_label‚Äô.

Let's try running this code.  Replace the program currently in your
