6.6.1 ‚Äòif‚Äô Expressions
----------------------

An ‚Äòif‚Äô expression allows you to branch your code depending on
conditions.  You provide a condition and then state, ‚ÄúIf this condition
is met, run this block of code.  If the condition is not met, do not run
this block of code.‚Äù

Create a new project called ‚Äòbranches‚Äô in your ‚Äòprojects‚Äô directory to
explore the ‚Äòif‚Äô expression.  In the ‚Äòsrc/main.rs‚Äô file, input the
following:

Filename: src/main.rs

fn main() {
    let number = 3;

    if number < 5 {
        println!("condition was true");
    } else {
        println!("condition was false");
    }
}

All ‚Äòif‚Äô expressions start with the keyword ‚Äòif‚Äô, followed by a
condition.  In this case, the condition checks whether or not the
variable ‚Äònumber‚Äô has a value less than 5.  We place the block of code
to execute if the condition is ‚Äòtrue‚Äô immediately after the condition
inside curly brackets.  Blocks of code associated with the conditions in
‚Äòif‚Äô expressions are sometimes called ‚Äòarms‚Äô, just like the arms in
‚Äòmatch‚Äô expressions that we discussed in the *note ‚ÄúComparing the Guess
to the Secret Number‚Äù: Comparing the Guess to the Secret Number. section
of Chapter 2.

Optionally, we can also include an ‚Äòelse‚Äô expression, which we chose to
do here, to give the program an alternative block of code to execute
should the condition evaluate to ‚Äòfalse‚Äô.  If you don't provide an
‚Äòelse‚Äô expression and the condition is ‚Äòfalse‚Äô, the program will just
skip the ‚Äòif‚Äô block and move on to the next bit of code.

Try running this code; you should see the following output:

$ cargo run
   Compiling branches v0.1.0 (file:///projects/branches)
    Finished `dev` profile [unoptimized + debuginfo] target(s) in 0.31s
     Running `target/debug/branches`
condition was true

Let's try changing the value of ‚Äònumber‚Äô to a value that makes the
condition ‚Äòfalse‚Äô to see what happens:

    let number = 7;

Run the program again, and look at the output:

$ cargo run
   Compiling branches v0.1.0 (file:///projects/branches)
    Finished `dev` profile [unoptimized + debuginfo] target(s) in 0.31s
     Running `target/debug/branches`
condition was false

It's also worth noting that the condition in this code ‚Äòmust‚Äô be a
‚Äòbool‚Äô.  If the condition isn't a ‚Äòbool‚Äô, we'll get an error.  For
example, try running the following code:

Filename: src/main.rs

fn main() {
    let number = 3;

    if number {
        println!("number was three");
    }
}

The ‚Äòif‚Äô condition evaluates to a value of ‚Äò3‚Äô this time, and Rust
throws an error:

$ cargo run
   Compiling branches v0.1.0 (file:///projects/branches)
error[E0308]: mismatched types
 --> src/main.rs:4:8
  |
4 |     if number {
  |        ^^^^^^ expected `bool`, found integer

For more information about this error, try `rustc --explain E0308`.
error: could not compile `branches` (bin "branches") due to 1 previous error

The error indicates that Rust expected a ‚Äòbool‚Äô but got an integer.
Unlike languages such as Ruby and JavaScript, Rust will not
automatically try to convert non-Boolean types to a Boolean.  You must
be explicit and always provide ‚Äòif‚Äô with a Boolean as its condition.  If
we want the ‚Äòif‚Äô code block to run only when a number is not equal to
‚Äò0‚Äô, for example, we can change the ‚Äòif‚Äô expression to the following:

Filename: src/main.rs

fn main() {
    let number = 3;

    if number != 0 {
        println!("number was something other than zero");
    }
}

Running this code will print ‚Äònumber was something other than zero‚Äô.
Handling Multiple Conditions with ‚Äòelse if‚Äô You can use multiple
conditions by combining ‚Äòif‚Äô and ‚Äòelse‚Äô in an ‚Äòelse if‚Äô expression.  For
example:

Filename: src/main.rs

fn main() {
    let number = 6;

    if number % 4 == 0 {
        println!("number is divisible by 4");
    } else if number % 3 == 0 {
        println!("number is divisible by 3");
    } else if number % 2 == 0 {
        println!("number is divisible by 2");
    } else {
        println!("number is not divisible by 4, 3, or 2");
    }
}

This program has four possible paths it can take.  After running it, you
should see the following output:

$ cargo run
   Compiling branches v0.1.0 (file:///projects/branches)
    Finished `dev` profile [unoptimized + debuginfo] target(s) in 0.31s
     Running `target/debug/branches`
number is divisible by 3

When this program executes, it checks each ‚Äòif‚Äô expression in turn and
executes the first body for which the condition evaluates to ‚Äòtrue‚Äô.
Note that even though 6 is divisible by 2, we don't see the output
‚Äònumber is divisible by 2‚Äô, nor do we see the ‚Äònumber is not divisible
by 4, 3, or 2‚Äô text from the ‚Äòelse‚Äô block.  That's because Rust only
executes the block for the first ‚Äòtrue‚Äô condition, and once it finds
one, it doesn't even check the rest.

Using too many ‚Äòelse if‚Äô expressions can clutter your code, so if you
have more than one, you might want to refactor your code.  Chapter 6
describes a powerful Rust branching construct called ‚Äòmatch‚Äô for these
cases.  Using ‚Äòif‚Äô in a ‚Äòlet‚Äô Statement Because ‚Äòif‚Äô is an expression,
we can use it on the right side of a ‚Äòlet‚Äô statement to assign the
outcome to a variable, as in Listing 3-2.

fn main() {
    let condition = true;
    let number = if condition { 5 } else { 6 };

    println!("The value of number is: {number}");
}

