    loop {
        println!("again!");
    }
}

When we run this program, we'll see ‚Äòagain!‚Äô printed over and over
continuously until we stop the program manually.  Most terminals support
the keyboard shortcut ctrl-c to interrupt a program that is stuck in a
continual loop.  Give it a try:

$ cargo run
   Compiling loops v0.1.0 (file:///projects/loops)
    Finished `dev` profile [unoptimized + debuginfo] target(s) in 0.08s
     Running `target/debug/loops`
again!
again!
again!
again!
^Cagain!

The symbol ‚Äò^C‚Äô represents where you pressed ctrl-c.  You may or may not
see the word ‚Äòagain!‚Äô printed after the ‚Äò^C‚Äô, depending on where the
code was in the loop when it received the interrupt signal.

Fortunately, Rust also provides a way to break out of a loop using code.
You can place the ‚Äòbreak‚Äô keyword within the loop to tell the program
when to stop executing the loop.  Recall that we did this in the
guessing game in the *note ‚ÄúQuitting After a Correct Guess‚Äù: Quitting
After a Correct Guess. section of Chapter 2 to exit the program when the
user won the game by guessing the correct number.

We also used ‚Äòcontinue‚Äô in the guessing game, which in a loop tells the
program to skip over any remaining code in this iteration of the loop
and go to the next iteration.  Returning Values from Loops One of the
uses of a ‚Äòloop‚Äô is to retry an operation you know might fail, such as
checking whether a thread has completed its job.  You might also need to
pass the result of that operation out of the loop to the rest of your
code.  To do this, you can add the value you want returned after the
‚Äòbreak‚Äô expression you use to stop the loop; that value will be returned
out of the loop so you can use it, as shown here:

fn main() {
    let mut counter = 0;

    let result = loop {
        counter += 1;

        if counter == 10 {
            break counter * 2;
        }
    };

    println!("The result is {result}");
}

Before the loop, we declare a variable named ‚Äòcounter‚Äô and initialize it
to ‚Äò0‚Äô.  Then we declare a variable named ‚Äòresult‚Äô to hold the value
returned from the loop.  On every iteration of the loop, we add ‚Äò1‚Äô to
the ‚Äòcounter‚Äô variable, and then check whether the ‚Äòcounter‚Äô is equal to
‚Äò10‚Äô.  When it is, we use the ‚Äòbreak‚Äô keyword with the value ‚Äòcounter *
2‚Äô.  After the loop, we use a semicolon to end the statement that
assigns the value to ‚Äòresult‚Äô.  Finally, we print the value in ‚Äòresult‚Äô,
which in this case is ‚Äò20‚Äô.

You can also ‚Äòreturn‚Äô from inside a loop.  While ‚Äòbreak‚Äô only exits the
current loop, ‚Äòreturn‚Äô always exits the current function.  Loop Labels
