7.1.4 The ‚ÄòString‚Äô Type
-----------------------

To illustrate the rules of ownership, we need a data type that is more
complex than those we covered in the *note ‚ÄúData Types‚Äù: Data Types.
section of Chapter 3.  The types covered previously are of a known size,
can be stored on the stack and popped off the stack when their scope is
over, and can be quickly and trivially copied to make a new, independent
instance if another part of code needs to use the same value in a
different scope.  But we want to look at data that is stored on the heap
and explore how Rust knows when to clean up that data, and the ‚ÄòString‚Äô
type is a great example.

We'll concentrate on the parts of ‚ÄòString‚Äô that relate to ownership.
These aspects also apply to other complex data types, whether they are
provided by the standard library or created by you.  We'll discuss
‚ÄòString‚Äô in more depth in *note Chapter 8: Storing UTF-8 Encoded Text
