The length is how much memory, in bytes, the contents of the ‚ÄòString‚Äô
are currently using.  The capacity is the total amount of memory, in
bytes, that the ‚ÄòString‚Äô has received from the allocator.  The
difference between length and capacity matters, but not in this context,
so for now, it's fine to ignore the capacity.

When we assign ‚Äòs1‚Äô to ‚Äòs2‚Äô, the ‚ÄòString‚Äô data is copied, meaning we
copy the pointer, the length, and the capacity that are on the stack.
We do not copy the data on the heap that the pointer refers to.  In
