Earlier, we said that when a variable goes out of scope, Rust
automatically calls the ‚Äòdrop‚Äô function and cleans up the heap memory
for that variable.  But Figure 4-2 shows both data pointers pointing to
the same location.  This is a problem: when ‚Äòs2‚Äô and ‚Äòs1‚Äô go out of
scope, they will both try to free the same memory.  This is known as a
‚Äòdouble free‚Äô error and is one of the memory safety bugs we mentioned
previously.  Freeing memory twice can lead to memory corruption, which
can potentially lead to security vulnerabilities.

To ensure memory safety, after the line ‚Äòlet s2 = s1;‚Äô, Rust considers
‚Äòs1‚Äô as no longer valid.  Therefore, Rust doesn't need to free anything
when ‚Äòs1‚Äô goes out of scope.  Check out what happens when you try to use
‚Äòs1‚Äô after ‚Äòs2‚Äô is created; it won't work:

    let s1 = String::from("hello");
    let s2 = s1;

    println!("{s1}, world!");

