In addition, there's a design choice that's implied by this: Rust will
never automatically create ‚Äúdeep‚Äù copies of your data.  Therefore, any
‚Äòautomatic‚Äô copying can be assumed to be inexpensive in terms of runtime
performance.  Scope and Assignment The inverse of this is true for the
relationship between scoping, ownership, and memory being freed via the
‚Äòdrop‚Äô function as well.  When you assign a completely new value to an
existing variable, Rust will call ‚Äòdrop‚Äô and free the original value's
memory immediately.  Consider this code, for example:

    let mut s = String::from("hello");
    s = String::from("ahoy");

    println!("{s}, world!");

We initially declare a variable ‚Äòs‚Äô and bind it to a ‚ÄòString‚Äô with the
value ‚Äò"hello"‚Äô.  Then we immediately create a new ‚ÄòString‚Äô with the
value ‚Äò"ahoy"‚Äô and assign it to ‚Äòs‚Äô.  At this point, nothing is
referring to the original value on the heap at all.

