The original string thus immediately goes out of scope.  Rust will run
the ‚Äòdrop‚Äô function on it and its memory will be freed right away.  When
we print the value at the end, it will be ‚Äò"ahoy, world!"‚Äô.  Variables
and Data Interacting with Clone If we ‚Äòdo‚Äô want to deeply copy the heap
data of the ‚ÄòString‚Äô, not just the stack data, we can use a common
method called ‚Äòclone‚Äô.  We'll discuss method syntax in Chapter 5, but
because methods are a common feature in many programming languages,
you've probably seen them before.

Here's an example of the ‚Äòclone‚Äô method in action:

    let s1 = String::from("hello");
    let s2 = s1.clone();

    println!("s1 = {s1}, s2 = {s2}");

This works just fine and explicitly produces the behavior shown in
Figure 4-3, where the heap data ‚Äòdoes‚Äô get copied.

When you see a call to ‚Äòclone‚Äô, you know that some arbitrary code is
being executed and that code may be expensive.  It's a visual indicator
that something different is going on.  Stack-Only Data: Copy There's
another wrinkle we haven't talked about yet.  This code using
integers--part of which was shown in Listing 4-2--works and is valid:

    let x = 5;
    let y = x;

    println!("x = {x}, y = {y}");

But this code seems to contradict what we just learned: we don't have a
call to ‚Äòclone‚Äô, but ‚Äòx‚Äô is still valid and wasn't moved into ‚Äòy‚Äô.

The reason is that types such as integers that have a known size at
compile time are stored entirely on the stack, so copies of the actual
values are quick to make.  That means there's no reason we would want to
prevent ‚Äòx‚Äô from being valid after we create the variable ‚Äòy‚Äô.  In other
words, there's no difference between deep and shallow copying here, so
calling ‚Äòclone‚Äô wouldn't do anything different from the usual shallow
copying, and we can leave it out.

Rust has a special annotation called the ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô trait that we can place
on types that are stored on the stack, as integers are (we'll talk more
about traits in *note Chapter 10: Traits Defining Shared Behavior.).  If
a type implements the ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô trait, variables that use it do not move,
but rather are trivially copied, making them still valid after
assignment to another variable.

Rust won't let us annotate a type with ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô if the type, or any of its
parts, has implemented the ‚ÄòDrop‚Äô trait.  If the type needs something
special to happen when the value goes out of scope and we add the ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô
annotation to that type, we'll get a compile-time error.  To learn about
how to add the ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô annotation to your type to implement the trait,
see *note ‚ÄúDerivable Traits‚Äù: Appendix C Derivable Traits. in Appendix
C.

So, what types implement the ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô trait?  You can check the
documentation for the given type to be sure, but as a general rule, any
group of simple scalar values can implement ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô, and nothing that
requires allocation or is some form of resource can implement ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô.
Here are some of the types that implement ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô:

   ‚Ä¢ All the integer types, such as ‚Äòu32‚Äô.
   ‚Ä¢ The Boolean type, ‚Äòbool‚Äô, with values ‚Äòtrue‚Äô and ‚Äòfalse‚Äô.
   ‚Ä¢ All the floating-point types, such as ‚Äòf64‚Äô.
   ‚Ä¢ The character type, ‚Äòchar‚Äô.
   ‚Ä¢ Tuples, if they only contain types that also implement ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô.  For
     example, ‚Äò(i32, i32)‚Äô implements ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô, but ‚Äò(i32, String)‚Äô does
     not.


