7.2 References and Borrowing
============================

The issue with the tuple code in Listing 4-5 is that we have to return
the ‚ÄòString‚Äô to the calling function so we can still use the ‚ÄòString‚Äô
after the call to ‚Äòcalculate_length‚Äô, because the ‚ÄòString‚Äô was moved
into ‚Äòcalculate_length‚Äô.  Instead, we can provide a reference to the
‚ÄòString‚Äô value.  A ‚Äòreference‚Äô is like a pointer in that it's an address
we can follow to access the data stored at that address; that data is
owned by some other variable.  Unlike a pointer, a reference is
guaranteed to point to a valid value of a particular type for the life
of that reference.

Here is how you would define and use a ‚Äòcalculate_length‚Äô function that
has a reference to an object as a parameter instead of taking ownership
of the value:

fn main() {
    let s1 = String::from("hello");

    let len = calculate_length(&s1);

    println!("The length of '{s1}' is {len}.");
}

fn calculate_length(s: &String) -> usize {
    s.len()
}

First, notice that all the tuple code in the variable declaration and
the function return value is gone.  Second, note that we pass ‚Äò&s1‚Äô into
‚Äòcalculate_length‚Äô and, in its definition, we take ‚Äò&String‚Äô rather than
‚ÄòString‚Äô.  These ampersands represent ‚Äòreferences‚Äô, and they allow you
to refer to some value without taking ownership of it.  Figure 4-6
depicts this concept.

