7.2.1 Mutable References
------------------------

We can fix the code from Listing 4-6 to allow us to modify a borrowed
value with just a few small tweaks that use, instead, a ‚Äòmutable
reference‚Äô:

fn main() {
    let mut s = String::from("hello");

    change(&mut s);
}

fn change(some_string: &mut String) {
    some_string.push_str(", world");
}

First we change ‚Äòs‚Äô to be ‚Äòmut‚Äô.  Then we create a mutable reference
with ‚Äò&mut s‚Äô where we call the ‚Äòchange‚Äô function, and update the
function signature to accept a mutable reference with ‚Äòsome_string: &mut
String‚Äô.  This makes it very clear that the ‚Äòchange‚Äô function will
mutate the value it borrows.

Mutable references have one big restriction: if you have a mutable
reference to a value, you can have no other references to that value.
This code that attempts to create two mutable references to ‚Äòs‚Äô will
fail:

    let mut s = String::from("hello");

    let r1 = &mut s;
    let r2 = &mut s;

    println!("{}, {}", r1, r2);

Here's the error:

$ cargo run
   Compiling ownership v0.1.0 (file:///projects/ownership)
error[E0499]: cannot borrow `s` as mutable more than once at a time
 --> src/main.rs:5:14
  |
4 |     let r1 = &mut s;
  |              ------ first mutable borrow occurs here
5 |     let r2 = &mut s;
  |              ^^^^^^ second mutable borrow occurs here
6 |
7 |     println!("{}, {}", r1, r2);
  |                        -- first borrow later used here

