This error says that this code is invalid because we cannot borrow ‚Äòs‚Äô
as mutable more than once at a time.  The first mutable borrow is in
‚Äòr1‚Äô and must last until it's used in the ‚Äòprintln!‚Äô, but between the
creation of that mutable reference and its usage, we tried to create
another mutable reference in ‚Äòr2‚Äô that borrows the same data as ‚Äòr1‚Äô.

The restriction preventing multiple mutable references to the same data
at the same time allows for mutation but in a very controlled fashion.
It's something that new Rustaceans struggle with because most languages
let you mutate whenever you'd like.  The benefit of having this
restriction is that Rust can prevent data races at compile time.  A
‚Äòdata race‚Äô is similar to a race condition and happens when these three
behaviors occur:

   ‚Ä¢ Two or more pointers access the same data at the same time.
   ‚Ä¢ At least one of the pointers is being used to write to the data.
   ‚Ä¢ There's no mechanism being used to synchronize access to the data.

Data races cause undefined behavior and can be difficult to diagnose and
fix when you're trying to track them down at runtime; Rust prevents this
problem by refusing to compile code with data races!

As always, we can use curly brackets to create a new scope, allowing for
multiple mutable references, just not ‚Äòsimultaneous‚Äô ones:

    let mut s = String::from("hello");

    {
        let r1 = &mut s;
    } // r1 goes out of scope here, so we can make a new reference with no problems.

    let r2 = &mut s;

Rust enforces a similar rule for combining mutable and immutable
references.  This code results in an error:

    let mut s = String::from("hello");

    let r1 = &s; // no problem
    let r2 = &s; // no problem
    let r3 = &mut s; // BIG PROBLEM

