7.3.1 String Slices
-------------------

A ‚Äòstring slice‚Äô is a reference to part of a ‚ÄòString‚Äô, and it looks like
this:

    let s = String::from("hello world");

    let hello = &s[0..5];
    let world = &s[6..11];

Rather than a reference to the entire ‚ÄòString‚Äô, ‚Äòhello‚Äô is a reference
to a portion of the ‚ÄòString‚Äô, specified in the extra ‚Äò[0..5]‚Äô bit.  We
create slices using a range within brackets by specifying
‚Äò[starting_index..ending_index]‚Äô, where ‚Äòstarting_index‚Äô is the first
position in the slice and ‚Äòending_index‚Äô is one more than the last
position in the slice.  Internally, the slice data structure stores the
starting position and the length of the slice, which corresponds to
‚Äòending_index‚Äô minus ‚Äòstarting_index‚Äô.  So, in the case of ‚Äòlet world =
&s[6..11];‚Äô, ‚Äòworld‚Äô would be a slice that contains a pointer to the
byte at index 6 of ‚Äòs‚Äô with a length value of ‚Äò5‚Äô.

