Update Syntax It's often useful to create a new instance of a struct
that includes most of the values from another instance, but changes
some.  You can do this using ‚Äòstruct update syntax‚Äô.

First, in Listing 5-6 we show how to create a new ‚ÄòUser‚Äô instance in
‚Äòuser2‚Äô regularly, without the update syntax.  We set a new value for
‚Äòemail‚Äô but otherwise use the same values from ‚Äòuser1‚Äô that we created
in Listing 5-2.

fn main() {
    // --snip--

    let user2 = User {
        active: user1.active,
        username: user1.username,
        email: String::from("another@example.com"),
        sign_in_count: user1.sign_in_count,
    };
}

Using struct update syntax, we can achieve the same effect with less
code, as shown in Listing 5-7.  The syntax ‚Äò..‚Äô specifies that the
remaining fields not explicitly set should have the same value as the
fields in the given instance.

fn main() {
    // --snip--

    let user2 = User {
        email: String::from("another@example.com"),
        ..user1
    };
}

The code in Listing 5-7 also creates an instance in ‚Äòuser2‚Äô that has a
different value for ‚Äòemail‚Äô but has the same values for the ‚Äòusername‚Äô,
‚Äòactive‚Äô, and ‚Äòsign_in_count‚Äô fields from ‚Äòuser1‚Äô.  The ‚Äò..user1‚Äô must
come last to specify that any remaining fields should get their values
from the corresponding fields in ‚Äòuser1‚Äô, but we can choose to specify
values for as many fields as we want in any order, regardless of the
order of the fields in the struct's definition.

Note that the struct update syntax uses ‚Äò=‚Äô like an assignment; this is
because it moves the data, just as we saw in the *note ‚ÄúVariables and
Data Interacting with Move‚Äù:
#book__pandoc__texi__src__ch04-01-what-is-ownershipmd__variables-and-data-interacting-with-move.
section.  In this example, we can no longer use ‚Äòuser1‚Äô as a whole after
creating ‚Äòuser2‚Äô because the ‚ÄòString‚Äô in the ‚Äòusername‚Äô field of ‚Äòuser1‚Äô
was moved into ‚Äòuser2‚Äô.  If we had given ‚Äòuser2‚Äô new ‚ÄòString‚Äô values for
both ‚Äòemail‚Äô and ‚Äòusername‚Äô, and thus only used the ‚Äòactive‚Äô and
‚Äòsign_in_count‚Äô values from ‚Äòuser1‚Äô, then ‚Äòuser1‚Äô would still be valid
after creating ‚Äòuser2‚Äô.  Both ‚Äòactive‚Äô and ‚Äòsign_in_count‚Äô are types
that implement the ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô trait, so the behavior we discussed in the
*note ‚ÄúStack-Only Data Copy‚Äù:
#book__pandoc__texi__src__ch04-01-what-is-ownershipmd__stack-only-data-copy.
section would apply.  We can still use ‚Äòuser1.email‚Äô in this example,
since its value was ‚Äònot‚Äô moved out.


