8.1.1.3 Unit-Like Structs Without Any Fields
............................................

You can also define structs that don't have any fields!  These are
called ‚Äòunit-like structs‚Äô because they behave similarly to ‚Äò()‚Äô, the
unit type that we mentioned in *note ‚ÄúThe Tuple Type‚Äù:
#book__pandoc__texi__src__ch03-02-data-typesmd__the-tuple-type. section.
Unit-like structs can be useful when you need to implement a trait on
some type but don't have any data that you want to store in the type
itself.  We'll discuss traits in Chapter 10.  Here's an example of
declaring and instantiating a unit struct named ‚ÄòAlwaysEqual‚Äô:

struct AlwaysEqual;

fn main() {
    let subject = AlwaysEqual;
}

To define ‚ÄòAlwaysEqual‚Äô, we use the ‚Äòstruct‚Äô keyword, the name we want,
and then a semicolon.  No need for curly brackets or parentheses!  Then
we can get an instance of ‚ÄòAlwaysEqual‚Äô in the ‚Äòsubject‚Äô variable in a
similar way: using the name we defined, without any curly brackets or
parentheses.  Imagine that later we'll implement behavior for this type
such that every instance of ‚ÄòAlwaysEqual‚Äô is always equal to every
instance of any other type, perhaps to have a known result for testing
purposes.  We wouldn't need any data to implement that behavior!  You'll
see in Chapter 10 how to define traits and implement them on any type,
including unit-like structs.


