8.1.2.2 Refactoring with Structs: Adding More Meaning
.....................................................

We use structs to add meaning by labeling the data.  We can transform
the tuple we're using into a struct with a name for the whole as well as
names for the parts, as shown in Listing 5-10.

struct Rectangle {
    width: u32,
    height: u32,
}

fn main() {
    let rect1 = Rectangle {
        width: 30,
        height: 50,
    };

    println!(
        "The area of the rectangle is {} square pixels.",
        area(&rect1)
    );
}

fn area(rectangle: &Rectangle) -> u32 {
    rectangle.width * rectangle.height
}

Here we've defined a struct and named it ‚ÄòRectangle‚Äô.  Inside the curly
brackets, we defined the fields as ‚Äòwidth‚Äô and ‚Äòheight‚Äô, both of which
have type ‚Äòu32‚Äô.  Then, in ‚Äòmain‚Äô, we created a particular instance of
‚ÄòRectangle‚Äô that has a width of ‚Äò30‚Äô and a height of ‚Äò50‚Äô.

Our ‚Äòarea‚Äô function is now defined with one parameter, which we've named
‚Äòrectangle‚Äô, whose type is an immutable borrow of a struct ‚ÄòRectangle‚Äô
instance.  As mentioned in Chapter 4, we want to borrow the struct
rather than take ownership of it.  This way, ‚Äòmain‚Äô retains its
ownership and can continue using ‚Äòrect1‚Äô, which is the reason we use the
‚Äò&‚Äô in the function signature and where we call the function.

The ‚Äòarea‚Äô function accesses the ‚Äòwidth‚Äô and ‚Äòheight‚Äô fields of the
‚ÄòRectangle‚Äô instance (note that accessing fields of a borrowed struct
instance does not move the field values, which is why you often see
borrows of structs).  Our function signature for ‚Äòarea‚Äô now says exactly
what we mean: calculate the area of ‚ÄòRectangle‚Äô, using its ‚Äòwidth‚Äô and
‚Äòheight‚Äô fields.  This conveys that the width and height are related to
each other, and it gives descriptive names to the values rather than
using the tuple index values of ‚Äò0‚Äô and ‚Äò1‚Äô.  This is a win for clarity.


