8.1.2.3 Adding Useful Functionality with Derived Traits
.......................................................

It'd be useful to be able to print an instance of ‚ÄòRectangle‚Äô while
we're debugging our program and see the values for all its fields.
Listing 5-11 tries using the ‚Äòprintln!‚Äô macro
(https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/../std/macro.println.html) as we have
used in previous chapters.  This won't work, however.

struct Rectangle {
    width: u32,
    height: u32,
}

fn main() {
    let rect1 = Rectangle {
        width: 30,
        height: 50,
    };

    println!("rect1 is {}", rect1);
}

When we compile this code, we get an error with this core message:

error[E0277]: `Rectangle` doesn't implement `std::fmt::Display`

The ‚Äòprintln!‚Äô macro can do many kinds of formatting, and by default,
the curly brackets tell ‚Äòprintln!‚Äô to use formatting known as ‚ÄòDisplay‚Äô:
output intended for direct end user consumption.  The primitive types
we've seen so far implement ‚ÄòDisplay‚Äô by default because there's only
one way you'd want to show a ‚Äò1‚Äô or any other primitive type to a user.
But with structs, the way ‚Äòprintln!‚Äô should format the output is less
clear because there are more display possibilities: Do you want commas
or not?  Do you want to print the curly brackets?  Should all the fields
be shown?  Due to this ambiguity, Rust doesn't try to guess what we
want, and structs don't have a provided implementation of ‚ÄòDisplay‚Äô to
use with ‚Äòprintln!‚Äô and the ‚Äò{}‚Äô placeholder.

If we continue reading the errors, we'll find this helpful note:

   = help: the trait `std::fmt::Display` is not implemented for `Rectangle`
   = note: in format strings you may be able to use `{:?}` (or {:#?} for pretty-print) instead

Let's try it!  The ‚Äòprintln!‚Äô macro call will now look like
‚Äòprintln!("rect1 is {rect1:?}");‚Äô.  Putting the specifier ‚Äò:?‚Äô inside
the curly brackets tells ‚Äòprintln!‚Äô we want to use an output format
called ‚ÄòDebug‚Äô.  The ‚ÄòDebug‚Äô trait enables us to print our struct in a
way that is useful for developers so we can see its value while we're
debugging our code.

Compile the code with this change.  Drat!  We still get an error:

error[E0277]: `Rectangle` doesn't implement `Debug`

But again, the compiler gives us a helpful note:

   = help: the trait `Debug` is not implemented for `Rectangle`
   = note: add `#[derive(Debug)]` to `Rectangle` or manually `impl Debug for Rectangle`

Rust ‚Äòdoes‚Äô include functionality to print out debugging information,
but we have to explicitly opt in to make that functionality available
for our struct.  To do that, we add the outer attribute
‚Äò#[derive(Debug)]‚Äô just before the struct definition, as shown in
Listing 5-12.

struct Rectangle {
    width: u32,
    height: u32,
}

fn main() {
    let rect1 = Rectangle {
        width: 30,
        height: 50,
    };

    println!("rect1 is {rect1:?}");
}

Now when we run the program, we won't get any errors, and we'll see the
following output:

$ cargo run
   Compiling rectangles v0.1.0 (file:///projects/rectangles)
    Finished `dev` profile [unoptimized + debuginfo] target(s) in 0.48s
     Running `target/debug/rectangles`
rect1 is Rectangle { width: 30, height: 50 }

Nice!  It's not the prettiest output, but it shows the values of all the
fields for this instance, which would definitely help during debugging.
When we have larger structs, it's useful to have output that's a bit
easier to read; in those cases, we can use ‚Äò{:#?}‚Äô instead of ‚Äò{:?}‚Äô in
the ‚Äòprintln!‚Äô string.  In this example, using the ‚Äò{:#?}‚Äô style will
output the following:

$ cargo run
   Compiling rectangles v0.1.0 (file:///projects/rectangles)
    Finished `dev` profile [unoptimized + debuginfo] target(s) in 0.48s
     Running `target/debug/rectangles`
rect1 is Rectangle {
    width: 30,
    height: 50,
}

Another way to print out a value using the ‚ÄòDebug‚Äô format is to use the
‚Äòdbg!‚Äô macro (https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/../std/macro.dbg.html),
which takes ownership of an expression (as opposed to ‚Äòprintln!‚Äô, which
takes a reference), prints the file and line number of where that ‚Äòdbg!‚Äô
macro call occurs in your code along with the resultant value of that
expression, and returns ownership of the value.

Note: Calling the ‚Äòdbg!‚Äô macro prints to the standard error console
stream (‚Äòstderr‚Äô), as opposed to ‚Äòprintln!‚Äô, which prints to the
standard output console stream (‚Äòstdout‚Äô).  We'll talk more about
‚Äòstderr‚Äô and ‚Äòstdout‚Äô in the *note ‚ÄúWriting Error Messages to Standard
Error Instead of Standard Output‚Äù section in Chapter 12: Writing Error
Messages to Standard Error Instead of Standard Output.

Here's an example where we're interested in the value that gets assigned
to the ‚Äòwidth‚Äô field, as well as the value of the whole struct in
‚Äòrect1‚Äô:

struct Rectangle {
    width: u32,
    height: u32,
}

fn main() {
    let scale = 2;
    let rect1 = Rectangle {
        width: dbg!(30 * scale),
        height: 50,
    };

    dbg!(&rect1);
}

We can put ‚Äòdbg!‚Äô around the expression ‚Äò30 * scale‚Äô and, because ‚Äòdbg!‚Äô
returns ownership of the expression's value, the ‚Äòwidth‚Äô field will get
the same value as if we didn't have the ‚Äòdbg!‚Äô call there.  We don't
want ‚Äòdbg!‚Äô to take ownership of ‚Äòrect1‚Äô, so we use a reference to
‚Äòrect1‚Äô in the next call.  Here's what the output of this example looks
like:

$ cargo run
   Compiling rectangles v0.1.0 (file:///projects/rectangles)
    Finished `dev` profile [unoptimized + debuginfo] target(s) in 0.61s
     Running `target/debug/rectangles`
[src/main.rs:10:16] 30 * scale = 60
[src/main.rs:14:5] &rect1 = Rectangle {
    width: 60,
    height: 50,
}

We can see the first bit of output came from ‚Äòsrc/main.rs‚Äô line 10 where
we're debugging the expression ‚Äò30 * scale‚Äô, and its resultant value is
‚Äò60‚Äô (the ‚ÄòDebug‚Äô formatting implemented for integers is to print only
their value).  The ‚Äòdbg!‚Äô call on line 14 of ‚Äòsrc/main.rs‚Äô outputs the
value of ‚Äò&rect1‚Äô, which is the ‚ÄòRectangle‚Äô struct.  This output uses
the pretty ‚ÄòDebug‚Äô formatting of the ‚ÄòRectangle‚Äô type.  The ‚Äòdbg!‚Äô macro
can be really helpful when you're trying to figure out what your code is
doing!

In addition to the ‚ÄòDebug‚Äô trait, Rust has provided a number of traits
for us to use with the ‚Äòderive‚Äô attribute that can add useful behavior
