        width: 30,
        height: 50,
    };

    println!(
        "The area of the rectangle is {} square pixels.",
        rect1.area()
    );
}

To define the function within the context of ‚ÄòRectangle‚Äô, we start an
‚Äòimpl‚Äô (implementation) block for ‚ÄòRectangle‚Äô.  Everything within this
‚Äòimpl‚Äô block will be associated with the ‚ÄòRectangle‚Äô type.  Then we move
the ‚Äòarea‚Äô function within the ‚Äòimpl‚Äô curly brackets and change the
first (and in this case, only) parameter to be ‚Äòself‚Äô in the signature
and everywhere within the body.  In ‚Äòmain‚Äô, where we called the ‚Äòarea‚Äô
function and passed ‚Äòrect1‚Äô as an argument, we can instead use ‚Äòmethod
syntax‚Äô to call the ‚Äòarea‚Äô method on our ‚ÄòRectangle‚Äô instance.  The
method syntax goes after an instance: we add a dot followed by the
method name, parentheses, and any arguments.

In the signature for ‚Äòarea‚Äô, we use ‚Äò&self‚Äô instead of ‚Äòrectangle:
&Rectangle‚Äô.  The ‚Äò&self‚Äô is actually short for ‚Äòself: &Self‚Äô.  Within
an ‚Äòimpl‚Äô block, the type ‚ÄòSelf‚Äô is an alias for the type that the
‚Äòimpl‚Äô block is for.  Methods must have a parameter named ‚Äòself‚Äô of type
‚ÄòSelf‚Äô for their first parameter, so Rust lets you abbreviate this with
only the name ‚Äòself‚Äô in the first parameter spot.  Note that we still
need to use the ‚Äò&‚Äô in front of the ‚Äòself‚Äô shorthand to indicate that
this method borrows the ‚ÄòSelf‚Äô instance, just as we did in ‚Äòrectangle:
&Rectangle‚Äô.  Methods can take ownership of ‚Äòself‚Äô, borrow ‚Äòself‚Äô
immutably, as we've done here, or borrow ‚Äòself‚Äô mutably, just as they
can any other parameter.

We chose ‚Äò&self‚Äô here for the same reason we used ‚Äò&Rectangle‚Äô in the
function version: we don't want to take ownership, and we just want to
read the data in the struct, not write to it.  If we wanted to change
the instance that we've called the method on as part of what the method
does, we'd use ‚Äò&mut self‚Äô as the first parameter.  Having a method that
takes ownership of the instance by using just ‚Äòself‚Äô as the first
parameter is rare; this technique is usually used when the method
transforms ‚Äòself‚Äô into something else and you want to prevent the caller
from using the original instance after the transformation.

The main reason for using methods instead of functions, in addition to
providing method syntax and not having to repeat the type of ‚Äòself‚Äô in
every method's signature, is for organization.  We've put all the things
we can do with an instance of a type in one ‚Äòimpl‚Äô block rather than
making future users of our code search for capabilities of ‚ÄòRectangle‚Äô
in various places in the library we provide.

Note that we can choose to give a method the same name as one of the
struct's fields.  For example, we can define a method on ‚ÄòRectangle‚Äô
that is also named ‚Äòwidth‚Äô:

impl Rectangle {
    fn width(&self) -> bool {
        self.width > 0
    }
}

fn main() {
    let rect1 = Rectangle {
        width: 30,
        height: 50,
    };

    if rect1.width() {
        println!("The rectangle has a nonzero width; it is {}", rect1.width);
    }
}

Here, we're choosing to make the ‚Äòwidth‚Äô method return ‚Äòtrue‚Äô if the
value in the instance's ‚Äòwidth‚Äô field is greater than ‚Äò0‚Äô and ‚Äòfalse‚Äô if
the value is ‚Äò0‚Äô: we can use a field within a method of the same name
for any purpose.  In ‚Äòmain‚Äô, when we follow ‚Äòrect1.width‚Äô with
parentheses, Rust knows we mean the method ‚Äòwidth‚Äô.  When we don't use
parentheses, Rust knows we mean the field ‚Äòwidth‚Äô.

Often, but not always, when we give a method the same name as a field we
want it to only return the value in the field and do nothing else.
Methods like this are called ‚Äògetters‚Äô, and Rust does not implement them
automatically for struct fields as some other languages do.  Getters are
useful because you can make the field private but the method public, and
thus enable read-only access to that field as part of the type's public
API. We will discuss what public and private are and how to designate a
field or method as public or private in *note Chapter 7: Exposing Paths
with the pub Keyword.


