8.1.3.3 Methods with More Parameters
....................................

Let's practice using methods by implementing a second method on the
‚ÄòRectangle‚Äô struct.  This time we want an instance of ‚ÄòRectangle‚Äô to
take another instance of ‚ÄòRectangle‚Äô and return ‚Äòtrue‚Äô if the second
‚ÄòRectangle‚Äô can fit completely within ‚Äòself‚Äô (the first ‚ÄòRectangle‚Äô);
otherwise, it should return ‚Äòfalse‚Äô.  That is, once we've defined the
‚Äòcan_hold‚Äô method, we want to be able to write the program shown in
Listing 5-14.

fn main() {
    let rect1 = Rectangle {
        width: 30,
        height: 50,
    };
    let rect2 = Rectangle {
        width: 10,
        height: 40,
    };
    let rect3 = Rectangle {
        width: 60,
        height: 45,
    };

    println!("Can rect1 hold rect2? {}", rect1.can_hold(&rect2));
    println!("Can rect1 hold rect3? {}", rect1.can_hold(&rect3));
}

The expected output would look like the following because both
dimensions of ‚Äòrect2‚Äô are smaller than the dimensions of ‚Äòrect1‚Äô, but
‚Äòrect3‚Äô is wider than ‚Äòrect1‚Äô:

Can rect1 hold rect2? true
Can rect1 hold rect3? false

We know we want to define a method, so it will be within the ‚Äòimpl
Rectangle‚Äô block.  The method name will be ‚Äòcan_hold‚Äô, and it will take
an immutable borrow of another ‚ÄòRectangle‚Äô as a parameter.  We can tell
what the type of the parameter will be by looking at the code that calls
the method: ‚Äòrect1.can_hold(&rect2)‚Äô passes in ‚Äò&rect2‚Äô, which is an
immutable borrow to ‚Äòrect2‚Äô, an instance of ‚ÄòRectangle‚Äô.  This makes
sense because we only need to read ‚Äòrect2‚Äô (rather than write, which
would mean we'd need a mutable borrow), and we want ‚Äòmain‚Äô to retain
ownership of ‚Äòrect2‚Äô so we can use it again after calling the ‚Äòcan_hold‚Äô
method.  The return value of ‚Äòcan_hold‚Äô will be a Boolean, and the
implementation will check whether the width and height of ‚Äòself‚Äô are
greater than the width and height of the other ‚ÄòRectangle‚Äô,
respectively.  Let's add the new ‚Äòcan_hold‚Äô method to the ‚Äòimpl‚Äô block
from Listing 5-13, shown in Listing 5-15.

impl Rectangle {
    fn area(&self) -> u32 {
        self.width * self.height
    }

    fn can_hold(&self, other: &Rectangle) -> bool {
        self.width > other.width && self.height > other.height
    }
}

When we run this code with the ‚Äòmain‚Äô function in Listing 5-14, we'll
get our desired output.  Methods can take multiple parameters that we
add to the signature after the ‚Äòself‚Äô parameter, and those parameters
work just like parameters in functions.


