9.1.2 The ‚Äòmatch‚Äô Control Flow Construct
----------------------------------------

Rust has an extremely powerful control flow construct called ‚Äòmatch‚Äô
that allows you to compare a value against a series of patterns and then
execute code based on which pattern matches.  Patterns can be made up of
literal values, variable names, wildcards, and many other things; *note
Chapter 18: Patterns and Matching. covers all the different kinds of
patterns and what they do.  The power of ‚Äòmatch‚Äô comes from the
expressiveness of the patterns and the fact that the compiler confirms
that all possible cases are handled.

Think of a ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression as being like a coin-sorting machine:
coins slide down a track with variously sized holes along it, and each
coin falls through the first hole it encounters that it fits into.  In
the same way, values go through each pattern in a ‚Äòmatch‚Äô, and at the
first pattern the value ‚Äúfits,‚Äù the value falls into the associated code
block to be used during execution.

Speaking of coins, let's use them as an example using ‚Äòmatch‚Äô!  We can
write a function that takes an unknown US coin and, in a similar way as
the counting machine, determines which coin it is and returns its value
in cents, as shown in Listing 6-3.

enum Coin {
    Penny,
    Nickel,
    Dime,
    Quarter,
}

fn value_in_cents(coin: Coin) -> u8 {
    match coin {
        Coin::Penny => 1,
        Coin::Nickel => 5,
        Coin::Dime => 10,
        Coin::Quarter => 25,
    }
}

Let's break down the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô in the ‚Äòvalue_in_cents‚Äô function.  First we
list the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô keyword followed by an expression, which in this case
is the value ‚Äòcoin‚Äô.  This seems very similar to a conditional
expression used with ‚Äòif‚Äô, but there's a big difference: with ‚Äòif‚Äô, the
condition needs to evaluate to a Boolean value, but here it can be any
type.  The type of ‚Äòcoin‚Äô in this example is the ‚ÄòCoin‚Äô enum that we
defined on the first line.

Next are the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô arms.  An arm has two parts: a pattern and some
code.  The first arm here has a pattern that is the value ‚ÄòCoin::Penny‚Äô
and then the ‚Äò=>‚Äô operator that separates the pattern and the code to
run.  The code in this case is just the value ‚Äò1‚Äô.  Each arm is
separated from the next with a comma.

When the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression executes, it compares the resultant value
against the pattern of each arm, in order.  If a pattern matches the
value, the code associated with that pattern is executed.  If that
pattern doesn't match the value, execution continues to the next arm,
much as in a coin-sorting machine.  We can have as many arms as we need:
in Listing 6-3, our ‚Äòmatch‚Äô has four arms.

The code associated with each arm is an expression, and the resultant
value of the expression in the matching arm is the value that gets
returned for the entire ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression.

We don't typically use curly brackets if the match arm code is short, as
it is in Listing 6-3 where each arm just returns a value.  If you want
to run multiple lines of code in a match arm, you must use curly
brackets, and the comma following the arm is then optional.  For
example, the following code prints ‚ÄúLucky penny!‚Äù every time the method
is called with a ‚ÄòCoin::Penny‚Äô, but still returns the last value of the
block, ‚Äò1‚Äô:

fn value_in_cents(coin: Coin) -> u8 {
    match coin {
        Coin::Penny => {
            println!("Lucky penny!");
            1
        }
        Coin::Nickel => 5,
        Coin::Dime => 10,
        Coin::Quarter => 25,
    }
}

