9.1.2.1 Patterns That Bind to Values
....................................

Another useful feature of match arms is that they can bind to the parts
of the values that match the pattern.  This is how we can extract values
out of enum variants.

As an example, let's change one of our enum variants to hold data inside
it.  From 1999 through 2008, the United States minted quarters with
different designs for each of the 50 states on one side.  No other coins
got state designs, so only quarters have this extra value.  We can add
this information to our ‚Äòenum‚Äô by changing the ‚ÄòQuarter‚Äô variant to
include a ‚ÄòUsState‚Äô value stored inside it, which we've done in Listing
6-4.

enum UsState {
    Alabama,
    Alaska,
    // --snip--
}

enum Coin {
    Penny,
    Nickel,
    Dime,
    Quarter(UsState),
}

Let's imagine that a friend is trying to collect all 50 state quarters.
While we sort our loose change by coin type, we'll also call out the
name of the state associated with each quarter so that if it's one our
friend doesn't have, they can add it to their collection.

In the match expression for this code, we add a variable called ‚Äòstate‚Äô
to the pattern that matches values of the variant ‚ÄòCoin::Quarter‚Äô.  When
a ‚ÄòCoin::Quarter‚Äô matches, the ‚Äòstate‚Äô variable will bind to the value
of that quarter's state.  Then we can use ‚Äòstate‚Äô in the code for that
arm, like so:

fn value_in_cents(coin: Coin) -> u8 {
    match coin {
        Coin::Penny => 1,
        Coin::Nickel => 5,
        Coin::Dime => 10,
        Coin::Quarter(state) => {
            println!("State quarter from {state:?}!");
            25
        }
    }
}

If we were to call ‚Äòvalue_in_cents(Coin::Quarter(UsState::Alaska))‚Äô,
‚Äòcoin‚Äô would be ‚ÄòCoin::Quarter(UsState::Alaska)‚Äô.  When we compare that
value with each of the match arms, none of them match until we reach
‚ÄòCoin::Quarter(state)‚Äô.  At that point, the binding for ‚Äòstate‚Äô will be
the value ‚ÄòUsState::Alaska‚Äô.  We can then use that binding in the
‚Äòprintln!‚Äô expression, thus getting the inner state value out of the
‚ÄòCoin‚Äô enum variant for ‚ÄòQuarter‚Äô.


