9.1.2.2 Matching with ‚ÄòOption<T>‚Äô
.................................

In the previous section, we wanted to get the inner ‚ÄòT‚Äô value out of the
‚ÄòSome‚Äô case when using ‚ÄòOption<T>‚Äô; we can also handle ‚ÄòOption<T>‚Äô using
‚Äòmatch‚Äô, as we did with the ‚ÄòCoin‚Äô enum!  Instead of comparing coins,
we'll compare the variants of ‚ÄòOption<T>‚Äô, but the way the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô
expression works remains the same.

Let's say we want to write a function that takes an ‚ÄòOption<i32>‚Äô and,
if there's a value inside, adds 1 to that value.  If there isn't a value
inside, the function should return the ‚ÄòNone‚Äô value and not attempt to
perform any operations.

This function is very easy to write, thanks to ‚Äòmatch‚Äô, and will look
like Listing 6-5.

    fn plus_one(x: Option<i32>) -> Option<i32> {
        match x {
            None => None,
            Some(i) => Some(i + 1),
        }
    }

    let five = Some(5);
    let six = plus_one(five);
    let none = plus_one(None);

Let's examine the first execution of ‚Äòplus_one‚Äô in more detail.  When we
call ‚Äòplus_one(five)‚Äô, the variable ‚Äòx‚Äô in the body of ‚Äòplus_one‚Äô will
have the value ‚ÄòSome(5)‚Äô.  We then compare that against each match arm:

            None => None,

The ‚ÄòSome(5)‚Äô value doesn't match the pattern ‚ÄòNone‚Äô, so we continue to
the next arm:

            Some(i) => Some(i + 1),

Does ‚ÄòSome(5)‚Äô match ‚ÄòSome(i)‚Äô?  It does!  We have the same variant.
The ‚Äòi‚Äô binds to the value contained in ‚ÄòSome‚Äô, so ‚Äòi‚Äô takes the value
‚Äò5‚Äô.  The code in the match arm is then executed, so we add 1 to the
value of ‚Äòi‚Äô and create a new ‚ÄòSome‚Äô value with our total ‚Äò6‚Äô inside.

Now let's consider the second call of ‚Äòplus_one‚Äô in Listing 6-5, where
‚Äòx‚Äô is ‚ÄòNone‚Äô.  We enter the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô and compare to the first arm:

            None => None,

It matches!  There's no value to add to, so the program stops and
returns the ‚ÄòNone‚Äô value on the right side of ‚Äò=>‚Äô.  Because the first
arm matched, no other arms are compared.

Combining ‚Äòmatch‚Äô and enums is useful in many situations.  You'll see
this pattern a lot in Rust code: ‚Äòmatch‚Äô against an enum, bind a
variable to the data inside, and then execute code based on it.  It's a
bit tricky at first, but once you get used to it, you'll wish you had it
in all languages.  It's consistently a user favorite.


