9.1.2.3 Matches Are Exhaustive
..............................

There's one other aspect of ‚Äòmatch‚Äô we need to discuss: the arms'
patterns must cover all possibilities.  Consider this version of our
‚Äòplus_one‚Äô function, which has a bug and won't compile:

    fn plus_one(x: Option<i32>) -> Option<i32> {
        match x {
            Some(i) => Some(i + 1),
        }
    }

We didn't handle the ‚ÄòNone‚Äô case, so this code will cause a bug.
Luckily, it's a bug Rust knows how to catch.  If we try to compile this
code, we'll get this error:

$ cargo run
   Compiling enums v0.1.0 (file:///projects/enums)
error[E0004]: non-exhaustive patterns: `None` not covered
   --> src/main.rs:3:15
    |
3   |         match x {
    |               ^ pattern `None` not covered
    |
note: `Option<i32>` defined here
   --> file:///home/.rustup/toolchains/1.82/lib/rustlib/src/rust/library/core/src/option.rs:571:1
    |
571 | pub enum Option<T> {
    | ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
...
575 |     None,
    |     ---- not covered
    = note: the matched value is of type `Option<i32>`
help: ensure that all possible cases are being handled by adding a match arm with a wildcard pattern or an explicit pattern as shown
    |
4   ~             Some(i) => Some(i + 1),
5   ~             None => todo!(),
    |

For more information about this error, try `rustc --explain E0004`.
error: could not compile `enums` (bin "enums") due to 1 previous error

Rust knows that we didn't cover every possible case, and even knows
which pattern we forgot!  Matches in Rust are ‚Äòexhaustive‚Äô: we must
exhaust every last possibility in order for the code to be valid.
Especially in the case of ‚ÄòOption<T>‚Äô, when Rust prevents us from
forgetting to explicitly handle the ‚ÄòNone‚Äô case, it protects us from
assuming that we have a value when we might have null, thus making the
billion-dollar mistake discussed earlier impossible.


