9.1.3 Concise Control Flow with ‚Äòif let‚Äô
----------------------------------------

The ‚Äòif let‚Äô syntax lets you combine ‚Äòif‚Äô and ‚Äòlet‚Äô into a less verbose
way to handle values that match one pattern while ignoring the rest.
Consider the program in Listing 6-6 that matches on an ‚ÄòOption<u8>‚Äô
value in the ‚Äòconfig_max‚Äô variable but only wants to execute code if the
value is the ‚ÄòSome‚Äô variant.

    let config_max = Some(3u8);
    match config_max {
        Some(max) => println!("The maximum is configured to be {max}"),
        _ => (),
    }

If the value is ‚ÄòSome‚Äô, we print out the value in the ‚ÄòSome‚Äô variant by
binding the value to the variable ‚Äòmax‚Äô in the pattern.  We don't want
to do anything with the ‚ÄòNone‚Äô value.  To satisfy the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô
expression, we have to add ‚Äò_ => ()‚Äô after processing just one variant,
which is annoying boilerplate code to add.

Instead, we could write this in a shorter way using ‚Äòif let‚Äô.  The
following code behaves the same as the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô in Listing 6-6:

    let config_max = Some(3u8);
    if let Some(max) = config_max {
        println!("The maximum is configured to be {max}");
    }

The syntax ‚Äòif let‚Äô takes a pattern and an expression separated by an
equal sign.  It works the same way as a ‚Äòmatch‚Äô, where the expression is
given to the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô and the pattern is its first arm.  In this case,
the pattern is ‚ÄòSome(max)‚Äô, and the ‚Äòmax‚Äô binds to the value inside the
‚ÄòSome‚Äô.  We can then use ‚Äòmax‚Äô in the body of the ‚Äòif let‚Äô block in the
same way we used ‚Äòmax‚Äô in the corresponding ‚Äòmatch‚Äô arm.  The code in
the ‚Äòif let‚Äô block only runs if the value matches the pattern.

Using ‚Äòif let‚Äô means less typing, less indentation, and less boilerplate
code.  However, you lose the exhaustive checking that ‚Äòmatch‚Äô enforces.
Choosing between ‚Äòmatch‚Äô and ‚Äòif let‚Äô depends on what you're doing in
your particular situation and whether gaining conciseness is an
appropriate trade-off for losing exhaustive checking.

In other words, you can think of ‚Äòif let‚Äô as syntax sugar for a ‚Äòmatch‚Äô
that runs code when the value matches one pattern and then ignores all
other values.

We can include an ‚Äòelse‚Äô with an ‚Äòif let‚Äô.  The block of code that goes
with the ‚Äòelse‚Äô is the same as the block of code that would go with the
‚Äò_‚Äô case in the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression that is equivalent to the ‚Äòif let‚Äô
and ‚Äòelse‚Äô.  Recall the ‚ÄòCoin‚Äô enum definition in Listing 6-4, where the
‚ÄòQuarter‚Äô variant also held a ‚ÄòUsState‚Äô value.  If we wanted to count
all non-quarter coins we see while also announcing the state of the
quarters, we could do that with a ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression, like this:

    let mut count = 0;
    match coin {
        Coin::Quarter(state) => println!("State quarter from {state:?}!"),
        _ => count += 1,
    }

Or we could use an ‚Äòif let‚Äô and ‚Äòelse‚Äô expression, like this:

    let mut count = 0;
    if let Coin::Quarter(state) = coin {
        println!("State quarter from {state:?}!");
    } else {
        count += 1;
    }

If you have a situation in which your program has logic that is too
verbose to express using a ‚Äòmatch‚Äô, remember that ‚Äòif let‚Äô is in your
Rust toolbox as well.


