Before we get to the details of modules and paths, here we provide a
quick reference on how modules, paths, the ‚Äòuse‚Äô keyword, and the ‚Äòpub‚Äô
keyword work in the compiler, and how most developers organize their
code.  We'll be going through examples of each of these rules throughout
this chapter, but this is a great place to refer to as a reminder of how
modules work.

   ‚Ä¢ *Start from the crate root*: When compiling a crate, the compiler
     first looks in the crate root file (usually ‚Äòsrc/lib.rs‚Äô for a
     library crate or ‚Äòsrc/main.rs‚Äô for a binary crate) for code to
     compile.
   ‚Ä¢ *Declaring modules*: In the crate root file, you can declare new
     modules; say you declare a ‚Äúgarden‚Äù module with ‚Äòmod garden;‚Äô.  The
     compiler will look for the module's code in these places:
        ‚Ä¢ Inline, within curly brackets that replace the semicolon
          following ‚Äòmod garden‚Äô
        ‚Ä¢ In the file ‚Äòsrc/garden.rs‚Äô
        ‚Ä¢ In the file ‚Äòsrc/garden/mod.rs‚Äô

   ‚Ä¢ *Declaring submodules*: In any file other than the crate root, you
     can declare submodules.  For example, you might declare ‚Äòmod
     vegetables;‚Äô in ‚Äòsrc/garden.rs‚Äô.  The compiler will look for the
     submodule's code within the directory named for the parent module
     in these places:
        ‚Ä¢ Inline, directly following ‚Äòmod vegetables‚Äô, within curly
          brackets instead of the semicolon
        ‚Ä¢ In the file ‚Äòsrc/garden/vegetables.rs‚Äô
        ‚Ä¢ In the file ‚Äòsrc/garden/vegetables/mod.rs‚Äô

   ‚Ä¢ *Paths to code in modules*: Once a module is part of your crate,
     you can refer to code in that module from anywhere else in that
     same crate, as long as the privacy rules allow, using the path to
     the code.  For example, an ‚ÄòAsparagus‚Äô type in the garden
     vegetables module would be found at
     ‚Äòcrate::garden::vegetables::Asparagus‚Äô.
   ‚Ä¢ *Private vs.  public*: Code within a module is private from its
     parent modules by default.  To make a module public, declare it
     with ‚Äòpub mod‚Äô instead of ‚Äòmod‚Äô.  To make items within a public
     module public as well, use ‚Äòpub‚Äô before their declarations.
   ‚Ä¢ *The ‚Äòuse‚Äô keyword*: Within a scope, the ‚Äòuse‚Äô keyword creates
     shortcuts to items to reduce repetition of long paths.  In any
     scope that can refer to ‚Äòcrate::garden::vegetables::Asparagus‚Äô, you
     can create a shortcut with ‚Äòuse
     crate::garden::vegetables::Asparagus;‚Äô and from then on you only
     need to write ‚ÄòAsparagus‚Äô to make use of that type in the scope.

