10.1.2 Paths for Referring to an Item in the Module Tree
--------------------------------------------------------

To show Rust where to find an item in a module tree, we use a path in
the same way we use a path when navigating a filesystem.  To call a
function, we need to know its path.

A path can take two forms:

   ‚Ä¢ An ‚Äòabsolute path‚Äô is the full path starting from a crate root; for
     code from an external crate, the absolute path begins with the
     crate name, and for code from the current crate, it starts with the
     literal ‚Äòcrate‚Äô.
   ‚Ä¢ A ‚Äòrelative path‚Äô starts from the current module and uses ‚Äòself‚Äô,
     ‚Äòsuper‚Äô, or an identifier in the current module.

Both absolute and relative paths are followed by one or more identifiers
separated by double colons (‚Äò::‚Äô).

Returning to Listing 7-1, say we want to call the ‚Äòadd_to_waitlist‚Äô
function.  This is the same as asking: what's the path of the
‚Äòadd_to_waitlist‚Äô function?  Listing 7-3 contains Listing 7-1 with some
of the modules and functions removed.

We'll show two ways to call the ‚Äòadd_to_waitlist‚Äô function from a new
function, ‚Äòeat_at_restaurant‚Äô, defined in the crate root.  These paths
are correct, but there's another problem remaining that will prevent
this example from compiling as is.  We'll explain why in a bit.

The ‚Äòeat_at_restaurant‚Äô function is part of our library crate's public
API, so we mark it with the ‚Äòpub‚Äô keyword.  In the *note ‚ÄúExposing Paths
with the ‚Äòpub‚Äô Keyword‚Äù: Exposing Paths with the pub Keyword. section,
we'll go into more detail about ‚Äòpub‚Äô.

mod front_of_house {
    mod hosting {
        fn add_to_waitlist() {}
    }
}

pub fn eat_at_restaurant() {
    // Absolute path
    crate::front_of_house::hosting::add_to_waitlist();

    // Relative path
    front_of_house::hosting::add_to_waitlist();
}

The first time we call the ‚Äòadd_to_waitlist‚Äô function in
‚Äòeat_at_restaurant‚Äô, we use an absolute path.  The ‚Äòadd_to_waitlist‚Äô
function is defined in the same crate as ‚Äòeat_at_restaurant‚Äô, which
means we can use the ‚Äòcrate‚Äô keyword to start an absolute path.  We then
include each of the successive modules until we make our way to
‚Äòadd_to_waitlist‚Äô.  You can imagine a filesystem with the same
structure: we'd specify the path
‚Äò/front_of_house/hosting/add_to_waitlist‚Äô to run the ‚Äòadd_to_waitlist‚Äô
program; using the ‚Äòcrate‚Äô name to start from the crate root is like
using ‚Äò/‚Äô to start from the filesystem root in your shell.

The second time we call ‚Äòadd_to_waitlist‚Äô in ‚Äòeat_at_restaurant‚Äô, we use
a relative path.  The path starts with ‚Äòfront_of_house‚Äô, the name of the
module defined at the same level of the module tree as
‚Äòeat_at_restaurant‚Äô.  Here the filesystem equivalent would be using the
path ‚Äòfront_of_house/hosting/add_to_waitlist‚Äô.  Starting with a module
name means that the path is relative.

Choosing whether to use a relative or absolute path is a decision you'll
make based on your project, and it depends on whether you're more likely
to move item definition code separately from or together with the code
that uses the item.  For example, if we moved the ‚Äòfront_of_house‚Äô
module and the ‚Äòeat_at_restaurant‚Äô function into a module named
‚Äòcustomer_experience‚Äô, we'd need to update the absolute path to
‚Äòadd_to_waitlist‚Äô, but the relative path would still be valid.  However,
if we moved the ‚Äòeat_at_restaurant‚Äô function separately into a module
named ‚Äòdining‚Äô, the absolute path to the ‚Äòadd_to_waitlist‚Äô call would
stay the same, but the relative path would need to be updated.  Our
preference in general is to specify absolute paths because it's more
likely we'll want to move code definitions and item calls independently
of each other.

