10.1.2.3 Making Structs and Enums Public
........................................

We can also use ‚Äòpub‚Äô to designate structs and enums as public, but
there are a few extra details to the usage of ‚Äòpub‚Äô with structs and
enums.  If we use ‚Äòpub‚Äô before a struct definition, we make the struct
public, but the struct's fields will still be private.  We can make each
field public or not on a case-by-case basis.  In Listing 7-9, we've
defined a public ‚Äòback_of_house::Breakfast‚Äô struct with a public ‚Äòtoast‚Äô
field but a private ‚Äòseasonal_fruit‚Äô field.  This models the case in a
restaurant where the customer can pick the type of bread that comes with
a meal, but the chef decides which fruit accompanies the meal based on
what's in season and in stock.  The available fruit changes quickly, so
customers can't choose the fruit or even see which fruit they'll get.

mod back_of_house {
    pub struct Breakfast {
        pub toast: String,
        seasonal_fruit: String,
    }

    impl Breakfast {
        pub fn summer(toast: &str) -> Breakfast {
            Breakfast {
                toast: String::from(toast),
                seasonal_fruit: String::from("peaches"),
            }
        }
    }
}

pub fn eat_at_restaurant() {
    // Order a breakfast in the summer with Rye toast
    let mut meal = back_of_house::Breakfast::summer("Rye");
    // Change our mind about what bread we'd like
    meal.toast = String::from("Wheat");
    println!("I'd like {} toast please", meal.toast);

    // The next line won't compile if we uncomment it; we're not allowed
    // to see or modify the seasonal fruit that comes with the meal
    // meal.seasonal_fruit = String::from("blueberries");
}

Because the ‚Äòtoast‚Äô field in the ‚Äòback_of_house::Breakfast‚Äô struct is
public, in ‚Äòeat_at_restaurant‚Äô we can write and read to the ‚Äòtoast‚Äô
field using dot notation.  Notice that we can't use the ‚Äòseasonal_fruit‚Äô
field in ‚Äòeat_at_restaurant‚Äô, because ‚Äòseasonal_fruit‚Äô is private.  Try
uncommenting the line modifying the ‚Äòseasonal_fruit‚Äô field value to see
what error you get!

Also, note that because ‚Äòback_of_house::Breakfast‚Äô has a private field,
the struct needs to provide a public associated function that constructs
an instance of ‚ÄòBreakfast‚Äô (we've named it ‚Äòsummer‚Äô here).  If
‚ÄòBreakfast‚Äô didn't have such a function, we couldn't create an instance
of ‚ÄòBreakfast‚Äô in ‚Äòeat_at_restaurant‚Äô because we couldn't set the value
of the private ‚Äòseasonal_fruit‚Äô field in ‚Äòeat_at_restaurant‚Äô.

In contrast, if we make an enum public, all of its variants are then
public.  We only need the ‚Äòpub‚Äô before the ‚Äòenum‚Äô keyword, as shown in
Listing 7-10.

mod back_of_house {
    pub enum Appetizer {
        Soup,
        Salad,
    }
}

pub fn eat_at_restaurant() {
    let order1 = back_of_house::Appetizer::Soup;
    let order2 = back_of_house::Appetizer::Salad;
}

Because we made the ‚ÄòAppetizer‚Äô enum public, we can use the ‚ÄòSoup‚Äô and
‚ÄòSalad‚Äô variants in ‚Äòeat_at_restaurant‚Äô.

Enums aren't very useful unless their variants are public; it would be
annoying to have to annotate all enum variants with ‚Äòpub‚Äô in every case,
so the default for enum variants is to be public.  Structs are often
useful without their fields being public, so struct fields follow the
general rule of everything being private by default unless annotated
with ‚Äòpub‚Äô.

There's one more situation involving ‚Äòpub‚Äô that we haven't covered, and
that is our last module system feature: the ‚Äòuse‚Äô keyword.  We'll cover
‚Äòuse‚Äô by itself first, and then we'll show how to combine ‚Äòpub‚Äô and
‚Äòuse‚Äô.


