10.1.3 Bringing Paths into Scope with the ‚Äòuse‚Äô Keyword
-------------------------------------------------------

Having to write out the paths to call functions can feel inconvenient
and repetitive.  In Listing 7-7, whether we chose the absolute or
relative path to the ‚Äòadd_to_waitlist‚Äô function, every time we wanted to
call ‚Äòadd_to_waitlist‚Äô we had to specify ‚Äòfront_of_house‚Äô and ‚Äòhosting‚Äô
too.  Fortunately, there's a way to simplify this process: we can create
a shortcut to a path with the ‚Äòuse‚Äô keyword once, and then use the
shorter name everywhere else in the scope.

In Listing 7-11, we bring the ‚Äòcrate::front_of_house::hosting‚Äô module
into the scope of the ‚Äòeat_at_restaurant‚Äô function so we only have to
specify ‚Äòhosting::add_to_waitlist‚Äô to call the ‚Äòadd_to_waitlist‚Äô
function in ‚Äòeat_at_restaurant‚Äô.

mod front_of_house {
    pub mod hosting {
        pub fn add_to_waitlist() {}
    }
}

use crate::front_of_house::hosting;

pub fn eat_at_restaurant() {
    hosting::add_to_waitlist();
}

Adding ‚Äòuse‚Äô and a path in a scope is similar to creating a symbolic
link in the filesystem.  By adding ‚Äòuse crate::front_of_house::hosting‚Äô
in the crate root, ‚Äòhosting‚Äô is now a valid name in that scope, just as
though the ‚Äòhosting‚Äô module had been defined in the crate root.  Paths
brought into scope with ‚Äòuse‚Äô also check privacy, like any other paths.

Note that ‚Äòuse‚Äô only creates the shortcut for the particular scope in
which the ‚Äòuse‚Äô occurs.  Listing 7-12 moves the ‚Äòeat_at_restaurant‚Äô
function into a new child module named ‚Äòcustomer‚Äô, which is then a
different scope than the ‚Äòuse‚Äô statement, so the function body won't
compile.

mod front_of_house {
    pub mod hosting {
        pub fn add_to_waitlist() {}
    }
}

use crate::front_of_house::hosting;

mod customer {
    pub fn eat_at_restaurant() {
        hosting::add_to_waitlist();
    }
}

