10.1.3.2 Providing New Names with the ‚Äòas‚Äô Keyword
..................................................

There's another solution to the problem of bringing two types of the
same name into the same scope with ‚Äòuse‚Äô: after the path, we can specify
‚Äòas‚Äô and a new local name, or ‚Äòalias‚Äô, for the type.  Listing 7-16 shows
another way to write the code in Listing 7-15 by renaming one of the two
‚ÄòResult‚Äô types using ‚Äòas‚Äô.

use std::fmt::Result;
use std::io::Result as IoResult;

fn function1() -> Result {
    // --snip--
}

fn function2() -> IoResult<()> {
    // --snip--
}

In the second ‚Äòuse‚Äô statement, we chose the new name ‚ÄòIoResult‚Äô for the
‚Äòstd::io::Result‚Äô type, which won't conflict with the ‚ÄòResult‚Äô from
‚Äòstd::fmt‚Äô that we've also brought into scope.  Listing 7-15 and Listing
7-16 are considered idiomatic, so the choice is up to you!


