10.1.3.3 Re-exporting Names with ‚Äòpub use‚Äô
..........................................

When we bring a name into scope with the ‚Äòuse‚Äô keyword, the name
available in the new scope is private.  To enable the code that calls
our code to refer to that name as if it had been defined in that code's
scope, we can combine ‚Äòpub‚Äô and ‚Äòuse‚Äô.  This technique is called
‚Äòre-exporting‚Äô because we're bringing an item into scope but also making
that item available for others to bring into their scope.

Listing 7-17 shows the code in Listing 7-11 with ‚Äòuse‚Äô in the root
module changed to ‚Äòpub use‚Äô.

mod front_of_house {
    pub mod hosting {
        pub fn add_to_waitlist() {}
    }
}

pub use crate::front_of_house::hosting;

pub fn eat_at_restaurant() {
    hosting::add_to_waitlist();
}

Before this change, external code would have to call the
‚Äòadd_to_waitlist‚Äô function by using the path
‚Äòrestaurant::front_of_house::hosting::add_to_waitlist()‚Äô, which also
would have required the ‚Äòfront_of_house‚Äô module to be marked as ‚Äòpub‚Äô.
Now that this ‚Äòpub use‚Äô has re-exported the ‚Äòhosting‚Äô module from the
root module, external code can use the path
‚Äòrestaurant::hosting::add_to_waitlist()‚Äô instead.

Re-exporting is useful when the internal structure of your code is
different from how programmers calling your code would think about the
domain.  For example, in this restaurant metaphor, the people running
the restaurant think about ‚Äúfront of house‚Äù and ‚Äúback of house.‚Äù But
customers visiting a restaurant probably won't think about the parts of
the restaurant in those terms.  With ‚Äòpub use‚Äô, we can write our code
with one structure but expose a different structure.  Doing so makes our
library well organized for programmers working on the library and
programmers calling the library.  We'll look at another example of ‚Äòpub
use‚Äô and how it affects your crate's documentation in the *note
‚ÄúExporting a Convenient Public API with ‚Äòpub use‚Äô‚Äù: Exporting a
Convenient Public API with pub use. section of Chapter 14.


