10.1.3.4 Using External Packages
................................

In Chapter 2, we programmed a guessing game project that used an
external package called ‚Äòrand‚Äô to get random numbers.  To use ‚Äòrand‚Äô in
our project, we added this line to ‚ÄòCargo.toml‚Äô:

rand = "0.8.5"

Adding ‚Äòrand‚Äô as a dependency in ‚ÄòCargo.toml‚Äô tells Cargo to download
the ‚Äòrand‚Äô package and any dependencies from cratesio
(https://crates.io/) and make ‚Äòrand‚Äô available to our project.

Then, to bring ‚Äòrand‚Äô definitions into the scope of our package, we
added a ‚Äòuse‚Äô line starting with the name of the crate, ‚Äòrand‚Äô, and
listed the items we wanted to bring into scope.  Recall that in the
*note ‚ÄúGenerating a Random Number‚Äù: Generating a Random Number. section
in Chapter 2, we brought the ‚ÄòRng‚Äô trait into scope and called the
‚Äòrand::thread_rng‚Äô function:

use rand::Rng;

fn main() {
    let secret_number = rand::thread_rng().gen_range(1..=100);
}

Members of the Rust community have made many packages available at
cratesio (https://crates.io/), and pulling any of them into your package
involves these same steps: listing them in your package's ‚ÄòCargo.toml‚Äô
file and using ‚Äòuse‚Äô to bring items from their crates into scope.

Note that the standard ‚Äòstd‚Äô library is also a crate that's external to
our package.  Because the standard library is shipped with the Rust
language, we don't need to change ‚ÄòCargo.toml‚Äô to include ‚Äòstd‚Äô.  But we
do need to refer to it with ‚Äòuse‚Äô to bring items from there into our
package's scope.  For example, with ‚ÄòHashMap‚Äô we would use this line:

use std::collections::HashMap;

This is an absolute path starting with ‚Äòstd‚Äô, the name of the standard
library crate.


