10.1.3.5 Using Nested Paths to Clean Up Large ‚Äòuse‚Äô Lists
.........................................................

If we're using multiple items defined in the same crate or same module,
listing each item on its own line can take up a lot of vertical space in
our files.  For example, these two ‚Äòuse‚Äô statements we had in the
guessing game in Listing 2-4 bring items from ‚Äòstd‚Äô into scope:

// --snip--
use std::cmp::Ordering;
use std::io;
// --snip--

Instead, we can use nested paths to bring the same items into scope in
one line.  We do this by specifying the common part of the path,
followed by two colons, and then curly brackets around a list of the
parts of the paths that differ, as shown in Listing 7-18.

// --snip--
use std::{cmp::Ordering, io};
// --snip--

In bigger programs, bringing many items into scope from the same crate
or module using nested paths can reduce the number of separate ‚Äòuse‚Äô
statements needed by a lot!

We can use a nested path at any level in a path, which is useful when
combining two ‚Äòuse‚Äô statements that share a subpath.  For example,
Listing 7-19 shows two ‚Äòuse‚Äô statements: one that brings ‚Äòstd::io‚Äô into
scope and one that brings ‚Äòstd::io::Write‚Äô into scope.

use std::io;
use std::io::Write;

The common part of these two paths is ‚Äòstd::io‚Äô, and that's the complete
first path.  To merge these two paths into one ‚Äòuse‚Äô statement, we can
use ‚Äòself‚Äô in the nested path, as shown in Listing 7-20.

use std::io::{self, Write};

This line brings ‚Äòstd::io‚Äô and ‚Äòstd::io::Write‚Äô into scope.


