10.1.4 Separating Modules into Different Files
----------------------------------------------

So far, all the examples in this chapter defined multiple modules in one
file.  When modules get large, you might want to move their definitions
to a separate file to make the code easier to navigate.

For example, let's start from the code in Listing 7-17 that had multiple
restaurant modules.  We'll extract modules into files instead of having
all the modules defined in the crate root file.  In this case, the crate
root file is ‚Äòsrc/lib.rs‚Äô, but this procedure also works with binary
crates whose crate root file is ‚Äòsrc/main.rs‚Äô.

First we'll extract the ‚Äòfront_of_house‚Äô module to its own file.  Remove
the code inside the curly brackets for the ‚Äòfront_of_house‚Äô module,
leaving only the ‚Äòmod front_of_house;‚Äô declaration, so that ‚Äòsrc/lib.rs‚Äô
contains the code shown in Listing 7-21.  Note that this won't compile
until we create the ‚Äòsrc/front_of_house.rs‚Äô file in Listing 7-22.

mod front_of_house;

pub use crate::front_of_house::hosting;

pub fn eat_at_restaurant() {
    hosting::add_to_waitlist();
}

Next, place the code that was in the curly brackets into a new file
named ‚Äòsrc/front_of_house.rs‚Äô, as shown in Listing 7-22.  The compiler
knows to look in this file because it came across the module declaration
in the crate root with the name ‚Äòfront_of_house‚Äô.

pub mod hosting {
    pub fn add_to_waitlist() {}
}

Note that you only need to load a file using a ‚Äòmod‚Äô declaration ‚Äòonce‚Äô
in your module tree.  Once the compiler knows the file is part of the
project (and knows where in the module tree the code resides because of
where you've put the ‚Äòmod‚Äô statement), other files in your project
should refer to the loaded file's code using a path to where it was
declared, as covered in the *note ‚ÄúPaths for Referring to an Item in the
Module Tree‚Äù: Paths for Referring to an Item in the Module Tree.
section.  In other words, ‚Äòmod‚Äô is ‚Äònot‚Äô an ‚Äúinclude‚Äù operation that you
may have seen in other programming languages.

Next, we'll extract the ‚Äòhosting‚Äô module to its own file.  The process
is a bit different because ‚Äòhosting‚Äô is a child module of
‚Äòfront_of_house‚Äô, not of the root module.  We'll place the file for
‚Äòhosting‚Äô in a new directory that will be named for its ancestors in the
module tree, in this case ‚Äòsrc/front_of_house‚Äô.

To start moving ‚Äòhosting‚Äô, we change ‚Äòsrc/front_of_house.rs‚Äô to contain
only the declaration of the ‚Äòhosting‚Äô module:

pub mod hosting;

Then we create a ‚Äòsrc/front_of_house‚Äô directory and a ‚Äòhosting.rs‚Äô file
to contain the definitions made in the ‚Äòhosting‚Äô module:

pub fn add_to_waitlist() {}

If we instead put ‚Äòhosting.rs‚Äô in the ‚Äòsrc‚Äô directory, the compiler
would expect the ‚Äòhosting.rs‚Äô code to be in a ‚Äòhosting‚Äô module declared
in the crate root, and not declared as a child of the ‚Äòfront_of_house‚Äô
module.  The compiler's rules for which files to check for which
modules' code mean the directories and files more closely match the
module tree.

