10.1.4.1 Alternate File Paths
.............................

So far we've covered the most idiomatic file paths the Rust compiler
uses, but Rust also supports an older style of file path.  For a module
named ‚Äòfront_of_house‚Äô declared in the crate root, the compiler will
look for the module's code in:

   ‚Ä¢ ‚Äòsrc/front_of_house.rs‚Äô (what we covered)
   ‚Ä¢ ‚Äòsrc/front_of_house/mod.rs‚Äô (older style, still supported path)

For a module named ‚Äòhosting‚Äô that is a submodule of ‚Äòfront_of_house‚Äô,
the compiler will look for the module's code in:

   ‚Ä¢ ‚Äòsrc/front_of_house/hosting.rs‚Äô (what we covered)
   ‚Ä¢ ‚Äòsrc/front_of_house/hosting/mod.rs‚Äô (older style, still supported
     path)

If you use both styles for the same module, you'll get a compiler error.
Using a mix of both styles for different modules in the same project is
allowed, but might be confusing for people navigating your project.

The main downside to the style that uses files named ‚Äòmod.rs‚Äô is that
your project can end up with many files named ‚Äòmod.rs‚Äô, which can get
confusing when you have them open in your editor at the same time.

We've moved each module's code to a separate file, and the module tree
remains the same.  The function calls in ‚Äòeat_at_restaurant‚Äô will work
without any modification, even though the definitions live in different
files.  This technique lets you move modules to new files as they grow
in size.

Note that the ‚Äòpub use crate::front_of_house::hosting‚Äô statement in
‚Äòsrc/lib.rs‚Äô also hasn't changed, nor does ‚Äòuse‚Äô have any impact on what
files are compiled as part of the crate.  The ‚Äòmod‚Äô keyword declares
modules, and Rust looks in a file with the same name as the module for
the code that goes into that module.


