11.1.1.3 Iterating Over the Values in a Vector
..............................................

To access each element in a vector in turn, we would iterate through all
of the elements rather than use indices to access one at a time.
Listing 8-7 shows how to use a ‚Äòfor‚Äô loop to get immutable references to
each element in a vector of ‚Äòi32‚Äô values and print them.

    let v = vec![100, 32, 57];
    for i in &v {
        println!("{i}");
    }

We can also iterate over mutable references to each element in a mutable
vector in order to make changes to all the elements.  The ‚Äòfor‚Äô loop in
Listing 8-8 will add ‚Äò50‚Äô to each element.

    let mut v = vec![100, 32, 57];
    for i in &mut v {
        *i += 50;
    }

To change the value that the mutable reference refers to, we have to use
the ‚Äò*‚Äô dereference operator to get to the value in ‚Äòi‚Äô before we can
use the ‚Äò+=‚Äô operator.  We'll talk more about the dereference operator
in the *note ‚ÄúFollowing the Pointer to the Value with the Dereference
Operator‚Äù:
#book__pandoc__texi__src__ch15-02-derefmd__following-the-pointer-to-the-value-with-the-dereference-operator.
section of Chapter 15.

Iterating over a vector, whether immutably or mutably, is safe because
of the borrow checker's rules.  If we attempted to insert or remove
items in the ‚Äòfor‚Äô loop bodies in Listing 8-7 and Listing 8-8, we would
get a compiler error similar to the one we got with the code in Listing
8-6.  The reference to the vector that the ‚Äòfor‚Äô loop holds prevents
simultaneous modification of the whole vector.


