11.1.2.1 What Is a String?
..........................

We'll first define what we mean by the term ‚Äòstring‚Äô.  Rust has only one
string type in the core language, which is the string slice ‚Äòstr‚Äô that
is usually seen in its borrowed form ‚Äò&str‚Äô.  In Chapter 4, we talked
about ‚Äòstring slices‚Äô, which are references to some UTF-8 encoded string
data stored elsewhere.  String literals, for example, are stored in the
program's binary and are therefore string slices.

The ‚ÄòString‚Äô type, which is provided by Rust's standard library rather
than coded into the core language, is a growable, mutable, owned, UTF-8
encoded string type.  When Rustaceans refer to ‚Äústrings‚Äù in Rust, they
might be referring to either the ‚ÄòString‚Äô or the string slice ‚Äò&str‚Äô
types, not just one of those types.  Although this section is largely
about ‚ÄòString‚Äô, both types are used heavily in Rust's standard library,
and both ‚ÄòString‚Äô and string slices are UTF-8 encoded.


