11.1.2.3 Updating a String
..........................

A ‚ÄòString‚Äô can grow in size and its contents can change, just like the
contents of a ‚ÄòVec<T>‚Äô, if you push more data into it.  In addition, you
can conveniently use the ‚Äò+‚Äô operator or the ‚Äòformat!‚Äô macro to
concatenate ‚ÄòString‚Äô values.  Appending to a String with ‚Äòpush_str‚Äô and
‚Äòpush‚Äô We can grow a ‚ÄòString‚Äô by using the ‚Äòpush_str‚Äô method to append a
string slice, as shown in Listing 8-15.

    let mut s = String::from("foo");
    s.push_str("bar");

After these two lines, ‚Äòs‚Äô will contain ‚Äòfoobar‚Äô.  The ‚Äòpush_str‚Äô method
takes a string slice because we don't necessarily want to take ownership
of the parameter.  For example, in the code in Listing 8-16, we want to
be able to use ‚Äòs2‚Äô after appending its contents to ‚Äòs1‚Äô.

    let mut s1 = String::from("foo");
    let s2 = "bar";
    s1.push_str(s2);
    println!("s2 is {s2}");

If the ‚Äòpush_str‚Äô method took ownership of ‚Äòs2‚Äô, we wouldn't be able to
print its value on the last line.  However, this code works as we'd
expect!

The ‚Äòpush‚Äô method takes a single character as a parameter and adds it to
the ‚ÄòString‚Äô.  Listing 8-17 adds the letter ‚Äòl‚Äô to a ‚ÄòString‚Äô using the
‚Äòpush‚Äô method.

    let mut s = String::from("lo");
    s.push('l');

As a result, ‚Äòs‚Äô will contain ‚Äòlol‚Äô.  Concatenation with the ‚Äò+‚Äô
Operator or the ‚Äòformat!‚Äô Macro Often, you'll want to combine two
existing strings.  One way to do so is to use the ‚Äò+‚Äô operator, as shown
in Listing 8-18.

    let s1 = String::from("Hello, ");
    let s2 = String::from("world!");
    let s3 = s1 + &s2; // note s1 has been moved here and can no longer be used

The string ‚Äòs3‚Äô will contain ‚ÄòHello, world!‚Äô.  The reason ‚Äòs1‚Äô is no
longer valid after the addition, and the reason we used a reference to
‚Äòs2‚Äô, has to do with the signature of the method that's called when we
use the ‚Äò+‚Äô operator.  The ‚Äò+‚Äô operator uses the ‚Äòadd‚Äô method, whose
signature looks something like this:

fn add(self, s: &str) -> String {

In the standard library, you'll see ‚Äòadd‚Äô defined using generics and
associated types.  Here, we've substituted in concrete types, which is
what happens when we call this method with ‚ÄòString‚Äô values.  We'll
discuss generics in Chapter 10.  This signature gives us the clues we
need in order to understand the tricky bits of the ‚Äò+‚Äô operator.

First, ‚Äòs2‚Äô has an ‚Äò&‚Äô, meaning that we're adding a ‚Äòreference‚Äô of the
second string to the first string.  This is because of the ‚Äòs‚Äô parameter
in the ‚Äòadd‚Äô function: we can only add a ‚Äò&str‚Äô to a ‚ÄòString‚Äô; we can't
add two ‚ÄòString‚Äô values together.  But wait--the type of ‚Äò&s2‚Äô is
‚Äò&String‚Äô, not ‚Äò&str‚Äô, as specified in the second parameter to ‚Äòadd‚Äô.
So why does Listing 8-18 compile?

The reason we're able to use ‚Äò&s2‚Äô in the call to ‚Äòadd‚Äô is that the
compiler can ‚Äòcoerce‚Äô the ‚Äò&String‚Äô argument into a ‚Äò&str‚Äô.  When we
call the ‚Äòadd‚Äô method, Rust uses a ‚Äòderef coercion‚Äô, which here turns
‚Äò&s2‚Äô into ‚Äò&s2[..]‚Äô.  We'll discuss deref coercion in more depth in
Chapter 15.  Because ‚Äòadd‚Äô does not take ownership of the ‚Äòs‚Äô parameter,
‚Äòs2‚Äô will still be a valid ‚ÄòString‚Äô after this operation.

Second, we can see in the signature that ‚Äòadd‚Äô takes ownership of ‚Äòself‚Äô
because ‚Äòself‚Äô does ‚Äònot‚Äô have an ‚Äò&‚Äô.  This means ‚Äòs1‚Äô in Listing 8-18
will be moved into the ‚Äòadd‚Äô call and will no longer be valid after
that.  So, although ‚Äòlet s3 = s1 + &s2;‚Äô looks like it will copy both
strings and create a new one, this statement actually takes ownership of
‚Äòs1‚Äô, appends a copy of the contents of ‚Äòs2‚Äô, and then returns ownership
of the result.  In other words, it looks like it's making a lot of
copies, but it isn't; the implementation is more efficient than copying.

If we need to concatenate multiple strings, the behavior of the ‚Äò+‚Äô
operator gets unwieldy:

    let s1 = String::from("tic");
    let s2 = String::from("tac");
    let s3 = String::from("toe");

    let s = s1 + "-" + &s2 + "-" + &s3;

At this point, ‚Äòs‚Äô will be ‚Äòtic-tac-toe‚Äô.  With all of the ‚Äò+‚Äô and ‚Äò"‚Äô
characters, it's difficult to see what's going on.  For combining
strings in more complicated ways, we can instead use the ‚Äòformat!‚Äô
macro:

    let s1 = String::from("tic");
    let s2 = String::from("tac");
    let s3 = String::from("toe");

    let s = format!("{s1}-{s2}-{s3}");

This code also sets ‚Äòs‚Äô to ‚Äòtic-tac-toe‚Äô.  The ‚Äòformat!‚Äô macro works
like ‚Äòprintln!‚Äô, but instead of printing the output to the screen, it
returns a ‚ÄòString‚Äô with the contents.  The version of the code using
‚Äòformat!‚Äô is much easier to read, and the code generated by the
‚Äòformat!‚Äô macro uses references so that this call doesn't take ownership
of any of its parameters.


