11.1.3.1 Creating a New Hash Map
................................

One way to create an empty hash map is to use ‚Äònew‚Äô and to add elements
with ‚Äòinsert‚Äô.  In Listing 8-20, we're keeping track of the scores of
two teams whose names are ‚ÄòBlue‚Äô and ‚ÄòYellow‚Äô.  The Blue team starts
with 10 points, and the Yellow team starts with 50.

    use std::collections::HashMap;

    let mut scores = HashMap::new();

    scores.insert(String::from("Blue"), 10);
    scores.insert(String::from("Yellow"), 50);

Note that we need to first ‚Äòuse‚Äô the ‚ÄòHashMap‚Äô from the collections
portion of the standard library.  Of our three common collections, this
one is the least often used, so it's not included in the features
brought into scope automatically in the prelude.  Hash maps also have
less support from the standard library; there's no built-in macro to
construct them, for example.

Just like vectors, hash maps store their data on the heap.  This
‚ÄòHashMap‚Äô has keys of type ‚ÄòString‚Äô and values of type ‚Äòi32‚Äô.  Like
vectors, hash maps are homogeneous: all of the keys must have the same
type, and all of the values must have the same type.


