11.1.3.2 Accessing Values in a Hash Map
.......................................

We can get a value out of the hash map by providing its key to the ‚Äòget‚Äô
method, as shown in Listing 8-21.

    use std::collections::HashMap;

    let mut scores = HashMap::new();

    scores.insert(String::from("Blue"), 10);
    scores.insert(String::from("Yellow"), 50);

    let team_name = String::from("Blue");
    let score = scores.get(&team_name).copied().unwrap_or(0);

Here, ‚Äòscore‚Äô will have the value that's associated with the Blue team,
and the result will be ‚Äò10‚Äô.  The ‚Äòget‚Äô method returns an ‚ÄòOption<&V>‚Äô;
if there's no value for that key in the hash map, ‚Äòget‚Äô will return
‚ÄòNone‚Äô.  This program handles the ‚ÄòOption‚Äô by calling ‚Äòcopied‚Äô to get an
‚ÄòOption<i32>‚Äô rather than an ‚ÄòOption<&i32>‚Äô, then ‚Äòunwrap_or‚Äô to set
‚Äòscore‚Äô to zero if ‚Äòscores‚Äô doesn't have an entry for the key.

We can iterate over each key-value pair in a hash map in a similar
manner as we do with vectors, using a ‚Äòfor‚Äô loop:

    use std::collections::HashMap;

    let mut scores = HashMap::new();

    scores.insert(String::from("Blue"), 10);
    scores.insert(String::from("Yellow"), 50);

    for (key, value) in &scores {
        println!("{key}: {value}");
    }

This code will print each pair in an arbitrary order:

Yellow: 50
Blue: 10


