We can use the backtrace of the functions the ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô call came from to
figure out the part of our code that is causing the problem.  To
understand how to use a ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô backtrace, let's look at another
example and see what it's like when a ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô call comes from a library
because of a bug in our code instead of from our code calling the macro
directly.  Listing 9-1 has some code that attempts to access an index in
a vector beyond the range of valid indexes.

fn main() {
    let v = vec![1, 2, 3];

    v[99];
}

Here, we're attempting to access the 100th element of our vector (which
