12.1.2 Recoverable Errors with ‚ÄòResult‚Äô
---------------------------------------

Most errors aren't serious enough to require the program to stop
entirely.  Sometimes when a function fails it's for a reason that you
can easily interpret and respond to.  For example, if you try to open a
file and that operation fails because the file doesn't exist, you might
want to create the file instead of terminating the process.

Recall from *note ‚ÄúHandling Potential Failure with ‚ÄòResult‚Äô‚Äù: Handling
Potential Failure with Result. in Chapter 2 that the ‚ÄòResult‚Äô enum is
defined as having two variants, ‚ÄòOk‚Äô and ‚ÄòErr‚Äô, as follows:

enum Result<T, E> {
    Ok(T),
    Err(E),
}

The ‚ÄòT‚Äô and ‚ÄòE‚Äô are generic type parameters: we'll discuss generics in
more detail in Chapter 10.  What you need to know right now is that ‚ÄòT‚Äô
represents the type of the value that will be returned in a success case
within the ‚ÄòOk‚Äô variant, and ‚ÄòE‚Äô represents the type of the error that
will be returned in a failure case within the ‚ÄòErr‚Äô variant.  Because
‚ÄòResult‚Äô has these generic type parameters, we can use the ‚ÄòResult‚Äô type
and the functions defined on it in many different situations where the
success value and error value we want to return may differ.

Let's call a function that returns a ‚ÄòResult‚Äô value because the function
could fail.  In Listing 9-3 we try to open a file.

use std::fs::File;

fn main() {
    let greeting_file_result = File::open("hello.txt");
}

The return type of ‚ÄòFile::open‚Äô is a ‚ÄòResult<T, E>‚Äô.  The generic
parameter ‚ÄòT‚Äô has been filled in by the implementation of ‚ÄòFile::open‚Äô
with the type of the success value, ‚Äòstd::fs::File‚Äô, which is a file
handle.  The type of ‚ÄòE‚Äô used in the error value is ‚Äòstd::io::Error‚Äô.
This return type means the call to ‚ÄòFile::open‚Äô might succeed and return
a file handle that we can read from or write to.  The function call also
might fail: for example, the file might not exist, or we might not have
permission to access the file.  The ‚ÄòFile::open‚Äô function needs to have
a way to tell us whether it succeeded or failed and at the same time
give us either the file handle or error information.  This information
is exactly what the ‚ÄòResult‚Äô enum conveys.

In the case where ‚ÄòFile::open‚Äô succeeds, the value in the variable
‚Äògreeting_file_result‚Äô will be an instance of ‚ÄòOk‚Äô that contains a file
handle.  In the case where it fails, the value in ‚Äògreeting_file_result‚Äô
will be an instance of ‚ÄòErr‚Äô that contains more information about the
kind of error that occurred.

We need to add to the code in Listing 9-3 to take different actions
depending on the value ‚ÄòFile::open‚Äô returns.  Listing 9-4 shows one way
to handle the ‚ÄòResult‚Äô using a basic tool, the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression that
we discussed in Chapter 6.

use std::fs::File;

fn main() {
    let greeting_file_result = File::open("hello.txt");

    let greeting_file = match greeting_file_result {
        Ok(file) => file,
        Err(error) => panic!("Problem opening the file: {error:?}"),
    };
}

Note that, like the ‚ÄòOption‚Äô enum, the ‚ÄòResult‚Äô enum and its variants
have been brought into scope by the prelude, so we don't need to specify
‚ÄòResult::‚Äô before the ‚ÄòOk‚Äô and ‚ÄòErr‚Äô variants in the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô arms.

When the result is ‚ÄòOk‚Äô, this code will return the inner ‚Äòfile‚Äô value
out of the ‚ÄòOk‚Äô variant, and we then assign that file handle value to
the variable ‚Äògreeting_file‚Äô.  After the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô, we can use the file
handle for reading or writing.

The other arm of the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô handles the case where we get an ‚ÄòErr‚Äô
value from ‚ÄòFile::open‚Äô.  In this example, we've chosen to call the
‚Äòpanic!‚Äô macro.  If there's no file named ‚Äòhello.txt‚Äô in our current
