12.1.2.1 Matching on Different Errors
.....................................

The code in Listing 9-4 will ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô no matter why ‚ÄòFile::open‚Äô failed.
However, we want to take different actions for different failure
reasons.  If ‚ÄòFile::open‚Äô failed because the file doesn't exist, we want
to create the file and return the handle to the new file.  If
‚ÄòFile::open‚Äô failed for any other reason--for example, because we didn't
have permission to open the file--we still want the code to ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô in
the same way it did in Listing 9-4.  For this, we add an inner ‚Äòmatch‚Äô
expression, shown in Listing 9-5.

use std::fs::File;
use std::io::ErrorKind;

fn main() {
    let greeting_file_result = File::open("hello.txt");

    let greeting_file = match greeting_file_result {
        Ok(file) => file,
        Err(error) => match error.kind() {
            ErrorKind::NotFound => match File::create("hello.txt") {
                Ok(fc) => fc,
                Err(e) => panic!("Problem creating the file: {e:?}"),
            },
            other_error => {
                panic!("Problem opening the file: {other_error:?}");
            }
        },
    };
}

The type of the value that ‚ÄòFile::open‚Äô returns inside the ‚ÄòErr‚Äô variant
is ‚Äòio::Error‚Äô, which is a struct provided by the standard library.
This struct has a method ‚Äòkind‚Äô that we can call to get an
‚Äòio::ErrorKind‚Äô value.  The enum ‚Äòio::ErrorKind‚Äô is provided by the
standard library and has variants representing the different kinds of
errors that might result from an ‚Äòio‚Äô operation.  The variant we want to
use is ‚ÄòErrorKind::NotFound‚Äô, which indicates the file we're trying to
open doesn't exist yet.  So we match on ‚Äògreeting_file_result‚Äô, but we
also have an inner match on ‚Äòerror.kind()‚Äô.

The condition we want to check in the inner match is whether the value
returned by ‚Äòerror.kind()‚Äô is the ‚ÄòNotFound‚Äô variant of the ‚ÄòErrorKind‚Äô
enum.  If it is, we try to create the file with ‚ÄòFile::create‚Äô.
However, because ‚ÄòFile::create‚Äô could also fail, we need a second arm in
the inner ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression.  When the file can't be created, a
different error message is printed.  The second arm of the outer ‚Äòmatch‚Äô
stays the same, so the program panics on any error besides the missing
file error.

Alternatives to Using ‚Äòmatch‚Äô with ‚ÄòResult<T, E>‚Äô That's a lot of
‚Äòmatch‚Äô!  The ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression is very useful but also very much a
primitive.  In Chapter 13, you'll learn about closures, which are used
with many of the methods defined on ‚ÄòResult<T, E>‚Äô.  These methods can
be more concise than using ‚Äòmatch‚Äô when handling ‚ÄòResult<T, E>‚Äô values
in your code.

For example, here's another way to write the same logic as shown in
Listing 9-5, this time using closures and the ‚Äòunwrap_or_else‚Äô method:

use std::fs::File;
use std::io::ErrorKind;

fn main() {
    let greeting_file = File::open("hello.txt").unwrap_or_else(|error| {
        if error.kind() == ErrorKind::NotFound {
            File::create("hello.txt").unwrap_or_else(|error| {
                panic!("Problem creating the file: {error:?}");
            })
        } else {
            panic!("Problem opening the file: {error:?}");
        }
    });
}

Although this code has the same behavior as Listing 9-5, it doesn't
contain any ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expressions and is cleaner to read.  Come back to
this example after you've read Chapter 13, and look up the
‚Äòunwrap_or_else‚Äô method in the standard library documentation.  Many
more of these methods can clean up huge nested ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expressions when
you're dealing with errors.

Shortcuts for Panic on Error: ‚Äòunwrap‚Äô and ‚Äòexpect‚Äô Using ‚Äòmatch‚Äô works
well enough, but it can be a bit verbose and doesn't always communicate
intent well.  The ‚ÄòResult<T, E>‚Äô type has many helper methods defined on
it to do various, more specific tasks.  The ‚Äòunwrap‚Äô method is a
shortcut method implemented just like the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression we wrote in
Listing 9-4.  If the ‚ÄòResult‚Äô value is the ‚ÄòOk‚Äô variant, ‚Äòunwrap‚Äô will
return the value inside the ‚ÄòOk‚Äô.  If the ‚ÄòResult‚Äô is the ‚ÄòErr‚Äô variant,
‚Äòunwrap‚Äô will call the ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô macro for us.  Here is an example of
‚Äòunwrap‚Äô in action:

use std::fs::File;

fn main() {
    let greeting_file = File::open("hello.txt").unwrap();
}

If we run this code without a ‚Äòhello.txt‚Äô file, we'll see an error
message from the ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô call that the ‚Äòunwrap‚Äô method makes:

thread 'main' panicked at src/main.rs:4:49:
called `Result::unwrap()` on an `Err` value: Os { code: 2, kind: NotFound, message: "No such file or directory" }

Similarly, the ‚Äòexpect‚Äô method lets us also choose the ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô error
message.  Using ‚Äòexpect‚Äô instead of ‚Äòunwrap‚Äô and providing good error
messages can convey your intent and make tracking down the source of a
panic easier.  The syntax of ‚Äòexpect‚Äô looks like this:

use std::fs::File;

fn main() {
    let greeting_file = File::open("hello.txt")
        .expect("hello.txt should be included in this project");
}

We use ‚Äòexpect‚Äô in the same way as ‚Äòunwrap‚Äô: to return the file handle
or call the ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô macro.  The error message used by ‚Äòexpect‚Äô in its
call to ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô will be the parameter that we pass to ‚Äòexpect‚Äô, rather
than the default ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô message that ‚Äòunwrap‚Äô uses.  Here's what it
looks like:

thread 'main' panicked at src/main.rs:5:10:
hello.txt should be included in this project: Os { code: 2, kind: NotFound, message: "No such file or directory" }

In production-quality code, most Rustaceans choose ‚Äòexpect‚Äô rather than
‚Äòunwrap‚Äô and give more context about why the operation is expected to
always succeed.  That way, if your assumptions are ever proven wrong,
you have more information to use in debugging.


