12.1.2.2 Propagating Errors
...........................

When a function's implementation calls something that might fail,
instead of handling the error within the function itself you can return
the error to the calling code so that it can decide what to do.  This is
known as ‚Äòpropagating‚Äô the error and gives more control to the calling
code, where there might be more information or logic that dictates how
the error should be handled than what you have available in the context
of your code.

For example, Listing 9-6 shows a function that reads a username from a
file.  If the file doesn't exist or can't be read, this function will
return those errors to the code that called the function.

use std::fs::File;
use std::io::{self, Read};

fn read_username_from_file() -> Result<String, io::Error> {
    let username_file_result = File::open("hello.txt");

    let mut username_file = match username_file_result {
        Ok(file) => file,
        Err(e) => return Err(e),
    };

    let mut username = String::new();

    match username_file.read_to_string(&mut username) {
        Ok(_) => Ok(username),
        Err(e) => Err(e),
    }
}

This function can be written in a much shorter way, but we're going to
start by doing a lot of it manually in order to explore error handling;
at the end, we'll show the shorter way.  Let's look at the return type
of the function first: ‚ÄòResult<String, io::Error>‚Äô.  This means the
function is returning a value of the type ‚ÄòResult<T, E>‚Äô, where the
generic parameter ‚ÄòT‚Äô has been filled in with the concrete type ‚ÄòString‚Äô
and the generic type ‚ÄòE‚Äô has been filled in with the concrete type
‚Äòio::Error‚Äô.

If this function succeeds without any problems, the code that calls this
function will receive an ‚ÄòOk‚Äô value that holds a ‚ÄòString‚Äô--the
‚Äòusername‚Äô that this function read from the file.  If this function
encounters any problems, the calling code will receive an ‚ÄòErr‚Äô value
that holds an instance of ‚Äòio::Error‚Äô that contains more information
about what the problems were.  We chose ‚Äòio::Error‚Äô as the return type
of this function because that happens to be the type of the error value
returned from both of the operations we're calling in this function's
body that might fail: the ‚ÄòFile::open‚Äô function and the ‚Äòread_to_string‚Äô
method.

The body of the function starts by calling the ‚ÄòFile::open‚Äô function.
Then we handle the ‚ÄòResult‚Äô value with a ‚Äòmatch‚Äô similar to the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô
in Listing 9-4.  If ‚ÄòFile::open‚Äô succeeds, the file handle in the
pattern variable ‚Äòfile‚Äô becomes the value in the mutable variable
‚Äòusername_file‚Äô and the function continues.  In the ‚ÄòErr‚Äô case, instead
of calling ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô, we use the ‚Äòreturn‚Äô keyword to return early out of
the function entirely and pass the error value from ‚ÄòFile::open‚Äô, now in
the pattern variable ‚Äòe‚Äô, back to the calling code as this function's
error value.

So, if we have a file handle in ‚Äòusername_file‚Äô, the function then
creates a new ‚ÄòString‚Äô in variable ‚Äòusername‚Äô and calls the
‚Äòread_to_string‚Äô method on the file handle in ‚Äòusername_file‚Äô to read
the contents of the file into ‚Äòusername‚Äô.  The ‚Äòread_to_string‚Äô method
also returns a ‚ÄòResult‚Äô because it might fail, even though ‚ÄòFile::open‚Äô
succeeded.  So we need another ‚Äòmatch‚Äô to handle that ‚ÄòResult‚Äô: if
‚Äòread_to_string‚Äô succeeds, then our function has succeeded, and we
return the username from the file that's now in ‚Äòusername‚Äô wrapped in an
‚ÄòOk‚Äô.  If ‚Äòread_to_string‚Äô fails, we return the error value in the same
way that we returned the error value in the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô that handled the
return value of ‚ÄòFile::open‚Äô.  However, we don't need to explicitly say
‚Äòreturn‚Äô, because this is the last expression in the function.

The code that calls this code will then handle getting either an ‚ÄòOk‚Äô
value that contains a username or an ‚ÄòErr‚Äô value that contains an
‚Äòio::Error‚Äô.  It's up to the calling code to decide what to do with
those values.  If the calling code gets an ‚ÄòErr‚Äô value, it could call
‚Äòpanic!‚Äô and crash the program, use a default username, or look up the
username from somewhere other than a file, for example.  We don't have
enough information on what the calling code is actually trying to do, so
we propagate all the success or error information upward for it to
handle appropriately.

This pattern of propagating errors is so common in Rust that Rust
provides the question mark operator ‚Äò?‚Äô to make this easier.  A Shortcut
for Propagating Errors: the ‚Äò?‚Äô Operator Listing 9-7 shows an
implementation of ‚Äòread_username_from_file‚Äô that has the same
functionality as in Listing 9-6, but this implementation uses the ‚Äò?‚Äô
operator.

use std::fs::File;
use std::io::{self, Read};

fn read_username_from_file() -> Result<String, io::Error> {
    let mut username_file = File::open("hello.txt")?;
    let mut username = String::new();
    username_file.read_to_string(&mut username)?;
    Ok(username)
}

The ‚Äò?‚Äô placed after a ‚ÄòResult‚Äô value is defined to work in almost the
same way as the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expressions we defined to handle the ‚ÄòResult‚Äô
values in Listing 9-6.  If the value of the ‚ÄòResult‚Äô is an ‚ÄòOk‚Äô, the
value inside the ‚ÄòOk‚Äô will get returned from this expression, and the
program will continue.  If the value is an ‚ÄòErr‚Äô, the ‚ÄòErr‚Äô will be
returned from the whole function as if we had used the ‚Äòreturn‚Äô keyword
so the error value gets propagated to the calling code.

There is a difference between what the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression from Listing
9-6 does and what the ‚Äò?‚Äô operator does: error values that have the ‚Äò?‚Äô
operator called on them go through the ‚Äòfrom‚Äô function, defined in the
‚ÄòFrom‚Äô trait in the standard library, which is used to convert values
from one type into another.  When the ‚Äò?‚Äô operator calls the ‚Äòfrom‚Äô
function, the error type received is converted into the error type
defined in the return type of the current function.  This is useful when
a function returns one error type to represent all the ways a function
might fail, even if parts might fail for many different reasons.

For example, we could change the ‚Äòread_username_from_file‚Äô function in
Listing 9-7 to return a custom error type named ‚ÄòOurError‚Äô that we
define.  If we also define ‚Äòimpl From<io::Error> for OurError‚Äô to
construct an instance of ‚ÄòOurError‚Äô from an ‚Äòio::Error‚Äô, then the ‚Äò?‚Äô
operator calls in the body of ‚Äòread_username_from_file‚Äô will call ‚Äòfrom‚Äô
and convert the error types without needing to add any more code to the
function.

In the context of Listing 9-7, the ‚Äò?‚Äô at the end of the ‚ÄòFile::open‚Äô
call will return the value inside an ‚ÄòOk‚Äô to the variable
‚Äòusername_file‚Äô.  If an error occurs, the ‚Äò?‚Äô operator will return early
out of the whole function and give any ‚ÄòErr‚Äô value to the calling code.
The same thing applies to the ‚Äò?‚Äô at the end of the ‚Äòread_to_string‚Äô
call.

The ‚Äò?‚Äô operator eliminates a lot of boilerplate and makes this
function's implementation simpler.  We could even shorten this code
further by chaining method calls immediately after the ‚Äò?‚Äô, as shown in
Listing 9-8.

use std::fs::File;
use std::io::{self, Read};

fn read_username_from_file() -> Result<String, io::Error> {
    let mut username = String::new();

    File::open("hello.txt")?.read_to_string(&mut username)?;

    Ok(username)
}

We've moved the creation of the new ‚ÄòString‚Äô in ‚Äòusername‚Äô to the
beginning of the function; that part hasn't changed.  Instead of
creating a variable ‚Äòusername_file‚Äô, we've chained the call to
‚Äòread_to_string‚Äô directly onto the result of ‚ÄòFile::open("hello.txt")?‚Äô.
We still have a ‚Äò?‚Äô at the end of the ‚Äòread_to_string‚Äô call, and we
still return an ‚ÄòOk‚Äô value containing ‚Äòusername‚Äô when both ‚ÄòFile::open‚Äô
and ‚Äòread_to_string‚Äô succeed rather than returning errors.  The
functionality is again the same as in Listing 9-6 and Listing 9-7; this
is just a different, more ergonomic way to write it.

Listing 9-9 shows a way to make this even shorter using
‚Äòfs::read_to_string‚Äô.

use std::fs;
use std::io;

fn read_username_from_file() -> Result<String, io::Error> {
    fs::read_to_string("hello.txt")
}

Reading a file into a string is a fairly common operation, so the
standard library provides the convenient ‚Äòfs::read_to_string‚Äô function
that opens the file, creates a new ‚ÄòString‚Äô, reads the contents of the
file, puts the contents into that ‚ÄòString‚Äô, and returns it.  Of course,
using ‚Äòfs::read_to_string‚Äô doesn't give us the opportunity to explain
all the error handling, so we did it the longer way first.  Where The
‚Äò?‚Äô Operator Can Be Used The ‚Äò?‚Äô operator can only be used in functions
whose return type is compatible with the value the ‚Äò?‚Äô is used on.  This
is because the ‚Äò?‚Äô operator is defined to perform an early return of a
value out of the function, in the same manner as the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression
we defined in Listing 9-6.  In Listing 9-6, the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô was using a
‚ÄòResult‚Äô value, and the early return arm returned an ‚ÄòErr(e)‚Äô value.
The return type of the function has to be a ‚ÄòResult‚Äô so that it's
compatible with this ‚Äòreturn‚Äô.

In Listing 9-10, let's look at the error we'll get if we use the ‚Äò?‚Äô
operator in a ‚Äòmain‚Äô function with a return type that is incompatible
with the type of the value we use ‚Äò?‚Äô on.

use std::fs::File;

fn main() {
    let greeting_file = File::open("hello.txt")?;
}

This code opens a file, which might fail.  The ‚Äò?‚Äô operator follows the
‚ÄòResult‚Äô value returned by ‚ÄòFile::open‚Äô, but this ‚Äòmain‚Äô function has
the return type of ‚Äò()‚Äô, not ‚ÄòResult‚Äô.  When we compile this code, we
get the following error message:

$ cargo run
   Compiling error-handling v0.1.0 (file:///projects/error-handling)
error[E0277]: the `?` operator can only be used in a function that returns `Result` or `Option` (or another type that implements `FromResidual`)
 --> src/main.rs:4:48
  |
3 | fn main() {
  | --------- this function should return `Result` or `Option` to accept `?`
4 |     let greeting_file = File::open("hello.txt")?;
  |                                                ^ cannot use the `?` operator in a function that returns `()`
  |
  = help: the trait `FromResidual<Result<Infallible, std::io::Error>>` is not implemented for `()`
help: consider adding return type
  |
3 ~ fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
4 |     let greeting_file = File::open("hello.txt")?;
5 +     Ok(())
  |

For more information about this error, try `rustc --explain E0277`.
error: could not compile `error-handling` (bin "error-handling") due to 1 previous error

This error points out that we're only allowed to use the ‚Äò?‚Äô operator in
a function that returns ‚ÄòResult‚Äô, ‚ÄòOption‚Äô, or another type that
implements ‚ÄòFromResidual‚Äô.

To fix the error, you have two choices.  One choice is to change the
return type of your function to be compatible with the value you're
using the ‚Äò?‚Äô operator on as long as you have no restrictions preventing
that.  The other choice is to use a ‚Äòmatch‚Äô or one of the ‚ÄòResult<T, E>‚Äô
methods to handle the ‚ÄòResult<T, E>‚Äô in whatever way is appropriate.

The error message also mentioned that ‚Äò?‚Äô can be used with ‚ÄòOption<T>‚Äô
values as well.  As with using ‚Äò?‚Äô on ‚ÄòResult‚Äô, you can only use ‚Äò?‚Äô on
‚ÄòOption‚Äô in a function that returns an ‚ÄòOption‚Äô.  The behavior of the
‚Äò?‚Äô operator when called on an ‚ÄòOption<T>‚Äô is similar to its behavior
when called on a ‚ÄòResult<T, E>‚Äô: if the value is ‚ÄòNone‚Äô, the ‚ÄòNone‚Äô will
be returned early from the function at that point.  If the value is
‚ÄòSome‚Äô, the value inside the ‚ÄòSome‚Äô is the resultant value of the
expression, and the function continues.  Listing 9-11 has an example of
a function that finds the last character of the first line in the given
text.

fn last_char_of_first_line(text: &str) -> Option<char> {
    text.lines().next()?.chars().last()
}

This function returns ‚ÄòOption<char>‚Äô because it's possible that there is
a character there, but it's also possible that there isn't.  This code
takes the ‚Äòtext‚Äô string slice argument and calls the ‚Äòlines‚Äô method on
it, which returns an iterator over the lines in the string.  Because
this function wants to examine the first line, it calls ‚Äònext‚Äô on the
iterator to get the first value from the iterator.  If ‚Äòtext‚Äô is the
empty string, this call to ‚Äònext‚Äô will return ‚ÄòNone‚Äô, in which case we
use ‚Äò?‚Äô to stop and return ‚ÄòNone‚Äô from ‚Äòlast_char_of_first_line‚Äô.  If
‚Äòtext‚Äô is not the empty string, ‚Äònext‚Äô will return a ‚ÄòSome‚Äô value
containing a string slice of the first line in ‚Äòtext‚Äô.

The ‚Äò?‚Äô extracts the string slice, and we can call ‚Äòchars‚Äô on that
string slice to get an iterator of its characters.  We're interested in
the last character in this first line, so we call ‚Äòlast‚Äô to return the
last item in the iterator.  This is an ‚ÄòOption‚Äô because it's possible
that the first line is the empty string; for example, if ‚Äòtext‚Äô starts
with a blank line but has characters on other lines, as in ‚Äò"\nhi"‚Äô.
However, if there is a last character on the first line, it will be
returned in the ‚ÄòSome‚Äô variant.  The ‚Äò?‚Äô operator in the middle gives us
a concise way to express this logic, allowing us to implement the
function in one line.  If we couldn't use the ‚Äò?‚Äô operator on ‚ÄòOption‚Äô,
we'd have to implement this logic using more method calls or a ‚Äòmatch‚Äô
expression.

Note that you can use the ‚Äò?‚Äô operator on a ‚ÄòResult‚Äô in a function that
returns ‚ÄòResult‚Äô, and you can use the ‚Äò?‚Äô operator on an ‚ÄòOption‚Äô in a
function that returns ‚ÄòOption‚Äô, but you can't mix and match.  The ‚Äò?‚Äô
operator won't automatically convert a ‚ÄòResult‚Äô to an ‚ÄòOption‚Äô or vice
versa; in those cases, you can use methods like the ‚Äòok‚Äô method on
‚ÄòResult‚Äô or the ‚Äòok_or‚Äô method on ‚ÄòOption‚Äô to do the conversion
explicitly.

So far, all the ‚Äòmain‚Äô functions we've used return ‚Äò()‚Äô.  The ‚Äòmain‚Äô
function is special because it's the entry point and exit point of an
executable program, and there are restrictions on what its return type
can be for the program to behave as expected.

Luckily, ‚Äòmain‚Äô can also return a ‚ÄòResult<(), E>‚Äô.  Listing 9-12 has the
code from Listing 9-10, but we've changed the return type of ‚Äòmain‚Äô to
be ‚ÄòResult<(), Box<dyn Error>>‚Äô and added a return value ‚ÄòOk(())‚Äô to the
end.  This code will now compile.

use std::error::Error;
use std::fs::File;

fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn Error>> {
    let greeting_file = File::open("hello.txt")?;

    Ok(())
}

The ‚ÄòBox<dyn Error>‚Äô type is a ‚Äòtrait object‚Äô, which we'll talk about in
the *note ‚ÄúUsing Trait Objects that Allow for Values of Different
Types‚Äù: Using Trait Objects That Allow for Values of Different Types.
section in Chapter 18.  For now, you can read ‚ÄòBox<dyn Error>‚Äô to mean
‚Äúany kind of error.‚Äù Using ‚Äò?‚Äô on a ‚ÄòResult‚Äô value in a ‚Äòmain‚Äô function
with the error type ‚ÄòBox<dyn Error>‚Äô is allowed because it allows any
‚ÄòErr‚Äô value to be returned early.  Even though the body of this ‚Äòmain‚Äô
function will only ever return errors of type ‚Äòstd::io::Error‚Äô, by
specifying ‚ÄòBox<dyn Error>‚Äô, this signature will continue to be correct
even if more code that returns other errors is added to the body of
‚Äòmain‚Äô.

When a ‚Äòmain‚Äô function returns a ‚ÄòResult<(), E>‚Äô, the executable will
exit with a value of ‚Äò0‚Äô if ‚Äòmain‚Äô returns ‚ÄòOk(())‚Äô and will exit with a
nonzero value if ‚Äòmain‚Äô returns an ‚ÄòErr‚Äô value.  Executables written in
C return integers when they exit: programs that exit successfully return
the integer ‚Äò0‚Äô, and programs that error return some integer other than
‚Äò0‚Äô.  Rust also returns integers from executables to be compatible with
this convention.

The ‚Äòmain‚Äô function may return any types that implement the
‚ÄòstdprocessTermination‚Äô trait
(https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/../std/process/trait.Termination.html),
which contains a function ‚Äòreport‚Äô that returns an ‚ÄòExitCode‚Äô.  Consult
the standard library documentation for more information on implementing
the ‚ÄòTermination‚Äô trait for your own types.

Now that we've discussed the details of calling ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô or returning
‚ÄòResult‚Äô, let's return to the topic of how to decide which is
appropriate to use in which cases.


