12.1.3 To ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô or Not to ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô
-------------------------------------

So how do you decide when you should call ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô and when you should
return ‚ÄòResult‚Äô?  When code panics, there's no way to recover.  You
could call ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô for any error situation, whether there's a possible
way to recover or not, but then you're making the decision that a
situation is unrecoverable on behalf of the calling code.  When you
choose to return a ‚ÄòResult‚Äô value, you give the calling code options.
The calling code could choose to attempt to recover in a way that's
appropriate for its situation, or it could decide that an ‚ÄòErr‚Äô value in
this case is unrecoverable, so it can call ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô and turn your
recoverable error into an unrecoverable one.  Therefore, returning
‚ÄòResult‚Äô is a good default choice when you're defining a function that
might fail.

In situations such as examples, prototype code, and tests, it's more
appropriate to write code that panics instead of returning a ‚ÄòResult‚Äô.
Let's explore why, then discuss situations in which the compiler can't
tell that failure is impossible, but you as a human can.  The chapter
will conclude with some general guidelines on how to decide whether to
panic in library code.

