12.1.3.2 Cases in Which You Have More Information Than the
..........................................................

Compiler It would also be appropriate to call ‚Äòunwrap‚Äô or ‚Äòexpect‚Äô when
you have some other logic that ensures the ‚ÄòResult‚Äô will have an ‚ÄòOk‚Äô
value, but the logic isn't something the compiler understands.  You'll
still have a ‚ÄòResult‚Äô value that you need to handle: whatever operation
you're calling still has the possibility of failing in general, even
though it's logically impossible in your particular situation.  If you
can ensure by manually inspecting the code that you'll never have an
‚ÄòErr‚Äô variant, it's perfectly acceptable to call ‚Äòunwrap‚Äô, and even
better to document the reason you think you'll never have an ‚ÄòErr‚Äô
variant in the ‚Äòexpect‚Äô text.  Here's an example:

    use std::net::IpAddr;

    let home: IpAddr = "127.0.0.1"
        .parse()
        .expect("Hardcoded IP address should be valid");

We're creating an ‚ÄòIpAddr‚Äô instance by parsing a hardcoded string.  We
can see that ‚Äò127.0.0.1‚Äô is a valid IP address, so it's acceptable to
use ‚Äòexpect‚Äô here.  However, having a hardcoded, valid string doesn't
change the return type of the ‚Äòparse‚Äô method: we still get a ‚ÄòResult‚Äô
value, and the compiler will still make us handle the ‚ÄòResult‚Äô as if the
‚ÄòErr‚Äô variant is a possibility because the compiler isn't smart enough
to see that this string is always a valid IP address.  If the IP address
string came from a user rather than being hardcoded into the program and
therefore ‚Äòdid‚Äô have a possibility of failure, we'd definitely want to
handle the ‚ÄòResult‚Äô in a more robust way instead.  Mentioning the
assumption that this IP address is hardcoded will prompt us to change
‚Äòexpect‚Äô to better error-handling code if, in the future, we need to get
the IP address from some other source instead.


