13.1.1.4 In Method Definitions
..............................

We can implement methods on structs and enums (as we did in Chapter 5)
and use generic types in their definitions too.  Listing 10-9 shows the
‚ÄòPoint<T>‚Äô struct we defined in Listing 10-6 with a method named ‚Äòx‚Äô
implemented on it.

struct Point<T> {
    x: T,
    y: T,
}

impl<T> Point<T> {
    fn x(&self) -> &T {
        &self.x
    }
}

fn main() {
    let p = Point { x: 5, y: 10 };

    println!("p.x = {}", p.x());
}

Here, we've defined a method named ‚Äòx‚Äô on ‚ÄòPoint<T>‚Äô that returns a
reference to the data in the field ‚Äòx‚Äô.

Note that we have to declare ‚ÄòT‚Äô just after ‚Äòimpl‚Äô so we can use ‚ÄòT‚Äô to
specify that we're implementing methods on the type ‚ÄòPoint<T>‚Äô.  By
declaring ‚ÄòT‚Äô as a generic type after ‚Äòimpl‚Äô, Rust can identify that the
type in the angle brackets in ‚ÄòPoint‚Äô is a generic type rather than a
concrete type.  We could have chosen a different name for this generic
parameter than the generic parameter declared in the struct definition,
but using the same name is conventional.  Methods written within an
‚Äòimpl‚Äô that declares the generic type will be defined on any instance of
the type, no matter what concrete type ends up substituting for the
generic type.

We can also specify constraints on generic types when defining methods
on the type.  We could, for example, implement methods only on
‚ÄòPoint<f32>‚Äô instances rather than on ‚ÄòPoint<T>‚Äô instances with any
generic type.  In Listing 10-10 we use the concrete type ‚Äòf32‚Äô, meaning
we don't declare any types after ‚Äòimpl‚Äô.

impl Point<f32> {
    fn distance_from_origin(&self) -> f32 {
        (self.x.powi(2) + self.y.powi(2)).sqrt()
    }
}

This code means the type ‚ÄòPoint<f32>‚Äô will have a ‚Äòdistance_from_origin‚Äô
method; other instances of ‚ÄòPoint<T>‚Äô where ‚ÄòT‚Äô is not of type ‚Äòf32‚Äô
will not have this method defined.  The method measures how far our
point is from the point at coordinates (0.0, 0.0) and uses mathematical
operations that are available only for floating-point types.

Generic type parameters in a struct definition aren't always the same as
those you use in that same struct's method signatures.  Listing 10-11
uses the generic types ‚ÄòX1‚Äô and ‚ÄòY1‚Äô for the ‚ÄòPoint‚Äô struct and ‚ÄòX2‚Äô
‚ÄòY2‚Äô for the ‚Äòmixup‚Äô method signature to make the example clearer.  The
method creates a new ‚ÄòPoint‚Äô instance with the ‚Äòx‚Äô value from the ‚Äòself‚Äô
‚ÄòPoint‚Äô (of type ‚ÄòX1‚Äô) and the ‚Äòy‚Äô value from the passed-in ‚ÄòPoint‚Äô (of
type ‚ÄòY2‚Äô).

struct Point<X1, Y1> {
    x: X1,
    y: Y1,
}

impl<X1, Y1> Point<X1, Y1> {
    fn mixup<X2, Y2>(self, other: Point<X2, Y2>) -> Point<X1, Y2> {
        Point {
            x: self.x,
            y: other.y,
        }
    }
}

fn main() {
    let p1 = Point { x: 5, y: 10.4 };
    let p2 = Point { x: "Hello", y: 'c' };

    let p3 = p1.mixup(p2);

    println!("p3.x = {}, p3.y = {}", p3.x, p3.y);
}

In ‚Äòmain‚Äô, we've defined a ‚ÄòPoint‚Äô that has an ‚Äòi32‚Äô for ‚Äòx‚Äô (with value
‚Äò5‚Äô) and an ‚Äòf64‚Äô for ‚Äòy‚Äô (with value ‚Äò10.4‚Äô).  The ‚Äòp2‚Äô variable is a
‚ÄòPoint‚Äô struct that has a string slice for ‚Äòx‚Äô (with value ‚Äò"Hello"‚Äô)
and a ‚Äòchar‚Äô for ‚Äòy‚Äô (with value ‚Äòc‚Äô).  Calling ‚Äòmixup‚Äô on ‚Äòp1‚Äô with the
argument ‚Äòp2‚Äô gives us ‚Äòp3‚Äô, which will have an ‚Äòi32‚Äô for ‚Äòx‚Äô because
‚Äòx‚Äô came from ‚Äòp1‚Äô.  The ‚Äòp3‚Äô variable will have a ‚Äòchar‚Äô for ‚Äòy‚Äô
because ‚Äòy‚Äô came from ‚Äòp2‚Äô.  The ‚Äòprintln!‚Äô macro call will print ‚Äòp3.x
= 5, p3.y = c‚Äô.

The purpose of this example is to demonstrate a situation in which some
generic parameters are declared with ‚Äòimpl‚Äô and some are declared with
the method definition.  Here, the generic parameters ‚ÄòX1‚Äô and ‚ÄòY1‚Äô are
declared after ‚Äòimpl‚Äô because they go with the struct definition.  The
generic parameters ‚ÄòX2‚Äô and ‚ÄòY2‚Äô are declared after ‚Äòfn mixup‚Äô because
they're only relevant to the method.


