13.1.2.2 Implementing a Trait on a Type
.......................................

Now that we've defined the desired signatures of the ‚ÄòSummary‚Äô trait's
methods, we can implement it on the types in our media aggregator.
Listing 10-13 shows an implementation of the ‚ÄòSummary‚Äô trait on the
‚ÄòNewsArticle‚Äô struct that uses the headline, the author, and the
location to create the return value of ‚Äòsummarize‚Äô.  For the ‚ÄòTweet‚Äô
struct, we define ‚Äòsummarize‚Äô as the username followed by the entire
text of the tweet, assuming that the tweet content is already limited to
280 characters.

pub struct NewsArticle {
    pub headline: String,
    pub location: String,
    pub author: String,
    pub content: String,
}

impl Summary for NewsArticle {
    fn summarize(&self) -> String {
        format!("{}, by {} ({})", self.headline, self.author, self.location)
    }
}

pub struct Tweet {
    pub username: String,
    pub content: String,
    pub reply: bool,
    pub retweet: bool,
}

impl Summary for Tweet {
    fn summarize(&self) -> String {
        format!("{}: {}", self.username, self.content)
    }
}

Implementing a trait on a type is similar to implementing regular
methods.  The difference is that after ‚Äòimpl‚Äô, we put the trait name we
want to implement, then use the ‚Äòfor‚Äô keyword, and then specify the name
of the type we want to implement the trait for.  Within the ‚Äòimpl‚Äô
block, we put the method signatures that the trait definition has
defined.  Instead of adding a semicolon after each signature, we use
curly brackets and fill in the method body with the specific behavior
that we want the methods of the trait to have for the particular type.

Now that the library has implemented the ‚ÄòSummary‚Äô trait on
‚ÄòNewsArticle‚Äô and ‚ÄòTweet‚Äô, users of the crate can call the trait methods
on instances of ‚ÄòNewsArticle‚Äô and ‚ÄòTweet‚Äô in the same way we call
regular methods.  The only difference is that the user must bring the
trait into scope as well as the types.  Here's an example of how a
binary crate could use our ‚Äòaggregator‚Äô library crate:

use aggregator::{Summary, Tweet};

fn main() {
    let tweet = Tweet {
        username: String::from("horse_ebooks"),
        content: String::from(
            "of course, as you probably already know, people",
        ),
        reply: false,
        retweet: false,
    };

    println!("1 new tweet: {}", tweet.summarize());
}

This code prints ‚Äò1 new tweet: horse_ebooks: of course, as you probably
already know, people‚Äô.

Other crates that depend on the ‚Äòaggregator‚Äô crate can also bring the
‚ÄòSummary‚Äô trait into scope to implement ‚ÄòSummary‚Äô on their own types.
One restriction to note is that we can implement a trait on a type only
if either the trait or the type, or both, are local to our crate.  For
example, we can implement standard library traits like ‚ÄòDisplay‚Äô on a
custom type like ‚ÄòTweet‚Äô as part of our ‚Äòaggregator‚Äô crate functionality
because the type ‚ÄòTweet‚Äô is local to our ‚Äòaggregator‚Äô crate.  We can
also implement ‚ÄòSummary‚Äô on ‚ÄòVec<T>‚Äô in our ‚Äòaggregator‚Äô crate because
the trait ‚ÄòSummary‚Äô is local to our ‚Äòaggregator‚Äô crate.

But we can't implement external traits on external types.  For example,
we can't implement the ‚ÄòDisplay‚Äô trait on ‚ÄòVec<T>‚Äô within our
‚Äòaggregator‚Äô crate because ‚ÄòDisplay‚Äô and ‚ÄòVec<T>‚Äô are both defined in
the standard library and aren't local to our ‚Äòaggregator‚Äô crate.  This
restriction is part of a property called ‚Äòcoherence‚Äô, and more
specifically the ‚Äòorphan rule‚Äô, so named because the parent type is not
present.  This rule ensures that other people's code can't break your
code and vice versa.  Without the rule, two crates could implement the
same trait for the same type, and Rust wouldn't know which
implementation to use.


