13.1.2.4 Traits as Parameters
.............................

Now that you know how to define and implement traits, we can explore how
to use traits to define functions that accept many different types.
We'll use the ‚ÄòSummary‚Äô trait we implemented on the ‚ÄòNewsArticle‚Äô and
‚ÄòTweet‚Äô types in Listing 10-13 to define a ‚Äònotify‚Äô function that calls
the ‚Äòsummarize‚Äô method on its ‚Äòitem‚Äô parameter, which is of some type
that implements the ‚ÄòSummary‚Äô trait.  To do this, we use the ‚Äòimpl
Trait‚Äô syntax, like this:

pub fn notify(item: &impl Summary) {
    println!("Breaking news! {}", item.summarize());
}

Instead of a concrete type for the ‚Äòitem‚Äô parameter, we specify the
‚Äòimpl‚Äô keyword and the trait name.  This parameter accepts any type that
implements the specified trait.  In the body of ‚Äònotify‚Äô, we can call
any methods on ‚Äòitem‚Äô that come from the ‚ÄòSummary‚Äô trait, such as
‚Äòsummarize‚Äô.  We can call ‚Äònotify‚Äô and pass in any instance of
‚ÄòNewsArticle‚Äô or ‚ÄòTweet‚Äô.  Code that calls the function with any other
type, such as a ‚ÄòString‚Äô or an ‚Äòi32‚Äô, won't compile because those types
don't implement ‚ÄòSummary‚Äô.  Trait Bound Syntax The ‚Äòimpl Trait‚Äô syntax
works for straightforward cases but is actually syntax sugar for a
longer form known as a ‚Äòtrait bound‚Äô; it looks like this:

pub fn notify<T: Summary>(item: &T) {
    println!("Breaking news! {}", item.summarize());
}

This longer form is equivalent to the example in the previous section
but is more verbose.  We place trait bounds with the declaration of the
generic type parameter after a colon and inside angle brackets.

The ‚Äòimpl Trait‚Äô syntax is convenient and makes for more concise code in
simple cases, while the fuller trait bound syntax can express more
complexity in other cases.  For example, we can have two parameters that
implement ‚ÄòSummary‚Äô.  Doing so with the ‚Äòimpl Trait‚Äô syntax looks like
this:

pub fn notify(item1: &impl Summary, item2: &impl Summary) {

Using ‚Äòimpl Trait‚Äô is appropriate if we want this function to allow
‚Äòitem1‚Äô and ‚Äòitem2‚Äô to have different types (as long as both types
implement ‚ÄòSummary‚Äô).  If we want to force both parameters to have the
same type, however, we must use a trait bound, like this:

pub fn notify<T: Summary>(item1: &T, item2: &T) {

The generic type ‚ÄòT‚Äô specified as the type of the ‚Äòitem1‚Äô and ‚Äòitem2‚Äô
parameters constrains the function such that the concrete type of the
value passed as an argument for ‚Äòitem1‚Äô and ‚Äòitem2‚Äô must be the same.
Specifying Multiple Trait Bounds with the ‚Äò+‚Äô Syntax We can also specify
more than one trait bound.  Say we wanted ‚Äònotify‚Äô to use display
formatting as well as ‚Äòsummarize‚Äô on ‚Äòitem‚Äô: we specify in the ‚Äònotify‚Äô
definition that ‚Äòitem‚Äô must implement both ‚ÄòDisplay‚Äô and ‚ÄòSummary‚Äô.  We
can do so using the ‚Äò+‚Äô syntax:

pub fn notify(item: &(impl Summary + Display)) {

The ‚Äò+‚Äô syntax is also valid with trait bounds on generic types:

pub fn notify<T: Summary + Display>(item: &T) {

With the two trait bounds specified, the body of ‚Äònotify‚Äô can call
‚Äòsummarize‚Äô and use ‚Äò{}‚Äô to format ‚Äòitem‚Äô.  Clearer Trait Bounds with
‚Äòwhere‚Äô Clauses Using too many trait bounds has its downsides.  Each
generic has its own trait bounds, so functions with multiple generic
type parameters can contain lots of trait bound information between the
function's name and its parameter list, making the function signature
hard to read.  For this reason, Rust has alternate syntax for specifying
trait bounds inside a ‚Äòwhere‚Äô clause after the function signature.  So,
instead of writing this:

fn some_function<T: Display + Clone, U: Clone + Debug>(t: &T, u: &U) -> i32 {

we can use a ‚Äòwhere‚Äô clause, like this:

fn some_function<T, U>(t: &T, u: &U) -> i32
where
    T: Display + Clone,
    U: Clone + Debug,
{

This function's signature is less cluttered: the function name,
parameter list, and return type are close together, similar to a
function without lots of trait bounds.


