13.1.3.2 The Borrow Checker
...........................

The Rust compiler has a ‚Äòborrow checker‚Äô that compares scopes to
determine whether all borrows are valid.  Listing 10-17 shows the same
code as Listing 10-16 but with annotations showing the lifetimes of the
variables.

fn main() {
    let r;                // ---------+-- 'a
                          //          |
    {                     //          |
        let x = 5;        // -+-- 'b  |
        r = &x;           //  |       |
    }                     // -+       |
                          //          |
    println!("r: {r}");   //          |
}                         // ---------+

Here, we've annotated the lifetime of ‚Äòr‚Äô with ‚Äò'a‚Äô and the lifetime of
‚Äòx‚Äô with ‚Äò'b‚Äô.  As you can see, the inner ‚Äò'b‚Äô block is much smaller
than the outer ‚Äò'a‚Äô lifetime block.  At compile time, Rust compares the
size of the two lifetimes and sees that ‚Äòr‚Äô has a lifetime of ‚Äò'a‚Äô but
that it refers to memory with a lifetime of ‚Äò'b‚Äô.  The program is
rejected because ‚Äò'b‚Äô is shorter than ‚Äò'a‚Äô: the subject of the reference
doesn't live as long as the reference.

Listing 10-18 fixes the code so it doesn't have a dangling reference and
it compiles without any errors.

fn main() {
    let x = 5;            // ----------+-- 'b
                          //           |
    let r = &x;           // --+-- 'a  |
                          //   |       |
    println!("r: {r}");   //   |       |
                          // --+       |
}                         // ----------+

Here, ‚Äòx‚Äô has the lifetime ‚Äò'b‚Äô, which in this case is larger than ‚Äò'a‚Äô.
This means ‚Äòr‚Äô can reference ‚Äòx‚Äô because Rust knows that the reference
in ‚Äòr‚Äô will always be valid while ‚Äòx‚Äô is valid.

Now that you know what the lifetimes of references are and how Rust
analyzes lifetimes to ensure references will always be valid, let's
explore generic lifetimes of parameters and return values in the context
of functions.


