13.1.3.10 The Static Lifetime
.............................

One special lifetime we need to discuss is ‚Äò'static‚Äô, which denotes that
the affected reference ‚Äòcan‚Äô live for the entire duration of the
program.  All string literals have the ‚Äò'static‚Äô lifetime, which we can
annotate as follows:

let s: &'static str = "I have a static lifetime.";

The text of this string is stored directly in the program's binary,
which is always available.  Therefore, the lifetime of all string
literals is ‚Äò'static‚Äô.

You might see suggestions to use the ‚Äò'static‚Äô lifetime in error
messages.  But before specifying ‚Äò'static‚Äô as the lifetime for a
reference, think about whether the reference you have actually lives the
entire lifetime of your program or not, and whether you want it to.
Most of the time, an error message suggesting the ‚Äò'static‚Äô lifetime
results from attempting to create a dangling reference or a mismatch of
the available lifetimes.  In such cases, the solution is to fix those
problems, not to specify the ‚Äò'static‚Äô lifetime.


