14.1.1 The Anatomy of a Test Function
-------------------------------------

At its simplest, a test in Rust is a function that's annotated with the
‚Äòtest‚Äô attribute.  Attributes are metadata about pieces of Rust code;
one example is the ‚Äòderive‚Äô attribute we used with structs in Chapter 5.
To change a function into a test function, add ‚Äò#[test]‚Äô on the line
before ‚Äòfn‚Äô.  When you run your tests with the ‚Äòcargo test‚Äô command,
Rust builds a test runner binary that runs the annotated functions and
reports on whether each test function passes or fails.

Whenever we make a new library project with Cargo, a test module with a
test function in it is automatically generated for us.  This module
gives you a template for writing your tests so you don't have to look up
the exact structure and syntax every time you start a new project.  You
can add as many additional test functions and as many test modules as
you want!

We'll explore some aspects of how tests work by experimenting with the
