In addition to checking return values, it's important to check that our
code handles error conditions as we expect.  For example, consider the
‚ÄòGuess‚Äô type that we created in Chapter 9, Listing 9-13.  Other code
that uses ‚ÄòGuess‚Äô depends on the guarantee that ‚ÄòGuess‚Äô instances will
contain only values between 1 and 100.  We can write a test that ensures
that attempting to create a ‚ÄòGuess‚Äô instance with a value outside that
range panics.

We do this by adding the attribute ‚Äòshould_panic‚Äô to our test function.
The test passes if the code inside the function panics; the test fails
if the code inside the function doesn't panic.

Listing 11-8 shows a test that checks that the error conditions of
‚ÄòGuess::new‚Äô happen when we expect them to.

pub struct Guess {
    value: i32,
}

impl Guess {
    pub fn new(value: i32) -> Guess {
        if value < 1 || value > 100 {
            panic!("Guess value must be between 1 and 100, got {value}.");
        }

        Guess { value }
    }
}

mod tests {
    use super::*;

    fn greater_than_100() {
        Guess::new(200);
    }
}

