14.1.1.5 Using ‚ÄòResult<T, E>‚Äô in Tests
......................................

Our tests so far all panic when they fail.  We can also write tests that
use ‚ÄòResult<T, E>‚Äô!  Here's the test from Listing 11-1, rewritten to use
‚ÄòResult<T, E>‚Äô and return an ‚ÄòErr‚Äô instead of panicking:

    fn it_works() -> Result<(), String> {
        let result = add(2, 2);

        if result == 4 {
            Ok(())
        } else {
            Err(String::from("two plus two does not equal four"))
        }
    }

The ‚Äòit_works‚Äô function now has the ‚ÄòResult<(), String>‚Äô return type.
In the body of the function, rather than calling the ‚Äòassert_eq!‚Äô macro,
we return ‚ÄòOk(())‚Äô when the test passes and an ‚ÄòErr‚Äô with a ‚ÄòString‚Äô
inside when the test fails.

Writing tests so they return a ‚ÄòResult<T, E>‚Äô enables you to use the
question mark operator in the body of tests, which can be a convenient
way to write tests that should fail if any operation within them returns
an ‚ÄòErr‚Äô variant.

You can't use the ‚Äò#[should_panic]‚Äô annotation on tests that use
‚ÄòResult<T, E>‚Äô.  To assert that an operation returns an ‚ÄòErr‚Äô variant,
‚Äòdon't‚Äô use the question mark operator on the ‚ÄòResult<T, E>‚Äô value.
Instead, use ‚Äòassert!(value.is_err())‚Äô.

