14.1.2 Controlling How Tests Are Run
------------------------------------

Just as ‚Äòcargo run‚Äô compiles your code and then runs the resultant
binary, ‚Äòcargo test‚Äô compiles your code in test mode and runs the
resultant test binary.  The default behavior of the binary produced by
‚Äòcargo test‚Äô is to run all the tests in parallel and capture output
generated during test runs, preventing the output from being displayed
and making it easier to read the output related to the test results.
You can, however, specify command line options to change this default
behavior.

Some command line options go to ‚Äòcargo test‚Äô, and some go to the
resultant test binary.  To separate these two types of arguments, you
list the arguments that go to ‚Äòcargo test‚Äô followed by the separator
‚Äò--‚Äô and then the ones that go to the test binary.  Running ‚Äòcargo test
--help‚Äô displays the options you can use with ‚Äòcargo test‚Äô, and running
‚Äòcargo test -- --help‚Äô displays the options you can use after the
separator.  Those options are also documented in the ‚ÄúTests‚Äù section
(https://doc.rust-lang.org/rustc/tests/index.html) of the the rustc book
(https://doc.rust-lang.org/rustc/index.html).

