14.1.3.1 Unit Tests
...................

The purpose of unit tests is to test each unit of code in isolation from
the rest of the code to quickly pinpoint where code is and isn't working
as expected.  You'll put unit tests in the ‚Äòsrc‚Äô directory in each file
with the code that they're testing.  The convention is to create a
module named ‚Äòtests‚Äô in each file to contain the test functions and to
annotate the module with ‚Äòcfg(test)‚Äô.  The Tests Module and
‚Äò#[cfg(test)]‚Äô The ‚Äò#[cfg(test)]‚Äô annotation on the ‚Äòtests‚Äô module tells
Rust to compile and run the test code only when you run ‚Äòcargo test‚Äô,
not when you run ‚Äòcargo build‚Äô.  This saves compile time when you only
want to build the library and saves space in the resultant compiled
artifact because the tests are not included.  You'll see that because
integration tests go in a different directory, they don't need the
‚Äò#[cfg(test)]‚Äô annotation.  However, because unit tests go in the same
files as the code, you'll use ‚Äò#[cfg(test)]‚Äô to specify that they
shouldn't be included in the compiled result.

Recall that when we generated the new ‚Äòadder‚Äô project in the first
section of this chapter, Cargo generated this code for us:

Filename: src/lib.rs

pub fn add(left: u64, right: u64) -> u64 {
    left + right
}

mod tests {
    use super::*;

    fn it_works() {
        let result = add(2, 2);
        assert_eq!(result, 4);
    }
}

On the automatically generated ‚Äòtests‚Äô module, the attribute ‚Äòcfg‚Äô
stands for ‚Äòconfiguration‚Äô and tells Rust that the following item should
only be included given a certain configuration option.  In this case,
the configuration option is ‚Äòtest‚Äô, which is provided by Rust for
compiling and running tests.  By using the ‚Äòcfg‚Äô attribute, Cargo
compiles our test code only if we actively run the tests with ‚Äòcargo
test‚Äô.  This includes any helper functions that might be within this
module, in addition to the functions annotated with ‚Äò#[test]‚Äô.  Testing
Private Functions There's debate within the testing community about
whether or not private functions should be tested directly, and other
languages make it difficult or impossible to test private functions.
Regardless of which testing ideology you adhere to, Rust's privacy rules
do allow you to test private functions.  Consider the code in Listing
11-12 with the private function ‚Äòinternal_adder‚Äô.

pub fn add_two(a: usize) -> usize {
    internal_adder(a, 2)
}

fn internal_adder(left: usize, right: usize) -> usize {
    left + right
}

mod tests {
    use super::*;

    fn internal() {
        let result = internal_adder(2, 2);
        assert_eq!(result, 4);
    }
}

Note that the ‚Äòinternal_adder‚Äô function is not marked as ‚Äòpub‚Äô.  Tests
are just Rust code, and the ‚Äòtests‚Äô module is just another module.  As
we discussed in the *note ‚ÄúPaths for Referring to an Item in the Module
Tree‚Äù: Paths for Referring to an Item in the Module Tree. section, items
in child modules can use the items in their ancestor modules.  In this
test, we bring all of the ‚Äòtests‚Äô module's parent's items into scope
with ‚Äòuse super::*‚Äô, and then the test can call ‚Äòinternal_adder‚Äô.  If
you don't think private functions should be tested, there's nothing in
Rust that will compel you to do so.


