14.1.3.2 Integration Tests
..........................

In Rust, integration tests are entirely external to your library.  They
use your library in the same way any other code would, which means they
can only call functions that are part of your library's public API.
Their purpose is to test whether many parts of your library work
together correctly.  Units of code that work correctly on their own
could have problems when integrated, so test coverage of the integrated
code is important as well.  To create integration tests, you first need
a ‚Äòtests‚Äô directory.  The ‚Äòtests‚Äô Directory We create a ‚Äòtests‚Äô
directory at the top level of our project directory, next to ‚Äòsrc‚Äô.
Cargo knows to look for integration test files in this directory.  We
can then make as many test files as we want, and Cargo will compile each
of the files as an individual crate.

Let's create an integration test.  With the code in Listing 11-12 still
in the ‚Äòsrc/lib.rs‚Äô file, make a ‚Äòtests‚Äô directory, and create a new
file named ‚Äòtests/integration_test.rs‚Äô.  Your directory structure should
look like this:

