15.1.1 Reading the Argument Values
----------------------------------

To enable ‚Äòminigrep‚Äô to read the values of command line arguments we
pass to it, we'll need the ‚Äòstd::env::args‚Äô function provided in Rust's
standard library.  This function returns an iterator of the command line
arguments passed to ‚Äòminigrep‚Äô.  We'll cover iterators fully in *note
Chapter 13: Functional Language Features Iterators and Closures.  For
now, you only need to know two details about iterators: iterators
produce a series of values, and we can call the ‚Äòcollect‚Äô method on an
iterator to turn it into a collection, such as a vector, that contains
all the elements the iterator produces.

The code in Listing 12-1 allows your ‚Äòminigrep‚Äô program to read any
command line arguments passed to it, and then collect the values into a
vector.

use std::env;

fn main() {
    let args: Vec<String> = env::args().collect();
    dbg!(args);
}

First we bring the ‚Äòstd::env‚Äô module into scope with a ‚Äòuse‚Äô statement
so we can use its ‚Äòargs‚Äô function.  Notice that the ‚Äòstd::env::args‚Äô
function is nested in two levels of modules.  As we discussed in *note
Chapter 7: Creating Idiomatic use Paths, in cases where the desired
function is nested in more than one module, we've chosen to bring the
parent module into scope rather than the function.  By doing so, we can
easily use other functions from ‚Äòstd::env‚Äô.  It's also less ambiguous
than adding ‚Äòuse std::env::args‚Äô and then calling the function with just
‚Äòargs‚Äô, because ‚Äòargs‚Äô might easily be mistaken for a function that's
defined in the current module.


