15.1.3.1 Separation of Concerns for Binary Projects
...................................................

The organizational problem of allocating responsibility for multiple
tasks to the ‚Äòmain‚Äô function is common to many binary projects.  As a
result, the Rust community has developed guidelines for splitting the
separate concerns of a binary program when ‚Äòmain‚Äô starts getting large.
This process has the following steps:

   ‚Ä¢ Split your program into a ‚Äòmain.rs‚Äô file and a ‚Äòlib.rs‚Äô file and
     move your program's logic to ‚Äòlib.rs‚Äô.
   ‚Ä¢ As long as your command line parsing logic is small, it can remain
     in ‚Äòmain.rs‚Äô.
   ‚Ä¢ When the command line parsing logic starts getting complicated,
     extract it from ‚Äòmain.rs‚Äô and move it to ‚Äòlib.rs‚Äô.

The responsibilities that remain in the ‚Äòmain‚Äô function after this
process should be limited to the following:

   ‚Ä¢ Calling the command line parsing logic with the argument values
   ‚Ä¢ Setting up any other configuration
   ‚Ä¢ Calling a ‚Äòrun‚Äô function in ‚Äòlib.rs‚Äô
   ‚Ä¢ Handling the error if ‚Äòrun‚Äô returns an error

This pattern is about separating concerns: ‚Äòmain.rs‚Äô handles running the
program and ‚Äòlib.rs‚Äô handles all the logic of the task at hand.  Because
you can't test the ‚Äòmain‚Äô function directly, this structure lets you
test all of your program's logic by moving it into functions in
‚Äòlib.rs‚Äô.  The code that remains in ‚Äòmain.rs‚Äô will be small enough to
verify its correctness by reading it.  Let's rework our program by
following this process.  Extracting the Argument Parser We'll extract
the functionality for parsing arguments into a function that ‚Äòmain‚Äô will
call to prepare for moving the command line parsing logic to
‚Äòsrc/lib.rs‚Äô.  Listing 12-5 shows the new start of ‚Äòmain‚Äô that calls a
new function ‚Äòparse_config‚Äô, which we'll define in ‚Äòsrc/main.rs‚Äô for the
moment.

fn main() {
    let args: Vec<String> = env::args().collect();

    let (query, file_path) = parse_config(&args);

    // --snip--
}

fn parse_config(args: &[String]) -> (&str, &str) {
    let query = &args[1];
    let file_path = &args[2];

    (query, file_path)
}

We're still collecting the command line arguments into a vector, but
instead of assigning the argument value at index 1 to the variable
‚Äòquery‚Äô and the argument value at index 2 to the variable ‚Äòfile_path‚Äô
within the ‚Äòmain‚Äô function, we pass the whole vector to the
‚Äòparse_config‚Äô function.  The ‚Äòparse_config‚Äô function then holds the
logic that determines which argument goes in which variable and passes
the values back to ‚Äòmain‚Äô.  We still create the ‚Äòquery‚Äô and ‚Äòfile_path‚Äô
variables in ‚Äòmain‚Äô, but ‚Äòmain‚Äô no longer has the responsibility of
determining how the command line arguments and variables correspond.

This rework may seem like overkill for our small program, but we're
refactoring in small, incremental steps.  After making this change, run
the program again to verify that the argument parsing still works.  It's
good to check your progress often, to help identify the cause of
problems when they occur.  Grouping Configuration Values We can take
another small step to improve the ‚Äòparse_config‚Äô function further.  At
the moment, we're returning a tuple, but then we immediately break that
tuple into individual parts again.  This is a sign that perhaps we don't
have the right abstraction yet.

Another indicator that shows there's room for improvement is the
‚Äòconfig‚Äô part of ‚Äòparse_config‚Äô, which implies that the two values we
return are related and are both part of one configuration value.  We're
not currently conveying this meaning in the structure of the data other
than by grouping the two values into a tuple; we'll instead put the two
values into one struct and give each of the struct fields a meaningful
name.  Doing so will make it easier for future maintainers of this code
to understand how the different values relate to each other and what
their purpose is.

Listing 12-6 shows the improvements to the ‚Äòparse_config‚Äô function.

fn main() {
    let args: Vec<String> = env::args().collect();

    let config = parse_config(&args);

    println!("Searching for {}", config.query);
    println!("In file {}", config.file_path);

    let contents = fs::read_to_string(config.file_path)
        .expect("Should have been able to read the file");

    // --snip--
}

struct Config {
    query: String,
    file_path: String,
}

fn parse_config(args: &[String]) -> Config {
    let query = args[1].clone();
    let file_path = args[2].clone();

    Config { query, file_path }
}

We've added a struct named ‚ÄòConfig‚Äô defined to have fields named ‚Äòquery‚Äô
and ‚Äòfile_path‚Äô.  The signature of ‚Äòparse_config‚Äô now indicates that it
returns a ‚ÄòConfig‚Äô value.  In the body of ‚Äòparse_config‚Äô, where we used
to return string slices that reference ‚ÄòString‚Äô values in ‚Äòargs‚Äô, we now
define ‚ÄòConfig‚Äô to contain owned ‚ÄòString‚Äô values.  The ‚Äòargs‚Äô variable
in ‚Äòmain‚Äô is the owner of the argument values and is only letting the
‚Äòparse_config‚Äô function borrow them, which means we'd violate Rust's
borrowing rules if ‚ÄòConfig‚Äô tried to take ownership of the values in
‚Äòargs‚Äô.

There are a number of ways we could manage the ‚ÄòString‚Äô data; the
easiest, though somewhat inefficient, route is to call the ‚Äòclone‚Äô
method on the values.  This will make a full copy of the data for the
‚ÄòConfig‚Äô instance to own, which takes more time and memory than storing
a reference to the string data.  However, cloning the data also makes
our code very straightforward because we don't have to manage the
lifetimes of the references; in this circumstance, giving up a little
performance to gain simplicity is a worthwhile trade-off.


