15.1.3.2 The Trade-Offs of Using ‚Äòclone‚Äô
........................................

There's a tendency among many Rustaceans to avoid using ‚Äòclone‚Äô to fix
ownership problems because of its runtime cost.  In *note Chapter 13:
Functional Language Features Iterators and Closures, you'll learn how to
use more efficient methods in this type of situation.  But for now, it's
okay to copy a few strings to continue making progress because you'll
make these copies only once and your file path and query string are very
small.  It's better to have a working program that's a bit inefficient
than to try to hyperoptimize code on your first pass.  As you become
more experienced with Rust, it'll be easier to start with the most
efficient solution, but for now, it's perfectly acceptable to call
‚Äòclone‚Äô.

We've updated ‚Äòmain‚Äô so it places the instance of ‚ÄòConfig‚Äô returned by
‚Äòparse_config‚Äô into a variable named ‚Äòconfig‚Äô, and we updated the code
that previously used the separate ‚Äòquery‚Äô and ‚Äòfile_path‚Äô variables so
it now uses the fields on the ‚ÄòConfig‚Äô struct instead.

Now our code more clearly conveys that ‚Äòquery‚Äô and ‚Äòfile_path‚Äô are
related and that their purpose is to configure how the program will
work.  Any code that uses these values knows to find them in the
‚Äòconfig‚Äô instance in the fields named for their purpose.  Creating a
Constructor for ‚ÄòConfig‚Äô So far, we've extracted the logic responsible
for parsing the command line arguments from ‚Äòmain‚Äô and placed it in the
‚Äòparse_config‚Äô function.  Doing so helped us see that the ‚Äòquery‚Äô and
‚Äòfile_path‚Äô values were related, and that relationship should be
conveyed in our code.  We then added a ‚ÄòConfig‚Äô struct to name the
related purpose of ‚Äòquery‚Äô and ‚Äòfile_path‚Äô and to be able to return the
values' names as struct field names from the ‚Äòparse_config‚Äô function.

So now that the purpose of the ‚Äòparse_config‚Äô function is to create a
‚ÄòConfig‚Äô instance, we can change ‚Äòparse_config‚Äô from a plain function to
a function named ‚Äònew‚Äô that is associated with the ‚ÄòConfig‚Äô struct.
Making this change will make the code more idiomatic.  We can create
instances of types in the standard library, such as ‚ÄòString‚Äô, by calling
‚ÄòString::new‚Äô.  Similarly, by changing ‚Äòparse_config‚Äô into a ‚Äònew‚Äô
function associated with ‚ÄòConfig‚Äô, we'll be able to create instances of
‚ÄòConfig‚Äô by calling ‚ÄòConfig::new‚Äô.  Listing 12-7 shows the changes we
need to make.

fn main() {
    let args: Vec<String> = env::args().collect();

    let config = Config::new(&args);

    // --snip--
}

// --snip--

impl Config {
    fn new(args: &[String]) -> Config {
        let query = args[1].clone();
        let file_path = args[2].clone();

        Config { query, file_path }
