impl Config {
    fn build(args: &[String]) -> Result<Config, &'static str> {
        if args.len() < 3 {
            return Err("not enough arguments");
        }

        let query = args[1].clone();
        let file_path = args[2].clone();

        Ok(Config { query, file_path })
    }
}

Our ‚Äòbuild‚Äô function returns a ‚ÄòResult‚Äô with a ‚ÄòConfig‚Äô instance in the
success case and a string literal in the error case.  Our error values
will always be string literals that have the ‚Äò'static‚Äô lifetime.

We've made two changes in the body of the function: instead of calling
‚Äòpanic!‚Äô when the user doesn't pass enough arguments, we now return an
‚ÄòErr‚Äô value, and we've wrapped the ‚ÄòConfig‚Äô return value in an ‚ÄòOk‚Äô.
These changes make the function conform to its new type signature.

Returning an ‚ÄòErr‚Äô value from ‚ÄòConfig::build‚Äô allows the ‚Äòmain‚Äô function
to handle the ‚ÄòResult‚Äô value returned from the ‚Äòbuild‚Äô function and exit
the process more cleanly in the error case.  Calling ‚ÄòConfig::build‚Äô and
Handling Errors To handle the error case and print a user-friendly
message, we need to update ‚Äòmain‚Äô to handle the ‚ÄòResult‚Äô being returned
by ‚ÄòConfig::build‚Äô, as shown in Listing 12-10.  We'll also take the
responsibility of exiting the command line tool with a nonzero error
code away from ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô and instead implement it by hand.  A nonzero
exit status is a convention to signal to the process that called our
program that the program exited with an error state.

use std::process;

fn main() {
