need to make to the signature and body of ‚Äòrun‚Äô.

use std::error::Error;

// --snip--

fn run(config: Config) -> Result<(), Box<dyn Error>> {
    let contents = fs::read_to_string(config.file_path)?;

    println!("With text:\n{contents}");

    Ok(())
}

We've made three significant changes here.  First, we changed the return
type of the ‚Äòrun‚Äô function to ‚ÄòResult<(), Box<dyn Error>>‚Äô.  This
function previously returned the unit type, ‚Äò()‚Äô, and we keep that as
the value returned in the ‚ÄòOk‚Äô case.

For the error type, we used the ‚Äòtrait object‚Äô ‚ÄòBox<dyn Error>‚Äô (and
we've brought ‚Äòstd::error::Error‚Äô into scope with a ‚Äòuse‚Äô statement at
the top).  We'll cover trait objects in *note Chapter 18:
Object-Oriented Programming Features of Rust.  For now, just know that
‚ÄòBox<dyn Error>‚Äô means the function will return a type that implements
the ‚ÄòError‚Äô trait, but we don't have to specify what particular type the
return value will be.  This gives us flexibility to return error values
that may be of different types in different error cases.  The ‚Äòdyn‚Äô
keyword is short for ‚Äòdynamic‚Äô.

Second, we've removed the call to ‚Äòexpect‚Äô in favor of the ‚Äò?‚Äô operator,
as we talked about in *note Chapter 9:
#book__pandoc__texi__src__ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-resultmd__a-shortcut-for-propagating-errors-the--operator.
Rather than ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô on an error, ‚Äò?‚Äô will return the error value from
the current function for the caller to handle.

Third, the ‚Äòrun‚Äô function now returns an ‚ÄòOk‚Äô value in the success case.
We've declared the ‚Äòrun‚Äô function's success type as ‚Äò()‚Äô in the
signature, which means we need to wrap the unit type value in the ‚ÄòOk‚Äô
