The ‚Äòsearch_case_insensitive‚Äô function, shown in Listing 12-21, will be
almost the same as the ‚Äòsearch‚Äô function.  The only difference is that
we'll lowercase the ‚Äòquery‚Äô and each ‚Äòline‚Äô so that whatever the case of
the input arguments, they'll be the same case when we check whether the
line contains the query.

pub fn search_case_insensitive<'a>(
    query: &str,
    contents: &'a str,
) -> Vec<&'a str> {
    let query = query.to_lowercase();
    let mut results = Vec::new();

    for line in contents.lines() {
        if line.to_lowercase().contains(&query) {
            results.push(line);
        }
    }

    results
}

First we lowercase the ‚Äòquery‚Äô string and store it in a new variable
with the same name, shadowing the original.  Calling ‚Äòto_lowercase‚Äô on
the query is necessary so that no matter whether the user's query is
‚Äò"rust"‚Äô, ‚Äò"RUST"‚Äô, ‚Äò"Rust"‚Äô, or ‚Äò"rUsT"‚Äô, we'll treat the query as if
it were ‚Äò"rust"‚Äô and be insensitive to the case.  While ‚Äòto_lowercase‚Äô
will handle basic Unicode, it won't be 100% accurate.  If we were
writing a real application, we'd want to do a bit more work here, but
this section is about environment variables, not Unicode, so we'll leave
it at that here.

Note that ‚Äòquery‚Äô is now a ‚ÄòString‚Äô rather than a string slice because
calling ‚Äòto_lowercase‚Äô creates new data rather than referencing existing
data.  Say the query is ‚Äò"rUsT"‚Äô, as an example: that string slice
doesn't contain a lowercase ‚Äòu‚Äô or ‚Äòt‚Äô for us to use, so we have to
allocate a new ‚ÄòString‚Äô containing ‚Äò"rust"‚Äô.  When we pass ‚Äòquery‚Äô as an
argument to the ‚Äòcontains‚Äô method now, we need to add an ampersand
because the signature of ‚Äòcontains‚Äô is defined to take a string slice.

