Every so often, our t-shirt company gives away an exclusive,
limited-edition shirt to someone on our mailing list as a promotion.
People on the mailing list can optionally add their favorite color to
their profile.  If the person chosen for a free shirt has their favorite
color set, they get that color shirt.  If the person hasn't specified a
favorite color, they get whatever color the company currently has the
most of.

There are many ways to implement this.  For this example, we're going to
use an enum called ‚ÄòShirtColor‚Äô that has the variants ‚ÄòRed‚Äô and ‚ÄòBlue‚Äô
(limiting the number of colors available for simplicity).  We represent
the company's inventory with an ‚ÄòInventory‚Äô struct that has a field
named ‚Äòshirts‚Äô that contains a ‚ÄòVec<ShirtColor>‚Äô representing the shirt
colors currently in stock.  The method ‚Äògiveaway‚Äô defined on ‚ÄòInventory‚Äô
gets the optional shirt color preference of the free shirt winner, and
returns the shirt color the person will get.  This setup is shown in
Listing 13-1:

enum ShirtColor {
    Red,
    Blue,
}

struct Inventory {
    shirts: Vec<ShirtColor>,
}

impl Inventory {
    fn giveaway(&self, user_preference: Option<ShirtColor>) -> ShirtColor {
        user_preference.unwrap_or_else(|| self.most_stocked())
    }

    fn most_stocked(&self) -> ShirtColor {
        let mut num_red = 0;
        let mut num_blue = 0;

        for color in &self.shirts {
            match color {
                ShirtColor::Red => num_red += 1,
                ShirtColor::Blue => num_blue += 1,
            }
        }
        if num_red > num_blue {
            ShirtColor::Red
        } else {
            ShirtColor::Blue
        }
    }
}

fn main() {
    let store = Inventory {
        shirts: vec![ShirtColor::Blue, ShirtColor::Red, ShirtColor::Blue],
    };

    let user_pref1 = Some(ShirtColor::Red);
    let giveaway1 = store.giveaway(user_pref1);
    println!(
        "The user with preference {:?} gets {:?}",
        user_pref1, giveaway1
    );

    let user_pref2 = None;
    let giveaway2 = store.giveaway(user_pref2);
    println!(
        "The user with preference {:?} gets {:?}",
        user_pref2, giveaway2
    );
}

The ‚Äòstore‚Äô defined in ‚Äòmain‚Äô has two blue shirts and one red shirt
remaining to distribute for this limited-edition promotion.  We call the
‚Äògiveaway‚Äô method for a user with a preference for a red shirt and a
user without any preference.

Again, this code could be implemented in many ways, and here, to focus
on closures, we've stuck to concepts you've already learned except for
the body of the ‚Äògiveaway‚Äô method that uses a closure.  In the
‚Äògiveaway‚Äô method, we get the user preference as a parameter of type
‚ÄòOption<ShirtColor>‚Äô and call the ‚Äòunwrap_or_else‚Äô method on
‚Äòuser_preference‚Äô.  The ‚Äòunwrap_or_else‚Äô method on ‚ÄòOption<T>‚Äô
(https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/../std/option/enum.Option.html) is
defined by the standard library.  It takes one argument: a closure
without any arguments that returns a value ‚ÄòT‚Äô (the same type stored in
the ‚ÄòSome‚Äô variant of the ‚ÄòOption<T>‚Äô, in this case ‚ÄòShirtColor‚Äô).  If
the ‚ÄòOption<T>‚Äô is the ‚ÄòSome‚Äô variant, ‚Äòunwrap_or_else‚Äô returns the
value from within the ‚ÄòSome‚Äô.  If the ‚ÄòOption<T>‚Äô is the ‚ÄòNone‚Äô variant,
‚Äòunwrap_or_else‚Äô calls the closure and returns the value returned by the
closure.

We specify the closure expression ‚Äò|| self.most_stocked()‚Äô as the
argument to ‚Äòunwrap_or_else‚Äô.  This is a closure that takes no
parameters itself (if the closure had parameters, they would appear
between the two vertical bars).  The body of the closure calls
‚Äòself.most_stocked()‚Äô.  We're defining the closure here, and the
implementation of ‚Äòunwrap_or_else‚Äô will evaluate the closure later if
the result is needed.

