16.1.1.3 Moving Captured Values Out of Closures and the ‚ÄòFn‚Äô
............................................................

Traits Once a closure has captured a reference or captured ownership of
a value from the environment where the closure is defined (thus
affecting what, if anything, is moved ‚Äòinto‚Äô the closure), the code in
the body of the closure defines what happens to the references or values
when the closure is evaluated later (thus affecting what, if anything,
is moved ‚Äòout of‚Äô the closure).  A closure body can do any of the
following: move a captured value out of the closure, mutate the captured
value, neither move nor mutate the value, or capture nothing from the
environment to begin with.

The way a closure captures and handles values from the environment
affects which traits the closure implements, and traits are how
functions and structs can specify what kinds of closures they can use.
Closures will automatically implement one, two, or all three of these
‚ÄòFn‚Äô traits, in an additive fashion, depending on how the closure's body
handles the values:

  1. ‚ÄòFnOnce‚Äô applies to closures that can be called once.  All closures
     implement at least this trait, because all closures can be called.
     A closure that moves captured values out of its body will only
     implement ‚ÄòFnOnce‚Äô and none of the other ‚ÄòFn‚Äô traits, because it
     can only be called once.
  2. ‚ÄòFnMut‚Äô applies to closures that don't move captured values out of
     their body, but that might mutate the captured values.  These
     closures can be called more than once.
  3. ‚ÄòFn‚Äô applies to closures that don't move captured values out of
     their body and that don't mutate captured values, as well as
     closures that capture nothing from their environment.  These
     closures can be called more than once without mutating their
     environment, which is important in cases such as calling a closure
     multiple times concurrently.

Let's look at the definition of the ‚Äòunwrap_or_else‚Äô method on
‚ÄòOption<T>‚Äô that we used in Listing 13-1:

impl<T> Option<T> {
    pub fn unwrap_or_else<F>(self, f: F) -> T
    where
        F: FnOnce() -> T
    {
        match self {
            Some(x) => x,
            None => f(),
        }
    }
}

Recall that ‚ÄòT‚Äô is the generic type representing the type of the value
in the ‚ÄòSome‚Äô variant of an ‚ÄòOption‚Äô.  That type ‚ÄòT‚Äô is also the return
type of the ‚Äòunwrap_or_else‚Äô function: code that calls ‚Äòunwrap_or_else‚Äô
on an ‚ÄòOption<String>‚Äô, for example, will get a ‚ÄòString‚Äô.

Next, notice that the ‚Äòunwrap_or_else‚Äô function has the additional
generic type parameter ‚ÄòF‚Äô.  The ‚ÄòF‚Äô type is the type of the parameter
named ‚Äòf‚Äô, which is the closure we provide when calling
‚Äòunwrap_or_else‚Äô.

The trait bound specified on the generic type ‚ÄòF‚Äô is ‚ÄòFnOnce() -> T‚Äô,
which means ‚ÄòF‚Äô must be able to be called once, take no arguments, and
return a ‚ÄòT‚Äô.  Using ‚ÄòFnOnce‚Äô in the trait bound expresses the
constraint that ‚Äòunwrap_or_else‚Äô is only going to call ‚Äòf‚Äô at most one
time.  In the body of ‚Äòunwrap_or_else‚Äô, we can see that if the ‚ÄòOption‚Äô
is ‚ÄòSome‚Äô, ‚Äòf‚Äô won't be called.  If the ‚ÄòOption‚Äô is ‚ÄòNone‚Äô, ‚Äòf‚Äô will be
called once.  Because all closures implement ‚ÄòFnOnce‚Äô, ‚Äòunwrap_or_else‚Äô
accepts all three kinds of closures and is as flexible as it can be.

Note: Functions can implement all three of the ‚ÄòFn‚Äô traits too.  If what
we want to do doesn't require capturing a value from the environment, we
can use the name of a function rather than a closure where we need
something that implements one of the ‚ÄòFn‚Äô traits.  For example, on an
‚ÄòOption<Vec<T>>‚Äô value, we could call ‚Äòunwrap_or_else(Vec::new)‚Äô to get
a new, empty vector if the value is ‚ÄòNone‚Äô.

Now let's look at the standard library method ‚Äòsort_by_key‚Äô defined on
slices, to see how that differs from ‚Äòunwrap_or_else‚Äô and why
‚Äòsort_by_key‚Äô uses ‚ÄòFnMut‚Äô instead of ‚ÄòFnOnce‚Äô for the trait bound.  The
closure gets one argument in the form of a reference to the current item
in the slice being considered, and returns a value of type ‚ÄòK‚Äô that can
be ordered.  This function is useful when you want to sort a slice by a
particular attribute of each item.  In Listing 13-7, we have a list of
‚ÄòRectangle‚Äô instances and we use ‚Äòsort_by_key‚Äô to order them by their
‚Äòwidth‚Äô attribute from low to high:

struct Rectangle {
    width: u32,
    height: u32,
}

fn main() {
    let mut list = [
        Rectangle { width: 10, height: 1 },
        Rectangle { width: 3, height: 5 },
        Rectangle { width: 7, height: 12 },
    ];

    list.sort_by_key(|r| r.width);
    println!("{list:#?}");
}

