16.1.2.1 The ‚ÄòIterator‚Äô Trait and the ‚Äònext‚Äô Method
...................................................

All iterators implement a trait named ‚ÄòIterator‚Äô that is defined in the
standard library.  The definition of the trait looks like this:

pub trait Iterator {
    type Item;

    fn next(&mut self) -> Option<Self::Item>;

    // methods with default implementations elided
}

Notice this definition uses some new syntax: ‚Äòtype Item‚Äô and
‚ÄòSelf::Item‚Äô, which are defining an ‚Äòassociated type‚Äô with this trait.
We'll talk about associated types in depth in Chapter 20.  For now, all
you need to know is that this code says implementing the ‚ÄòIterator‚Äô
trait requires that you also define an ‚ÄòItem‚Äô type, and this ‚ÄòItem‚Äô type
is used in the return type of the ‚Äònext‚Äô method.  In other words, the
‚ÄòItem‚Äô type will be the type returned from the iterator.

The ‚ÄòIterator‚Äô trait only requires implementors to define one method:
the ‚Äònext‚Äô method, which returns one item of the iterator at a time
wrapped in ‚ÄòSome‚Äô and, when iteration is over, returns ‚ÄòNone‚Äô.

We can call the ‚Äònext‚Äô method on iterators directly; Listing 13-12
demonstrates what values are returned from repeated calls to ‚Äònext‚Äô on
the iterator created from the vector.

    fn iterator_demonstration() {
        let v1 = vec![1, 2, 3];

        let mut v1_iter = v1.iter();

        assert_eq!(v1_iter.next(), Some(&1));
        assert_eq!(v1_iter.next(), Some(&2));
        assert_eq!(v1_iter.next(), Some(&3));
        assert_eq!(v1_iter.next(), None);
    }

Note that we needed to make ‚Äòv1_iter‚Äô mutable: calling the ‚Äònext‚Äô method
on an iterator changes internal state that the iterator uses to keep
track of where it is in the sequence.  In other words, this code
‚Äòconsumes‚Äô, or uses up, the iterator.  Each call to ‚Äònext‚Äô eats up an
item from the iterator.  We didn't need to make ‚Äòv1_iter‚Äô mutable when
we used a ‚Äòfor‚Äô loop because the loop took ownership of ‚Äòv1_iter‚Äô and
made it mutable behind the scenes.

Also note that the values we get from the calls to ‚Äònext‚Äô are immutable
references to the values in the vector.  The ‚Äòiter‚Äô method produces an
iterator over immutable references.  If we want to create an iterator
that takes ownership of ‚Äòv1‚Äô and returns owned values, we can call
‚Äòinto_iter‚Äô instead of ‚Äòiter‚Äô.  Similarly, if we want to iterate over
mutable references, we can call ‚Äòiter_mut‚Äô instead of ‚Äòiter‚Äô.


