specified never gets called.  The warning reminds us why: iterator
adapters are lazy, and we need to consume the iterator here.

To fix this warning and consume the iterator, we'll use the ‚Äòcollect‚Äô
method, which we used in Chapter 12 with ‚Äòenv::args‚Äô in Listing 12-1.
This method consumes the iterator and collects the resulting values into
a collection data type.

In Listing 13-15, we collect the results of iterating over the iterator
that's returned from the call to ‚Äòmap‚Äô into a vector.  This vector will
end up containing each item from the original vector incremented by 1.

    let v1: Vec<i32> = vec![1, 2, 3];

    let v2: Vec<_> = v1.iter().map(|x| x + 1).collect();

    assert_eq!(v2, vec![2, 3, 4]);

Because ‚Äòmap‚Äô takes a closure, we can specify any operation we want to
perform on each item.  This is a great example of how closures let you
customize some behavior while reusing the iteration behavior that the
‚ÄòIterator‚Äô trait provides.

You can chain multiple calls to iterator adapters to perform complex
actions in a readable way.  But because all iterators are lazy, you have
to call one of the consuming adapter methods to get results from calls
to iterator adapters.


