16.1.2.4 Using Closures that Capture Their Environment
......................................................

Many iterator adapters take closures as arguments, and commonly the
closures we'll specify as arguments to iterator adapters will be
closures that capture their environment.

For this example, we'll use the ‚Äòfilter‚Äô method that takes a closure.
The closure gets an item from the iterator and returns a ‚Äòbool‚Äô.  If the
closure returns ‚Äòtrue‚Äô, the value will be included in the iteration
produced by ‚Äòfilter‚Äô.  If the closure returns ‚Äòfalse‚Äô, the value won't
be included.

In Listing 13-16, we use ‚Äòfilter‚Äô with a closure that captures the
‚Äòshoe_size‚Äô variable from its environment to iterate over a collection
of ‚ÄòShoe‚Äô struct instances.  It will return only shoes that are the
specified size.

struct Shoe {
    size: u32,
    style: String,
}

fn shoes_in_size(shoes: Vec<Shoe>, shoe_size: u32) -> Vec<Shoe> {
    shoes.into_iter().filter(|s| s.size == shoe_size).collect()
}

mod tests {
    use super::*;

    fn filters_by_size() {
        let shoes = vec![
            Shoe {
                size: 10,
                style: String::from("sneaker"),
            },
            Shoe {
                size: 13,
                style: String::from("sandal"),
            },
            Shoe {
                size: 10,
                style: String::from("boot"),
            },
        ];

        let in_my_size = shoes_in_size(shoes, 10);

        assert_eq!(
            in_my_size,
            vec![
                Shoe {
                    size: 10,
                    style: String::from("sneaker")
                },
                Shoe {
                    size: 10,
                    style: String::from("boot")
                },
            ]
        );
    }
}

The ‚Äòshoes_in_size‚Äô function takes ownership of a vector of shoes and a
shoe size as parameters.  It returns a vector containing only shoes of
the specified size.

In the body of ‚Äòshoes_in_size‚Äô, we call ‚Äòinto_iter‚Äô to create an
iterator that takes ownership of the vector.  Then we call ‚Äòfilter‚Äô to
adapt that iterator into a new iterator that only contains elements for
which the closure returns ‚Äòtrue‚Äô.

The closure captures the ‚Äòshoe_size‚Äô parameter from the environment and
compares the value with each shoe's size, keeping only shoes of the size
specified.  Finally, calling ‚Äòcollect‚Äô gathers the values returned by
the adapted iterator into a vector that's returned by the function.

The test shows that when we call ‚Äòshoes_in_size‚Äô, we get back only shoes
that have the same size as the value we specified.


