17.1 Customizing Builds with Release Profiles
=============================================

In Rust, ‚Äòrelease profiles‚Äô are predefined and customizable profiles
with different configurations that allow a programmer to have more
control over various options for compiling code.  Each profile is
configured independently of the others.

Cargo has two main profiles: the ‚Äòdev‚Äô profile Cargo uses when you run
‚Äòcargo build‚Äô and the ‚Äòrelease‚Äô profile Cargo uses when you run ‚Äòcargo
build --release‚Äô.  The ‚Äòdev‚Äô profile is defined with good defaults for
development, and the ‚Äòrelease‚Äô profile has good defaults for release
builds.

These profile names might be familiar from the output of your builds:

$ cargo build
    Finished `dev` profile [unoptimized + debuginfo] target(s) in 0.00s
$ cargo build --release
    Finished `release` profile [optimized] target(s) in 0.32s

The ‚Äòdev‚Äô and ‚Äòrelease‚Äô are these different profiles used by the
compiler.

Cargo has default settings for each of the profiles that apply when you
haven't explicitly added any ‚Äò[profile.*]‚Äô sections in the project's
‚ÄòCargo.toml‚Äô file.  By adding ‚Äò[profile.*]‚Äô sections for any profile you
want to customize, you override any subset of the default settings.  For
example, here are the default values for the ‚Äòopt-level‚Äô setting for the
‚Äòdev‚Äô and ‚Äòrelease‚Äô profiles:

Filename: Cargo.toml

[profile.dev]
opt-level = 0

[profile.release]
opt-level = 3

The ‚Äòopt-level‚Äô setting controls the number of optimizations Rust will
apply to your code, with a range of 0 to 3.  Applying more optimizations
extends compiling time, so if you're in development and compiling your
code often, you'll want fewer optimizations to compile faster even if
the resulting code runs slower.  The default ‚Äòopt-level‚Äô for ‚Äòdev‚Äô is
therefore ‚Äò0‚Äô.  When you're ready to release your code, it's best to
spend more time compiling.  You'll only compile in release mode once,
but you'll run the compiled program many times, so release mode trades
longer compile time for code that runs faster.  That is why the default
‚Äòopt-level‚Äô for the ‚Äòrelease‚Äô profile is ‚Äò3‚Äô.

You can override a default setting by adding a different value for it in
‚ÄòCargo.toml‚Äô.  For example, if we want to use optimization level 1 in
the development profile, we can add these two lines to our project's
‚ÄòCargo.toml‚Äô file:

Filename: Cargo.toml

[profile.dev]
opt-level = 1

This code overrides the default setting of ‚Äò0‚Äô.  Now when we run ‚Äòcargo
build‚Äô, Cargo will use the defaults for the ‚Äòdev‚Äô profile plus our
customization to ‚Äòopt-level‚Äô.  Because we set ‚Äòopt-level‚Äô to ‚Äò1‚Äô, Cargo
will apply more optimizations than the default, but not as many as in a
release build.

For the full list of configuration options and defaults for each
profile, see Cargo's documentation
(https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/reference/profiles.html).


