17.1.1.7 Deprecating Versions from Crates.io with
.................................................

‚Äòcargo yank‚Äô Although you can't remove previous versions of a crate, you
can prevent any future projects from adding them as a new dependency.
This is useful when a crate version is broken for one reason or another.
In such situations, Cargo supports ‚Äòyanking‚Äô a crate version.

Yanking a version prevents new projects from depending on that version
while allowing all existing projects that depend on it to continue.
Essentially, a yank means that all projects with a ‚ÄòCargo.lock‚Äô will not
break, and any future ‚ÄòCargo.lock‚Äô files generated will not use the
yanked version.

To yank a version of a crate, in the directory of the crate that you've
previously published, run ‚Äòcargo yank‚Äô and specify which version you
want to yank.  For example, if we've published a crate named
‚Äòguessing_game‚Äô version 1.0.1 and we want to yank it, in the project
directory for ‚Äòguessing_game‚Äô we'd run:

$ cargo yank --vers 1.0.1
    Updating crates.io index
        Yank guessing_game@1.0.1

By adding ‚Äò--undo‚Äô to the command, you can also undo a yank and allow
projects to start depending on a version again:

$ cargo yank --vers 1.0.1 --undo
    Updating crates.io index
