18.1 Using ‚ÄòBox<T>‚Äô to Point to Data on the Heap
================================================

The most straightforward smart pointer is a ‚Äòbox‚Äô, whose type is written
‚ÄòBox<T>‚Äô.  Boxes allow you to store data on the heap rather than the
stack.  What remains on the stack is the pointer to the heap data.
Refer to Chapter 4 to review the difference between the stack and the
heap.

Boxes don't have performance overhead, other than storing their data on
the heap instead of on the stack.  But they don't have many extra
capabilities either.  You'll use them most often in these situations:

   ‚Ä¢ When you have a type whose size can't be known at compile time and
     you want to use a value of that type in a context that requires an
     exact size
   ‚Ä¢ When you have a large amount of data and you want to transfer
     ownership but ensure the data won't be copied when you do so
   ‚Ä¢ When you want to own a value and you care only that it's a type
     that implements a particular trait rather than being of a specific
     type

We'll demonstrate the first situation in the *note ‚ÄúEnabling Recursive
Types with Boxes‚Äù: Enabling Recursive Types with Boxes. section.  In the
second case, transferring ownership of a large amount of data can take a
long time because the data is copied around on the stack.  To improve
performance in this situation, we can store the large amount of data on
the heap in a box.  Then, only the small amount of pointer data is
copied around on the stack, while the data it references stays in one
place on the heap.  The third case is known as a ‚Äòtrait object‚Äô, and
Chapter 18 devotes an entire section, *note ‚ÄúUsing Trait Objects That
Allow for Values of Different Types‚Äù: Using Trait Objects That Allow for
Values of Different Types. just to that topic.  So what you learn here
you'll apply again in Chapter 18!

