18.1.1 Using a ‚ÄòBox<T>‚Äô to Store Data on the Heap
-------------------------------------------------

Before we discuss the heap storage use case for ‚ÄòBox<T>‚Äô, we'll cover
the syntax and how to interact with values stored within a ‚ÄòBox<T>‚Äô.

Listing 15-1 shows how to use a box to store an ‚Äòi32‚Äô value on the heap:

fn main() {
    let b = Box::new(5);
    println!("b = {b}");
}

We define the variable ‚Äòb‚Äô to have the value of a ‚ÄòBox‚Äô that points to
the value ‚Äò5‚Äô, which is allocated on the heap.  This program will print
‚Äòb = 5‚Äô; in this case, we can access the data in the box similar to how
we would if this data were on the stack.  Just like any owned value,
when a box goes out of scope, as ‚Äòb‚Äô does at the end of ‚Äòmain‚Äô, it will
be deallocated.  The deallocation happens both for the box (stored on
the stack) and the data it points to (stored on the heap).

Putting a single value on the heap isn't very useful, so you won't use
boxes by themselves in this way very often.  Having values like a single
‚Äòi32‚Äô on the stack, where they're stored by default, is more appropriate
in the majority of situations.  Let's look at a case where boxes allow
us to define types that we wouldn't be allowed to if we didn't have
