18.1.1.1 Enabling Recursive Types with Boxes
............................................

A value of ‚Äòrecursive type‚Äô can have another value of the same type as
part of itself.  Recursive types pose an issue because at compile time
Rust needs to know how much space a type takes up.  However, the nesting
of values of recursive types could theoretically continue infinitely, so
Rust can't know how much space the value needs.  Because boxes have a
known size, we can enable recursive types by inserting a box in the
recursive type definition.

As an example of a recursive type, let's explore the ‚Äòcons list‚Äô.  This
is a data type commonly found in functional programming languages.  The
cons list type we'll define is straightforward except for the recursion;
therefore, the concepts in the example we'll work with will be useful
any time you get into more complex situations involving recursive types.
More Information About the Cons List A ‚Äòcons list‚Äô is a data structure
that comes from the Lisp programming language and its dialects and is
made up of nested pairs, and is the Lisp version of a linked list.  Its
name comes from the ‚Äòcons‚Äô function (short for ‚Äúconstruct function‚Äù) in
Lisp that constructs a new pair from its two arguments.  By calling
‚Äòcons‚Äô on a pair consisting of a value and another pair, we can
construct cons lists made up of recursive pairs.

For example, here's a pseudocode representation of a cons list
containing the list 1, 2, 3 with each pair in parentheses:

(1, (2, (3, Nil)))

Each item in a cons list contains two elements: the value of the current
item and the next item.  The last item in the list contains only a value
called ‚ÄòNil‚Äô without a next item.  A cons list is produced by
recursively calling the ‚Äòcons‚Äô function.  The canonical name to denote
the base case of the recursion is ‚ÄòNil‚Äô.  Note that this is not the same
as the ‚Äúnull‚Äù or ‚Äúnil‚Äù concept in Chapter 6, which is an invalid or
absent value.

The cons list isn't a commonly used data structure in Rust.  Most of the
time when you have a list of items in Rust, ‚ÄòVec<T>‚Äô is a better choice
to use.  Other, more complex recursive data types ‚Äòare‚Äô useful in
various situations, but by starting with the cons list in this chapter,
we can explore how boxes let us define a recursive data type without
much distraction.

Listing 15-2 contains an enum definition for a cons list.  Note that
this code won't compile yet because the ‚ÄòList‚Äô type doesn't have a known
size, which we'll demonstrate.

enum List {
    Cons(i32, List),
    Nil,
}

Note: We're implementing a cons list that holds only ‚Äòi32‚Äô values for
the purposes of this example.  We could have implemented it using
generics, as we discussed in Chapter 10, to define a cons list type that
could store values of any type.

Using the ‚ÄòList‚Äô type to store the list ‚Äò1, 2, 3‚Äô would look like the
code in Listing 15-3:

use crate::List::{Cons, Nil};

fn main() {
    let list = Cons(1, Cons(2, Cons(3, Nil)));
}

The first ‚ÄòCons‚Äô value holds ‚Äò1‚Äô and another ‚ÄòList‚Äô value.  This ‚ÄòList‚Äô
value is another ‚ÄòCons‚Äô value that holds ‚Äò2‚Äô and another ‚ÄòList‚Äô value.
This ‚ÄòList‚Äô value is one more ‚ÄòCons‚Äô value that holds ‚Äò3‚Äô and a ‚ÄòList‚Äô
value, which is finally ‚ÄòNil‚Äô, the non-recursive variant that signals
the end of the list.

If we try to compile the code in Listing 15-3, we get the error shown in
