The error shows this type ‚Äúhas infinite size.‚Äù The reason is that we've
defined ‚ÄòList‚Äô with a variant that is recursive: it holds another value
of itself directly.  As a result, Rust can't figure out how much space
it needs to store a ‚ÄòList‚Äô value.  Let's break down why we get this
error.  First, we'll look at how Rust decides how much space it needs to
store a value of a non-recursive type.  Computing the Size of a
Non-Recursive Type Recall the ‚ÄòMessage‚Äô enum we defined in Listing 6-2
when we discussed enum definitions in Chapter 6:

enum Message {
    Quit,
    Move { x: i32, y: i32 },
    Write(String),
    ChangeColor(i32, i32, i32),
}

To determine how much space to allocate for a ‚ÄòMessage‚Äô value, Rust goes
through each of the variants to see which variant needs the most space.
Rust sees that ‚ÄòMessage::Quit‚Äô doesn't need any space, ‚ÄòMessage::Move‚Äô
needs enough space to store two ‚Äòi32‚Äô values, and so forth.  Because
only one variant will be used, the most space a ‚ÄòMessage‚Äô value will
need is the space it would take to store the largest of its variants.

Contrast this with what happens when Rust tries to determine how much
space a recursive type like the ‚ÄòList‚Äô enum in Listing 15-2 needs.  The
compiler starts by looking at the ‚ÄòCons‚Äô variant, which holds a value of
type ‚Äòi32‚Äô and a value of type ‚ÄòList‚Äô.  Therefore, ‚ÄòCons‚Äô needs an
amount of space equal to the size of an ‚Äòi32‚Äô plus the size of a ‚ÄòList‚Äô.
To figure out how much memory the ‚ÄòList‚Äô type needs, the compiler looks
at the variants, starting with the ‚ÄòCons‚Äô variant.  The ‚ÄòCons‚Äô variant
holds a value of type ‚Äòi32‚Äô and a value of type ‚ÄòList‚Äô, and this process
continues infinitely, as shown in Figure 15-1.

Figure 15-1: An infinite ‚ÄòList‚Äô consisting of infinite ‚ÄòCons‚Äô variants
Using ‚ÄòBox<T>‚Äô to Get a Recursive Type with a Known Size Because Rust
can't figure out how much space to allocate for recursively defined
types, the compiler gives an error with this helpful suggestion:

help: insert some indirection (e.g., a `Box`, `Rc`, or `&`) to break the cycle
  |
2 |     Cons(i32, Box<List>),
  |               ++++    +

In this suggestion, ‚Äúindirection‚Äù means that instead of storing a value
directly, we should change the data structure to store the value
indirectly by storing a pointer to the value instead.

Because a ‚ÄòBox<T>‚Äô is a pointer, Rust always knows how much space a
‚ÄòBox<T>‚Äô needs: a pointer's size doesn't change based on the amount of
data it's pointing to.  This means we can put a ‚ÄòBox<T>‚Äô inside the
‚ÄòCons‚Äô variant instead of another ‚ÄòList‚Äô value directly.  The ‚ÄòBox<T>‚Äô
will point to the next ‚ÄòList‚Äô value that will be on the heap rather than
inside the ‚ÄòCons‚Äô variant.  Conceptually, we still have a list, created
with lists holding other lists, but this implementation is now more like
placing the items next to one another rather than inside one another.

We can change the definition of the ‚ÄòList‚Äô enum in Listing 15-2 and the
usage of the ‚ÄòList‚Äô in Listing 15-3 to the code in Listing 15-5, which
will compile:

enum List {
    Cons(i32, Box<List>),
    Nil,
}

use crate::List::{Cons, Nil};

fn main() {
    let list = Cons(1, Box::new(Cons(2, Box::new(Cons(3, Box::new(Nil))))));
}

The ‚ÄòCons‚Äô variant needs the size of an ‚Äòi32‚Äô plus the space to store
the box's pointer data.  The ‚ÄòNil‚Äô variant stores no values, so it needs
less space than the ‚ÄòCons‚Äô variant.  We now know that any ‚ÄòList‚Äô value
will take up the size of an ‚Äòi32‚Äô plus the size of a box's pointer data.
By using a box, we've broken the infinite, recursive chain, so the
compiler can figure out the size it needs to store a ‚ÄòList‚Äô value.
Figure 15-2 shows what the ‚ÄòCons‚Äô variant looks like now.

Figure 15-2: A ‚ÄòList‚Äô that is not infinitely sized because ‚ÄòCons‚Äô holds
a ‚ÄòBox‚Äô

Boxes provide only the indirection and heap allocation; they don't have
any other special capabilities, like those we'll see with the other
smart pointer types.  They also don't have the performance overhead that
these special capabilities incur, so they can be useful in cases like
the cons list where the indirection is the only feature we need.  We'll
look at more use cases for boxes in Chapter 18, too.

The ‚ÄòBox<T>‚Äô type is a smart pointer because it implements the ‚ÄòDeref‚Äô
trait, which allows ‚ÄòBox<T>‚Äô values to be treated like references.  When
a ‚ÄòBox<T>‚Äô value goes out of scope, the heap data that the box is
pointing to is cleaned up as well because of the ‚ÄòDrop‚Äô trait
implementation.  These two traits will be even more important to the
functionality provided by the other smart pointer types we'll discuss in
the rest of this chapter.  Let's explore these two traits in more
detail.


