A regular reference is a type of pointer, and one way to think of a
pointer is as an arrow to a value stored somewhere else.  In Listing
15-6, we create a reference to an ‚Äòi32‚Äô value and then use the
dereference operator to follow the reference to the value:

fn main() {
    let x = 5;
    let y = &x;

    assert_eq!(5, x);
    assert_eq!(5, *y);
}

The variable ‚Äòx‚Äô holds an ‚Äòi32‚Äô value ‚Äò5‚Äô.  We set ‚Äòy‚Äô equal to a
reference to ‚Äòx‚Äô.  We can assert that ‚Äòx‚Äô is equal to ‚Äò5‚Äô.  However, if
we want to make an assertion about the value in ‚Äòy‚Äô, we have to use ‚Äò*y‚Äô
to follow the reference to the value it's pointing to (hence
‚Äòdereference‚Äô) so the compiler can compare the actual value.  Once we
dereference ‚Äòy‚Äô, we have access to the integer value ‚Äòy‚Äô is pointing to
that we can compare with ‚Äò5‚Äô.

