‚ÄòDeref‚Äô Trait As discussed in the *note ‚ÄúImplementing a Trait on a
Type‚Äù: Implementing a Trait on a Type. section of Chapter 10, to
implement a trait, we need to provide implementations for the trait's
required methods.  The ‚ÄòDeref‚Äô trait, provided by the standard library,
requires us to implement one method named ‚Äòderef‚Äô that borrows ‚Äòself‚Äô
and returns a reference to the inner data.  Listing 15-10 contains an
implementation of ‚ÄòDeref‚Äô to add to the definition of ‚ÄòMyBox‚Äô:

use std::ops::Deref;

impl<T> Deref for MyBox<T> {
    type Target = T;

    fn deref(&self) -> &Self::Target {
        &self.0
    }
}

The ‚Äòtype Target = T;‚Äô syntax defines an associated type for the ‚ÄòDeref‚Äô
trait to use.  Associated types are a slightly different way of
declaring a generic parameter, but you don't need to worry about them
for now; we'll cover them in more detail in Chapter 20.

We fill in the body of the ‚Äòderef‚Äô method with ‚Äò&self.0‚Äô so ‚Äòderef‚Äô
returns a reference to the value we want to access with the ‚Äò*‚Äô
operator; recall from the *note ‚ÄúUsing Tuple Structs without Named
Fields to Create Different Types‚Äù: Using Tuple Structs Without Named
Fields to Create Different Types. section of Chapter 5 that ‚Äò.0‚Äô
accesses the first value in a tuple struct.  The ‚Äòmain‚Äô function in
Listing 15-9 that calls ‚Äò*‚Äô on the ‚ÄòMyBox<T>‚Äô value now compiles, and
the assertions pass!

Without the ‚ÄòDeref‚Äô trait, the compiler can only dereference ‚Äò&‚Äô
references.  The ‚Äòderef‚Äô method gives the compiler the ability to take a
value of any type that implements ‚ÄòDeref‚Äô and call the ‚Äòderef‚Äô method to
get a ‚Äò&‚Äô reference that it knows how to dereference.

When we entered ‚Äò*y‚Äô in Listing 15-9, behind the scenes Rust actually
ran this code:

*(y.deref())

Rust substitutes the ‚Äò*‚Äô operator with a call to the ‚Äòderef‚Äô method and
then a plain dereference so we don't have to think about whether or not
we need to call the ‚Äòderef‚Äô method.  This Rust feature lets us write
code that functions identically whether we have a regular reference or a
type that implements ‚ÄòDeref‚Äô.

The reason the ‚Äòderef‚Äô method returns a reference to a value, and that
the plain dereference outside the parentheses in ‚Äò*(y.deref())‚Äô is still
necessary, is to do with the ownership system.  If the ‚Äòderef‚Äô method
returned the value directly instead of a reference to the value, the
value would be moved out of ‚Äòself‚Äô.  We don't want to take ownership of
the inner value inside ‚ÄòMyBox<T>‚Äô in this case or in most cases where we
use the dereference operator.

Note that the ‚Äò*‚Äô operator is replaced with a call to the ‚Äòderef‚Äô method
and then a call to the ‚Äò*‚Äô operator just once, each time we use a ‚Äò*‚Äô in
our code.  Because the substitution of the ‚Äò*‚Äô operator does not recurse
infinitely, we end up with data of type ‚Äòi32‚Äô, which matches the ‚Äò5‚Äô in
‚Äòassert_eq!‚Äô in Listing 15-9.


