18.1.2.5 Implicit Deref Coercions with Functions and Methods
............................................................

‚ÄòDeref coercion‚Äô converts a reference to a type that implements the
‚ÄòDeref‚Äô trait into a reference to another type.  For example, deref
coercion can convert ‚Äò&String‚Äô to ‚Äò&str‚Äô because ‚ÄòString‚Äô implements the
‚ÄòDeref‚Äô trait such that it returns ‚Äò&str‚Äô.  Deref coercion is a
convenience Rust performs on arguments to functions and methods, and
works only on types that implement the ‚ÄòDeref‚Äô trait.  It happens
automatically when we pass a reference to a particular type's value as
an argument to a function or method that doesn't match the parameter
type in the function or method definition.  A sequence of calls to the
‚Äòderef‚Äô method converts the type we provided into the type the parameter
needs.

Deref coercion was added to Rust so that programmers writing function
and method calls don't need to add as many explicit references and
dereferences with ‚Äò&‚Äô and ‚Äò*‚Äô.  The deref coercion feature also lets us
write more code that can work for either references or smart pointers.

To see deref coercion in action, let's use the ‚ÄòMyBox<T>‚Äô type we
defined in Listing 15-8 as well as the implementation of ‚ÄòDeref‚Äô that we
added in Listing 15-10.  Listing 15-11 shows the definition of a
function that has a string slice parameter:

fn hello(name: &str) {
    println!("Hello, {name}!");
}

We can call the ‚Äòhello‚Äô function with a string slice as an argument,
such as ‚Äòhello("Rust");‚Äô for example.  Deref coercion makes it possible
to call ‚Äòhello‚Äô with a reference to a value of type ‚ÄòMyBox<String>‚Äô, as
shown in Listing 15-12:

fn main() {
    let m = MyBox::new(String::from("Rust"));
    hello(&m);
}

Here we're calling the ‚Äòhello‚Äô function with the argument ‚Äò&m‚Äô, which is
a reference to a ‚ÄòMyBox<String>‚Äô value.  Because we implemented the
‚ÄòDeref‚Äô trait on ‚ÄòMyBox<T>‚Äô in Listing 15-10, Rust can turn
‚Äò&MyBox<String>‚Äô into ‚Äò&String‚Äô by calling ‚Äòderef‚Äô.  The standard
library provides an implementation of ‚ÄòDeref‚Äô on ‚ÄòString‚Äô that returns a
string slice, and this is in the API documentation for ‚ÄòDeref‚Äô.  Rust
calls ‚Äòderef‚Äô again to turn the ‚Äò&String‚Äô into ‚Äò&str‚Äô, which matches the
‚Äòhello‚Äô function's definition.

If Rust didn't implement deref coercion, we would have to write the code
in Listing 15-13 instead of the code in Listing 15-12 to call ‚Äòhello‚Äô
with a value of type ‚Äò&MyBox<String>‚Äô.

fn main() {
    let m = MyBox::new(String::from("Rust"));
    hello(&(*m)[..]);
}

The ‚Äò(*m)‚Äô dereferences the ‚ÄòMyBox<String>‚Äô into a ‚ÄòString‚Äô.  Then the
‚Äò&‚Äô and ‚Äò[..]‚Äô take a string slice of the ‚ÄòString‚Äô that is equal to the
whole string to match the signature of ‚Äòhello‚Äô.  This code without deref
coercions is harder to read, write, and understand with all of these
symbols involved.  Deref coercion allows Rust to handle these
conversions for us automatically.

When the ‚ÄòDeref‚Äô trait is defined for the types involved, Rust will
analyze the types and use ‚ÄòDeref::deref‚Äô as many times as necessary to
get a reference to match the parameter's type.  The number of times that
‚ÄòDeref::deref‚Äô needs to be inserted is resolved at compile time, so
there is no runtime penalty for taking advantage of deref coercion!


