18.1.3 Running Code on Cleanup with the ‚ÄòDrop‚Äô Trait
----------------------------------------------------

The second trait important to the smart pointer pattern is ‚ÄòDrop‚Äô, which
lets you customize what happens when a value is about to go out of
scope.  You can provide an implementation for the ‚ÄòDrop‚Äô trait on any
type, and that code can be used to release resources like files or
network connections.

We're introducing ‚ÄòDrop‚Äô in the context of smart pointers because the
functionality of the ‚ÄòDrop‚Äô trait is almost always used when
implementing a smart pointer.  For example, when a ‚ÄòBox<T>‚Äô is dropped
it will deallocate the space on the heap that the box points to.

In some languages, for some types, the programmer must call code to free
memory or resources every time they finish using an instance of those
types.  Examples include file handles, sockets, or locks.  If they
forget, the system might become overloaded and crash.  In Rust, you can
specify that a particular bit of code be run whenever a value goes out
of scope, and the compiler will insert this code automatically.  As a
result, you don't need to be careful about placing cleanup code
everywhere in a program that an instance of a particular type is
finished with--you still won't leak resources!

You specify the code to run when a value goes out of scope by
implementing the ‚ÄòDrop‚Äô trait.  The ‚ÄòDrop‚Äô trait requires you to
implement one method named ‚Äòdrop‚Äô that takes a mutable reference to
‚Äòself‚Äô.  To see when Rust calls ‚Äòdrop‚Äô, let's implement ‚Äòdrop‚Äô with
‚Äòprintln!‚Äô statements for now.

Listing 15-14 shows a ‚ÄòCustomSmartPointer‚Äô struct whose only custom
functionality is that it will print ‚ÄòDropping CustomSmartPointer!‚Äô when
the instance goes out of scope, to show when Rust runs the ‚Äòdrop‚Äô
function.

struct CustomSmartPointer {
    data: String,
}

impl Drop for CustomSmartPointer {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        println!("Dropping CustomSmartPointer with data `{}`!", self.data);
    }
}

fn main() {
    let c = CustomSmartPointer {
        data: String::from("my stuff"),
    };
    let d = CustomSmartPointer {
        data: String::from("other stuff"),
    };
    println!("CustomSmartPointers created.");
}

The ‚ÄòDrop‚Äô trait is included in the prelude, so we don't need to bring
it into scope.  We implement the ‚ÄòDrop‚Äô trait on ‚ÄòCustomSmartPointer‚Äô
and provide an implementation for the ‚Äòdrop‚Äô method that calls
‚Äòprintln!‚Äô.  The body of the ‚Äòdrop‚Äô function is where you would place
any logic that you wanted to run when an instance of your type goes out
of scope.  We're printing some text here to demonstrate visually when
Rust will call ‚Äòdrop‚Äô.

In ‚Äòmain‚Äô, we create two instances of ‚ÄòCustomSmartPointer‚Äô and then
print ‚ÄòCustomSmartPointers created‚Äô.  At the end of ‚Äòmain‚Äô, our
instances of ‚ÄòCustomSmartPointer‚Äô will go out of scope, and Rust will
call the code we put in the ‚Äòdrop‚Äô method, printing our final message.
Note that we didn't need to call the ‚Äòdrop‚Äô method explicitly.

When we run this program, we'll see the following output:

