18.1.5 ‚ÄòRefCell<T>‚Äô and the Interior Mutability Pattern
-------------------------------------------------------

‚ÄòInterior mutability‚Äô is a design pattern in Rust that allows you to
mutate data even when there are immutable references to that data;
normally, this action is disallowed by the borrowing rules.  To mutate
data, the pattern uses ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô code inside a data structure to bend
Rust's usual rules that govern mutation and borrowing.  Unsafe code
indicates to the compiler that we're checking the rules manually instead
of relying on the compiler to check them for us; we will discuss unsafe
code more in Chapter 20.

We can use types that use the interior mutability pattern only when we
can ensure that the borrowing rules will be followed at runtime, even
though the compiler can't guarantee that.  The ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô code involved is
then wrapped in a safe API, and the outer type is still immutable.

Let's explore this concept by looking at the ‚ÄòRefCell<T>‚Äô type that
follows the interior mutability pattern.

