We call ‚Äòborrow_mut‚Äô on the ‚ÄòRefCell<Vec<String>>‚Äô in
‚Äòself.sent_messages‚Äô to get a mutable reference to the value inside the
‚ÄòRefCell<Vec<String>>‚Äô, which is the vector.  Then we can call ‚Äòpush‚Äô on
the mutable reference to the vector to keep track of the messages sent
during the test.

The last change we have to make is in the assertion: to see how many
items are in the inner vector, we call ‚Äòborrow‚Äô on the
‚ÄòRefCell<Vec<String>>‚Äô to get an immutable reference to the vector.

Now that you've seen how to use ‚ÄòRefCell<T>‚Äô, let's dig into how it
works!  Keeping Track of Borrows at Runtime with ‚ÄòRefCell<T>‚Äô When
creating immutable and mutable references, we use the ‚Äò&‚Äô and ‚Äò&mut‚Äô
syntax, respectively.  With ‚ÄòRefCell<T>‚Äô, we use the ‚Äòborrow‚Äô and
‚Äòborrow_mut‚Äô methods, which are part of the safe API that belongs to
‚ÄòRefCell<T>‚Äô.  The ‚Äòborrow‚Äô method returns the smart pointer type
‚ÄòRef<T>‚Äô, and ‚Äòborrow_mut‚Äô returns the smart pointer type ‚ÄòRefMut<T>‚Äô.
Both types implement ‚ÄòDeref‚Äô, so we can treat them like regular
references.

The ‚ÄòRefCell<T>‚Äô keeps track of how many ‚ÄòRef<T>‚Äô and ‚ÄòRefMut<T>‚Äô smart
pointers are currently active.  Every time we call ‚Äòborrow‚Äô, the
‚ÄòRefCell<T>‚Äô increases its count of how many immutable borrows are
active.  When a ‚ÄòRef<T>‚Äô value goes out of scope, the count of immutable
borrows goes down by one.  Just like the compile-time borrowing rules,
‚ÄòRefCell<T>‚Äô lets us have many immutable borrows or one mutable borrow
at any point in time.

If we try to violate these rules, rather than getting a compiler error
as we would with references, the implementation of ‚ÄòRefCell<T>‚Äô will
panic at runtime.  Listing 15-23 shows a modification of the
implementation of ‚Äòsend‚Äô in Listing 15-22.  We're deliberately trying to
create two mutable borrows active for the same scope to illustrate that
‚ÄòRefCell<T>‚Äô prevents us from doing this at runtime.

    impl Messenger for MockMessenger {
        fn send(&self, message: &str) {
            let mut one_borrow = self.sent_messages.borrow_mut();
            let mut two_borrow = self.sent_messages.borrow_mut();

            one_borrow.push(String::from(message));
            two_borrow.push(String::from(message));
        }
    }

We create a variable ‚Äòone_borrow‚Äô for the ‚ÄòRefMut<T>‚Äô smart pointer
returned from ‚Äòborrow_mut‚Äô.  Then we create another mutable borrow in
the same way in the variable ‚Äòtwo_borrow‚Äô.  This makes two mutable
references in the same scope, which isn't allowed.  When we run the
