‚ÄòRc<T>‚Äô and ‚ÄòRefCell<T>‚Äô A common way to use ‚ÄòRefCell<T>‚Äô is in
combination with ‚ÄòRc<T>‚Äô.  Recall that ‚ÄòRc<T>‚Äô lets you have multiple
owners of some data, but it only gives immutable access to that data.
If you have an ‚ÄòRc<T>‚Äô that holds a ‚ÄòRefCell<T>‚Äô, you can get a value
that can have multiple owners ‚Äòand‚Äô that you can mutate!

For example, recall the cons list example in Listing 15-18 where we used
‚ÄòRc<T>‚Äô to allow multiple lists to share ownership of another list.
Because ‚ÄòRc<T>‚Äô holds only immutable values, we can't change any of the
values in the list once we've created them.  Let's add in ‚ÄòRefCell<T>‚Äô
to gain the ability to change the values in the lists.  Listing 15-24
shows that by using a ‚ÄòRefCell<T>‚Äô in the ‚ÄòCons‚Äô definition, we can
modify the value stored in all the lists:

enum List {
    Cons(Rc<RefCell<i32>>, Rc<List>),
    Nil,
}

use crate::List::{Cons, Nil};
use std::cell::RefCell;
use std::rc::Rc;

fn main() {
    let value = Rc::new(RefCell::new(5));

    let a = Rc::new(Cons(Rc::clone(&value), Rc::new(Nil)));

    let b = Cons(Rc::new(RefCell::new(3)), Rc::clone(&a));
    let c = Cons(Rc::new(RefCell::new(4)), Rc::clone(&a));

    *value.borrow_mut() += 10;

    println!("a after = {a:?}");
    println!("b after = {b:?}");
    println!("c after = {c:?}");
}

We create a value that is an instance of ‚ÄòRc<RefCell<i32>>‚Äô and store it
in a variable named ‚Äòvalue‚Äô so we can access it directly later.  Then we
create a ‚ÄòList‚Äô in ‚Äòa‚Äô with a ‚ÄòCons‚Äô variant that holds ‚Äòvalue‚Äô.  We
need to clone ‚Äòvalue‚Äô so both ‚Äòa‚Äô and ‚Äòvalue‚Äô have ownership of the
inner ‚Äò5‚Äô value rather than transferring ownership from ‚Äòvalue‚Äô to ‚Äòa‚Äô
or having ‚Äòa‚Äô borrow from ‚Äòvalue‚Äô.

We wrap the list ‚Äòa‚Äô in an ‚ÄòRc<T>‚Äô so when we create lists ‚Äòb‚Äô and ‚Äòc‚Äô,
they can both refer to ‚Äòa‚Äô, which is what we did in Listing 15-18.

After we've created the lists in ‚Äòa‚Äô, ‚Äòb‚Äô, and ‚Äòc‚Äô, we want to add 10 to
the value in ‚Äòvalue‚Äô.  We do this by calling ‚Äòborrow_mut‚Äô on ‚Äòvalue‚Äô,
which uses the automatic dereferencing feature we discussed in Chapter 5
(see the section *note ‚ÄúWhere's the ‚Äò->‚Äô Operator?‚Äù: Where's the ->
Operator?.) to dereference the ‚ÄòRc<T>‚Äô to the inner ‚ÄòRefCell<T>‚Äô value.
The ‚Äòborrow_mut‚Äô method returns a ‚ÄòRefMut<T>‚Äô smart pointer, and we use
the dereference operator on it and change the inner value.

When we print ‚Äòa‚Äô, ‚Äòb‚Äô, and ‚Äòc‚Äô, we can see that they all have the
