   ‚Ä¢ Tokio is the most widely used async runtime in Rust today,
     especially (but not only!)  for web applications.  There are other
     great runtimes out there, and they may be more suitable for your
     purposes.  We use Tokio under the hood for ‚Äòtrpl‚Äô because it's
     well-tested and widely used.

In some cases, ‚Äòtrpl‚Äô also renames or wraps the original APIs to let us
stay focused on the details relevant to this chapter.  If you want to
understand what the crate does, we encourage you to check out its source
code (https://github.com/rust-lang/book/tree/main/packages/trpl).
You'll be able to see what crate each re-export comes from, and we've
left extensive comments explaining what the crate does.

Create a new binary project named ‚Äòhello-async‚Äô and add the ‚Äòtrpl‚Äô crate
as a dependency:

$ cargo new hello-async
$ cd hello-async
$ cargo add trpl

Now we can use the various pieces provided by ‚Äòtrpl‚Äô to write our first
async program.  We'll build a little command line tool which fetches two
web pages, pulls the ‚Äò<title>‚Äô element from each, and prints out the
title of whichever finishes that whole process first.

Let's start by writing a function that takes one page URL as a
parameter, makes a request to it, and returns the text of the title
element:

use trpl::Html;

async fn page_title(url: &str) -> Option<String> {
    let response = trpl::get(url).await;
    let response_text = response.text().await;
    Html::parse(&response_text)
        .select_first("title")
        .map(|title_element| title_element.inner_html())
}

In Listing 17-1, we define a function named ‚Äòpage_title‚Äô, and we mark it
with the ‚Äòasync‚Äô keyword.  Then we use the ‚Äòtrpl::get‚Äô function to fetch
whatever URL is passed in, and we await the response by using the
‚Äòawait‚Äô keyword.  Then we get the text of the response by calling its
‚Äòtext‚Äô method, and once again await it with the ‚Äòawait‚Äô keyword.  Both
of these steps are asynchronous.  For ‚Äòget‚Äô, we need to wait for the
server to send back the first part of its response, which will include
HTTP headers, cookies, and so on.  That part of the response can be
delivered separately from the body of the request.  Especially if the
body is very large, it can take some time for it all to arrive.  Thus,
we have to wait for the ‚Äòentirety‚Äô of the response to arrive, so the
‚Äòtext‚Äô method is also async.

We have to explicitly await both of these futures, because futures in
Rust are ‚Äòlazy‚Äô: they don't do anything until you ask them to with
‚Äòawait‚Äô.  (In fact, Rust will show a compiler warning if you don't use a
future.)  This should remind you of our discussion of iterators *note
back in Chapter 13: Processing a Series of Items with Iterators.
Iterators do nothing unless you call their ‚Äònext‚Äô method--whether
directly, or using ‚Äòfor‚Äô loops or methods such as ‚Äòmap‚Äô which use ‚Äònext‚Äô
under the hood.  With futures, the same basic idea applies: they do
nothing unless you explicitly ask them to.  This laziness allows Rust to
avoid running async code until it's actually needed.

Note: This is different from the behavior we saw when using
‚Äòthread::spawn‚Äô in the previous chapter, where the closure we passed to
another thread started running immediately.  It's also different from
how many other languages approach async!  But it's important for Rust.
We'll see why that is later.

Once we have ‚Äòresponse_text‚Äô, we can then parse it into an instance of
the ‚ÄòHtml‚Äô type using ‚ÄòHtml::parse‚Äô.  Instead of a raw string, we now
have a data type we can use to work with the HTML as a richer data
structure.  In particular, we can use the ‚Äòselect_first‚Äô method to find
the first instance of a given CSS selector.  By passing the string
‚Äò"title"‚Äô, we'll get the first ‚Äò<title>‚Äô element in the document, if
there is one.  Because there may not be any matching element,
‚Äòselect_first‚Äô returns an ‚ÄòOption<ElementRef>‚Äô.  Finally, we use the
‚ÄòOption::map‚Äô method, which lets us work with the item in the ‚ÄòOption‚Äô
if it's present, and do nothing if it isn't.  (We could also use a
‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression here, but ‚Äòmap‚Äô is more idiomatic.)  In the body of
the function we supply to ‚Äòmap‚Äô, we call ‚Äòinner_html‚Äô on the
‚Äòtitle_element‚Äô to get its content, which is a ‚ÄòString‚Äô.  When all is
said and done, we have an ‚ÄòOption<String>‚Äô.

Notice that Rust's ‚Äòawait‚Äô keyword goes after the expression you're
awaiting, not before it.  That is, it's a ‚Äòpostfix keyword‚Äô.  This may
be different from what you might be used to if you have used async in
other languages.  Rust chose this because it makes chains of methods
much nicer to work with.  As a result, we can change the body of
‚Äòpage_url_for‚Äô to chain the ‚Äòtrpl::get‚Äô and ‚Äòtext‚Äô function calls
together with ‚Äòawait‚Äô between them, as shown in Listing 17-2:

    let response_text = trpl::get(url).await.text().await;

With that, we have successfully written our first async function!
Before we add some code in ‚Äòmain‚Äô to call it, let's talk a little more
about what we've written and what it means.

When Rust sees a block marked with the ‚Äòasync‚Äô keyword, it compiles it
into a unique, anonymous data type which implements the ‚ÄòFuture‚Äô trait.
When Rust sees a function marked with ‚Äòasync‚Äô, it compiles it into a
non-async function whose body is an async block.  An async function's
return type is the type of the anonymous data type the compiler creates
for that async block.

Thus, writing ‚Äòasync fn‚Äô is equivalent to writing a function which
returns a ‚Äòfuture‚Äô of the return type.  When the compiler sees a
function definition such as the ‚Äòasync fn page_title‚Äô in Listing 17-1,
it's equivalent to a non-async function defined like this:

use std::future::Future;
use trpl::Html;

fn page_title(url: &str) -> impl Future<Output = Option<String>> + '_ {
    async move {
        let text = trpl::get(url).await.text().await;
        Html::parse(&text)
            .select_first("title")
            .map(|title| title.inner_html())
    }
}

Let's walk through each part of the transformed version:

   ‚Ä¢ It uses the ‚Äòimpl Trait‚Äô syntax we discussed back in the *note
     ‚ÄúTraits as Parameters‚Äù: Traits as Parameters. section in Chapter
     10.
   ‚Ä¢ The returned trait is a ‚ÄòFuture‚Äô, with an associated type of
     ‚ÄòOutput‚Äô.  Notice that the ‚ÄòOutput‚Äô type is ‚ÄòOption<String>‚Äô, which
     is the same as the the original return type from the ‚Äòasync fn‚Äô
     version of ‚Äòpage_title‚Äô.
   ‚Ä¢ All of the code called in the body of the original function is
     wrapped in an ‚Äòasync move‚Äô block.  Remember that blocks are
     expressions.  This whole block is the expression returned from the
     function.
   ‚Ä¢ This async block produces a value with the type ‚ÄòOption<String>‚Äô,
     as described above.  That value matches the ‚ÄòOutput‚Äô type in the
     return type.  This is just like other blocks you have seen.
   ‚Ä¢ The new function body is an ‚Äòasync move‚Äô block because of how it
     uses the ‚Äòurl‚Äô parameter.  (We'll talk about ‚Äòasync‚Äô vs.  ‚Äòasync
     move‚Äô much more later in the chapter.)
   ‚Ä¢ The new version of the function has a kind of lifetime we haven't
     seen before in the output type: ‚Äò'_‚Äô.  Because the function returns
     a ‚ÄòFuture‚Äô which refers to a reference--in this case, the reference
     from the ‚Äòurl‚Äô parameter--we need to tell Rust that we mean for
     that reference to be included.  We don't have to name the lifetime
     here, because Rust is smart enough to know there is only one
     reference which could be involved, but we ‚Äòdo‚Äô have to be explicit
     that the resulting ‚ÄòFuture‚Äô is bound by that lifetime.

Now we can call ‚Äòpage_title‚Äô in ‚Äòmain‚Äô.  To start, we'll just get the
title for a single page.  In Listing 17-3, we follow the same pattern we
used for getting command line arguments back in Chapter 12.  Then we
pass the first URL ‚Äòpage_title‚Äô, and await the result.  Because the
value produced by the future is an ‚ÄòOption<String>‚Äô, we use a ‚Äòmatch‚Äô
expression to print different messages to account for whether the page
had a ‚Äò<title>‚Äô.

async fn main() {
    let args: Vec<String> = std::env::args().collect();
    let url = &args[1];
    match page_title(url).await {
        Some(title) => println!("The title for {url} was {title}"),
        None => println!("{url} had no title"),
