6 | async fn main() {
  | ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ `main` function is not allowed to be `async`

The reason ‚Äòmain‚Äô can't be marked ‚Äòasync‚Äô is that async code needs a
‚Äòruntime‚Äô: a Rust crate which manages the details of executing
asynchronous code.  A program's ‚Äòmain‚Äô function can ‚Äòinitialize‚Äô a
runtime, but it's not a runtime ‚Äòitself‚Äô.  (We'll see more about why
this is a bit later.)  Every Rust program that executes async code has
at least one place where it sets up a runtime and executes the futures.

Most languages which support async bundle a runtime with the language.
Rust does not.  Instead, there are many different async runtimes
available, each of which makes different tradeoffs suitable to the use
case they target.  For example, a high-throughput web server with many
CPU cores and a large amount of RAM has very different needs than a
microcontroller with a single core, a small amount of RAM, and no
ability to do heap allocations.  The crates which provide those runtimes
also often supply async versions of common functionality such as file or
network I/O.

Here, and throughout the rest of this chapter, we'll use the ‚Äòrun‚Äô
function from the ‚Äòtrpl‚Äô crate, which takes a future as an argument and
runs it to completion.  Behind the scenes, calling ‚Äòrun‚Äô sets up a
runtime to use to run the future passed in.  Once the future completes,
‚Äòrun‚Äô returns whatever value the future produced.

We could pass the future returned by ‚Äòpage_title‚Äô directly to ‚Äòrun‚Äô.
Once it completed, we would be able to match on the resulting
‚ÄòOption<String>‚Äô, the way we tried to do in Listing 17-3.  However, for
most of the examples in the chapter (and most async code in the real
world!), we'll be doing more than just one async function call, so
instead we'll pass an ‚Äòasync‚Äô block and explicitly await the result of
calling ‚Äòpage_title‚Äô, as in Listing 17-4.

fn main() {
    let args: Vec<String> = std::env::args().collect();

    trpl::run(async {
        let url = &args[1];
        match page_title(url).await {
            Some(title) => println!("The title for {url} was {title}"),
            None => println!("{url} had no title"),
        }
    })
}

