we can run it.  Before we add code to race two sites against each other,
let's briefly turn our attention back to how futures work.

Each ‚Äòawait point‚Äô--that is, every place where the code uses the ‚Äòawait‚Äô
keyword--represents a place where control gets handed back to the
runtime.  To make that work, Rust needs to keep track of the state
involved in the async block, so that the runtime can kick off some other
work and then come back when it's ready to try advancing this one again.
This is an invisible state machine, as if you wrote an enum in this way
to save the current state at each ‚Äòawait‚Äô point:

enum PageTitleFuture<'a> {
    Initial { url: &'a str },
    GetAwaitPoint { url: &'a str },
    TextAwaitPoint { response: trpl::Response },
}

Writing the code to transition between each state by hand would be
tedious and error-prone, especially when adding more functionality and
more states to the code later.  Instead, the Rust compiler creates and
manages the state machine data structures for async code automatically.
If you're wondering: yep, the normal borrowing and ownership rules
around data structures all apply.  Happily, the compiler also handles
checking those for us, and has good error messages.  We'll work through
a few of those later in the chapter!

Ultimately, something has to execute that state machine.  That something
is a runtime.  (This is why you may sometimes come across references to
‚Äòexecutors‚Äô when looking into runtimes: an executor is the part of a
runtime responsible for executing the async code.)

Now we can understand why the compiler stopped us from making ‚Äòmain‚Äô
itself an async function back in Listing 17-3.  If ‚Äòmain‚Äô were an async
function, something else would need to manage the state machine for
whatever future ‚Äòmain‚Äô returned, but ‚Äòmain‚Äô is the starting point for
the program!  Instead, we call the ‚Äòtrpl::run‚Äô function in ‚Äòmain‚Äô, which
sets up a runtime and runs the future returned by the ‚Äòasync‚Äô block
until it returns ‚ÄòReady‚Äô.

Note: some runtimes provide macros to make it so you ‚Äòcan‚Äô write an
async main function.  Those macros rewrite ‚Äòasync fn main() { ... }‚Äô to
be a normal ‚Äòfn main‚Äô which does the same thing we did by hand in
Listing 17-5: call a function which runs a future to completion the way
‚Äòtrpl::run‚Äô does.

Let's put these pieces together and see how we can write concurrent
code, by calling ‚Äòpage_title‚Äô with two different URLs passed in from the
command line and racing them.

use trpl::{Either, Html};

fn main() {
    let args: Vec<String> = std::env::args().collect();

    trpl::run(async {
        let title_fut_1 = page_title(&args[1]);
        let title_fut_2 = page_title(&args[2]);

        let (url, maybe_title) =
            match trpl::race(title_fut_1, title_fut_2).await {
                Either::Left(left) => left,
                Either::Right(right) => right,
            };

        println!("{url} returned first");
        match maybe_title {
            Some(title) => println!("Its page title is: '{title}'"),
            None => println!("Its title could not be parsed."),
        }
    })
}

async fn page_title(url: &str) -> (&str, Option<String>) {
    let text = trpl::get(url).await.text().await;
    let title = Html::parse(&text)
        .select_first("title")
        .map(|title| title.inner_html());
    (url, title)
}

In Listing 17-5, we begin by calling ‚Äòpage_title‚Äô for each of the
user-supplied URLs.  We save the futures produced by calling
‚Äòpage_title‚Äô as ‚Äòtitle_fut_1‚Äô and ‚Äòtitle_fut_2‚Äô.  Remember, these don't
do anything yet, because futures are lazy, and we haven't yet awaited
them.  Then we pass the futures to ‚Äòtrpl::race‚Äô, which returns a value
to indicate which of the futures passed to it finishes first.

Note: Under the hood, ‚Äòrace‚Äô is built on a more general function,
‚Äòselect‚Äô, which you will encounter more often in real-world Rust code.
A ‚Äòselect‚Äô function can do a lot of things that ‚Äòtrpl::race‚Äô function
can't, but it also has some additional complexity that we can skip over
for now.

Either future can legitimately ‚Äúwin,‚Äù so it doesn't make sense to return
a ‚ÄòResult‚Äô.  Instead, ‚Äòrace‚Äô returns a type we haven't seen before,
‚Äòtrpl::Either‚Äô.  The ‚ÄòEither‚Äô type is somewhat similar to a ‚ÄòResult‚Äô, in
that it has two cases.  Unlike ‚ÄòResult‚Äô, though, there is no notion of
success or failure baked into ‚ÄòEither‚Äô.  Instead, it uses ‚ÄòLeft‚Äô and
‚ÄòRight‚Äô to indicate ‚Äúone or the other‚Äù.

enum Either<A, B> {
    Left(A),
    Right(B),
}

The ‚Äòrace‚Äô function returns ‚ÄòLeft‚Äô if the first argument finishes first,
with that future's output, and ‚ÄòRight‚Äô with the second future argument's
output if ‚Äòthat‚Äô one finishes first.  This matches the order the
arguments appear when calling the function: the first argument is to the
left of the second argument.

We also update ‚Äòpage_title‚Äô to return the same URL passed in.  That way,
if the page which returns first does not have a ‚Äò<title>‚Äô we can
resolve, we can still print a meaningful message.  With that information
available, we wrap up by updating our ‚Äòprintln!‚Äô output to indicate both
which URL finished first and what the ‚Äò<title>‚Äô was for the web page at
that URL, if any.

