19.2.4.1 Racing futures
.......................

When we ‚Äújoin‚Äù futures with the ‚Äòjoin‚Äô family of functions and macros,
we require ‚Äòall‚Äô of them to finish before we move on.  Sometimes,
though, we only need ‚Äòsome‚Äô future from a set to finish before we move
on--kind of similar to racing one future against another.

In Listing 17-21, we once again use ‚Äòtrpl::race‚Äô to run two futures,
‚Äòslow‚Äô and ‚Äòfast‚Äô, against each other.  Each one prints a message when
it starts running, pauses for some amount of time by calling and
awaiting ‚Äòsleep‚Äô, and then prints another message when it finishes.
Then we pass both to ‚Äòtrpl::race‚Äô and wait for one of them to finish.
(The outcome here won't be too surprising: ‚Äòfast‚Äô wins!)  Unlike when we
used ‚Äòrace‚Äô back in *note ‚ÄúOur First Async Program‚Äù: Our First Async
Program, we just ignore the ‚ÄòEither‚Äô instance it returns here, because
all of the interesting behavior happens in the body of the async blocks.

        let slow = async {
            println!("'slow' started.");
            trpl::sleep(Duration::from_millis(100)).await;
            println!("'slow' finished.");
        };

        let fast = async {
            println!("'fast' started.");
            trpl::sleep(Duration::from_millis(50)).await;
            println!("'fast' finished.");
        };

        trpl::race(slow, fast).await;

Notice that if you flip the order of the arguments to ‚Äòrace‚Äô, the order
of the ‚Äústarted‚Äù messages changes, even though the ‚Äòfast‚Äô future always
completes first.  That's because the implementation of this particular
‚Äòrace‚Äô function is not fair.  It always runs the futures passed as
arguments in the order they're passed.  Other implementations ‚Äòare‚Äô
fair, and will randomly choose which future to poll first.  Regardless
of whether the implementation of race we're using is fair, though, ‚Äòone‚Äô
of the futures will run up to the first ‚Äòawait‚Äô in its body before
another task can start.

Recall from *note Our First Async Program: Our First Async Program. that
at each await point, Rust gives a runtime a chance to pause the task and
switch to another one if the future being awaited isn't ready.  The
inverse is also true: Rust ‚Äòonly‚Äô pauses async blocks and hands control
back to a runtime at an await point.  Everything between await points is
synchronous.

That means if you do a bunch of work in an async block without an await
point, that future will block any other futures from making progress.
You may sometimes hear this referred to as one future ‚Äòstarving‚Äô other
futures.  In some cases, that may not be a big deal.  However, if you
are doing some kind of expensive setup or long-running work, or if you
have a future which will keep doing some particular task indefinitely,
you'll need to think about when and where to hand control back to the
runtime.

By the same token, if you have long-running blocking operations, async
can be a useful tool for providing ways for different parts of the
program to relate to each other.

But ‚Äòhow‚Äô would you hand control back to the runtime in those cases?


