We could do this with the regular ‚ÄòReceiver‚Äô API, or even the regular
‚ÄòIterator‚Äô API, though.  Let's add something that requires streams:
adding a timeout which applies to every item in the stream, and a delay
on the items we emit.

In Listing 17-34, we start by adding a timeout to the stream with the
‚Äòtimeout‚Äô method, which comes from the ‚ÄòStreamExt‚Äô trait.  Then we
update the body of the ‚Äòwhile let‚Äô loop, because the stream now returns
a ‚ÄòResult‚Äô.  The ‚ÄòOk‚Äô variant indicates a message arrived in time; the
‚ÄòErr‚Äô variant indicates that the timeout elapsed before any message
arrived.  We ‚Äòmatch‚Äô on that result and either print the message when we
receive it successfully, or print a notice about the timeout.  Finally,
notice that we pin the messages after applying the timeout to them,
because the timeout helper produces a stream which needs to be pinned to
be polled.

use std::{pin::pin, time::Duration};
use trpl::{ReceiverStream, Stream, StreamExt};

fn main() {
    trpl::run(async {
        let mut messages =
            pin!(get_messages().timeout(Duration::from_millis(200)));

        while let Some(result) = messages.next().await {
            match result {
                Ok(message) => println!("{message}"),
                Err(reason) => eprintln!("Problem: {reason:?}"),
            }
        }
    })
}

However, because there are no delays between messages, this timeout does
not change the behavior of the program.  Let's add a variable delay to
the messages we send.  In ‚Äòget_messages‚Äô, we use the ‚Äòenumerate‚Äô
iterator method with the ‚Äòmessages‚Äô array so that we can get the index
of each item we are sending along with the item itself.  Then we apply a
100 millisecond delay to even-index items and a 300 millisecond delay to
odd-index items, to simulate the different delays we might see from a
stream of messages in the real world.  Because our timeout is for 200
milliseconds, this should affect half of the messages.

fn get_messages() -> impl Stream<Item = String> {
    let (tx, rx) = trpl::channel();

    trpl::spawn_task(async move {
        let messages = ["a", "b", "c", "d", "e", "f", "g", "h", "i", "j"];
        for (index, message) in messages.into_iter().enumerate() {
            let time_to_sleep = if index % 2 == 0 { 100 } else { 300 };
            trpl::sleep(Duration::from_millis(time_to_sleep)).await;

            tx.send(format!("Message: '{message}'")).unwrap();
        }
    });

    ReceiverStream::new(rx)
}

To sleep between messages in the ‚Äòget_messages‚Äô function without
blocking, we need to use async.  However, we can't make ‚Äòget_messages‚Äô
itself into an async function, because then we'd return a ‚ÄòFuture<Output
= Stream<Item = String>>‚Äô instead of a ‚ÄòStream<Item = String>>‚Äô.  The
caller would have to await ‚Äòget_messages‚Äô itself to get access to the
stream.  But remember: everything in a given future happens linearly;
concurrency happens ‚Äòbetween‚Äô futures.  Awaiting ‚Äòget_messages‚Äô would
require it to send all the messages, including sleeping between sending
each message, before returning the receiver stream.  As a result, the
timeout would end up useless.  There would be no delays in the stream
itself: the delays would all happen before the stream was even
available.

Instead, we leave ‚Äòget_messages‚Äô as a regular function which returns a
stream, and spawn a task to handle the async ‚Äòsleep‚Äô calls.

Note: calling ‚Äòspawn_task‚Äô in this way works because we already set up
our runtime.  Calling this particular implementation of ‚Äòspawn_task‚Äô
‚Äòwithout‚Äô first setting up a runtime will cause a panic.  Other
implementations choose different tradeoffs: they might spawn a new
runtime and so avoid the panic but end up with a bit of extra overhead,
or simply not provide a standalone way to spawn tasks without reference
to a runtime.  You should make sure you know what tradeoff your runtime
has chosen and write your code accordingly!

Now our code has a much more interesting result!  Between every other
pair of messages, we see an error reported: ‚ÄòProblem: Elapsed(())‚Äô.

