19.2.5.2 Merging Streams
........................

First, let's create another stream, which will emit an item every
millisecond if we let it run directly.  For simplicity, we can use the
‚Äòsleep‚Äô function to send a message on a delay, and combine it with the
same approach of creating a stream from a channel we used in
‚Äòget_messages‚Äô.  The difference is that this time, we're going to send
back the count of intervals which has elapsed, so the return type will
be ‚Äòimpl Stream<Item = u32>‚Äô, and we can call the function
‚Äòget_intervals‚Äô.

In Listing 17-36, we start by defining a ‚Äòcount‚Äô in the task.  (We could
define it outside the task, too, but it is clearer to limit the scope of
any given variable.)  Then we create an infinite loop.  Each iteration
of the loop asynchronously sleeps for one millisecond, increments the
count, and then sends it over the channel.  Because this is all wrapped
in the task created by ‚Äòspawn_task‚Äô, all of it will get cleaned up along
with the runtime, including the infinite loop.

fn get_intervals() -> impl Stream<Item = u32> {
    let (tx, rx) = trpl::channel();

    trpl::spawn_task(async move {
        let mut count = 0;
        loop {
            trpl::sleep(Duration::from_millis(1)).await;
            count += 1;
            tx.send(count).unwrap();
        }
    });

    ReceiverStream::new(rx)
}

This kind of infinite loop, which only ends when the whole runtime gets
torn down, is fairly common in async Rust: many programs need to keep
running indefinitely.  With async, this doesn't block anything else, as
long as there is at least one await point in each iteration through the
loop.

Back in our main function's async block, we start by calling
‚Äòget_intervals‚Äô.  Then we merge the ‚Äòmessages‚Äô and ‚Äòintervals‚Äô streams
with the ‚Äòmerge‚Äô method, which combines multiple streams into one stream
that produces items from any of the source streams as soon as the items
are available, without imposing any particular ordering.  Finally, we
loop over that combined stream instead of over ‚Äòmessages‚Äô (Listing
17-37).

        let messages = get_messages().timeout(Duration::from_millis(200));
        let intervals = get_intervals();
        let merged = messages.merge(intervals);

At this point, neither ‚Äòmessages‚Äô nor ‚Äòintervals‚Äô needs to be pinned or
mutable, because both will be combined into the single ‚Äòmerged‚Äô stream.
However, this call to ‚Äòmerge‚Äô does not compile!  (Neither does the
‚Äònext‚Äô call in the ‚Äòwhile let‚Äô loop, but we'll come back to that after
fixing this.)  The two streams have different types.  The ‚Äòmessages‚Äô
stream has the type ‚ÄòTimeout<impl Stream<Item = String>>‚Äô, where
‚ÄòTimeout‚Äô is the type which implements ‚ÄòStream‚Äô for a ‚Äòtimeout‚Äô call.
Meanwhile, the ‚Äòintervals‚Äô stream has the type ‚Äòimpl Stream<Item =
u32>‚Äô.  To merge these two streams, we need to transform one of them to
match the other.

In Listing 17-38, we rework the ‚Äòintervals‚Äô stream, because ‚Äòmessages‚Äô
is already in the basic format we want and has to handle timeout errors.
First, we can use the ‚Äòmap‚Äô helper method to transform the ‚Äòintervals‚Äô
into a string.  Second, we need to match the ‚ÄòTimeout‚Äô from ‚Äòmessages‚Äô.
Because we don't actually ‚Äòwant‚Äô a timeout for ‚Äòintervals‚Äô, though, we
can just create a timeout which is longer than the other durations we
are using.  Here, we create a 10-second timeout with
‚ÄòDuration::from_secs(10)‚Äô.  Finally, we need to make ‚Äòstream‚Äô mutable,
so that the ‚Äòwhile let‚Äô loop's ‚Äònext‚Äô calls can iterate through the
stream, and pin it so that it's safe to do so.

        let messages = get_messages().timeout(Duration::from_millis(200));
        let intervals = get_intervals()
            .map(|count| format!("Interval: {count}"))
            .timeout(Duration::from_secs(10));
        let merged = messages.merge(intervals);
        let mut stream = pin!(merged);

That gets us ‚Äòalmost‚Äô to where we need to be.  Everything type checks.
If you run this, though, there will be two problems.  First, it will
never stop!  You'll need to stop it with ctrl-c.  Second, the messages
