19.2.6.1 Future
...............

Back in *note ‚ÄúFutures and the Async Syntax‚Äù: Futures and the Async
Syntax, we noted that ‚ÄòFuture‚Äô is a trait.  Let's start by taking a
closer look at how it works.  Here is how Rust defines a ‚ÄòFuture‚Äô:

use std::pin::Pin;
use std::task::{Context, Poll};

pub trait Future {
    type Output;

    fn poll(self: Pin<&mut Self>, cx: &mut Context<'_>) -> Poll<Self::Output>;
}

That trait definition includes a bunch of new types and also some syntax
we haven't seen before, so let's walk through the definition piece by
piece.

First, ‚ÄòFuture‚Äô's associated type ‚ÄòOutput‚Äô says what the future resolves
to.  This is analogous to the ‚ÄòItem‚Äô associated type for the ‚ÄòIterator‚Äô
trait.  Second, ‚ÄòFuture‚Äô also has the ‚Äòpoll‚Äô method, which takes a
special ‚ÄòPin‚Äô reference for its ‚Äòself‚Äô parameter and a mutable reference
to a ‚ÄòContext‚Äô type, and returns a ‚ÄòPoll<Self::Output>‚Äô.  We'll talk a
little more about ‚ÄòPin‚Äô and ‚ÄòContext‚Äô later in the section.  For now,
let's focus on what the method returns, the ‚ÄòPoll‚Äô type:

enum Poll<T> {
    Ready(T),
    Pending,
}

This ‚ÄòPoll‚Äô type is similar to an ‚ÄòOption‚Äô: it has one variant which has
a value (‚ÄòReady(T)‚Äô), and one which does not (‚ÄòPending‚Äô).  It means
something quite different, though!  The ‚ÄòPending‚Äô variant indicates that
the future still has work to do, so the caller will need to check again
later.  The ‚ÄòReady‚Äô variant indicates that the ‚ÄòFuture‚Äô has finished its
work and the ‚ÄòT‚Äô value is available.

Note: With most futures, the caller should not call ‚Äòpoll‚Äô again after
the future has returned ‚ÄòReady‚Äô.  Many futures will panic if polled
again after becoming ready!  Futures which are safe to poll again will
say so explicitly in their documentation.  This is similar to how
‚ÄòIterator::next‚Äô behaves!

Under the hood, when you see code which uses ‚Äòawait‚Äô, Rust compiles that
to code which calls ‚Äòpoll‚Äô.  If you look back at Listing 17-4, where we
printed out the page title for a single URL once it resolved, Rust
compiles it into something kind of (although not exactly) like this:

match page_title(url).poll() {
    Ready(page_title) => match page_title {
        Some(title) => println!("The title for {url} was {title}"),
        None => println!("{url} had no title"),
    }
    Pending => {
        // But what goes here?
    }
}

What should we do when the ‚ÄòFuture‚Äô is still ‚ÄòPending‚Äô?  We need some
way to try again... and again, and again, until the future is finally
ready.  In other words, a loop:

let mut page_title_fut = page_title(url);
loop {
    match page_title_fut.poll() {
        Ready(value) => match page_title {
            Some(title) => println!("The title for {url} was {title}"),
            None => println!("{url} had no title"),
        }
        Pending => {
            // continue
        }
    }
}

If Rust compiled it to exactly that code, though, every ‚Äòawait‚Äô would be
blocking--exactly the opposite of what we were going for!  Instead, Rust
makes sure that the loop can hand off control to something which can
pause work on this future and work on other futures and check this one
again later.  That ‚Äúsomething‚Äù is an async runtime, and this scheduling
and coordination work is one of the main jobs for a runtime.

Recall our description (in the *note Counting: Concurrency With Async.
section) of waiting on ‚Äòrx.recv‚Äô.  The ‚Äòrecv‚Äô call returns a ‚ÄòFuture‚Äô,
and awaiting it polls it.  In our initial discussion, we noted that a
runtime will pause the future until it's ready with either
‚ÄòSome(message)‚Äô or ‚ÄòNone‚Äô when the channel closes.  With our deeper
understanding of ‚ÄòFuture‚Äô in place, and specifically ‚ÄòFuture::poll‚Äô, we
can see how that works.  The runtime knows the future isn't ready when
it returns ‚ÄòPoll::Pending‚Äô.  Conversely, the runtime knows the future is
ready and advances it when ‚Äòpoll‚Äô returns ‚ÄòPoll::Ready(Some(message))‚Äô
or ‚ÄòPoll::Ready(None)‚Äô.

The exact details of how a runtime does that are more than we will cover
in even this deep dive section.  The key here is to see the basic
mechanic of futures: a runtime ‚Äòpolls‚Äô each future it is responsible
for, putting it back to sleep when it is not yet ready.


