19.2.6.2 Pinning and the Pin and Unpin Traits
.............................................

When we introduced the idea of pinning while working on Listing 17-16,
we ran into a very gnarly error message.  Here is the relevant part of
it again:

error[E0277]: `{async block@src/main.rs:10:23: 10:33}` cannot be unpinned
  --> src/main.rs:48:33
   |
48 |         trpl::join_all(futures).await;
   |                                 ^^^^^ the trait `Unpin` is not implemented for `{async block@src/main.rs:10:23: 10:33}`, which is required by `Box<{async block@src/main.rs:10:23: 10:33}>: Future`
   |
   = note: consider using the `pin!` macro
           consider using `Box::pin` if you need to access the pinned value outside of the current scope
   = note: required for `Box<{async block@src/main.rs:10:23: 10:33}>` to implement `Future`
note: required by a bound in `futures_util::future::join_all::JoinAll`
  --> file:///home/.cargo/registry/src/index.crates.io-6f17d22bba15001f/futures-util-0.3.30/src/future/join_all.rs:29:8
   |
27 | pub struct JoinAll<F>
   |            ------- required by a bound in this struct
28 | where
29 |     F: Future,
   |        ^^^^^^ required by this bound in `JoinAll`

When we read this error message carefully, it not only tells us that we
need to pin the values, but also tells us why pinning is required.  The
‚Äòtrpl::join_all‚Äô function returns a struct called ‚ÄòJoinAll‚Äô.  That
struct is generic over a type ‚ÄòF‚Äô, which is constrained to implement the
‚ÄòFuture‚Äô trait.  Directly awaiting a future with ‚Äòawait‚Äô pins the future
implicitly.  That's why we don't need to use ‚Äòpin!‚Äô everywhere we want
to await futures.

However, we're not directly awaiting a future here.  Instead, we
construct a new future, ‚ÄòJoinAll‚Äô, by passing a collection of futures to
the ‚Äòjoin_all‚Äô function.  The signature for ‚Äòjoin_all‚Äô requires that the
type of the items in the collection all implement the ‚ÄòFuture‚Äô trait,
and ‚ÄòBox<T>‚Äô only implements ‚ÄòFuture‚Äô if the ‚ÄòT‚Äô that it wraps is a
future which implements the ‚ÄòUnpin‚Äô trait.

That's a lot!  But we can understand it, if we dive a little further
into how the ‚ÄòFuture‚Äô type actually works, in particular around
‚Äòpinning‚Äô.

Let's look again at the definition of ‚ÄòFuture‚Äô:

use std::pin::Pin;
use std::task::{Context, Poll};

pub trait Future {
    type Output;

    // Required method
    fn poll(self: Pin<&mut Self>, cx: &mut Context<'_>) -> Poll<Self::Output>;
}

The ‚Äòcx‚Äô parameter and its ‚ÄòContext‚Äô type is the key to how a runtime
actually knows when to check any given future, while still being lazy.
The details of how that works are beyond the scope of this chapter,
though: you generally only need to worry about it when writing a custom
‚ÄòFuture‚Äô implementation.

Instead, we'll focus on the type for ‚Äòself‚Äô.  This is the first time
we've seen a method where ‚Äòself‚Äô has a type annotation.  A type
annotation for ‚Äòself‚Äô is similar to type annotations for other function
parameters, with two key differences.  First, when we specify the type
of ‚Äòself‚Äô in this way, we're telling Rust what type ‚Äòself‚Äô must be to
call this method.  Second, a type annotation on ‚Äòself‚Äô can't be just any
type.  It's only allowed to be the type on which the method is
implemented, a reference or smart pointer to that type, or a ‚ÄòPin‚Äô
wrapping a reference to that type.  We'll see more on this syntax in
Chapter 18.  For now, it's enough to know that if we want to poll a
future (to check whether it is ‚ÄòPending‚Äô or ‚ÄòReady(Output)‚Äô), we need a
mutable reference to the type, which is wrapped in a ‚ÄòPin‚Äô.

‚ÄòPin‚Äô is a wrapper type.  In some ways, it's similar to the ‚ÄòBox‚Äô, ‚ÄòRc‚Äô,
and other smart pointer types we saw in Chapter 15, which also wrap
other types.  Unlike those, however, ‚ÄòPin‚Äô only works with ‚Äòpointer
types‚Äô such as references (‚Äò&‚Äô and ‚Äò&mut‚Äô) and smart pointers (‚ÄòBox‚Äô,
‚ÄòRc‚Äô, and so on).  To be precise, ‚ÄòPin‚Äô works with types which implement
the ‚ÄòDeref‚Äô or ‚ÄòDerefMut‚Äô traits, which we covered in Chapter 15.  You
can think of this restriction as equivalent to only working with
pointers, though, because implementing ‚ÄòDeref‚Äô or ‚ÄòDerefMut‚Äô means your
type behaves similarly to a pointer type.  ‚ÄòPin‚Äô is also not a pointer
itself, and it doesn't have any behavior of its own the way ‚ÄòRc‚Äô and
‚ÄòArc‚Äô do with ref counting.  It's purely a tool the compiler can use to
uphold the relevant guarantees, by wrapping pointers in the type.

Recalling that ‚Äòawait‚Äô is implemented in terms of calls to ‚Äòpoll‚Äô, this
starts to explain the error message we saw above--but that was in terms
of ‚ÄòUnpin‚Äô, not ‚ÄòPin‚Äô.  So what exactly are ‚ÄòPin‚Äô and ‚ÄòUnpin‚Äô, how do
they relate, and why does ‚ÄòFuture‚Äô need ‚Äòself‚Äô to be in a ‚ÄòPin‚Äô type to
call ‚Äòpoll‚Äô?

In *note Our First Async Program: Our First Async Program, we described
how a series of await points in a future get compiled into a state
machine--and noted how the compiler helps make sure that state machine
follows all of Rust's normal rules around safety, including borrowing
and ownership.  To make that work, Rust looks at what data is needed
between each await point and the next await point or the end of the
async block.  It then creates a corresponding variant in the state
machine it creates.  Each variant gets the access it needs to the data
that will be used in that section of the source code, whether by taking
ownership of that data or by getting a mutable or immutable reference to
it.

So far so good: if we get anything wrong about the ownership or
references in a given async block, the borrow checker will tell us.
When we want to move around the future that corresponds to that
block--like moving it into a ‚ÄòVec‚Äô to pass to ‚Äòjoin_all‚Äô, the way we did
back in the *note ‚ÄúWorking With Any Number of Futures‚Äù: Working With Any
Number of Futures. section--things get trickier.

When we move a future--whether by pushing into a data structure to use
as an iterator with ‚Äòjoin_all‚Äô, or returning them from a function--that
actually means moving the state machine Rust creates for us.  And unlike
most other types in Rust, the futures Rust creates for async blocks can
end up with references to themselves in the fields of any given variant,
as in Figure 17-4 (a simplified illustration to help you get a feel for
the idea, rather than digging into what are often fairly complicated
details).

By default, though, any object which has a reference to itself is unsafe
to move, because references always point to the actual memory address of
the thing they refer to.  If you move the data structure itself, those
internal references will be left pointing to the old location.  However,
that memory location is now invalid.  For one thing, its value will not
be updated when you make changes to the data structure.  For
another--and more importantly!--the computer is now free to reuse that
memory for other things!  You could end up reading completely unrelated
data later.

In principle, the Rust compiler could try to update every reference to
an object every time it gets moved.  That would potentially be a lot of
performance overhead, especially given there can be a whole web of
references that need updating.  On the other hand, if we could make sure
the data structure in question ‚Äòdoesn't move in memory‚Äô, we don't have
to update any references.  This is exactly what Rust's borrow checker
requires: you can't move an item which has any active references to it
using safe code.

‚ÄòPin‚Äô builds on that to give us the exact guarantee we need.  When we
‚Äòpin‚Äô a value by wrapping a pointer to that value in ‚ÄòPin‚Äô, it can no
longer move.  Thus, if you have ‚ÄòPin<Box<SomeType>>‚Äô, you actually pin
the ‚ÄòSomeType‚Äô value, ‚Äònot‚Äô the ‚ÄòBox‚Äô pointer.  Figure 17-6 illustrates
this:

In fact, the ‚ÄòBox‚Äô pointer can still move around freely.  Remember: we
care about making sure the data ultimately being referenced stays in its
place.  If a pointer moves around, but the data it points to is in the
same place, as in Figure 17-7, there's no potential problem.  (How you
would do this with a ‚ÄòPin‚Äô wrapping a ‚ÄòBox‚Äô is more than we'll get into
in this particular discussion, but it would make for a good exercise!
If you look at the docs for the types as well as the ‚Äòstd::pin‚Äô module,
you might be able to work out how you would do that.)  The key is that
the self-referential type itself cannot move, because it is still
pinned.

However, most types are perfectly safe to move around, even if they
happen to be behind a ‚ÄòPin‚Äô pointer.  We only need to think about
pinning when items have internal references.  Primitive values such as
numbers and booleans don't have any internal references, so they're
obviously safe.  Neither do most types you normally work with in Rust.
A ‚ÄòVec‚Äô, for example, doesn't have any internal references it needs to
keep up to date this way, so you can move it around without worrying.
If you have a ‚ÄòPin<Vec<String>>‚Äô, you'd have to do everything via the
safe but restrictive APIs provided by ‚ÄòPin‚Äô, even though a ‚ÄòVec<String>‚Äô
is always safe to move if there are no other references to it.  We need
a way to tell the compiler that it's actually just fine to move items
around in cases such as these.  For that, we have ‚ÄòUnpin‚Äô.

‚ÄòUnpin‚Äô is a marker trait, similar to the ‚ÄòSend‚Äô and ‚ÄòSync‚Äô traits we
saw in Chapter 16.  Recall that marker traits have no functionality of
their own.  They exist only to tell the compiler that it's safe to use
the type which implements a given trait in a particular context.
‚ÄòUnpin‚Äô informs the compiler that a given type does ‚Äònot‚Äô need to uphold
any particular guarantees about whether the value in question can be
moved.

Just as with ‚ÄòSend‚Äô and ‚ÄòSync‚Äô, the compiler implements ‚ÄòUnpin‚Äô
automatically for all types where it can prove it is safe.  The special
case, again similar to ‚ÄòSend‚Äô and ‚ÄòSync‚Äô, is the case where ‚ÄòUnpin‚Äô is
‚Äònot‚Äô implemented for a type.  The notation for this is ‚Äòimpl !Unpin for
SomeType‚Äô, where ‚ÄòSomeType‚Äô is the name of a type which ‚Äòdoes‚Äô need to
uphold those guarantees to be safe whenever a pointer to that type is
used in a ‚ÄòPin‚Äô.

In other words, there are two things to keep in mind about the
relationship between ‚ÄòPin‚Äô and ‚ÄòUnpin‚Äô.  First, ‚ÄòUnpin‚Äô is the ‚Äúnormal‚Äù
case, and ‚Äò!Unpin‚Äô is the special case.  Second, whether a type
implements ‚ÄòUnpin‚Äô or ‚Äò!Unpin‚Äô ‚Äòonly‚Äô matters when using a pinned
pointer to that type like ‚ÄòPin<&mut SomeType>‚Äô.

To make that concrete, think about a ‚ÄòString‚Äô: it has a length and the
Unicode characters which make it up.  We can wrap a ‚ÄòString‚Äô in ‚ÄòPin‚Äô,
as seen in Figure 17-8.  However, ‚ÄòString‚Äô automatically implements
‚ÄòUnpin‚Äô, the same as most other types in Rust.

As a result, we can do things which would be illegal if ‚ÄòString‚Äô
implemented ‚Äò!Unpin‚Äô instead, such as replace one string with another at
the exact same location in memory as in Figure 17-9.  This doesn't
violate the ‚ÄòPin‚Äô contract, because ‚ÄòString‚Äô has no internal references
that make it unsafe to move around!  That is precisely why it implements
‚ÄòUnpin‚Äô rather than ‚Äò!Unpin‚Äô.

Now we know enough to understand the errors reported for that ‚Äòjoin_all‚Äô
call from back in Listing 17-17.  We originally tried to move the
futures produced by async blocks into a ‚ÄòVec<Box<dyn Future<Output =
()>>>‚Äô, but as we've seen, those futures may have internal references,
so they don't implement ‚ÄòUnpin‚Äô.  They need to be pinned, and then we
can pass the ‚ÄòPin‚Äô type into the ‚ÄòVec‚Äô, confident that the underlying
data in the futures will ‚Äònot‚Äô be moved.

‚ÄòPin‚Äô and ‚ÄòUnpin‚Äô are mostly important for building lower-level
libraries, or when you're building a runtime itself, rather than for day
to day Rust code.  When you see these traits in error messages, though,
now you'll have a better idea of how to fix the code!

Note: This combination of ‚ÄòPin‚Äô and ‚ÄòUnpin‚Äô allows a whole class of
complex types to be safe in Rust which are otherwise difficult to
implement because they're self-referential.  Types which require ‚ÄòPin‚Äô
show up ‚Äòmost‚Äô commonly in async Rust today, but you might--very
rarely!--see it in other contexts, too.

The specifics of how ‚ÄòPin‚Äô and ‚ÄòUnpin‚Äô work, and the rules they're
required to uphold, are covered extensively in the API documentation for
‚Äòstd::pin‚Äô, so if you'd like to understand them more deeply, that's a
great place to start.

If you want to understand how things work ‚Äúunder the hood‚Äù in even more
detail, the official ‚ÄòAsynchronous Programming in Rust‚Äô
(https://rust-lang.github.io/async-book/) book has you covered:

