19.2.6.3 The Stream Trait
.........................

Now that we have a deeper grasp on the ‚ÄòFuture‚Äô, ‚ÄòPin‚Äô, and ‚ÄòUnpin‚Äô
traits, we can turn our attention to the ‚ÄòStream‚Äô trait.  As described
in the section introducing streams, streams are similar to asynchronous
iterators.  Unlike ‚ÄòIterator‚Äô and ‚ÄòFuture‚Äô, there is no definition of a
‚ÄòStream‚Äô trait in the standard library as of the time of writing, but
there ‚Äòis‚Äô a very common definition from the ‚Äòfutures‚Äô crate used
throughout the ecosystem.

Let's review the definitions of the ‚ÄòIterator‚Äô and ‚ÄòFuture‚Äô traits, so
we can build up to how a ‚ÄòStream‚Äô trait that merges them together might
look.  From ‚ÄòIterator‚Äô, we have the idea of a sequence: its ‚Äònext‚Äô
method provides an ‚ÄòOption<Self::Item>‚Äô.  From ‚ÄòFuture‚Äô, we have the
idea of readiness over time: its ‚Äòpoll‚Äô method provides a
‚ÄòPoll<Self::Output>‚Äô.  To represent a sequence of items which become
ready over time, we define a ‚ÄòStream‚Äô trait which puts those features
together:

use std::pin::Pin;
use std::task::{Context, Poll};

trait Stream {
    type Item;

    fn poll_next(
        self: Pin<&mut Self>,
        cx: &mut Context<'_>
    ) -> Poll<Option<Self::Item>>;
}

The ‚ÄòStream‚Äô trait defines an associated type ‚ÄòItem‚Äô for the type of the
items produced by the stream.  This is similar to ‚ÄòIterator‚Äô: there may
be zero to many of these, and unlike ‚ÄòFuture‚Äô, where there is always a
single ‚ÄòOutput‚Äô (even if it's the unit type ‚Äò()‚Äô).

‚ÄòStream‚Äô also defines a method to get those items.  We call it
‚Äòpoll_next‚Äô, to make it clear that it polls in the same way
‚ÄòFuture::poll‚Äô does and produces a sequence of items in the same way
‚ÄòIterator::next‚Äô does.  Its return type combines ‚ÄòPoll‚Äô with ‚ÄòOption‚Äô.
The outer type is ‚ÄòPoll‚Äô, because it has to be checked for readiness,
just as a future does.  The inner type is ‚ÄòOption‚Äô, because it needs to
signal whether there are more messages, just as an iterator does.

Something very similar to this will likely end up standardized as part
of Rust's standard library.  In the meantime, it's part of the toolkit
of most runtimes, so you can rely on it, and everything we cover below
should generally apply!

In the example we saw in the section on streaming, though, we didn't use
‚Äòpoll_next‚Äô ‚Äòor‚Äô ‚ÄòStream‚Äô, but instead used ‚Äònext‚Äô and ‚ÄòStreamExt‚Äô.  We
‚Äòcould‚Äô work directly in terms of the ‚Äòpoll_next‚Äô API by hand-writing
our own ‚ÄòStream‚Äô state machines, of course, just as we ‚Äòcould‚Äô work with
futures directly via their ‚Äòpoll‚Äô method.  Using ‚Äòawait‚Äô is much nicer,
though, so the ‚ÄòStreamExt‚Äô trait supplies the ‚Äònext‚Äô method so we can do
just that.

trait StreamExt: Stream {
    async fn next(&mut self) -> Option<Self::Item>
    where
        Self: Unpin;

    // other methods...
}

Note: The actual definition we used earlier in the chapter looks
slightly different than this, because it supports versions of Rust which
did not yet support using async functions in traits.  As a result, it
looks like this:

fn next(&mut self) -> Next<'_, Self> where Self: Unpin;

That ‚ÄòNext‚Äô type is a ‚Äòstruct‚Äô which implements ‚ÄòFuture‚Äô and gives a way
to name the lifetime of the reference to ‚Äòself‚Äô with ‚ÄòNext<'_, Self>‚Äô,
so that ‚Äòawait‚Äô can work with this method!

The ‚ÄòStreamExt‚Äô trait is also the home of all the interesting methods
available to use with streams.  ‚ÄòStreamExt‚Äô is automatically implemented
for every type which implements ‚ÄòStream‚Äô, but these traits are defined
separately so that the community can iterate on the foundational trait
distinctly from the convenience APIs.

In the version of ‚ÄòStreamExt‚Äô used in the ‚Äòtrpl‚Äô crate, the trait not
only defines the ‚Äònext‚Äô method, it also supplies an implementation of
‚Äònext‚Äô, which correctly handles the details of calling
‚ÄòStream::poll_next‚Äô.  This means that even when you need to write your
own streaming data type, you ‚Äòonly‚Äô have to implement ‚ÄòStream‚Äô, and then
anyone who uses your data type can use ‚ÄòStreamExt‚Äô and its methods with
it automatically.

That's all we're going to cover for the lower-level details on these
traits.  To wrap up, let's consider how futures (including streams),
tasks, and threads all fit together!


