20.1.1 Objects Contain Data and Behavior
----------------------------------------

The book ‚ÄòDesign Patterns: Elements of Reusable Object-Oriented
Software‚Äô by Erich Gamma, Richard Helm, Ralph Johnson, and John
Vlissides (Addison-Wesley Professional, 1994), colloquially referred to
as ‚ÄòThe Gang of Four‚Äô book, is a catalog of object-oriented design
patterns.  It defines OOP this way:

Object-oriented programs are made up of objects.  An ‚Äòobject‚Äô packages
both data and the procedures that operate on that data.  The procedures
are typically called ‚Äòmethods‚Äô or ‚Äòoperations‚Äô.

Using this definition, Rust is object-oriented: structs and enums have
data, and ‚Äòimpl‚Äô blocks provide methods on structs and enums.  Even
though structs and enums with methods aren't ‚Äòcalled‚Äô objects, they
provide the same functionality, according to the Gang of Four's
definition of objects.


