20.1.1.1 Encapsulation that Hides Implementation Details
........................................................

Another aspect commonly associated with OOP is the idea of
‚Äòencapsulation‚Äô, which means that the implementation details of an
object aren't accessible to code using that object.  Therefore, the only
way to interact with an object is through its public API; code using the
object shouldn't be able to reach into the object's internals and change
data or behavior directly.  This enables the programmer to change and
refactor an object's internals without needing to change the code that
uses the object.

We discussed how to control encapsulation in Chapter 7: we can use the
‚Äòpub‚Äô keyword to decide which modules, types, functions, and methods in
our code should be public, and by default everything else is private.
For example, we can define a struct ‚ÄòAveragedCollection‚Äô that has a
field containing a vector of ‚Äòi32‚Äô values.  The struct can also have a
field that contains the average of the values in the vector, meaning the
average doesn't have to be computed on demand whenever anyone needs it.
In other words, ‚ÄòAveragedCollection‚Äô will cache the calculated average
for us.  Listing 18-1 has the definition of the ‚ÄòAveragedCollection‚Äô
struct:

pub struct AveragedCollection {
    list: Vec<i32>,
    average: f64,
}

The struct is marked ‚Äòpub‚Äô so that other code can use it, but the fields
within the struct remain private.  This is important in this case
because we want to ensure that whenever a value is added or removed from
the list, the average is also updated.  We do this by implementing
‚Äòadd‚Äô, ‚Äòremove‚Äô, and ‚Äòaverage‚Äô methods on the struct, as shown in
Listing 18-2:

impl AveragedCollection {
    pub fn add(&mut self, value: i32) {
        self.list.push(value);
        self.update_average();
    }

    pub fn remove(&mut self) -> Option<i32> {
        let result = self.list.pop();
        match result {
            Some(value) => {
                self.update_average();
                Some(value)
            }
            None => None,
        }
    }

    pub fn average(&self) -> f64 {
        self.average
    }

    fn update_average(&mut self) {
        let total: i32 = self.list.iter().sum();
        self.average = total as f64 / self.list.len() as f64;
    }
}

The public methods ‚Äòadd‚Äô, ‚Äòremove‚Äô, and ‚Äòaverage‚Äô are the only ways to
access or modify data in an instance of ‚ÄòAveragedCollection‚Äô.  When an
item is added to ‚Äòlist‚Äô using the ‚Äòadd‚Äô method or removed using the
‚Äòremove‚Äô method, the implementations of each call the private
‚Äòupdate_average‚Äô method that handles updating the ‚Äòaverage‚Äô field as
well.

We leave the ‚Äòlist‚Äô and ‚Äòaverage‚Äô fields private so there is no way for
external code to add or remove items to or from the ‚Äòlist‚Äô field
directly; otherwise, the ‚Äòaverage‚Äô field might become out of sync when
the ‚Äòlist‚Äô changes.  The ‚Äòaverage‚Äô method returns the value in the
‚Äòaverage‚Äô field, allowing external code to read the ‚Äòaverage‚Äô but not
modify it.

Because we've encapsulated the implementation details of the struct
‚ÄòAveragedCollection‚Äô, we can easily change aspects, such as the data
structure, in the future.  For instance, we could use a ‚ÄòHashSet<i32>‚Äô
instead of a ‚ÄòVec<i32>‚Äô for the ‚Äòlist‚Äô field.  As long as the signatures
of the ‚Äòadd‚Äô, ‚Äòremove‚Äô, and ‚Äòaverage‚Äô public methods stay the same, code
using ‚ÄòAveragedCollection‚Äô wouldn't need to change in order to compile.
If we made ‚Äòlist‚Äô public instead, this wouldn't necessarily be the case:
‚ÄòHashSet<i32>‚Äô and ‚ÄòVec<i32>‚Äô have different methods for adding and
removing items, so the external code would likely have to change if it
were modifying ‚Äòlist‚Äô directly.

If encapsulation is a required aspect for a language to be considered
object-oriented, then Rust meets that requirement.  The option to use
‚Äòpub‚Äô or not for different parts of code enables encapsulation of
implementation details.


