20.1.2 Using Trait Objects That Allow for Values of Different Types
-------------------------------------------------------------------

In Chapter 8, we mentioned that one limitation of vectors is that they
can store elements of only one type.  We created a workaround in Listing
8-9 where we defined a ‚ÄòSpreadsheetCell‚Äô enum that had variants to hold
integers, floats, and text.  This meant we could store different types
of data in each cell and still have a vector that represented a row of
cells.  This is a perfectly good solution when our interchangeable items
are a fixed set of types that we know when our code is compiled.

However, sometimes we want our library user to be able to extend the set
of types that are valid in a particular situation.  To show how we might
achieve this, we'll create an example graphical user interface (GUI)
tool that iterates through a list of items, calling a ‚Äòdraw‚Äô method on
each one to draw it to the screen--a common technique for GUI tools.
We'll create a library crate called ‚Äògui‚Äô that contains the structure of
a GUI library.  This crate might include some types for people to use,
such as ‚ÄòButton‚Äô or ‚ÄòTextField‚Äô.  In addition, ‚Äògui‚Äô users will want to
create their own types that can be drawn: for instance, one programmer
might add an ‚ÄòImage‚Äô and another might add a ‚ÄòSelectBox‚Äô.

We won't implement a fully fledged GUI library for this example but will
show how the pieces would fit together.  At the time of writing the
library, we can't know and define all the types other programmers might
want to create.  But we do know that ‚Äògui‚Äô needs to keep track of many
values of different types, and it needs to call a ‚Äòdraw‚Äô method on each
of these differently typed values.  It doesn't need to know exactly what
will happen when we call the ‚Äòdraw‚Äô method, just that the value will
have that method available for us to call.

To do this in a language with inheritance, we might define a class named
‚ÄòComponent‚Äô that has a method named ‚Äòdraw‚Äô on it.  The other classes,
such as ‚ÄòButton‚Äô, ‚ÄòImage‚Äô, and ‚ÄòSelectBox‚Äô, would inherit from
‚ÄòComponent‚Äô and thus inherit the ‚Äòdraw‚Äô method.  They could each
override the ‚Äòdraw‚Äô method to define their custom behavior, but the
framework could treat all of the types as if they were ‚ÄòComponent‚Äô
instances and call ‚Äòdraw‚Äô on them.  But because Rust doesn't have
inheritance, we need another way to structure the ‚Äògui‚Äô library to allow
users to extend it with new types.

