20.1.2.2 Implementing the Trait
...............................

Now we'll add some types that implement the ‚ÄòDraw‚Äô trait.  We'll provide
the ‚ÄòButton‚Äô type.  Again, actually implementing a GUI library is beyond
the scope of this book, so the ‚Äòdraw‚Äô method won't have any useful
implementation in its body.  To imagine what the implementation might
look like, a ‚ÄòButton‚Äô struct might have fields for ‚Äòwidth‚Äô, ‚Äòheight‚Äô,
and ‚Äòlabel‚Äô, as shown in Listing 18-7:

pub struct Button {
    pub width: u32,
    pub height: u32,
    pub label: String,
}

impl Draw for Button {
    fn draw(&self) {
        // code to actually draw a button
    }
}

The ‚Äòwidth‚Äô, ‚Äòheight‚Äô, and ‚Äòlabel‚Äô fields on ‚ÄòButton‚Äô will differ from
the fields on other components; for example, a ‚ÄòTextField‚Äô type might
have those same fields plus a ‚Äòplaceholder‚Äô field.  Each of the types we
want to draw on the screen will implement the ‚ÄòDraw‚Äô trait but will use
different code in the ‚Äòdraw‚Äô method to define how to draw that
particular type, as ‚ÄòButton‚Äô has here (without the actual GUI code, as
mentioned).  The ‚ÄòButton‚Äô type, for instance, might have an additional
‚Äòimpl‚Äô block containing methods related to what happens when a user
clicks the button.  These kinds of methods won't apply to types like
‚ÄòTextField‚Äô.

If someone using our library decides to implement a ‚ÄòSelectBox‚Äô struct
that has ‚Äòwidth‚Äô, ‚Äòheight‚Äô, and ‚Äòoptions‚Äô fields, they implement the
‚ÄòDraw‚Äô trait on the ‚ÄòSelectBox‚Äô type as well, as shown in Listing 18-8:

use gui::Draw;

struct SelectBox {
    width: u32,
    height: u32,
    options: Vec<String>,
}

impl Draw for SelectBox {
    fn draw(&self) {
        // code to actually draw a select box
    }
}

Our library's user can now write their ‚Äòmain‚Äô function to create a
‚ÄòScreen‚Äô instance.  To the ‚ÄòScreen‚Äô instance, they can add a ‚ÄòSelectBox‚Äô
and a ‚ÄòButton‚Äô by putting each in a ‚ÄòBox<T>‚Äô to become a trait object.
They can then call the ‚Äòrun‚Äô method on the ‚ÄòScreen‚Äô instance, which will
call ‚Äòdraw‚Äô on each of the components.  Listing 18-9 shows this
implementation:

use gui::{Button, Screen};

fn main() {
    let screen = Screen {
        components: vec![
            Box::new(SelectBox {
                width: 75,
                height: 10,
                options: vec![
                    String::from("Yes"),
                    String::from("Maybe"),
                    String::from("No"),
                ],
            }),
            Box::new(Button {
                width: 50,
                height: 10,
                label: String::from("OK"),
            }),
        ],
    };

    screen.run();
}

When we wrote the library, we didn't know that someone might add the
‚ÄòSelectBox‚Äô type, but our ‚ÄòScreen‚Äô implementation was able to operate on
the new type and draw it because ‚ÄòSelectBox‚Äô implements the ‚ÄòDraw‚Äô
trait, which means it implements the ‚Äòdraw‚Äô method.

This concept--of being concerned only with the messages a value responds
to rather than the value's concrete type--is similar to the concept of
‚Äòduck typing‚Äô in dynamically typed languages: if it walks like a duck
and quacks like a duck, then it must be a duck!  In the implementation
of ‚Äòrun‚Äô on ‚ÄòScreen‚Äô in Listing 18-5, ‚Äòrun‚Äô doesn't need to know what
the concrete type of each component is.  It doesn't check whether a
component is an instance of a ‚ÄòButton‚Äô or a ‚ÄòSelectBox‚Äô, it just calls
the ‚Äòdraw‚Äô method on the component.  By specifying ‚ÄòBox<dyn Draw>‚Äô as
the type of the values in the ‚Äòcomponents‚Äô vector, we've defined
‚ÄòScreen‚Äô to need values that we can call the ‚Äòdraw‚Äô method on.

The advantage of using trait objects and Rust's type system to write
code similar to code using duck typing is that we never have to check
whether a value implements a particular method at runtime or worry about
getting errors if a value doesn't implement a method but we call it
anyway.  Rust won't compile our code if the values don't implement the
traits that the trait objects need.

For example, Listing 18-10 shows what happens if we try to create a
‚ÄòScreen‚Äô with a ‚ÄòString‚Äô as a component:

use gui::Screen;

fn main() {
    let screen = Screen {
        components: vec![Box::new(String::from("Hi"))],
    };

    screen.run();
}

