20.1.3.4 Requesting a Review of the Post Changes Its State
..........................................................

Next, we need to add functionality to request a review of a post, which
should change its state from ‚ÄòDraft‚Äô to ‚ÄòPendingReview‚Äô.  Listing 18-15
shows this code:

impl Post {
    // --snip--
    pub fn request_review(&mut self) {
        if let Some(s) = self.state.take() {
            self.state = Some(s.request_review())
        }
    }
}

trait State {
    fn request_review(self: Box<Self>) -> Box<dyn State>;
}

struct Draft {}

impl State for Draft {
    fn request_review(self: Box<Self>) -> Box<dyn State> {
        Box::new(PendingReview {})
    }
}

struct PendingReview {}

impl State for PendingReview {
    fn request_review(self: Box<Self>) -> Box<dyn State> {
        self
    }
}

We give ‚ÄòPost‚Äô a public method named ‚Äòrequest_review‚Äô that will take a
mutable reference to ‚Äòself‚Äô.  Then we call an internal ‚Äòrequest_review‚Äô
method on the current state of ‚ÄòPost‚Äô, and this second ‚Äòrequest_review‚Äô
method consumes the current state and returns a new state.

We add the ‚Äòrequest_review‚Äô method to the ‚ÄòState‚Äô trait; all types that
implement the trait will now need to implement the ‚Äòrequest_review‚Äô
method.  Note that rather than having ‚Äòself‚Äô, ‚Äò&self‚Äô, or ‚Äò&mut self‚Äô as
the first parameter of the method, we have ‚Äòself: Box<Self>‚Äô.  This
syntax means the method is only valid when called on a ‚ÄòBox‚Äô holding the
type.  This syntax takes ownership of ‚ÄòBox<Self>‚Äô, invalidating the old
state so the state value of the ‚ÄòPost‚Äô can transform into a new state.

To consume the old state, the ‚Äòrequest_review‚Äô method needs to take
ownership of the state value.  This is where the ‚ÄòOption‚Äô in the ‚Äòstate‚Äô
field of ‚ÄòPost‚Äô comes in: we call the ‚Äòtake‚Äô method to take the ‚ÄòSome‚Äô
value out of the ‚Äòstate‚Äô field and leave a ‚ÄòNone‚Äô in its place, because
Rust doesn't let us have unpopulated fields in structs.  This lets us
move the ‚Äòstate‚Äô value out of ‚ÄòPost‚Äô rather than borrowing it.  Then
we'll set the post's ‚Äòstate‚Äô value to the result of this operation.

We need to set ‚Äòstate‚Äô to ‚ÄòNone‚Äô temporarily rather than setting it
directly with code like ‚Äòself.state = self.state.request_review();‚Äô to
get ownership of the ‚Äòstate‚Äô value.  This ensures ‚ÄòPost‚Äô can't use the
old ‚Äòstate‚Äô value after we've transformed it into a new state.

The ‚Äòrequest_review‚Äô method on ‚ÄòDraft‚Äô returns a new, boxed instance of
a new ‚ÄòPendingReview‚Äô struct, which represents the state when a post is
waiting for a review.  The ‚ÄòPendingReview‚Äô struct also implements the
‚Äòrequest_review‚Äô method but doesn't do any transformations.  Rather, it
returns itself, because when we request a review on a post already in
the ‚ÄòPendingReview‚Äô state, it should stay in the ‚ÄòPendingReview‚Äô state.

Now we can start seeing the advantages of the state pattern: the
‚Äòrequest_review‚Äô method on ‚ÄòPost‚Äô is the same no matter its ‚Äòstate‚Äô
value.  Each state is responsible for its own rules.

We'll leave the ‚Äòcontent‚Äô method on ‚ÄòPost‚Äô as is, returning an empty
string slice.  We can now have a ‚ÄòPost‚Äô in the ‚ÄòPendingReview‚Äô state as
well as in the ‚ÄòDraft‚Äô state, but we want the same behavior in the
‚ÄòPendingReview‚Äô state.  Listing 18-11 now works up to line 10!


