20.1.3.6 Trade-offs of the State Pattern
........................................

We've shown that Rust is capable of implementing the object-oriented
state pattern to encapsulate the different kinds of behavior a post
should have in each state.  The methods on ‚ÄòPost‚Äô know nothing about the
various behaviors.  The way we organized the code, we have to look in
only one place to know the different ways a published post can behave:
the implementation of the ‚ÄòState‚Äô trait on the ‚ÄòPublished‚Äô struct.

If we were to create an alternative implementation that didn't use the
state pattern, we might instead use ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expressions in the methods
on ‚ÄòPost‚Äô or even in the ‚Äòmain‚Äô code that checks the state of the post
and changes behavior in those places.  That would mean we would have to
look in several places to understand all the implications of a post
being in the published state!  This would only increase the more states
we added: each of those ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expressions would need another arm.

With the state pattern, the ‚ÄòPost‚Äô methods and the places we use ‚ÄòPost‚Äô
don't need ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expressions, and to add a new state, we would only
need to add a new struct and implement the trait methods on that one
struct.

The implementation using the state pattern is easy to extend to add more
functionality.  To see the simplicity of maintaining code that uses the
state pattern, try a few of these suggestions:

   ‚Ä¢ Add a ‚Äòreject‚Äô method that changes the post's state from
     ‚ÄòPendingReview‚Äô back to ‚ÄòDraft‚Äô.
   ‚Ä¢ Require two calls to ‚Äòapprove‚Äô before the state can be changed to
     ‚ÄòPublished‚Äô.
   ‚Ä¢ Allow users to add text content only when a post is in the ‚ÄòDraft‚Äô
     state.  Hint: have the state object responsible for what might
     change about the content but not responsible for modifying the
     ‚ÄòPost‚Äô.

One downside of the state pattern is that, because the states implement
the transitions between states, some of the states are coupled to each
other.  If we add another state between ‚ÄòPendingReview‚Äô and ‚ÄòPublished‚Äô,
such as ‚ÄòScheduled‚Äô, we would have to change the code in ‚ÄòPendingReview‚Äô
to transition to ‚ÄòScheduled‚Äô instead.  It would be less work if
‚ÄòPendingReview‚Äô didn't need to change with the addition of a new state,
but that would mean switching to another design pattern.

Another downside is that we've duplicated some logic.  To eliminate some
of the duplication, we might try to make default implementations for the
‚Äòrequest_review‚Äô and ‚Äòapprove‚Äô methods on the ‚ÄòState‚Äô trait that return
‚Äòself‚Äô; however, this would not be dyn compatible, because the trait
doesn't know what the concrete ‚Äòself‚Äô will be exactly.  We want to be
able to use ‚ÄòState‚Äô as a trait object, so we need its methods to be dyn
compatible.

Other duplication includes the similar implementations of the
‚Äòrequest_review‚Äô and ‚Äòapprove‚Äô methods on ‚ÄòPost‚Äô.  Both methods delegate
to the implementation of the same method on the value in the ‚Äòstate‚Äô
field of ‚ÄòOption‚Äô and set the new value of the ‚Äòstate‚Äô field to the
result.  If we had a lot of methods on ‚ÄòPost‚Äô that followed this
pattern, we might consider defining a macro to eliminate the repetition
(see the *note ‚ÄúMacros‚Äù: Macros. section in Chapter 20).

By implementing the state pattern exactly as it's defined for
object-oriented languages, we're not taking as full advantage of Rust's
strengths as we could.  Let's look at some changes we can make to the
‚Äòblog‚Äô crate that can make invalid states and transitions into compile
time errors.  Encoding States and Behavior as Types We'll show you how
to rethink the state pattern to get a different set of trade-offs.
Rather than encapsulating the states and transitions completely so
outside code has no knowledge of them, we'll encode the states into
different types.  Consequently, Rust's type checking system will prevent
attempts to use draft posts where only published posts are allowed by
issuing a compiler error.

Let's consider the first part of ‚Äòmain‚Äô in Listing 18-11:

fn main() {
    let mut post = Post::new();

    post.add_text("I ate a salad for lunch today");
    assert_eq!("", post.content());
}

We still enable the creation of new posts in the draft state using
‚ÄòPost::new‚Äô and the ability to add text to the post's content.  But
instead of having a ‚Äòcontent‚Äô method on a draft post that returns an
empty string, we'll make it so draft posts don't have the ‚Äòcontent‚Äô
method at all.  That way, if we try to get a draft post's content, we'll
get a compiler error telling us the method doesn't exist.  As a result,
it will be impossible for us to accidentally display draft post content
in production, because that code won't even compile.  Listing 18-19
shows the definition of a ‚ÄòPost‚Äô struct and a ‚ÄòDraftPost‚Äô struct, as
well as methods on each:

pub struct Post {
    content: String,
}

pub struct DraftPost {
    content: String,
}

impl Post {
    pub fn new() -> DraftPost {
        DraftPost {
            content: String::new(),
        }
    }

    pub fn content(&self) -> &str {
        &self.content
    }
}

impl DraftPost {
    pub fn add_text(&mut self, text: &str) {
        self.content.push_str(text);
    }
}

Both the ‚ÄòPost‚Äô and ‚ÄòDraftPost‚Äô structs have a private ‚Äòcontent‚Äô field
that stores the blog post text.  The structs no longer have the ‚Äòstate‚Äô
field because we're moving the encoding of the state to the types of the
structs.  The ‚ÄòPost‚Äô struct will represent a published post, and it has
a ‚Äòcontent‚Äô method that returns the ‚Äòcontent‚Äô.

We still have a ‚ÄòPost::new‚Äô function, but instead of returning an
instance of ‚ÄòPost‚Äô, it returns an instance of ‚ÄòDraftPost‚Äô.  Because
‚Äòcontent‚Äô is private and there aren't any functions that return ‚ÄòPost‚Äô,
it's not possible to create an instance of ‚ÄòPost‚Äô right now.

The ‚ÄòDraftPost‚Äô struct has an ‚Äòadd_text‚Äô method, so we can add text to
‚Äòcontent‚Äô as before, but note that ‚ÄòDraftPost‚Äô does not have a ‚Äòcontent‚Äô
method defined!  So now the program ensures all posts start as draft
posts, and draft posts don't have their content available for display.
Any attempt to get around these constraints will result in a compiler
error.  Implementing Transitions as Transformations into Different Types
So how do we get a published post?  We want to enforce the rule that a
draft post has to be reviewed and approved before it can be published.
A post in the pending review state should still not display any content.
Let's implement these constraints by adding another struct,
‚ÄòPendingReviewPost‚Äô, defining the ‚Äòrequest_review‚Äô method on ‚ÄòDraftPost‚Äô
to return a ‚ÄòPendingReviewPost‚Äô, and defining an ‚Äòapprove‚Äô method on
‚ÄòPendingReviewPost‚Äô to return a ‚ÄòPost‚Äô, as shown in Listing 18-20:

impl DraftPost {
    // --snip--
    pub fn request_review(self) -> PendingReviewPost {
        PendingReviewPost {
            content: self.content,
        }
    }
}

pub struct PendingReviewPost {
    content: String,
}

impl PendingReviewPost {
    pub fn approve(self) -> Post {
        Post {
            content: self.content,
        }
    }
}

The ‚Äòrequest_review‚Äô and ‚Äòapprove‚Äô methods take ownership of ‚Äòself‚Äô,
thus consuming the ‚ÄòDraftPost‚Äô and ‚ÄòPendingReviewPost‚Äô instances and
transforming them into a ‚ÄòPendingReviewPost‚Äô and a published ‚ÄòPost‚Äô,
respectively.  This way, we won't have any lingering ‚ÄòDraftPost‚Äô
instances after we've called ‚Äòrequest_review‚Äô on them, and so forth.
The ‚ÄòPendingReviewPost‚Äô struct doesn't have a ‚Äòcontent‚Äô method defined
on it, so attempting to read its content results in a compiler error, as
with ‚ÄòDraftPost‚Äô.  Because the only way to get a published ‚ÄòPost‚Äô
instance that does have a ‚Äòcontent‚Äô method defined is to call the
‚Äòapprove‚Äô method on a ‚ÄòPendingReviewPost‚Äô, and the only way to get a
‚ÄòPendingReviewPost‚Äô is to call the ‚Äòrequest_review‚Äô method on a
‚ÄòDraftPost‚Äô, we've now encoded the blog post workflow into the type
system.

But we also have to make some small changes to ‚Äòmain‚Äô.  The
‚Äòrequest_review‚Äô and ‚Äòapprove‚Äô methods return new instances rather than
modifying the struct they're called on, so we need to add more ‚Äòlet post
=‚Äô shadowing assignments to save the returned instances.  We also can't
have the assertions about the draft and pending review posts' contents
be empty strings, nor do we need them: we can't compile code that tries
to use the content of posts in those states any longer.  The updated
code in ‚Äòmain‚Äô is shown in Listing 18-21:

use blog::Post;

fn main() {
    let mut post = Post::new();

    post.add_text("I ate a salad for lunch today");

    let post = post.request_review();

    let post = post.approve();

    assert_eq!("I ate a salad for lunch today", post.content());
}

The changes we needed to make to ‚Äòmain‚Äô to reassign ‚Äòpost‚Äô mean that
this implementation doesn't quite follow the object-oriented state
pattern anymore: the transformations between the states are no longer
encapsulated entirely within the ‚ÄòPost‚Äô implementation.  However, our
gain is that invalid states are now impossible because of the type
system and the type checking that happens at compile time!  This ensures
that certain bugs, such as display of the content of an unpublished
post, will be discovered before they make it to production.

Try the tasks suggested at the start of this section on the ‚Äòblog‚Äô crate
as it is after Listing 18-21 to see what you think about the design of
this version of the code.  Note that some of the tasks might be
completed already in this design.

We've seen that even though Rust is capable of implementing
object-oriented design patterns, other patterns, such as encoding state
into the type system, are also available in Rust.  These patterns have
different trade-offs.  Although you might be very familiar with
object-oriented patterns, rethinking the problem to take advantage of
Rust's features can provide benefits, such as preventing some bugs at
compile time.  Object-oriented patterns won't always be the best
solution in Rust due to certain features, like ownership, that
object-oriented languages don't have.


