21.1.1.4 ‚Äòlet‚Äô Statements
.........................

Prior to this chapter, we had only explicitly discussed using patterns
with ‚Äòmatch‚Äô and ‚Äòif let‚Äô, but in fact, we've used patterns in other
places as well, including in ‚Äòlet‚Äô statements.  For example, consider
this straightforward variable assignment with ‚Äòlet‚Äô:

let x = 5;

Every time you've used a ‚Äòlet‚Äô statement like this you've been using
patterns, although you might not have realized it!  More formally, a
‚Äòlet‚Äô statement looks like this:

let PATTERN = EXPRESSION;

In statements like ‚Äòlet x = 5;‚Äô with a variable name in the ‚ÄòPATTERN‚Äô
slot, the variable name is just a particularly simple form of a pattern.
Rust compares the expression against the pattern and assigns any names
it finds.  So in the ‚Äòlet x = 5;‚Äô example, ‚Äòx‚Äô is a pattern that means
‚Äúbind what matches here to the variable ‚Äòx‚Äô.‚Äù Because the name ‚Äòx‚Äô is
the whole pattern, this pattern effectively means ‚Äúbind everything to
the variable ‚Äòx‚Äô, whatever the value is.‚Äù

To see the pattern matching aspect of ‚Äòlet‚Äô more clearly, consider
Listing 19-4, which uses a pattern with ‚Äòlet‚Äô to destructure a tuple.

    let (x, y, z) = (1, 2, 3);

Here, we match a tuple against a pattern.  Rust compares the value ‚Äò(1,
2, 3)‚Äô to the pattern ‚Äò(x, y, z)‚Äô and sees that the value matches the
pattern, so Rust binds ‚Äò1‚Äô to ‚Äòx‚Äô, ‚Äò2‚Äô to ‚Äòy‚Äô, and ‚Äò3‚Äô to ‚Äòz‚Äô.  You can
think of this tuple pattern as nesting three individual variable
patterns inside it.

If the number of elements in the pattern doesn't match the number of
elements in the tuple, the overall type won't match and we'll get a
compiler error.  For example, Listing 19-5 shows an attempt to
destructure a tuple with three elements into two variables, which won't
work.

    let (x, y) = (1, 2, 3);

