Because we didn't cover (and couldn't cover!)  every valid value with
the pattern ‚ÄòSome(x)‚Äô, Rust rightfully produces a compiler error.

If we have a refutable pattern where an irrefutable pattern is needed,
we can fix it by changing the code that uses the pattern: instead of
using ‚Äòlet‚Äô, we can use ‚Äòif let‚Äô.  Then if the pattern doesn't match,
the code will just skip the code in the curly brackets, giving it a way
to continue validly.  Listing 19-9 shows how to fix the code in Listing
19-8.

    if let Some(x) = some_option_value {
        println!("{x}");
    }

We've given the code an out!  This code is perfectly valid now.
However, if we give ‚Äòif let‚Äô an irrefutable pattern (a pattern that will
always match), such as ‚Äòx‚Äô, as shown in Listing 19-10, the compiler will
give a warning.

    if let x = 5 {
        println!("{x}");
    };

Rust complains that it doesn't make sense to use ‚Äòif let‚Äô with an
irrefutable pattern:

$ cargo run
   Compiling patterns v0.1.0 (file:///projects/patterns)
warning: irrefutable `if let` pattern
 --> src/main.rs:2:8
  |
2 |     if let x = 5 {
  |        ^^^^^^^^^
  |
  = note: this pattern will always match, so the `if let` is useless
  = help: consider replacing the `if let` with a `let`
  = note: `#[warn(irrefutable_let_patterns)]` on by default

warning: `patterns` (bin "patterns") generated 1 warning
    Finished `dev` profile [unoptimized + debuginfo] target(s) in 0.39s
     Running `target/debug/patterns`
5

For this reason, match arms must use refutable patterns, except for the
last arm, which should match any remaining values with an irrefutable
pattern.  Rust allows us to use an irrefutable pattern in a ‚Äòmatch‚Äô with
only one arm, but this syntax isn't particularly useful and could be
replaced with a simpler ‚Äòlet‚Äô statement.

Now that you know where to use patterns and the difference between
refutable and irrefutable patterns, let's cover all the syntax we can
use to create patterns.


