21.1.3.2 Matching Named Variables
.................................

Named variables are irrefutable patterns that match any value, and we've
used them many times in the book.  However, there is a complication when
you use named variables in ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expressions.  Because ‚Äòmatch‚Äô starts
a new scope, variables declared as part of a pattern inside the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô
expression will shadow those with the same name outside the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô
construct, as is the case with all variables.  In Listing 19-11, we
declare a variable named ‚Äòx‚Äô with the value ‚ÄòSome(5)‚Äô and a variable ‚Äòy‚Äô
with the value ‚Äò10‚Äô.  We then create a ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression on the value
‚Äòx‚Äô.  Look at the patterns in the match arms and ‚Äòprintln!‚Äô at the end,
and try to figure out what the code will print before running this code
or reading further.

    let x = Some(5);
    let y = 10;

    match x {
        Some(50) => println!("Got 50"),
        Some(y) => println!("Matched, y = {y}"),
        _ => println!("Default case, x = {x:?}"),
    }

    println!("at the end: x = {x:?}, y = {y}");

Let's walk through what happens when the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression runs.  The
pattern in the first match arm doesn't match the defined value of ‚Äòx‚Äô,
so the code continues.

The pattern in the second match arm introduces a new variable named ‚Äòy‚Äô
that will match any value inside a ‚ÄòSome‚Äô value.  Because we're in a new
scope inside the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression, this is a new ‚Äòy‚Äô variable, not the
‚Äòy‚Äô we declared at the beginning with the value 10.  This new ‚Äòy‚Äô
binding will match any value inside a ‚ÄòSome‚Äô, which is what we have in
‚Äòx‚Äô.  Therefore, this new ‚Äòy‚Äô binds to the inner value of the ‚ÄòSome‚Äô in
‚Äòx‚Äô.  That value is ‚Äò5‚Äô, so the expression for that arm executes and
prints ‚ÄòMatched, y = 5‚Äô.

If ‚Äòx‚Äô had been a ‚ÄòNone‚Äô value instead of ‚ÄòSome(5)‚Äô, the patterns in the
first two arms wouldn't have matched, so the value would have matched to
the underscore.  We didn't introduce the ‚Äòx‚Äô variable in the pattern of
the underscore arm, so the ‚Äòx‚Äô in the expression is still the outer ‚Äòx‚Äô
that hasn't been shadowed.  In this hypothetical case, the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô would
print ‚ÄòDefault case, x = None‚Äô.

When the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression is done, its scope ends, and so does the
scope of the inner ‚Äòy‚Äô.  The last ‚Äòprintln!‚Äô produces ‚Äòat the end: x =
Some(5), y = 10‚Äô.

To create a ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression that compares the values of the outer ‚Äòx‚Äô
and ‚Äòy‚Äô, rather than introducing a new variable which shadows the
existing ‚Äòy‚Äô variable, we would need to use a match guard conditional
instead.  We'll talk about match guards later in the *note ‚ÄúExtra
Conditionals with Match Guards‚Äù: Extra Conditionals with Match Guards.
section.


