21.1.3.7 Extra Conditionals with Match Guards
.............................................

A ‚Äòmatch guard‚Äô is an additional ‚Äòif‚Äô condition, specified after the
pattern in a ‚Äòmatch‚Äô arm, that must also match for that arm to be
chosen.  Match guards are useful for expressing more complex ideas than
a pattern alone allows.

The condition can use variables created in the pattern.  Listing 19-26
shows a ‚Äòmatch‚Äô where the first arm has the pattern ‚ÄòSome(x)‚Äô and also
has a match guard of ‚Äòif x % 2 == 0‚Äô (which will be true if the number
is even).

    let num = Some(4);

    match num {
        Some(x) if x % 2 == 0 => println!("The number {x} is even"),
        Some(x) => println!("The number {x} is odd"),
        None => (),
    }

This example will print ‚ÄòThe number 4 is even‚Äô.  When ‚Äònum‚Äô is compared
to the pattern in the first arm, it matches, because ‚ÄòSome(4)‚Äô matches
‚ÄòSome(x)‚Äô.  Then the match guard checks whether the remainder of
dividing ‚Äòx‚Äô by 2 is equal to 0, and because it is, the first arm is
selected.

If ‚Äònum‚Äô had been ‚ÄòSome(5)‚Äô instead, the match guard in the first arm
would have been false because the remainder of 5 divided by 2 is 1,
which is not equal to 0.  Rust would then go to the second arm, which
would match because the second arm doesn't have a match guard and
therefore matches any ‚ÄòSome‚Äô variant.

There is no way to express the ‚Äòif x % 2 == 0‚Äô condition within a
pattern, so the match guard gives us the ability to express this logic.
The downside of this additional expressiveness is that the compiler
doesn't try to check for exhaustiveness when match guard expressions are
involved.

In Listing 19-11, we mentioned that we could use match guards to solve
our pattern-shadowing problem.  Recall that we created a new variable
inside the pattern in the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression instead of using the
variable outside the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô.  That new variable meant we couldn't test
against the value of the outer variable.  Listing 19-27 shows how we can
use a match guard to fix this problem.

fn main() {
    let x = Some(5);
    let y = 10;

    match x {
        Some(50) => println!("Got 50"),
        Some(n) if n == y => println!("Matched, n = {n}"),
        _ => println!("Default case, x = {x:?}"),
    }

    println!("at the end: x = {x:?}, y = {y}");
}

This code will now print ‚ÄòDefault case, x = Some(5)‚Äô.  The pattern in
the second match arm doesn't introduce a new variable ‚Äòy‚Äô that would
shadow the outer ‚Äòy‚Äô, meaning we can use the outer ‚Äòy‚Äô in the match
guard.  Instead of specifying the pattern as ‚ÄòSome(y)‚Äô, which would have
shadowed the outer ‚Äòy‚Äô, we specify ‚ÄòSome(n)‚Äô.  This creates a new
variable ‚Äòn‚Äô that doesn't shadow anything because there is no ‚Äòn‚Äô
variable outside the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô.

The match guard ‚Äòif n == y‚Äô is not a pattern and therefore doesn't
introduce new variables.  This ‚Äòy‚Äô ‚Äòis‚Äô the outer ‚Äòy‚Äô rather than a new
‚Äòy‚Äô shadowing it, and we can look for a value that has the same value as
the outer ‚Äòy‚Äô by comparing ‚Äòn‚Äô to ‚Äòy‚Äô.

You can also use the ‚Äòor‚Äô operator ‚Äò|‚Äô in a match guard to specify
multiple patterns; the match guard condition will apply to all the
patterns.  Listing 19-28 shows the precedence when combining a pattern
that uses ‚Äò|‚Äô with a match guard.  The important part of this example is
that the ‚Äòif y‚Äô match guard applies to ‚Äò4‚Äô, ‚Äò5‚Äô, ‚Äòand‚Äô ‚Äò6‚Äô, even though
it might look like ‚Äòif y‚Äô only applies to ‚Äò6‚Äô.

    let x = 4;
    let y = false;

    match x {
        4 | 5 | 6 if y => println!("yes"),
        _ => println!("no"),
    }

The match condition states that the arm only matches if the value of ‚Äòx‚Äô
is equal to ‚Äò4‚Äô, ‚Äò5‚Äô, or ‚Äò6‚Äô ‚Äòand‚Äô if ‚Äòy‚Äô is ‚Äòtrue‚Äô.  When this code
runs, the pattern of the first arm matches because ‚Äòx‚Äô is ‚Äò4‚Äô, but the
match guard ‚Äòif y‚Äô is false, so the first arm is not chosen.  The code
moves on to the second arm, which does match, and this program prints
‚Äòno‚Äô.  The reason is that the ‚Äòif‚Äô condition applies to the whole
pattern ‚Äò4 | 5 | 6‚Äô, not only to the last value ‚Äò6‚Äô.  In other words,
the precedence of a match guard in relation to a pattern behaves like
this:

(4 | 5 | 6) if y => ...

rather than this:

4 | 5 | (6 if y) => ...

After running the code, the precedence behavior is evident: if the match
guard were applied only to the final value in the list of values
specified using the ‚Äò|‚Äô operator, the arm would have matched and the
program would have printed ‚Äòyes‚Äô.


