22.1.1 Unsafe Superpowers
-------------------------

To switch to unsafe Rust, use the ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô keyword and then start a new
block that holds the unsafe code.  You can take five actions in unsafe
Rust that you can't in safe Rust, which we call ‚Äòunsafe superpowers‚Äô.
Those superpowers include the ability to:

   ‚Ä¢ Dereference a raw pointer
   ‚Ä¢ Call an unsafe function or method
   ‚Ä¢ Access or modify a mutable static variable
   ‚Ä¢ Implement an unsafe trait
   ‚Ä¢ Access fields of a ‚Äòunion‚Äô

It's important to understand that ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô doesn't turn off the borrow
checker or disable any other of Rust's safety checks: if you use a
reference in unsafe code, it will still be checked.  The ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô
keyword only gives you access to these five features that are then not
checked by the compiler for memory safety.  You'll still get some degree
of safety inside of an unsafe block.

In addition, ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô does not mean the code inside the block is
necessarily dangerous or that it will definitely have memory safety
problems: the intent is that as the programmer, you'll ensure the code
inside an ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô block will access memory in a valid way.

People are fallible, and mistakes will happen, but by requiring these
five unsafe operations to be inside blocks annotated with ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô
you'll know that any errors related to memory safety must be within an
‚Äòunsafe‚Äô block.  Keep ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô blocks small; you'll be thankful later
when you investigate memory bugs.

To isolate unsafe code as much as possible, it's best to enclose unsafe
code within a safe abstraction and provide a safe API, which we'll
discuss later in the chapter when we examine unsafe functions and
methods.  Parts of the standard library are implemented as safe
abstractions over unsafe code that has been audited.  Wrapping unsafe
code in a safe abstraction prevents uses of ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô from leaking out
into all the places that you or your users might want to use the
functionality implemented with ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô code, because using a safe
abstraction is safe.

Let's look at each of the five unsafe superpowers in turn.  We'll also
look at some abstractions that provide a safe interface to unsafe code.


