22.1.1.1 Dereferencing a Raw Pointer
....................................

In Chapter 4, in the *note ‚ÄúDangling References‚Äù: Dangling References.
section, we mentioned that the compiler ensures references are always
valid.  Unsafe Rust has two new types called ‚Äòraw pointers‚Äô that are
similar to references.  As with references, raw pointers can be
immutable or mutable and are written as ‚Äò*const T‚Äô and ‚Äò*mut T‚Äô,
respectively.  The asterisk isn't the dereference operator; it's part of
the type name.  In the context of raw pointers, ‚Äòimmutable‚Äô means that
the pointer can't be directly assigned to after being dereferenced.

Different from references and smart pointers, raw pointers:

   ‚Ä¢ Are allowed to ignore the borrowing rules by having both immutable
     and mutable pointers or multiple mutable pointers to the same
     location
   ‚Ä¢ Aren't guaranteed to point to valid memory
   ‚Ä¢ Are allowed to be null
   ‚Ä¢ Don't implement any automatic cleanup

By opting out of having Rust enforce these guarantees, you can give up
guaranteed safety in exchange for greater performance or the ability to
interface with another language or hardware where Rust's guarantees
don't apply.

Listing 20-1 shows how to create an immutable and a mutable raw pointer.

    let mut num = 5;

    let r1 = &raw const num;
    let r2 = &raw mut num;

Notice that we don't include the ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô keyword in this code.  We can
create raw pointers in safe code; we just can't dereference raw pointers
outside an unsafe block, as you'll see in a bit.

We've created raw pointers by using the raw borrow operators: ‚Äò&raw
const num‚Äô creates a ‚Äò*const i32‚Äô immutable raw pointer, and ‚Äò&raw mut
num‚Äô creates a ‚Äò*mut i32‚Äô mutable raw pointer.  Because we created them
directly from a local variable, we know these particular raw pointers
are valid, but we can't make that assumption about just any raw pointer.

To demonstrate this, next we'll create a raw pointer whose validity we
can't be so certain of, using ‚Äòas‚Äô to cast a value instead of using the
raw reference operators.  Listing 20-2 shows how to create a raw pointer
to an arbitrary location in memory.  Trying to use arbitrary memory is
undefined: there might be data at that address or there might not, the
compiler might optimize the code so there is no memory access, or the
program might error with a segmentation fault.  Usually, there is no
good reason to write code like this, especially in cases where you can
use a raw borrow operator instead, but it is possible.

    let address = 0x012345usize;
    let r = address as *const i32;

Recall that we can create raw pointers in safe code, but we can't
‚Äòdereference‚Äô raw pointers and read the data being pointed to.  In
Listing 20-3, we use the dereference operator ‚Äò*‚Äô on a raw pointer that
requires an ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô block.

    let mut num = 5;

    let r1 = &raw const num;
    let r2 = &raw mut num;

    unsafe {
        println!("r1 is: {}", *r1);
        println!("r2 is: {}", *r2);
    }

Creating a pointer does no harm; it's only when we try to access the
value that it points at that we might end up dealing with an invalid
value.

Note also that in Listing 20-1 and 20-3, we created ‚Äò*const i32‚Äô and
‚Äò*mut i32‚Äô raw pointers that both pointed to the same memory location,
where ‚Äònum‚Äô is stored.  If we instead tried to create an immutable and a
mutable reference to ‚Äònum‚Äô, the code would not have compiled because
Rust's ownership rules don't allow a mutable reference at the same time
as any immutable references.  With raw pointers, we can create a mutable
pointer and an immutable pointer to the same location and change data
through the mutable pointer, potentially creating a data race.  Be
careful!

With all of these dangers, why would you ever use raw pointers?  One
major use case is when interfacing with C code, as you'll see in the
next section, *note ‚ÄúCalling an Unsafe Function or Method‚Äù: Calling an
Unsafe Function or Method. Another case is when building up safe
abstractions that the borrow checker doesn't understand.  We'll
introduce unsafe functions and then look at an example of a safe
abstraction that uses unsafe code.


