error: could not compile `unsafe-example` (bin "unsafe-example") due to 1 previous error

Rust's borrow checker can't understand that we're borrowing different
parts of the slice; it only knows that we're borrowing from the same
slice twice.  Borrowing different parts of a slice is fundamentally okay
because the two slices aren't overlapping, but Rust isn't smart enough
to know this.  When we know code is okay, but Rust doesn't, it's time to
reach for unsafe code.

Listing 20-6 shows how to use an ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô block, a raw pointer, and some
calls to unsafe functions to make the implementation of ‚Äòsplit_at_mut‚Äô
work.

use std::slice;

fn split_at_mut(values: &mut [i32], mid: usize) -> (&mut [i32], &mut [i32]) {
    let len = values.len();
    let ptr = values.as_mut_ptr();

    assert!(mid <= len);

    unsafe {
        (
            slice::from_raw_parts_mut(ptr, mid),
            slice::from_raw_parts_mut(ptr.add(mid), len - mid),
        )
    }
}

Recall from *note ‚ÄúThe Slice Type‚Äù: The Slice Type. section in Chapter 4
that slices are a pointer to some data and the length of the slice.  We
use the ‚Äòlen‚Äô method to get the length of a slice and the ‚Äòas_mut_ptr‚Äô
method to access the raw pointer of a slice.  In this case, because we
have a mutable slice to ‚Äòi32‚Äô values, ‚Äòas_mut_ptr‚Äô returns a raw pointer
with the type ‚Äò*mut i32‚Äô, which we've stored in the variable ‚Äòptr‚Äô.

We keep the assertion that the ‚Äòmid‚Äô index is within the slice.  Then we
get to the unsafe code: the ‚Äòslice::from_raw_parts_mut‚Äô function takes a
raw pointer and a length, and it creates a slice.  We use this function
to create a slice that starts from ‚Äòptr‚Äô and is ‚Äòmid‚Äô items long.  Then
we call the ‚Äòadd‚Äô method on ‚Äòptr‚Äô with ‚Äòmid‚Äô as an argument to get a raw
pointer that starts at ‚Äòmid‚Äô, and we create a slice using that pointer
and the remaining number of items after ‚Äòmid‚Äô as the length.

The function ‚Äòslice::from_raw_parts_mut‚Äô is unsafe because it takes a
raw pointer and must trust that this pointer is valid.  The ‚Äòadd‚Äô method
on raw pointers is also unsafe, because it must trust that the offset
location is also a valid pointer.  Therefore, we had to put an ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô
block around our calls to ‚Äòslice::from_raw_parts_mut‚Äô and ‚Äòadd‚Äô so we
could call them.  By looking at the code and by adding the assertion
that ‚Äòmid‚Äô must be less than or equal to ‚Äòlen‚Äô, we can tell that all the
raw pointers used within the ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô block will be valid pointers to
data within the slice.  This is an acceptable and appropriate use of
‚Äòunsafe‚Äô.

Note that we don't need to mark the resulting ‚Äòsplit_at_mut‚Äô function as
‚Äòunsafe‚Äô, and we can call this function from safe Rust.  We've created a
safe abstraction to the unsafe code with an implementation of the
function that uses ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô code in a safe way, because it creates only
valid pointers from the data this function has access to.

In contrast, the use of ‚Äòslice::from_raw_parts_mut‚Äô in Listing 20-7
would likely crash when the slice is used.  This code takes an arbitrary
memory location and creates a slice 10,000 items long.

    use std::slice;

    let address = 0x01234usize;
    let r = address as *mut i32;

    let values: &[i32] = unsafe { slice::from_raw_parts_mut(r, 10000) };

We don't own the memory at this arbitrary location, and there is no
guarantee that the slice this code creates contains valid ‚Äòi32‚Äô values.
Attempting to use ‚Äòvalues‚Äô as though it's a valid slice results in
undefined behavior.  Using ‚Äòextern‚Äô Functions to Call External Code
Sometimes, your Rust code might need to interact with code written in
another language.  For this, Rust has the keyword ‚Äòextern‚Äô that
facilitates the creation and use of a ‚ÄòForeign Function Interface
(FFI)‚Äô.  An FFI is a way for a programming language to define functions
and enable a different (foreign) programming language to call those
functions.

Listing 20-8 demonstrates how to set up an integration with the ‚Äòabs‚Äô
function from the C standard library.  Functions declared within
‚Äòextern‚Äô blocks are usually unsafe to call from Rust code, so they must
also be marked ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô.  The reason is that other languages don't
enforce Rust's rules and guarantees, and Rust can't check them, so
responsibility falls on the programmer to ensure safety.

unsafe extern "C" {
    fn abs(input: i32) -> i32;
}

fn main() {
    unsafe {
        println!("Absolute value of -3 according to C: {}", abs(-3));
    }
}

Within the ‚Äòunsafe extern "C"‚Äô block, we list the names and signatures
of external functions from another language we want to call.  The ‚Äò"C"‚Äô
part defines which ‚Äòapplication binary interface (ABI)‚Äô the external
function uses: the ABI defines how to call the function at the assembly
level.  The ‚Äò"C"‚Äô ABI is the most common and follows the C programming
language's ABI.

This particular function does not have any memory safety considerations,
though.  In fact, we know that any call to ‚Äòabs‚Äô will always be safe for
any ‚Äòi32‚Äô, so we can use the ‚Äòsafe‚Äô keyword to say that this specific
function is safe to call even though it is in an ‚Äòunsafe extern‚Äô block.
Once we make that change, calling it no longer requires an ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô
block, as shown in Listing 20-9.

unsafe extern "C" {
    safe fn abs(input: i32) -> i32;
}

fn main() {
    println!("Absolute value of -3 according to C: {}", abs(-3));
}

Marking a function as ‚Äòsafe‚Äô does not inherently make it safe!  Instead,
it is like a promise you are making to Rust that it ‚Äòis‚Äô safe.  It is
still your responsibility to make sure that promise is kept!

Calling Rust Functions from Other Languages We can also use ‚Äòextern‚Äô to
create an interface that allows other languages to call Rust functions.
Instead of creating a whole ‚Äòextern‚Äô block, we add the ‚Äòextern‚Äô keyword
and specify the ABI to use just before the ‚Äòfn‚Äô keyword for the relevant
function.  We also need to add a ‚Äò#[unsafe(no_mangle)]‚Äô annotation to
tell the Rust compiler not to mangle the name of this function.
‚ÄòMangling‚Äô is when a compiler changes the name we've given a function to
a different name that contains more information for other parts of the
compilation process to consume but is less human readable.  Every
programming language compiler mangles names slightly differently, so for
a Rust function to be nameable by other languages, we must disable the
Rust compiler's name mangling.  This is unsafe because there might be
name collisions across libraries without the built-in mangling, so it is
our responsibility to make sure the name we have exported is safe to
export without mangling.

In the following example, we make the ‚Äòcall_from_c‚Äô function accessible
from C code, after it's compiled to a shared library and linked from C:

pub extern "C" fn call_from_c() {
    println!("Just called a Rust function from C!");
}

This usage of ‚Äòextern‚Äô does not require ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô.


