22.1.1.4 Implementing an Unsafe Trait
.....................................

We can use ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô to implement an unsafe trait.  A trait is unsafe
when at least one of its methods has some invariant that the compiler
can't verify.  We declare that a trait is ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô by adding the
‚Äòunsafe‚Äô keyword before ‚Äòtrait‚Äô and marking the implementation of the
trait as ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô too, as shown in Listing 20-12.

unsafe trait Foo {
    // methods go here
}

unsafe impl Foo for i32 {
    // method implementations go here
}

fn main() {}

By using ‚Äòunsafe impl‚Äô, we're promising that we'll uphold the invariants
that the compiler can't verify.

As an example, recall the ‚ÄòSync‚Äô and ‚ÄòSend‚Äô marker traits we discussed
in the *note ‚ÄúExtensible Concurrency with the ‚ÄòSync‚Äô and ‚ÄòSend‚Äô Traits‚Äù:
Extensible Concurrency with the Sync and Send Traits. section in Chapter
16: the compiler implements these traits automatically if our types are
composed entirely of ‚ÄòSend‚Äô and ‚ÄòSync‚Äô types.  If we implement a type
that contains a type that is not ‚ÄòSend‚Äô or ‚ÄòSync‚Äô, such as raw pointers,
and we want to mark that type as ‚ÄòSend‚Äô or ‚ÄòSync‚Äô, we must use ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô.
Rust can't verify that our type upholds the guarantees that it can be
safely sent across threads or accessed from multiple threads; therefore,
we need to do those checks manually and indicate as such with ‚Äòunsafe‚Äô.


