22.1.2.1 Specifying Placeholder Types in Trait Definitions with
...............................................................

Associated Types ‚ÄòAssociated types‚Äô connect a type placeholder with a
trait such that the trait method definitions can use these placeholder
types in their signatures.  The implementor of a trait will specify the
concrete type to be used instead of the placeholder type for the
particular implementation.  That way, we can define a trait that uses
some types without needing to know exactly what those types are until
the trait is implemented.

We've described most of the advanced features in this chapter as being
rarely needed.  Associated types are somewhere in the middle: they're
used more rarely than features explained in the rest of the book but
more commonly than many of the other features discussed in this chapter.

One example of a trait with an associated type is the ‚ÄòIterator‚Äô trait
that the standard library provides.  The associated type is named ‚ÄòItem‚Äô
and stands in for the type of the values the type implementing the
‚ÄòIterator‚Äô trait is iterating over.  The definition of the ‚ÄòIterator‚Äô
trait is as shown in Listing 20-13.

pub trait Iterator {
    type Item;

    fn next(&mut self) -> Option<Self::Item>;
}

The type ‚ÄòItem‚Äô is a placeholder, and the ‚Äònext‚Äô method's definition
shows that it will return values of type ‚ÄòOption<Self::Item>‚Äô.
Implementors of the ‚ÄòIterator‚Äô trait will specify the concrete type for
‚ÄòItem‚Äô, and the ‚Äònext‚Äô method will return an ‚ÄòOption‚Äô containing a value
of that concrete type.

Associated types might seem like a similar concept to generics, in that
the latter allow us to define a function without specifying what types
it can handle.  To examine the difference between the two concepts,
we'll look at an implementation of the ‚ÄòIterator‚Äô trait on a type named
‚ÄòCounter‚Äô that specifies the ‚ÄòItem‚Äô type is ‚Äòu32‚Äô:

impl Iterator for Counter {
    type Item = u32;

    fn next(&mut self) -> Option<Self::Item> {
        // --snip--

This syntax seems comparable to that of generics.  So why not just
define the ‚ÄòIterator‚Äô trait with generics, as shown in Listing 20-14?

pub trait Iterator<T> {
    fn next(&mut self) -> Option<T>;
}

The difference is that when using generics, as in Listing 20-14, we must
annotate the types in each implementation; because we can also implement
‚ÄòIterator<String> for Counter‚Äô or any other type, we could have multiple
implementations of ‚ÄòIterator‚Äô for ‚ÄòCounter‚Äô.  In other words, when a
trait has a generic parameter, it can be implemented for a type multiple
times, changing the concrete types of the generic type parameters each
time.  When we use the ‚Äònext‚Äô method on ‚ÄòCounter‚Äô, we would have to
provide type annotations to indicate which implementation of ‚ÄòIterator‚Äô
we want to use.

With associated types, we don't need to annotate types because we can't
implement a trait on a type multiple times.  In Listing 20-13 with the
definition that uses associated types, we can only choose what the type
of ‚ÄòItem‚Äô will be once, because there can only be one ‚Äòimpl Iterator for
Counter‚Äô.  We don't have to specify that we want an iterator of ‚Äòu32‚Äô
values everywhere that we call ‚Äònext‚Äô on ‚ÄòCounter‚Äô.

Associated types also become part of the trait's contract: implementors
of the trait must provide a type to stand in for the associated type
placeholder.  Associated types often have a name that describes how the
type will be used, and documenting the associated type in the API
documentation is good practice.


