22.1.2.2 Default Generic Type Parameters and Operator Overloading
.................................................................

When we use generic type parameters, we can specify a default concrete
type for the generic type.  This eliminates the need for implementors of
the trait to specify a concrete type if the default type works.  You
specify a default type when declaring a generic type with the
‚Äò<PlaceholderType=ConcreteType>‚Äô syntax.

A great example of a situation where this technique is useful is with
‚Äòoperator overloading‚Äô, in which you customize the behavior of an
operator (such as ‚Äò+‚Äô) in particular situations.

Rust doesn't allow you to create your own operators or overload
arbitrary operators.  But you can overload the operations and
corresponding traits listed in ‚Äòstd::ops‚Äô by implementing the traits
associated with the operator.  For example, in Listing 20-15 we overload
the ‚Äò+‚Äô operator to add two ‚ÄòPoint‚Äô instances together.  We do this by
implementing the ‚ÄòAdd‚Äô trait on a ‚ÄòPoint‚Äô struct:

use std::ops::Add;

struct Point {
    x: i32,
    y: i32,
}

impl Add for Point {
    type Output = Point;

    fn add(self, other: Point) -> Point {
        Point {
            x: self.x + other.x,
            y: self.y + other.y,
        }
    }
}

fn main() {
    assert_eq!(
        Point { x: 1, y: 0 } + Point { x: 2, y: 3 },
        Point { x: 3, y: 3 }
    );
}

The ‚Äòadd‚Äô method adds the ‚Äòx‚Äô values of two ‚ÄòPoint‚Äô instances and the
‚Äòy‚Äô values of two ‚ÄòPoint‚Äô instances to create a new ‚ÄòPoint‚Äô.  The ‚ÄòAdd‚Äô
trait has an associated type named ‚ÄòOutput‚Äô that determines the type
returned from the ‚Äòadd‚Äô method.

The default generic type in this code is within the ‚ÄòAdd‚Äô trait.  Here
is its definition:

trait Add<Rhs=Self> {
    type Output;

    fn add(self, rhs: Rhs) -> Self::Output;
}

This code should look generally familiar: a trait with one method and an
associated type.  The new part is ‚ÄòRhs=Self‚Äô: this syntax is called
‚Äòdefault type parameters‚Äô.  The ‚ÄòRhs‚Äô generic type parameter (short for
‚Äúright hand side‚Äù) defines the type of the ‚Äòrhs‚Äô parameter in the ‚Äòadd‚Äô
method.  If we don't specify a concrete type for ‚ÄòRhs‚Äô when we implement
the ‚ÄòAdd‚Äô trait, the type of ‚ÄòRhs‚Äô will default to ‚ÄòSelf‚Äô, which will be
the type we're implementing ‚ÄòAdd‚Äô on.

When we implemented ‚ÄòAdd‚Äô for ‚ÄòPoint‚Äô, we used the default for ‚ÄòRhs‚Äô
because we wanted to add two ‚ÄòPoint‚Äô instances.  Let's look at an
example of implementing the ‚ÄòAdd‚Äô trait where we want to customize the
‚ÄòRhs‚Äô type rather than using the default.

We have two structs, ‚ÄòMillimeters‚Äô and ‚ÄòMeters‚Äô, holding values in
different units.  This thin wrapping of an existing type in another
struct is known as the ‚Äònewtype pattern‚Äô, which we describe in more
detail in the *note ‚ÄúUsing the Newtype Pattern to Implement External
Traits on External Types‚Äù: Using the Newtype Pattern to Implement
External Traits on External Types. section.  We want to add values in
millimeters to values in meters and have the implementation of ‚ÄòAdd‚Äô do
the conversion correctly.  We can implement ‚ÄòAdd‚Äô for ‚ÄòMillimeters‚Äô with
‚ÄòMeters‚Äô as the ‚ÄòRhs‚Äô, as shown in Listing 20-16.

use std::ops::Add;

struct Millimeters(u32);
struct Meters(u32);

impl Add<Meters> for Millimeters {
    type Output = Millimeters;

    fn add(self, other: Meters) -> Millimeters {
        Millimeters(self.0 + (other.0 * 1000))
    }
}

To add ‚ÄòMillimeters‚Äô and ‚ÄòMeters‚Äô, we specify ‚Äòimpl Add<Meters>‚Äô to set
the value of the ‚ÄòRhs‚Äô type parameter instead of using the default of
‚ÄòSelf‚Äô.

You'll use default type parameters in two main ways:

   ‚Ä¢ To extend a type without breaking existing code
   ‚Ä¢ To allow customization in specific cases most users won't need

The standard library's ‚ÄòAdd‚Äô trait is an example of the second purpose:
usually, you'll add two like types, but the ‚ÄòAdd‚Äô trait provides the
ability to customize beyond that.  Using a default type parameter in the
‚ÄòAdd‚Äô trait definition means you don't have to specify the extra
parameter most of the time.  In other words, a bit of implementation
boilerplate isn't needed, making it easier to use the trait.

The first purpose is similar to the second but in reverse: if you want
to add a type parameter to an existing trait, you can give it a default
to allow extension of the functionality of the trait without breaking
the existing implementation code.


