22.1.2.3 Fully Qualified Syntax for Disambiguation: Calling
...........................................................

Methods with the Same Name Nothing in Rust prevents a trait from having
a method with the same name as another trait's method, nor does Rust
prevent you from implementing both traits on one type.  It's also
possible to implement a method directly on the type with the same name
as methods from traits.

When calling methods with the same name, you'll need to tell Rust which
one you want to use.  Consider the code in Listing 20-17 where we've
defined two traits, ‚ÄòPilot‚Äô and ‚ÄòWizard‚Äô, that both have a method called
‚Äòfly‚Äô.  We then implement both traits on a type ‚ÄòHuman‚Äô that already has
a method named ‚Äòfly‚Äô implemented on it.  Each ‚Äòfly‚Äô method does
something different.

trait Pilot {
    fn fly(&self);
}

trait Wizard {
    fn fly(&self);
}

struct Human;

impl Pilot for Human {
    fn fly(&self) {
        println!("This is your captain speaking.");
    }
}

impl Wizard for Human {
    fn fly(&self) {
        println!("Up!");
    }
}

impl Human {
    fn fly(&self) {
        println!("*waving arms furiously*");
    }
}

When we call ‚Äòfly‚Äô on an instance of ‚ÄòHuman‚Äô, the compiler defaults to
calling the method that is directly implemented on the type, as shown in
Listing 20-18.

fn main() {
    let person = Human;
    person.fly();
}

Running this code will print ‚Äò*waving arms furiously*‚Äô, showing that
Rust called the ‚Äòfly‚Äô method implemented on ‚ÄòHuman‚Äô directly.

To call the ‚Äòfly‚Äô methods from either the ‚ÄòPilot‚Äô trait or the ‚ÄòWizard‚Äô
trait, we need to use more explicit syntax to specify which ‚Äòfly‚Äô method
we mean.  Listing 20-19 demonstrates this syntax.

fn main() {
    let person = Human;
    Pilot::fly(&person);
    Wizard::fly(&person);
    person.fly();
}

Specifying the trait name before the method name clarifies to Rust which
implementation of ‚Äòfly‚Äô we want to call.  We could also write
‚ÄòHuman::fly(&person)‚Äô, which is equivalent to the ‚Äòperson.fly()‚Äô that we
