External Types In Chapter 10 in the *note ‚ÄúImplementing a Trait on a
Type‚Äù: Implementing a Trait on a Type. section, we mentioned the orphan
rule that states we're only allowed to implement a trait on a type if
either the trait or the type are local to our crate.  It's possible to
get around this restriction using the ‚Äònewtype pattern‚Äô, which involves
creating a new type in a tuple struct.  (We covered tuple structs in the
*note ‚ÄúUsing Tuple Structs without Named Fields to Create Different
Types‚Äù: Using Tuple Structs Without Named Fields to Create Different
Types. section of Chapter 5.)  The tuple struct will have one field and
be a thin wrapper around the type we want to implement a trait for.
Then the wrapper type is local to our crate, and we can implement the
trait on the wrapper.  ‚ÄòNewtype‚Äô is a term that originates from the
Haskell programming language.  There is no runtime performance penalty
for using this pattern, and the wrapper type is elided at compile time.

As an example, let's say we want to implement ‚ÄòDisplay‚Äô on ‚ÄòVec<T>‚Äô,
which the orphan rule prevents us from doing directly because the
‚ÄòDisplay‚Äô trait and the ‚ÄòVec<T>‚Äô type are defined outside our crate.  We
can make a ‚ÄòWrapper‚Äô struct that holds an instance of ‚ÄòVec<T>‚Äô; then we
can implement ‚ÄòDisplay‚Äô on ‚ÄòWrapper‚Äô and use the ‚ÄòVec<T>‚Äô value, as
shown in Listing 20-24.

use std::fmt;

struct Wrapper(Vec<String>);

impl fmt::Display for Wrapper {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut fmt::Formatter) -> fmt::Result {
        write!(f, "[{}]", self.0.join(", "))
    }
}

fn main() {
    let w = Wrapper(vec![String::from("hello"), String::from("world")]);
    println!("w = {w}");
}

The implementation of ‚ÄòDisplay‚Äô uses ‚Äòself.0‚Äô to access the inner
‚ÄòVec<T>‚Äô, because ‚ÄòWrapper‚Äô is a tuple struct and ‚ÄòVec<T>‚Äô is the item
at index 0 in the tuple.  Then we can use the functionality of the
‚ÄòDisplay‚Äô trait on ‚ÄòWrapper‚Äô.

The downside of using this technique is that ‚ÄòWrapper‚Äô is a new type, so
it doesn't have the methods of the value it's holding.  We would have to
implement all the methods of ‚ÄòVec<T>‚Äô directly on ‚ÄòWrapper‚Äô such that
the methods delegate to ‚Äòself.0‚Äô, which would allow us to treat
‚ÄòWrapper‚Äô exactly like a ‚ÄòVec<T>‚Äô.  If we wanted the new type to have
every method the inner type has, implementing the ‚ÄòDeref‚Äô trait
(discussed in Chapter 15 in the *note ‚ÄúTreating Smart Pointers Like
Regular References with the ‚ÄòDeref‚Äô Trait‚Äù: Treating Smart Pointers Like
Regular References with the Deref Trait. section) on the ‚ÄòWrapper‚Äô to
return the inner type would be a solution.  If we don't want the
‚ÄòWrapper‚Äô type to have all the methods of the inner type--for example,
to restrict the ‚ÄòWrapper‚Äô type's behavior--we would have to implement
just the methods we do want manually.

This newtype pattern is also useful even when traits are not involved.
Let's switch focus and look at some advanced ways to interact with
Rust's type system.


