22.1.3.3 The Never Type that Never Returns
..........................................

Rust has a special type named ‚Äò!‚Äô that's known in type theory lingo as
the ‚Äòempty type‚Äô because it has no values.  We prefer to call it the
‚Äònever type‚Äô because it stands in the place of the return type when a
function will never return.  Here is an example:

fn bar() -> ! {
    // --snip--
}

This code is read as ‚Äúthe function ‚Äòbar‚Äô returns never.‚Äù Functions that
return never are called ‚Äòdiverging functions‚Äô.  We can't create values
of the type ‚Äò!‚Äô so ‚Äòbar‚Äô can never possibly return.

But what use is a type you can never create values for?  Recall the code
from Listing 2-5, part of the number guessing game; we've reproduced a
bit of it here in Listing 20-27.

        let guess: u32 = match guess.trim().parse() {
            Ok(num) => num,
            Err(_) => continue,
        };

At the time, we skipped over some details in this code.  In Chapter 6 in
*note ‚ÄúThe ‚Äòmatch‚Äô Control Flow Operator‚Äù:
#book__pandoc__texi__src__ch06-02-matchmd__the-match-control-flow-operator.
section, we discussed that ‚Äòmatch‚Äô arms must all return the same type.
So, for example, the following code doesn't work:

    let guess = match guess.trim().parse() {
        Ok(_) => 5,
        Err(_) => "hello",
    };

The type of ‚Äòguess‚Äô in this code would have to be an integer ‚Äòand‚Äô a
string, and Rust requires that ‚Äòguess‚Äô have only one type.  So what does
‚Äòcontinue‚Äô return?  How were we allowed to return a ‚Äòu32‚Äô from one arm
and have another arm that ends with ‚Äòcontinue‚Äô in Listing 20-27?

As you might have guessed, ‚Äòcontinue‚Äô has a ‚Äò!‚Äô value.  That is, when
Rust computes the type of ‚Äòguess‚Äô, it looks at both match arms, the
former with a value of ‚Äòu32‚Äô and the latter with a ‚Äò!‚Äô value.  Because
‚Äò!‚Äô can never have a value, Rust decides that the type of ‚Äòguess‚Äô is
‚Äòu32‚Äô.

The formal way of describing this behavior is that expressions of type
‚Äò!‚Äô can be coerced into any other type.  We're allowed to end this
‚Äòmatch‚Äô arm with ‚Äòcontinue‚Äô because ‚Äòcontinue‚Äô doesn't return a value;
instead, it moves control back to the top of the loop, so in the ‚ÄòErr‚Äô
case, we never assign a value to ‚Äòguess‚Äô.

The never type is useful with the ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô macro as well.  Recall the
‚Äòunwrap‚Äô function that we call on ‚ÄòOption<T>‚Äô values to produce a value
or panic with this definition:

impl<T> Option<T> {
    pub fn unwrap(self) -> T {
        match self {
            Some(val) => val,
            None => panic!("called `Option::unwrap()` on a `None` value"),
        }
    }
}

In this code, the same thing happens as in the ‚Äòmatch‚Äô in Listing 20-27:
Rust sees that ‚Äòval‚Äô has the type ‚ÄòT‚Äô and ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô has the type ‚Äò!‚Äô, so
the result of the overall ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression is ‚ÄòT‚Äô.  This code works
because ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô doesn't produce a value; it ends the program.  In the
‚ÄòNone‚Äô case, we won't be returning a value from ‚Äòunwrap‚Äô, so this code
is valid.

One final expression that has the type ‚Äò!‚Äô is a ‚Äòloop‚Äô:

    print!("forever ");

    loop {
        print!("and ever ");
    }

Here, the loop never ends, so ‚Äò!‚Äô is the value of the expression.
However, this wouldn't be true if we included a ‚Äòbreak‚Äô, because the
loop would terminate when it got to the ‚Äòbreak‚Äô.


