22.1.3.4 Dynamically Sized Types and the ‚ÄòSized‚Äô Trait
......................................................

Rust needs to know certain details about its types, such as how much
space to allocate for a value of a particular type.  This leaves one
corner of its type system a little confusing at first: the concept of
‚Äòdynamically sized types‚Äô.  Sometimes referred to as ‚ÄòDSTs‚Äô or ‚Äòunsized
types‚Äô, these types let us write code using values whose size we can
know only at runtime.

Let's dig into the details of a dynamically sized type called ‚Äòstr‚Äô,
which we've been using throughout the book.  That's right, not ‚Äò&str‚Äô,
but ‚Äòstr‚Äô on its own, is a DST. We can't know how long the string is
until runtime, meaning we can't create a variable of type ‚Äòstr‚Äô, nor can
we take an argument of type ‚Äòstr‚Äô.  Consider the following code, which
does not work:

    let s1: str = "Hello there!";
    let s2: str = "How's it going?";

Rust needs to know how much memory to allocate for any value of a
particular type, and all values of a type must use the same amount of
memory.  If Rust allowed us to write this code, these two ‚Äòstr‚Äô values
would need to take up the same amount of space.  But they have different
lengths: ‚Äòs1‚Äô needs 12 bytes of storage and ‚Äòs2‚Äô needs 15.  This is why
it's not possible to create a variable holding a dynamically sized type.

So what do we do?  In this case, you already know the answer: we make
the types of ‚Äòs1‚Äô and ‚Äòs2‚Äô a ‚Äò&str‚Äô rather than a ‚Äòstr‚Äô.  Recall from
the *note ‚ÄúString Slices‚Äù: String Slices. section of Chapter 4 that the
slice data structure just stores the starting position and the length of
the slice.  So although a ‚Äò&T‚Äô is a single value that stores the memory
address of where the ‚ÄòT‚Äô is located, a ‚Äò&str‚Äô is ‚Äòtwo‚Äô values: the
address of the ‚Äòstr‚Äô and its length.  As such, we can know the size of a
‚Äò&str‚Äô value at compile time: it's twice the length of a ‚Äòusize‚Äô.  That
is, we always know the size of a ‚Äò&str‚Äô, no matter how long the string
it refers to is.  In general, this is the way in which dynamically sized
types are used in Rust: they have an extra bit of metadata that stores
the size of the dynamic information.  The golden rule of dynamically
sized types is that we must always put values of dynamically sized types
behind a pointer of some kind.

We can combine ‚Äòstr‚Äô with all kinds of pointers: for example, ‚ÄòBox<str>‚Äô
or ‚ÄòRc<str>‚Äô.  In fact, you've seen this before but with a different
dynamically sized type: traits.  Every trait is a dynamically sized type
we can refer to by using the name of the trait.  In Chapter 18 in the
*note ‚ÄúUsing Trait Objects That Allow for Values of Different Types‚Äù:
Using Trait Objects That Allow for Values of Different Types. section,
we mentioned that to use traits as trait objects, we must put them
behind a pointer, such as ‚Äò&dyn Trait‚Äô or ‚ÄòBox<dyn Trait>‚Äô (‚ÄòRc<dyn
Trait>‚Äô would work too).

To work with DSTs, Rust provides the ‚ÄòSized‚Äô trait to determine whether
or not a type's size is known at compile time.  This trait is
automatically implemented for everything whose size is known at compile
time.  In addition, Rust implicitly adds a bound on ‚ÄòSized‚Äô to every
generic function.  That is, a generic function definition like this:

fn generic<T>(t: T) {
    // --snip--
}

is actually treated as though we had written this:

fn generic<T: Sized>(t: T) {
    // --snip--
}

By default, generic functions will work only on types that have a known
size at compile time.  However, you can use the following special syntax
to relax this restriction:

fn generic<T: ?Sized>(t: &T) {
    // --snip--
}

A trait bound on ‚Äò?Sized‚Äô means ‚Äú‚ÄòT‚Äô may or may not be ‚ÄòSized‚Äô‚Äù and this
notation overrides the default that generic types must have a known size
at compile time.  The ‚Äò?Trait‚Äô syntax with this meaning is only
available for ‚ÄòSized‚Äô, not any other traits.

Also note that we switched the type of the ‚Äòt‚Äô parameter from ‚ÄòT‚Äô to
‚Äò&T‚Äô.  Because the type might not be ‚ÄòSized‚Äô, we need to use it behind
some kind of pointer.  In this case, we've chosen a reference.

Next, we'll talk about functions and closures!


