22.1.4.1 Function Pointers
..........................

We've talked about how to pass closures to functions; you can also pass
regular functions to functions!  This technique is useful when you want
to pass a function you've already defined rather than defining a new
closure.  Functions coerce to the type ‚Äòfn‚Äô (with a lowercase f), not to
be confused with the ‚ÄòFn‚Äô closure trait.  The ‚Äòfn‚Äô type is called a
‚Äòfunction pointer‚Äô.  Passing functions with function pointers will allow
you to use functions as arguments to other functions.

The syntax for specifying that a parameter is a function pointer is
similar to that of closures, as shown in Listing 20-28, where we've
defined a function ‚Äòadd_one‚Äô that adds one to its parameter.  The
function ‚Äòdo_twice‚Äô takes two parameters: a function pointer to any
function that takes an ‚Äòi32‚Äô parameter and returns an ‚Äòi32‚Äô, and one
‚Äòi32‚Äô value.  The ‚Äòdo_twice‚Äô function calls the function ‚Äòf‚Äô twice,
passing it the ‚Äòarg‚Äô value, then adds the two function call results
together.  The ‚Äòmain‚Äô function calls ‚Äòdo_twice‚Äô with the arguments
‚Äòadd_one‚Äô and ‚Äò5‚Äô.

fn add_one(x: i32) -> i32 {
    x + 1
}

fn do_twice(f: fn(i32) -> i32, arg: i32) -> i32 {
    f(arg) + f(arg)
}

fn main() {
    let answer = do_twice(add_one, 5);

    println!("The answer is: {answer}");
}

This code prints ‚ÄòThe answer is: 12‚Äô.  We specify that the parameter ‚Äòf‚Äô
in ‚Äòdo_twice‚Äô is an ‚Äòfn‚Äô that takes one parameter of type ‚Äòi32‚Äô and
returns an ‚Äòi32‚Äô.  We can then call ‚Äòf‚Äô in the body of ‚Äòdo_twice‚Äô.  In
‚Äòmain‚Äô, we can pass the function name ‚Äòadd_one‚Äô as the first argument to
‚Äòdo_twice‚Äô.

Unlike closures, ‚Äòfn‚Äô is a type rather than a trait, so we specify ‚Äòfn‚Äô
as the parameter type directly rather than declaring a generic type
parameter with one of the ‚ÄòFn‚Äô traits as a trait bound.

Function pointers implement all three of the closure traits (‚ÄòFn‚Äô,
‚ÄòFnMut‚Äô, and ‚ÄòFnOnce‚Äô), meaning you can always pass a function pointer
as an argument for a function that expects a closure.  It's best to
write functions using a generic type and one of the closure traits so
your functions can accept either functions or closures.

That said, one example of where you would want to only accept ‚Äòfn‚Äô and
not closures is when interfacing with external code that doesn't have
closures: C functions can accept functions as arguments, but C doesn't
have closures.

As an example of where you could use either a closure defined inline or
a named function, let's look at a use of the ‚Äòmap‚Äô method provided by
the ‚ÄòIterator‚Äô trait in the standard library.  To use the ‚Äòmap‚Äô function
to turn a vector of numbers into a vector of strings, we could use a
closure, like this:

    let list_of_numbers = vec![1, 2, 3];
    let list_of_strings: Vec<String> =
        list_of_numbers.iter().map(|i| i.to_string()).collect();

Or we could name a function as the argument to ‚Äòmap‚Äô instead of the
closure, like this:

    let list_of_numbers = vec![1, 2, 3];
    let list_of_strings: Vec<String> =
        list_of_numbers.iter().map(ToString::to_string).collect();

Note that we must use the fully qualified syntax that we talked about
earlier in the *note ‚ÄúAdvanced Traits‚Äù: Advanced Traits. section because
there are multiple functions available named ‚Äòto_string‚Äô.  Here, we're
using the ‚Äòto_string‚Äô function defined in the ‚ÄòToString‚Äô trait, which
the standard library has implemented for any type that implements
‚ÄòDisplay‚Äô.

Recall from the *note ‚ÄúEnum values‚Äù: Enum Values. section of Chapter 6
that the name of each enum variant that we define also becomes an
initializer function.  We can use these initializer functions as
function pointers that implement the closure traits, which means we can
specify the initializer functions as arguments for methods that take
closures, like so:

    enum Status {
        Value(u32),
        Stop,
    }

    let list_of_statuses: Vec<Status> = (0u32..20).map(Status::Value).collect();

Here we create ‚ÄòStatus::Value‚Äô instances using each ‚Äòu32‚Äô value in the
range that ‚Äòmap‚Äô is called on by using the initializer function of
‚ÄòStatus::Value‚Äô.  Some people prefer this style, and some people prefer
to use closures.  They compile to the same code, so use whichever style
is clearer to you.


