22.1.5.2 Declarative Macros with ‚Äòmacro_rules!‚Äô for General
...........................................................

Metaprogramming The most widely used form of macros in Rust is the
‚Äòdeclarative macro‚Äô.  These are also sometimes referred to as ‚Äúmacros by
example,‚Äù ‚Äú‚Äòmacro_rules!‚Äô macros,‚Äù or just plain ‚Äúmacros.‚Äù At their
core, declarative macros allow you to write something similar to a Rust
‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression.  As discussed in Chapter 6, ‚Äòmatch‚Äô expressions are
control structures that take an expression, compare the resulting value
of the expression to patterns, and then run the code associated with the
matching pattern.  Macros also compare a value to patterns that are
associated with particular code: in this situation, the value is the
literal Rust source code passed to the macro; the patterns are compared
with the structure of that source code; and the code associated with
each pattern, when matched, replaces the code passed to the macro.  This
all happens during compilation.

To define a macro, you use the ‚Äòmacro_rules!‚Äô construct.  Let's explore
how to use ‚Äòmacro_rules!‚Äô by looking at how the ‚Äòvec!‚Äô macro is defined.
Chapter 8 covered how we can use the ‚Äòvec!‚Äô macro to create a new vector
with particular values.  For example, the following macro creates a new
vector containing three integers:

let v: Vec<u32> = vec![1, 2, 3];

We could also use the ‚Äòvec!‚Äô macro to make a vector of two integers or a
vector of five string slices.  We wouldn't be able to use a function to
do the same because we wouldn't know the number or type of values up
front.

Listing 20-29 shows a slightly simplified definition of the ‚Äòvec!‚Äô
macro.

macro_rules! vec {
    ( $( $x:expr ),* ) => {
        {
            let mut temp_vec = Vec::new();
            $(
                temp_vec.push($x);
            )*
            temp_vec
        }
    };
}

Note: The actual definition of the ‚Äòvec!‚Äô macro in the standard library
includes code to preallocate the correct amount of memory up front.
That code is an optimization that we don't include here to make the
example simpler.

The ‚Äò#[macro_export]‚Äô annotation indicates that this macro should be
made available whenever the crate in which the macro is defined is
brought into scope.  Without this annotation, the macro can't be brought
into scope.

We then start the macro definition with ‚Äòmacro_rules!‚Äô and the name of
the macro we're defining ‚Äòwithout‚Äô the exclamation mark.  The name, in
this case ‚Äòvec‚Äô, is followed by curly brackets denoting the body of the
macro definition.

The structure in the ‚Äòvec!‚Äô body is similar to the structure of a
‚Äòmatch‚Äô expression.  Here we have one arm with the pattern ‚Äò( $( $x:expr
),* )‚Äô, followed by ‚Äò=>‚Äô and the block of code associated with this
pattern.  If the pattern matches, the associated block of code will be
emitted.  Given that this is the only pattern in this macro, there is
only one valid way to match; any other pattern will result in an error.
More complex macros will have more than one arm.

Valid pattern syntax in macro definitions is different than the pattern
syntax covered in Chapter 19 because macro patterns are matched against
Rust code structure rather than values.  Let's walk through what the
pattern pieces in Listing 20-29 mean; for the full macro pattern syntax,
see the Rust Reference
(https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/../reference/macros-by-example.html).

First, we use a set of parentheses to encompass the whole pattern.  We
use a dollar sign (‚Äò$‚Äô) to declare a variable in the macro system that
will contain the Rust code matching the pattern.  The dollar sign makes
it clear this is a macro variable as opposed to a regular Rust variable.
Next comes a set of parentheses that captures values that match the
pattern within the parentheses for use in the replacement code.  Within
‚Äò$()‚Äô is ‚Äò$x:expr‚Äô, which matches any Rust expression and gives the
expression the name ‚Äò$x‚Äô.

The comma following ‚Äò$()‚Äô indicates that a literal comma separator
character could optionally appear after the code that matches the code
in ‚Äò$()‚Äô.  The ‚Äò*‚Äô specifies that the pattern matches zero or more of
whatever precedes the ‚Äò*‚Äô.

When we call this macro with ‚Äòvec![1, 2, 3];‚Äô, the ‚Äò$x‚Äô pattern matches
three times with the three expressions ‚Äò1‚Äô, ‚Äò2‚Äô, and ‚Äò3‚Äô.

Now let's look at the pattern in the body of the code associated with
this arm: ‚Äòtemp_vec.push()‚Äô within ‚Äò$()*‚Äô is generated for each part
that matches ‚Äò$()‚Äô in the pattern zero or more times depending on how
many times the pattern matches.  The ‚Äò$x‚Äô is replaced with each
expression matched.  When we call this macro with ‚Äòvec![1, 2, 3];‚Äô, the
code generated that replaces this macro call will be the following:

{
    let mut temp_vec = Vec::new();
    temp_vec.push(1);
    temp_vec.push(2);
    temp_vec.push(3);
    temp_vec
}

We've defined a macro that can take any number of arguments of any type
and can generate code to create a vector containing the specified
elements.

To learn more about how to write macros, consult the online
documentation or other resources, such as ‚ÄúThe Little Book of Rust
Macros‚Äù (https://veykril.github.io/tlborm/) started by Daniel Keep and
continued by Lukas Wirth.


