22.1.5.4 How to Write a Custom ‚Äòderive‚Äô Macro
.............................................

Let's create a crate named ‚Äòhello_macro‚Äô that defines a trait named
‚ÄòHelloMacro‚Äô with one associated function named ‚Äòhello_macro‚Äô.  Rather
than making our users implement the ‚ÄòHelloMacro‚Äô trait for each of their
types, we'll provide a procedural macro so users can annotate their type
with ‚Äò#[derive(HelloMacro)]‚Äô to get a default implementation of the
‚Äòhello_macro‚Äô function.  The default implementation will print ‚ÄòHello,
Macro! My name is TypeName!‚Äô where ‚ÄòTypeName‚Äô is the name of the type on
which this trait has been defined.  In other words, we'll write a crate
that enables another programmer to write code like Listing 20-31 using
our crate.

use hello_macro::HelloMacro;
use hello_macro_derive::HelloMacro;

struct Pancakes;

fn main() {
    Pancakes::hello_macro();
}

This code will print ‚ÄòHello, Macro! My name is Pancakes!‚Äô when we're
done.  The first step is to make a new library crate, like this:

$ cargo new hello_macro --lib

Next, we'll define the ‚ÄòHelloMacro‚Äô trait and its associated function:

pub trait HelloMacro {
    fn hello_macro();
}

We have a trait and its function.  At this point, our crate user could
implement the trait to achieve the desired functionality, like so:

use hello_macro::HelloMacro;

struct Pancakes;

impl HelloMacro for Pancakes {
    fn hello_macro() {
        println!("Hello, Macro! My name is Pancakes!");
    }
}

fn main() {
    Pancakes::hello_macro();
}

However, they would need to write the implementation block for each type
they wanted to use with ‚Äòhello_macro‚Äô; we want to spare them from having
to do this work.

Additionally, we can't yet provide the ‚Äòhello_macro‚Äô function with
default implementation that will print the name of the type the trait is
implemented on: Rust doesn't have reflection capabilities, so it can't
look up the type's name at runtime.  We need a macro to generate code at
compile time.

The next step is to define the procedural macro.  At the time of this
writing, procedural macros need to be in their own crate.  Eventually,
this restriction might be lifted.  The convention for structuring crates
and macro crates is as follows: for a crate named ‚Äòfoo‚Äô, a custom derive
procedural macro crate is called ‚Äòfoo_derive‚Äô.  Let's start a new crate
called ‚Äòhello_macro_derive‚Äô inside our ‚Äòhello_macro‚Äô project:

$ cargo new hello_macro_derive --lib

Our two crates are tightly related, so we create the procedural macro
crate within the directory of our ‚Äòhello_macro‚Äô crate.  If we change the
trait definition in ‚Äòhello_macro‚Äô, we'll have to change the
implementation of the procedural macro in ‚Äòhello_macro_derive‚Äô as well.
The two crates will need to be published separately, and programmers
using these crates will need to add both as dependencies and bring them
both into scope.  We could instead have the ‚Äòhello_macro‚Äô crate use
‚Äòhello_macro_derive‚Äô as a dependency and re-export the procedural macro
code.  However, the way we've structured the project makes it possible
for programmers to use ‚Äòhello_macro‚Äô even if they don't want the
‚Äòderive‚Äô functionality.

We need to declare the ‚Äòhello_macro_derive‚Äô crate as a procedural macro
crate.  We'll also need functionality from the ‚Äòsyn‚Äô and ‚Äòquote‚Äô crates,
as you'll see in a moment, so we need to add them as dependencies.  Add
the following to the ‚ÄòCargo.toml‚Äô file for ‚Äòhello_macro_derive‚Äô:

[lib]
proc-macro = true

[dependencies]
syn = "2.0"
quote = "1.0"

To start defining the procedural macro, place the code in Listing 20-32
into your ‚Äòsrc/lib.rs‚Äô file for the ‚Äòhello_macro_derive‚Äô crate.  Note
that this code won't compile until we add a definition for the
‚Äòimpl_hello_macro‚Äô function.

use proc_macro::TokenStream;
use quote::quote;

pub fn hello_macro_derive(input: TokenStream) -> TokenStream {
    // Construct a representation of Rust code as a syntax tree
    // that we can manipulate
    let ast = syn::parse(input).unwrap();

    // Build the trait implementation
    impl_hello_macro(&ast)
}

Notice that we've split the code into the ‚Äòhello_macro_derive‚Äô function,
which is responsible for parsing the ‚ÄòTokenStream‚Äô, and the
‚Äòimpl_hello_macro‚Äô function, which is responsible for transforming the
syntax tree: this makes writing a procedural macro more convenient.  The
code in the outer function (‚Äòhello_macro_derive‚Äô in this case) will be
the same for almost every procedural macro crate you see or create.  The
code you specify in the body of the inner function (‚Äòimpl_hello_macro‚Äô
in this case) will be different depending on your procedural macro's
purpose.

We've introduced three new crates: ‚Äòproc_macro‚Äô, ‚Äòsyn‚Äô
(https://crates.io/crates/syn), and ‚Äòquote‚Äô
(https://crates.io/crates/quote).  The ‚Äòproc_macro‚Äô crate comes with
Rust, so we didn't need to add that to the dependencies in ‚ÄòCargo.toml‚Äô.
The ‚Äòproc_macro‚Äô crate is the compiler's API that allows us to read and
manipulate Rust code from our code.

The ‚Äòsyn‚Äô crate parses Rust code from a string into a data structure
that we can perform operations on.  The ‚Äòquote‚Äô crate turns ‚Äòsyn‚Äô data
structures back into Rust code.  These crates make it much simpler to
parse any sort of Rust code we might want to handle: writing a full
parser for Rust code is no simple task.

The ‚Äòhello_macro_derive‚Äô function will be called when a user of our
library specifies ‚Äò#[derive(HelloMacro)]‚Äô on a type.  This is possible
because we've annotated the ‚Äòhello_macro_derive‚Äô function here with
‚Äòproc_macro_derive‚Äô and specified the name ‚ÄòHelloMacro‚Äô, which matches
our trait name; this is the convention most procedural macros follow.

The ‚Äòhello_macro_derive‚Äô function first converts the ‚Äòinput‚Äô from a
‚ÄòTokenStream‚Äô to a data structure that we can then interpret and perform
operations on.  This is where ‚Äòsyn‚Äô comes into play.  The ‚Äòparse‚Äô
function in ‚Äòsyn‚Äô takes a ‚ÄòTokenStream‚Äô and returns a ‚ÄòDeriveInput‚Äô
struct representing the parsed Rust code.  Listing 20-33 shows the
relevant parts of the ‚ÄòDeriveInput‚Äô struct we get from parsing the
‚Äòstruct Pancakes;‚Äô string:

DeriveInput {
    // --snip--

    ident: Ident {
        ident: "Pancakes",
        span: #0 bytes(95..103)
    },
    data: Struct(
        DataStruct {
            struct_token: Struct,
            fields: Unit,
            semi_token: Some(
                Semi
            )
        }
    )
}

The fields of this struct show that the Rust code we've parsed is a unit
struct with the ‚Äòident‚Äô (identifier, meaning the name) of ‚ÄòPancakes‚Äô.
There are more fields on this struct for describing all sorts of Rust
code; check the ‚Äòsyn‚Äô documentation for ‚ÄòDeriveInput‚Äô
(https://docs.rs/syn/2.0/syn/struct.DeriveInput.html) for more
information.

Soon we'll define the ‚Äòimpl_hello_macro‚Äô function, which is where we'll
build the new Rust code we want to include.  But before we do, note that
the output for our derive macro is also a ‚ÄòTokenStream‚Äô.  The returned
‚ÄòTokenStream‚Äô is added to the code that our crate users write, so when
they compile their crate, they'll get the extra functionality that we
provide in the modified ‚ÄòTokenStream‚Äô.

You might have noticed that we're calling ‚Äòunwrap‚Äô to cause the
‚Äòhello_macro_derive‚Äô function to panic if the call to the ‚Äòsyn::parse‚Äô
function fails here.  It's necessary for our procedural macro to panic
on errors because ‚Äòproc_macro_derive‚Äô functions must return
‚ÄòTokenStream‚Äô rather than ‚ÄòResult‚Äô to conform to the procedural macro
API. We've simplified this example by using ‚Äòunwrap‚Äô; in production
code, you should provide more specific error messages about what went
wrong by using ‚Äòpanic!‚Äô or ‚Äòexpect‚Äô.

Now that we have the code to turn the annotated Rust code from a
‚ÄòTokenStream‚Äô into a ‚ÄòDeriveInput‚Äô instance, let's generate the code
that implements the ‚ÄòHelloMacro‚Äô trait on the annotated type, as shown
in Listing 20-34.

fn impl_hello_macro(ast: &syn::DeriveInput) -> TokenStream {
    let name = &ast.ident;
    let gen = quote! {
        impl HelloMacro for #name {
            fn hello_macro() {
                println!("Hello, Macro! My name is {}!", stringify!(#name));
            }
        }
    };
    gen.into()
}

We get an ‚ÄòIdent‚Äô struct instance containing the name (identifier) of
the annotated type using ‚Äòast.ident‚Äô.  The struct in Listing 20-33 shows
that when we run the ‚Äòimpl_hello_macro‚Äô function on the code in Listing
20-31, the ‚Äòident‚Äô we get will have the ‚Äòident‚Äô field with a value of
‚Äò"Pancakes"‚Äô.  Thus, the ‚Äòname‚Äô variable in Listing 20-34 will contain
an ‚ÄòIdent‚Äô struct instance that, when printed, will be the string
‚Äò"Pancakes"‚Äô, the name of the struct in Listing 20-31.

The ‚Äòquote!‚Äô macro lets us define the Rust code that we want to return.
The compiler expects something different to the direct result of the
‚Äòquote!‚Äô macro's execution, so we need to convert it to a ‚ÄòTokenStream‚Äô.
We do this by calling the ‚Äòinto‚Äô method, which consumes this
intermediate representation and returns a value of the required
‚ÄòTokenStream‚Äô type.

The ‚Äòquote!‚Äô macro also provides some very cool templating mechanics: we
can enter ‚Äò#name‚Äô, and ‚Äòquote!‚Äô will replace it with the value in the
variable ‚Äòname‚Äô.  You can even do some repetition similar to the way
regular macros work.  Check out the ‚Äòquote‚Äô crate's docs
(https://docs.rs/quote) for a thorough introduction.

We want our procedural macro to generate an implementation of our
‚ÄòHelloMacro‚Äô trait for the type the user annotated, which we can get by
using ‚Äò#name‚Äô.  The trait implementation has the one function
‚Äòhello_macro‚Äô, whose body contains the functionality we want to provide:
printing ‚ÄòHello, Macro! My name is‚Äô and then the name of the annotated
type.

The ‚Äòstringify!‚Äô macro used here is built into Rust.  It takes a Rust
expression, such as ‚Äò1 + 2‚Äô, and at compile time turns the expression
into a string literal, such as ‚Äò"1 + 2"‚Äô.  This is different than
‚Äòformat!‚Äô or ‚Äòprintln!‚Äô, macros which evaluate the expression and then
turn the result into a ‚ÄòString‚Äô.  There is a possibility that the
‚Äò#name‚Äô input might be an expression to print literally, so we use
‚Äòstringify!‚Äô.  Using ‚Äòstringify!‚Äô also saves an allocation by converting
‚Äò#name‚Äô to a string literal at compile time.

At this point, ‚Äòcargo build‚Äô should complete successfully in both
‚Äòhello_macro‚Äô and ‚Äòhello_macro_derive‚Äô.  Let's hook up these crates to
the code in Listing 20-31 to see the procedural macro in action!  Create
a new binary project in your ‚Äòprojects‚Äô directory using ‚Äòcargo new
pancakes‚Äô.  We need to add ‚Äòhello_macro‚Äô and ‚Äòhello_macro_derive‚Äô as
dependencies in the ‚Äòpancakes‚Äô crate's ‚ÄòCargo.toml‚Äô.  If you're
publishing your versions of ‚Äòhello_macro‚Äô and ‚Äòhello_macro_derive‚Äô to
cratesio (https://crates.io/), they would be regular dependencies; if
not, you can specify them as ‚Äòpath‚Äô dependencies as follows:

hello_macro = { path = "../hello_macro" }
hello_macro_derive = { path = "../hello_macro/hello_macro_derive" }

Put the code in Listing 20-31 into ‚Äòsrc/main.rs‚Äô, and run ‚Äòcargo run‚Äô:
it should print ‚ÄòHello, Macro! My name is Pancakes!‚Äô The implementation
of the ‚ÄòHelloMacro‚Äô trait from the procedural macro was included without
the ‚Äòpancakes‚Äô crate needing to implement it; the
‚Äò#[derive(HelloMacro)]‚Äô added the trait implementation.

