22.1.5.5 Attribute-like macros
..............................

Attribute-like macros are similar to custom derive macros, but instead
of generating code for the ‚Äòderive‚Äô attribute, they allow you to create
new attributes.  They're also more flexible: ‚Äòderive‚Äô only works for
structs and enums; attributes can be applied to other items as well,
such as functions.  Here's an example of using an attribute-like macro:
say you have an attribute named ‚Äòroute‚Äô that annotates functions when
using a web application framework:

fn index() {

This ‚Äò#[route]‚Äô attribute would be defined by the framework as a
procedural macro.  The signature of the macro definition function would
look like this:

pub fn route(attr: TokenStream, item: TokenStream) -> TokenStream {

Here, we have two parameters of type ‚ÄòTokenStream‚Äô.  The first is for
the contents of the attribute: the ‚ÄòGET, "/"‚Äô part.  The second is the
body of the item the attribute is attached to: in this case, ‚Äòfn index()
{}‚Äô and the rest of the function's body.

Other than that, attribute-like macros work the same way as custom
derive macros: you create a crate with the ‚Äòproc-macro‚Äô crate type and
implement a function that generates the code you want!


