23.1.1.1 Reading the Request
............................

Let's implement the functionality to read the request from the browser!
To separate the concerns of first getting a connection and then taking
some action with the connection, we'll start a new function for
processing connections.  In this new ‚Äòhandle_connection‚Äô function, we'll
read data from the TCP stream and print it so we can see the data being
sent from the browser.  Change the code to look like Listing 21-2.

use std::{
    io::{prelude::*, BufReader},
    net::{TcpListener, TcpStream},
};

fn main() {
    let listener = TcpListener::bind("127.0.0.1:7878").unwrap();

    for stream in listener.incoming() {
        let stream = stream.unwrap();

        handle_connection(stream);
    }
}

fn handle_connection(mut stream: TcpStream) {
    let buf_reader = BufReader::new(&stream);
    let http_request: Vec<_> = buf_reader
        .lines()
        .map(|result| result.unwrap())
        .take_while(|line| !line.is_empty())
        .collect();

    println!("Request: {http_request:#?}");
}

We bring ‚Äòstd::io::prelude‚Äô and ‚Äòstd::io::BufReader‚Äô into scope to get
access to traits and types that let us read from and write to the
stream.  In the ‚Äòfor‚Äô loop in the ‚Äòmain‚Äô function, instead of printing a
message that says we made a connection, we now call the new
‚Äòhandle_connection‚Äô function and pass the ‚Äòstream‚Äô to it.

In the ‚Äòhandle_connection‚Äô function, we create a new ‚ÄòBufReader‚Äô
instance that wraps a reference to the ‚Äòstream‚Äô.  The ‚ÄòBufReader‚Äô adds
buffering by managing calls to the ‚Äòstd::io::Read‚Äô trait methods for us.

We create a variable named ‚Äòhttp_request‚Äô to collect the lines of the
request the browser sends to our server.  We indicate that we want to
collect these lines in a vector by adding the ‚ÄòVec<_>‚Äô type annotation.

‚ÄòBufReader‚Äô implements the ‚Äòstd::io::BufRead‚Äô trait, which provides the
‚Äòlines‚Äô method.  The ‚Äòlines‚Äô method returns an iterator of
‚ÄòResult<String, std::io::Error>‚Äô by splitting the stream of data
whenever it sees a newline byte.  To get each ‚ÄòString‚Äô, we map and
‚Äòunwrap‚Äô each ‚ÄòResult‚Äô.  The ‚ÄòResult‚Äô might be an error if the data
isn't valid UTF-8 or if there was a problem reading from the stream.
Again, a production program should handle these errors more gracefully,
but we're choosing to stop the program in the error case for simplicity.

The browser signals the end of an HTTP request by sending two newline
characters in a row, so to get one request from the stream, we take
lines until we get a line that is the empty string.  Once we've
collected the lines into the vector, we're printing them out using
pretty debug formatting so we can take a look at the instructions the
web browser is sending to our server.

