then we call ‚Äòunwrap‚Äô to panic on any errors.  Acquiring a lock might
fail if the mutex is in a ‚Äòpoisoned‚Äô state, which can happen if some
other thread panicked while holding the lock rather than releasing the
lock.  In this situation, calling ‚Äòunwrap‚Äô to have this thread panic is
the correct action to take.  Feel free to change this ‚Äòunwrap‚Äô to an
‚Äòexpect‚Äô with an error message that is meaningful to you.

If we get the lock on the mutex, we call ‚Äòrecv‚Äô to receive a ‚ÄòJob‚Äô from
the channel.  A final ‚Äòunwrap‚Äô moves past any errors here as well, which
might occur if the thread holding the sender has shut down, similar to
how the ‚Äòsend‚Äô method returns ‚ÄòErr‚Äô if the receiver shuts down.

The call to ‚Äòrecv‚Äô blocks, so if there is no job yet, the current thread
will wait until a job becomes available.  The ‚ÄòMutex<T>‚Äô ensures that
