23.1.3.2 Signaling to the Threads to Stop Listening for Jobs
............................................................

With all the changes we've made, our code compiles without any warnings.
However, the bad news is this code doesn't function the way we want it
to yet.  The key is the logic in the closures run by the threads of the
‚ÄòWorker‚Äô instances: at the moment, we call ‚Äòjoin‚Äô, but that won't shut
down the threads because they ‚Äòloop‚Äô forever looking for jobs.  If we
try to drop our ‚ÄòThreadPool‚Äô with our current implementation of ‚Äòdrop‚Äô,
the main thread will block forever waiting for the first thread to
finish.

To fix this problem, we'll need a change in the ‚ÄòThreadPool‚Äô ‚Äòdrop‚Äô
implementation and then a change in the ‚ÄòWorker‚Äô loop.

First, we'll change the ‚ÄòThreadPool‚Äô ‚Äòdrop‚Äô implementation to explicitly
drop the ‚Äòsender‚Äô before waiting for the threads to finish.  Listing
21-23 shows the changes to ‚ÄòThreadPool‚Äô to explicitly drop ‚Äòsender‚Äô.  We
use the same ‚ÄòOption‚Äô and ‚Äòtake‚Äô technique as we did with the thread to
be able to move ‚Äòsender‚Äô out of ‚ÄòThreadPool‚Äô:

pub struct ThreadPool {
    workers: Vec<Worker>,
    sender: Option<mpsc::Sender<Job>>,
}
// --snip--
impl ThreadPool {
    pub fn new(size: usize) -> ThreadPool {
        // --snip--

        ThreadPool {
            workers,
            sender: Some(sender),
        }
    }

    pub fn execute<F>(&self, f: F)
    where
        F: FnOnce() + Send + 'static,
    {
        let job = Box::new(f);

        self.sender.as_ref().unwrap().send(job).unwrap();
    }
}

impl Drop for ThreadPool {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        drop(self.sender.take());

        for worker in &mut self.workers {
            println!("Shutting down worker {}", worker.id);

            if let Some(thread) = worker.thread.take() {
                thread.join().unwrap();
            }
        }
    }
}

Dropping ‚Äòsender‚Äô closes the channel, which indicates no more messages
will be sent.  When that happens, all the calls to ‚Äòrecv‚Äô that the
workers do in the infinite loop will return an error.  In Listing 21-24,
we change the ‚ÄòWorker‚Äô loop to gracefully exit the loop in that case,
which means the threads will finish when the ‚ÄòThreadPool‚Äô ‚Äòdrop‚Äô
implementation calls ‚Äòjoin‚Äô on them.

impl Worker {
    fn new(id: usize, receiver: Arc<Mutex<mpsc::Receiver<Job>>>) -> Worker {
        let thread = thread::spawn(move || loop {
            let message = receiver.lock().unwrap().recv();

            match message {
                Ok(job) => {
                    println!("Worker {id} got a job; executing.");

                    job();
                }
                Err(_) => {
                    println!("Worker {id} disconnected; shutting down.");
                    break;
                }
            }
        });

        Worker {
            id,
            thread: Some(thread),
        }
    }
}

