24.1.1.2 Raw Identifiers
........................

‚ÄòRaw identifiers‚Äô are the syntax that lets you use keywords where they
wouldn't normally be allowed.  You use a raw identifier by prefixing a
keyword with ‚Äòr#‚Äô.

For example, ‚Äòmatch‚Äô is a keyword.  If you try to compile the following
function that uses ‚Äòmatch‚Äô as its name:

Filename: src/main.rs

fn match(needle: &str, haystack: &str) -> bool {
    haystack.contains(needle)
}

you'll get this error:

error: expected identifier, found keyword `match`
 --> src/main.rs:4:4
  |
4 | fn match(needle: &str, haystack: &str) -> bool {
  |    ^^^^^ expected identifier, found keyword

The error shows that you can't use the keyword ‚Äòmatch‚Äô as the function
identifier.  To use ‚Äòmatch‚Äô as a function name, you need to use the raw
identifier syntax, like this:

Filename: src/main.rs

fn r#match(needle: &str, haystack: &str) -> bool {
    haystack.contains(needle)
}

fn main() {
    assert!(r#match("foo", "foobar"));
}

This code will compile without any errors.  Note the ‚Äòr#‚Äô prefix on the
function name in its definition as well as where the function is called
in ‚Äòmain‚Äô.

Raw identifiers allow you to use any word you choose as an identifier,
even if that word happens to be a reserved keyword.  This gives us more
freedom to choose identifier names, as well as lets us integrate with
programs written in a language where these words aren't keywords.  In
addition, raw identifiers allow you to use libraries written in a
different Rust edition than your crate uses.  For example, ‚Äòtry‚Äô isn't a
keyword in the 2015 edition but is in the 2018 edition.  If you depend
on a library that's written using the 2015 edition and has a ‚Äòtry‚Äô
function, you'll need to use the raw identifier syntax, ‚Äòr#try‚Äô in this
case, to call that function from your 2018 edition code.  See *note
Appendix E: Appendix E - Editions. for more information on editions.


