24.1.3 Appendix C: Derivable Traits
-----------------------------------

In various places in the book, we've discussed the ‚Äòderive‚Äô attribute,
which you can apply to a struct or enum definition.  The ‚Äòderive‚Äô
attribute generates code that will implement a trait with its own
default implementation on the type you've annotated with the ‚Äòderive‚Äô
syntax.

In this appendix, we provide a reference of all the traits in the
standard library that you can use with ‚Äòderive‚Äô.  Each section covers:

   ‚Ä¢ What operators and methods deriving this trait will enable
   ‚Ä¢ What the implementation of the trait provided by ‚Äòderive‚Äô does
   ‚Ä¢ What implementing the trait signifies about the type
   ‚Ä¢ The conditions in which you're allowed or not allowed to implement
     the trait
   ‚Ä¢ Examples of operations that require the trait

If you want different behavior from that provided by the ‚Äòderive‚Äô
attribute, consult the standard library documentation
(https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/../std/index.html) for each trait for
details of how to manually implement them.

These traits listed here are the only ones defined by the standard
library that can be implemented on your types using ‚Äòderive‚Äô.  Other
traits defined in the standard library don't have sensible default
behavior, so it's up to you to implement them in the way that makes
sense for what you're trying to accomplish.

An example of a trait that can't be derived is ‚ÄòDisplay‚Äô, which handles
formatting for end users.  You should always consider the appropriate
way to display a type to an end user.  What parts of the type should an
end user be allowed to see?  What parts would they find relevant?  What
format of the data would be most relevant to them?  The Rust compiler
doesn't have this insight, so it can't provide appropriate default
behavior for you.

The list of derivable traits provided in this appendix is not
comprehensive: libraries can implement ‚Äòderive‚Äô for their own traits,
making the list of traits you can use ‚Äòderive‚Äô with truly open-ended.
Implementing ‚Äòderive‚Äô involves using a procedural macro, which is
covered in the *note ‚ÄúMacros‚Äù: Macros. section of Chapter 20.

