24.1.3.2 ‚ÄòPartialEq‚Äô and ‚ÄòEq‚Äô for Equality Comparisons
......................................................

The ‚ÄòPartialEq‚Äô trait allows you to compare instances of a type to check
for equality and enables use of the ‚Äò==‚Äô and ‚Äò!=‚Äô operators.

Deriving ‚ÄòPartialEq‚Äô implements the ‚Äòeq‚Äô method.  When ‚ÄòPartialEq‚Äô is
derived on structs, two instances are equal only if ‚Äòall‚Äô fields are
equal, and the instances are not equal if any fields are not equal.
When derived on enums, each variant is equal to itself and not equal to
the other variants.

The ‚ÄòPartialEq‚Äô trait is required, for example, with the use of the
‚Äòassert_eq!‚Äô macro, which needs to be able to compare two instances of a
type for equality.

The ‚ÄòEq‚Äô trait has no methods.  Its purpose is to signal that for every
value of the annotated type, the value is equal to itself.  The ‚ÄòEq‚Äô
trait can only be applied to types that also implement ‚ÄòPartialEq‚Äô,
although not all types that implement ‚ÄòPartialEq‚Äô can implement ‚ÄòEq‚Äô.
One example of this is floating point number types: the implementation
of floating point numbers states that two instances of the not-a-number
(‚ÄòNaN‚Äô) value are not equal to each other.

An example of when ‚ÄòEq‚Äô is required is for keys in a ‚ÄòHashMap<K, V>‚Äô so
the ‚ÄòHashMap<K, V>‚Äô can tell whether two keys are the same.


