24.1.3.3 ‚ÄòPartialOrd‚Äô and ‚ÄòOrd‚Äô for Ordering Comparisons
........................................................

The ‚ÄòPartialOrd‚Äô trait allows you to compare instances of a type for
sorting purposes.  A type that implements ‚ÄòPartialOrd‚Äô can be used with
the ‚Äò<‚Äô, ‚Äò>‚Äô, ‚Äò<=‚Äô, and ‚Äò>=‚Äô operators.  You can only apply the
‚ÄòPartialOrd‚Äô trait to types that also implement ‚ÄòPartialEq‚Äô.

Deriving ‚ÄòPartialOrd‚Äô implements the ‚Äòpartial_cmp‚Äô method, which returns
an ‚ÄòOption<Ordering>‚Äô that will be ‚ÄòNone‚Äô when the values given don't
produce an ordering.  An example of a value that doesn't produce an
ordering, even though most values of that type can be compared, is the
not-a-number (‚ÄòNaN‚Äô) floating point value.  Calling ‚Äòpartial_cmp‚Äô with
any floating point number and the ‚ÄòNaN‚Äô floating point value will return
‚ÄòNone‚Äô.

When derived on structs, ‚ÄòPartialOrd‚Äô compares two instances by
comparing the value in each field in the order in which the fields
appear in the struct definition.  When derived on enums, variants of the
enum declared earlier in the enum definition are considered less than
the variants listed later.

The ‚ÄòPartialOrd‚Äô trait is required, for example, for the ‚Äògen_range‚Äô
method from the ‚Äòrand‚Äô crate that generates a random value in the range
specified by a range expression.

The ‚ÄòOrd‚Äô trait allows you to know that for any two values of the
annotated type, a valid ordering will exist.  The ‚ÄòOrd‚Äô trait implements
the ‚Äòcmp‚Äô method, which returns an ‚ÄòOrdering‚Äô rather than an
‚ÄòOption<Ordering>‚Äô because a valid ordering will always be possible.
You can only apply the ‚ÄòOrd‚Äô trait to types that also implement
‚ÄòPartialOrd‚Äô and ‚ÄòEq‚Äô (and ‚ÄòEq‚Äô requires ‚ÄòPartialEq‚Äô).  When derived on
structs and enums, ‚Äòcmp‚Äô behaves the same way as the derived
implementation for ‚Äòpartial_cmp‚Äô does with ‚ÄòPartialOrd‚Äô.

An example of when ‚ÄòOrd‚Äô is required is when storing values in a
‚ÄòBTreeSet<T>‚Äô, a data structure that stores data based on the sort order
of the values.


