24.1.3.4 ‚ÄòClone‚Äô and ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô for Duplicating Values
..................................................

The ‚ÄòClone‚Äô trait allows you to explicitly create a deep copy of a
value, and the duplication process might involve running arbitrary code
and copying heap data.  See the *note ‚ÄúWays Variables and Data Interact
Clone‚Äù:
#book__pandoc__texi__src__ch04-01-what-is-ownershipmd__ways-variables-and-data-interact-clone.
section in Chapter 4 for more information on ‚ÄòClone‚Äô.

Deriving ‚ÄòClone‚Äô implements the ‚Äòclone‚Äô method, which when implemented
for the whole type, calls ‚Äòclone‚Äô on each of the parts of the type.
This means all the fields or values in the type must also implement
‚ÄòClone‚Äô to derive ‚ÄòClone‚Äô.

An example of when ‚ÄòClone‚Äô is required is when calling the ‚Äòto_vec‚Äô
method on a slice.  The slice doesn't own the type instances it
contains, but the vector returned from ‚Äòto_vec‚Äô will need to own its
instances, so ‚Äòto_vec‚Äô calls ‚Äòclone‚Äô on each item.  Thus, the type
stored in the slice must implement ‚ÄòClone‚Äô.

The ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô trait allows you to duplicate a value by only copying bits
stored on the stack; no arbitrary code is necessary.  See the *note
‚ÄúStack-Only Data Copy‚Äù:
#book__pandoc__texi__src__ch04-01-what-is-ownershipmd__stack-only-data-copy.
section in Chapter 4 for more information on ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô.

The ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô trait doesn't define any methods to prevent programmers from
overloading those methods and violating the assumption that no arbitrary
code is being run.  That way, all programmers can assume that copying a
value will be very fast.

You can derive ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô on any type whose parts all implement ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô.  A
type that implements ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô must also implement ‚ÄòClone‚Äô, because a type
that implements ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô has a trivial implementation of ‚ÄòClone‚Äô that
performs the same task as ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô.

The ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô trait is rarely required; types that implement ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô have
optimizations available, meaning you don't have to call ‚Äòclone‚Äô, which
makes the code more concise.

Everything possible with ‚ÄòCopy‚Äô you can also accomplish with ‚ÄòClone‚Äô,
but the code might be slower or have to use ‚Äòclone‚Äô in places.


