24.1.3.5 ‚ÄòHash‚Äô for Mapping a Value to a Value of Fixed Size
............................................................

The ‚ÄòHash‚Äô trait allows you to take an instance of a type of arbitrary
size and map that instance to a value of fixed size using a hash
function.  Deriving ‚ÄòHash‚Äô implements the ‚Äòhash‚Äô method.  The derived
implementation of the ‚Äòhash‚Äô method combines the result of calling
‚Äòhash‚Äô on each of the parts of the type, meaning all fields or values
must also implement ‚ÄòHash‚Äô to derive ‚ÄòHash‚Äô.

An example of when ‚ÄòHash‚Äô is required is in storing keys in a
‚ÄòHashMap<K, V>‚Äô to store data efficiently.


