24.1.3.6 ‚ÄòDefault‚Äô for Default Values
.....................................

The ‚ÄòDefault‚Äô trait allows you to create a default value for a type.
Deriving ‚ÄòDefault‚Äô implements the ‚Äòdefault‚Äô function.  The derived
implementation of the ‚Äòdefault‚Äô function calls the ‚Äòdefault‚Äô function on
each part of the type, meaning all fields or values in the type must
also implement ‚ÄòDefault‚Äô to derive ‚ÄòDefault‚Äô.

The ‚ÄòDefault::default‚Äô function is commonly used in combination with the
struct update syntax discussed in the *note ‚ÄúCreating Instances From
Other Instances With Struct Update Syntax‚Äù: Creating Instances from
Other Instances with Struct Update Syntax. section in Chapter 5.  You
can customize a few fields of a struct and then set and use a default
value for the rest of the fields by using ‚Äò..Default::default()‚Äô.

The ‚ÄòDefault‚Äô trait is required when you use the method
‚Äòunwrap_or_default‚Äô on ‚ÄòOption<T>‚Äô instances, for example.  If the
‚ÄòOption<T>‚Äô is ‚ÄòNone‚Äô, the method ‚Äòunwrap_or_default‚Äô will return the
result of ‚ÄòDefault::default‚Äô for the type ‚ÄòT‚Äô stored in the ‚ÄòOption<T>‚Äô.


