24.1.7.1 Stability Without Stagnation
.....................................

As a language, Rust cares a ‚Äòlot‚Äô about the stability of your code.  We
want Rust to be a rock-solid foundation you can build on, and if things
were constantly changing, that would be impossible.  At the same time,
if we can't experiment with new features, we may not find out important
flaws until after their release, when we can no longer change things.

Our solution to this problem is what we call ‚Äústability without
stagnation‚Äù, and our guiding principle is this: you should never have to
fear upgrading to a new version of stable Rust.  Each upgrade should be
painless, but should also bring you new features, fewer bugs, and faster
compile times.


